Chairman of the State Affairs Commission)\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1982|1|8|df=y}} (North Korean records)<ref name=\"Birth-1982\"/><br />{{birth date and age|1983|1|8|df=y}}<br /> ([[South Korea]]n records)<ref name=NYTRodman>{{cite news|title=Rodman Gives Details on Trip to North Korea |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=9 September 2013 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/10/world/asia/rodman-gives-details-on-trip-to-north-korea.html |accessdate=10 September 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130910200226/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/09/10/world/asia/rodman-gives-details-on-trip-to-north-korea.html |archivedate=10 September 2013 }}</ref><br />{{birth date and age|1984|1|8|df=y}}<br /> (American records)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-au/news/world/we-finally-know-the-age-of-north-korean-dictator-kim-jong-un/ar-BBu4zLO?li=AAgfLCP&ocid=mailsignout |title=We finally know the age of North Korean dictator Kim Jong Un |website=www.msn.com |accessdate=20 May 2017 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216233643/http://www.msn.com/en-au/news/world/we-finally-know-the-age-of-north-korean-dictator-kim-jong-un/ar-BBu4zLO?li=AAgfLCP&ocid=mailsignout |archivedate=16 February 2017 }}</ref><ref name=\"secret-life-of-aunt\">{{cite news|title=The secret life of Kim Jong-un's aunt, who has lived in the U.S. since 1998 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/the-secret-life-of-kim-jong-uns-aunt-who-has-lived-in-the-us-since-1998/2016/05/26/522e4ec8-12d7-11e6-a9b5-bf703a5a7191_story.html |work=The Washington Post |date=27 May 2016 |accessdate=28 May 2016 |quote=They can reveal, for example, that Kim Jong-un was born in 1984 \u2013 not 1982 or 1983, as has been widely believed. The reason they're certain? It was the same year that their first son was born. \"He and my son were playmates from birth. I changed both of their diapers\", Ko said with a laugh. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529082608/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/the-secret-life-of-kim-jong-uns-aunt-who-has-lived-in-the-us-since-1998/2016/05/26/522e4ec8-12d7-11e6-a9b5-bf703a5a7191_story.html |archivedate=29 May 2016 }}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Pyongyang]], North Korea\n| party = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|[[Ri Sol-ju]]|2009}}\n| partner = \n| children = 1\u20133\n| parents = [[Kim Jong-il]]<br />[[Ko Yong-hui]]\n| alma_mater = [[Kim Il-sung University]]<br />[[Kim Il-sung Military University]]\n| allegiance = [[North Korea]]\n| branch = [[Korean People's Army]]\n| serviceyears = 2010\u2013present\n| rank = [[Wonsu|Marshal of the Republic]]\n| signature = Kim Jong-un Signature.svg\n| footnotes = {{Collapsible list\n|titlestyle = background-color:#FCF;text-align:center;\n|title = Central institution membership\n|bullets = on\n| 2012\u2013present: Member, Presidium of the Political Bureau of the 6th, 7th Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea\n| 2012\u2013present: Member, Political Bureau of the 6th, 7th Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea\n| 2010\u2013present: Member, 6th, 7th Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea\n| 2014\u20132019: Deputy, 13th Supreme People's Assembly}}\n----\n{{Collapsible list\n|titlestyle= background-color:#FCF;text-align:center;\n|title=Other offices held\n|bullets=on\n| 2012\u2013present: Chairman, Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea\n| 2010\u20132012: Vice Chairman, Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea\n}}\n----\n<center>'''[[List of leaders of North Korea|Leader of the Democratic People's <br /> Republic of Korea]]'''<br />\n{{flatlist|\n*{{big|'''\u2190'''}} [[Kim Jong-il]]\n*''Current holder''\n}}\n</center>\n| module =\n{{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n|title = '''Kim Jong-un''' or '''Kim Jong Un'''\n|image = Kim Jong-un (Korean and Chinese characters).svg\n|image_size = 160px\n|caption = \"Kim Jong-un\" in [[Hangul|Chos\u014fn'g\u016dl]] (top) and [[Hanja|hancha]] (bottom) scripts\n|context = north\n|hangul = {{linktext|\uae40|\uc815|\uc740}}\n|hanja = {{lang|ko|{{linktext|\u91d1|\u6b63|\u6069}}}}<ref name=\"hanja\">{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/liveweb/http://news.naver.com/main/hotissue/read.nhn?mid=hot&sid1=100&gid=438117&cid=565935&iid=259968&oid=020&aid=0002171110&ptype=011 |script-title=ko:[\u5317 \ub9c9\uc624\ub978 \uae40\uc815\uc740 \uc2dc\ub300]\uc870\uc120\uc911\uc559\ud1b5\uc2e0 \ubcf4\ub3c4, \u91d1\u6b63\u9280(\uff38) \u91d1\u6b63\u6069 |publisher=[[Naver]] |date=2 October 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2010 |language=ko}}</ref>\n|rr = Gim Jeong(-)eun\n|mr = Kim Ch\u014fng\u016dn\n}}\n}}\n'''Kim Jong-un''' (officially [[Transcription (linguistics)|transcribed]] '''Kim Jong Un'''; {{Lang-ko|\uae40\uc815\uc740}} ([[Hanja]]: {{lang|ko|{{linktext|\u91d1|\u6b63|\u6069}}}}); {{IPA-ko|kim.dz\u0254\u014b.\u026fn}};{{efn|The given name ''Jong-un'' / ''Jong Un'' is pronounced {{IPA-ko|ts\u0254\u014b.\u026fn}} in isolation.}} born 8 January 1983 or 1984) is a [[North Korea]]n politician serving as [[List of leaders of North Korea#Supreme leader of the DPRK|Supreme Leader of North Korea]] since 2011, and has served as the [[Chairman of the Workers' Party of Korea|leader]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] since 2012.{{efn|Supreme Leader Kim Jong-un has served as leader of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]] as [[General Secretary of the Communist Party|First Secretary]] between 2012 and 2016, and [[Chairman of the Workers' Party of Korea|Party Chairman]] since 2016.}} He is the second child of [[Kim Jong-il]] (1941\u20132011), who was North Korea's second leader from 1994 to 2011, and [[Ko Yong-hui]] (1952\u20132004). He is the grandson of [[Kim Il-sung]], who was the founder and led North Korea from its establishment in 1948 until [[Death and state funeral of Kim Il-sung|his death]] in 1994.\n\nFrom late 2010, Kim Jong-un was viewed as [[heir apparent]] to the leadership of North Korea, and following [[Death and state funeral of Kim Jong-il|the elder Kim's death]], North Korean state television announced him as the \"Great Successor\". Kim holds the titles of Chairman of the Workers' Party of Korea (as [[General Secretary of the Communist Party|First Secretary]] between 2012 and 2016) and ''[[Ex officio member|ex officio]]'' [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea|Chairman of the Central Military Commission]], [[Chairman of the State Affairs Commission]], commander-in-chief (as SAC chairman), and member of the [[Presidium of the Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Presidium]] of the [[Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo]] of the Workers' Party of Korea, the highest decision-making body in North Korea. Kim was promoted to the rank of [[Wonsu|Marshal]] of North Korea in the [[Korean People's Army]] on 18 July 2012, consolidating his position as the [[Supreme Commander of the Armed Forces of North Korea|Supreme Commander of the Armed Forces]]. [[Media of North Korea|North Korean state media]] often refers to him as Marshal Kim Jong-un, \"the Marshal\" or \"Dear Respected.\"\n\nKim rules a [[dictatorship]] where [[Elections in North Korea|elections are not free and fair]], government critics are [[Persecution|persecuted]], [[Freedom of the press|media is controlled by the regime]], [[Internet in North Korea|internet access]] is limited by the regime, and there is no [[freedom of religion]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-44234505|title=North Korea's sidelined human rights crisis|date=18 February 2019|access-date=22 October 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.routledge.com/The-Authoritarian-Public-Sphere-Legitimation-and-Autocratic-Power-in-North/Dukalskis/p/book/9781138210356|title=The Authoritarian Public Sphere: Legitimation and Autocratic Power in North Korea, Burma, and China, 1st Edition (Hardback) - Routledge|website=Routledge.com|language=en|access-date=22 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://cup.columbia.edu/book/nuclear-north-korea/9780231189231|title=Nuclear North Korea: A Debate on Engagement Strategies, revised and updated edition|last=Cha|first=Victor D.|last2=Haggard|first2=David C. Kang|date=2018|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=9780231548243|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/why-communism-did-not-collapse/3D9518947D79D23A0A20D31746A4DC82|title=Why Communism Did Not Collapse edited by Martin K. Dimitrov|last=|first=|date=2013|website=Cambridge University Press|language=en|access-date=22 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Koo|first=Bon Sang|last2=Choi|first2=Jun Young|last3=Kim|first3=Junseok|date=2016|title=Analyzing Kim Jong-un's Survival Strategy from the Comparative Authoritarian Perspective|journal=Pacific Focus|language=en|volume=31|issue=2|pages=211\u2013231|doi=10.1111/pafo.12071|issn=1976-5118}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Corner|first=Paul|chapter=Non-compliance, Indifference and Resistance in Regimes of Mass Dictatorship|date=2016|pages=413\u2013425|editor-last=Corner|editor-first=Paul|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan UK|language=en|doi=10.1057/978-1-137-43763-1_33|isbn=9781137437631|editor2-last=Lim|editor2-first=Jie-Hyun|title=The Palgrave Handbook of Mass Dictatorship}}</ref> His regime operates an extensive network of [[Prisons in North Korea|prisons and labor camps]] that has imprisoned and killed millions of people; the regime convicts people for [[political crime]]s and uses [[collective punishment]] whereby members of a family get punished for the crimes of one person.<ref name=\":0\" /> According to the [[United Nations]], North Koreans live under \"systematic, widespread and gross human rights violations\" where the regime \"seeks to dominate every aspect of its citizens\u2019 lives and terrorizes them from within.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.brookings.edu/essay/the-education-of-kim-jong-un/|title=The education of Kim Jong-un|date=6 February 2018|website=Brookings|language=en-US|access-date=22 October 2019}}</ref> The regime exerts extensive control over the North Korean economy, with substantial state-controlled economic enterprises and significant restrictions on North Koreans' ability to engage in foreign economic activity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sup.org/books/title/?id=27340|title=Hard Target: Sanctions, Inducements, and the Case of North Korea {{!}} Stephan Haggard and Marcus Noland|last=Press|first=Stanford University|website=www.sup.org|language=en|access-date=22 October 2019}}</ref> On 12 December 2013, Kim ordered the execution of his uncle [[Jang Song-thaek]] for \"treachery\". Kim is widely believed to have ordered the assassination of his half-brother, [[Kim Jong-nam]], in Malaysia in February 2017. On 12 June 2018, Kim and [[President of the United States|US President]] [[Donald Trump]] met for a [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States Singapore Summit|summit]] in [[Singapore]], the first-ever talks held between a North Korean leader and a sitting US president, to discuss the [[North Korea and weapons of mass destruction|North Korean nuclear program]].\n\n== Early life==\nNorth Korean authorities and state-run media have stated that Kim's birthdate was 8 January 1982,<ref name=\"Birth-1982\">{{cite news |title=Everything you need to know about North Korean leader Kim Jong Un |url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/north-korean-leader-kim-jong/story?id=46804057 |accessdate=15 June 2018 |work=ABC News }}</ref> but South Korean intelligence officials believe the actual date is a year later.<ref name=NYTRodman/> It is thought that Kim's official birth year was changed for symbolic reasons; 1982 marks 70 years after the birth of his grandfather, [[Kim Il-sung]], and 40 years after the official birth of his father [[Kim Jong-il]]. The [[US Treasury Department]] lists Kim Jong-un's official birthdate as 8 January 1984.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Szoldra |first1=Paul |last2=Bondranenko |first2=Veronika |title=How North Korean leader Kim Jong-un, 33, became one of the world's scariest dictators |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/how-north-korean-leader-kim-jong-un-33-became-one-of-the-worlds-scariest-dictators-a7691396.html |accessdate=15 June 2018 |work=The Independent |date=19 April 2017}}</ref> Former basketball star [[Dennis Rodman]] confirmed that 8 January was Kim Jong-un's birthdate after meeting in September 2013 in North Korea, and that Kim was 30 years of age at the time.<ref name=NYTRodman/>\n\nKim Jong-un is the second of three children [[Ko Yong-hui]] bore to Kim Jong-il; his elder brother [[Kim Jong-chul]] was born in 1981, while his younger sister, [[Kim Yo-jong]], is believed to have been born in 1987.<ref name=\"Lee2012\">{{cite news|title=Kim Jong-un's sister is having a ball |url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2957573 |archive-date=16 October 2015 |work=Korea JoongAng Daily |date=8 August 2012 |last1=Lee |first1=Young-jong |last2=Kim |first2=Hee-jin |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016211015/http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2957573 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"Kim Yo Jong\">{{cite web |title=Kim Yo Jong |url=https://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/kji-2/kim-yo-jong/ |publisher=North Korea Leadership Watch |accessdate=15 October 2014 |date=11 July 2012}}</ref><ref>Moore, Malcolm. [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/5428300/Kim-Jong-un-a-profile-of-North-Koreas-next-leader.html Kim Jong-un: a profile of North Korea's next leader] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605153019/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/5428300/Kim-Jong-un-a-profile-of-North-Koreas-next-leader.html|date=5 June 2009}}. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''. 2 June 2009</ref> He is the grandson of Kim Il-sung, who was the founder and led North Korea from [[Day of the Foundation of the Republic|its establishment]] in 1948 until [[Death and state funeral of Kim Il-sung|his death]] in 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynk.com/korean/read.php?cataId=nk00500&num=55181|date=15 April 2008|work=DailyNK|language=Korean|script-title=ko:\uae40\uc77c\uc131, \ucfe0\ubc14\uc758 '\ud601\uba85\uc601\uc6c5' \uccb4\uac8c\ubc14\ub77c\ub97c \ub9cc\ub09c \ub0a0|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429064851/http://www.dailynk.com/korean/read.php?cataId=nk00500&num=55181|archivedate=29 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nAll the children of Kim Jong-il are said to have lived in Switzerland, as well as the mother of the two youngest sons, who lived in [[Geneva]] for some time.<ref name=\"Figaro\" />\nFirst reports said that Kim Jong-un attended the private English-language International School in [[G\u00fcmligen]] in Switzerland under the name \"Chol-pak\" or \"Pak-chol\" from 1993 to 1998.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/01/AR2009060103750.html |work=The Washington Post |author=Blaine Harden |title=Son Named Heir to North Korea's Kim Studied in Switzerland, Reportedly Loves NBA |date=3 June 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204205420/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/01/AR2009060103750.html |archivedate=4 February 2011 }}<br/>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/7810203/Rare-photos-of-Kim-Jong-ils-youngest-son-Kim-Jong-un-released.html |location=London, UK |work=The Daily Telegraph |author=Peter Foster |title=Rare photos of Kim Jong-il's youngest son, Kim Jong-un, released |date=8 June 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611052037/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/7810203/Rare-photos-of-Kim-Jong-ils-youngest-son-Kim-Jong-un-released.html |archivedate=11 June 2010 }}</ref> He was described as shy, a good student who got along well with his classmates, and was a basketball fan.<ref name=\"Guardian2009\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jun/02/kim-jong-il-names-son-successor |title=North Korean leader Kim Jong\u2011il 'names youngest son as successor' |agency=Associated Press |work=The Guardian |location=London, UK |issn=0261-3077 |date=2 June 2009 |archive-date=16 October 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016211014/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jun/02/kim-jong-il-names-son-successor |df= }}</ref> He was chaperoned by an older student, who was thought to be his bodyguard.<ref name=\"Henckel2009\">{{cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/welt_print/article3985896/Kim-Jong-un-und-sein-Unterricht-bei-den-Schweizern.html |title=Kim Jong-un und sein Unterricht bei den Schweizern |work=Die Welt |issn=0173-8437 |location=Berlin |first=Elisalex |last=Henckel |date=24 June 2009 |language=German |archivedate=27 July 2015 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727053343/http://www.welt.de/welt_print/article3985896/Kim-Jong-un-und-sein-Unterricht-bei-den-Schweizern.html |df= }}</ref> However, it was later suggested that the student at the G\u00fcmligen was not Kim Jong-un, but his elder brother Kim Jong-chul.<ref name=\"Plattner2009\">{{cite journal|title=Der Diktator spricht Deutsch |first1=Titus |last1=Plattner |first2=Julie |last2=Zaugg |date=8 May 2009 |journal=Cicero |url=http://www.cicero.de/weltb\u00fchne/der-diktator-spricht-deutsch/39681 |language=de |archive-date=30 September 2015 |issn=1613-4826 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150930081816/http://www.cicero.de/weltb%C3%BChne/der-diktator-spricht-deutsch/39681 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Schule Liebefeld-Steinh\u00f6lzli, K\u00f6niz.jpg|thumb|left|The Liebefeld-Steinh\u00f6lzli public school in [[K\u00f6niz]], [[Switzerland]], which Kim Jong-un is reported to have attended]]\nLater, it was reported that Kim Jong-un attended the Liebefeld Steinh\u00f6lzli [[state school]] in [[K\u00f6niz]] near Bern under the name \"Pak-un\" or \"Un-pak\" from 1998 until 2000 as the son of an employee of the North Korean embassy in Bern. Authorities confirmed that a North Korean student from North Korea attended the school during that period. Pak-un first attended a special class for foreign-language children and later attended the regular classes of the 6th, 7th, 8th and part of the final 9th year, leaving the school abruptly in the autumn of 2000. He was described as a well-integrated and ambitious student who liked to play basketball.<ref name=\"NZZ1.2748091\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nzz.ch/nachrichten/panorama/weitere_nordkoreanische_spuren_in_bern_1.2748091.html |title=Weitere nordkoreanische Spuren in Bern |newspaper=Neue Z\u00fcrcher Zeitung |date=16 June 2009 |language=German |accessdate=19 December 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211122422/http://www.nzz.ch/nachrichten/panorama/weitere_nordkoreanische_spuren_in_bern_1.2748091.html |archivedate=11 February 2012 }}</ref> However, his grades and attendance rating are reported to have been poor.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/education/latest-news/poor-school-marks-of-north-koreas-kim-jongun-exposed-3068333.html|work=Irish Independent|issn=0791-685X|title=Poor school marks of North Korea's Kim Jong-un exposed|date=2 April 2012|archive-url=https://webcitation.org/query?date=2015-12-26&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.independent.ie%2Flife%2Ffamily%2Flearning%2Fpoor-school-marks-of-north-koreas-kim-jongun-exposed-26838819.html|archive-date=26 December 2015|url-status=live}}<br/>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/9180501/Kim-Jong-uns-poor-marks-exposed.html |location=London, UK |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=Kim Jong-un's poor marks exposed |date=2 April 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120506125857/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/9180501/Kim-Jong-uns-poor-marks-exposed.html |archivedate=6 May 2012 }}</ref> The ambassador of North Korea in Switzerland, [[Ri Su-yong|Ri Chol]], had a close relationship with him and acted as a mentor.<ref name=\"Figaro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/international/2010/09/05/01003-20100905ARTFIG00221-kim-jong-un-une-education-suisse-entouree-de-mysteres.php |title=Kim Jong-un : une \u00e9ducation suisse entour\u00e9e de myst\u00e8res |work=Le Figaro |language=French |accessdate=19 December 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111219104625/http://www.lefigaro.fr/international/2010/09/05/01003-20100905ARTFIG00221-kim-jong-un-une-education-suisse-entouree-de-mysteres.php |archivedate=19 December 2011 |date=5 September 2010 }}</ref> One of Pak-un's classmates told reporters that he had told him that he was the son of the leader of North Korea.<ref name=\"Shubert2010\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/asiapcf/09/28/north.korea.heir.friend/ |publisher=CNN |title=North Korea: Nuclear Tension |date=29 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150609120331/http://www.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/asiapcf/09/28/north.korea.heir.friend |archivedate= 9 June 2015 |url-status=live |first=Atika |last=Shubert |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"ta2909\">{{cite web|title=Mein Freund, der zuk\u00fcnftige Diktator Nordkoreas |author=Bernhard Odenahl |date=29 September 2009 |work=Tages-Anzeiger |language=German |url=http://www.tagesanzeiger.ch/ausland/asien-und-ozeanien/Mein-Freund-der-zukuenftige-Diktator-Nordkoreas-/story/20634972 |accessdate=29 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101002204137/http://www.tagesanzeiger.ch/ausland/asien-und-ozeanien/Mein-Freund-der-zukuenftige-Diktator-Nordkoreas-/story/20634972 |archivedate=2 October 2010 }}</ref> According to some reports, Kim was described by classmates as a shy child who was awkward with girls and indifferent to political issues, but who distinguished himself in sports and had a fascination with the American [[National Basketball Association]] and [[Michael Jordan]]. One friend claimed that he had been shown pictures of Pak-un with [[Kobe Bryant]] and [[Toni Kuko\u010d]].<ref name=\"Chosun\">{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/07/17/2009071700693.html |title=Classmates Recall Kim Jong-un's Basketball Obsession |work=The Chosun Ilbo |date=17 July 2009 |accessdate=14 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218082737/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/07/17/2009071700693.html |archivedate=18 February 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2012, new documents came to light indicating that Kim Jong-un had lived in Switzerland since 1991 or 1992, earlier than previously thought.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lematin.ch/suisse/kim-jongun-reste-neuf-ans-suisse/story/20273993 |title=Kim Jong-un est rest\u00e9 neuf ans en Suisse |author=Titus Plattner |accessdate=24 April 2012 |date=21 April 2012 |work=Le Matin |language=French |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130823194510/http://www.lematin.ch/suisse/kim-jongun-reste-neuf-ans-suisse/story/20273993 |archivedate=23 August 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe Laboratory of Anatomic Anthropology at the [[University of Lyon]], France, compared the picture of Pak-un taken at the Liebefeld Steinh\u00f6lzli school in 1999 with a picture of Kim Jong-un from 2012 and concluded that the faces show a conformity of 95%, suggesting that it is most likely that they are the same person.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Titus Plattner |author2=Daniel Glaus |author3=Julian Schmidli |url=http://www.sonntagszeitung.ch/fokus/artikel-detailseite/?newsid=212533 |title=Der Diktator aus Liebefeld |work=[[SonntagsZeitung]] |date=1 April 2012 |page=17 |language=German |accessdate=2 April 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/66cIlKe2M?url=http://www.sonntagszeitung.ch/fokus/artikel-detailseite/?newsid=212533 |archivedate= 2 April 2012 |df= }}<br/>\"Der Sch\u00fcler Un Pak ist identisch mit Kim Jong-un.\"</ref>\n\n''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported in 2009 that Kim Jong-un's school friends recalled he \"spent hours doing meticulous pencil drawings of [[Chicago Bulls]] superstar Michael Jordan\".<ref name=\"Higgins2009\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/15/AR2009071503930_pf.html |title=Who Will Succeed Kim Jong Il? |date=16 July 2009 |work=The Washington Post |archive-url=https://webcitation.org/query?date=2015-12-26&url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.washingtonpost.com%2Fwp-dyn%2Fcontent%2Farticle%2F2009%2F07%2F15%2FAR2009071503930_pf.html |archive-date=26 December 2015 |url-status=live |first=Andrew |last=Higgins |page=A01  }}</ref> He was obsessed with basketball and [[computer games]],<ref name=\"Chosun\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Freeman |first1=Colin |last2=Sherwell |first2=Philip |title=North Korea leadership: 'My happy days at school with North Korea's future leader' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/8025015/North-Korea-leadership-My-happy-days-at-school-with-North-Koreas-future-leader.html |accessdate=14 February 2017 |work=The Telegraph |date=26 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214181910/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/8025015/North-Korea-leadership-My-happy-days-at-school-with-North-Koreas-future-leader.html |archivedate=14 February 2017 }}<br/>{{cite news|last1=Fisher |first1=Max |title=Kim Jong Eun inherited an eccentric obsession with basketball from father Kim Jong Il |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2013/03/01/kim-jong-eun-inherited-an-eccentric-obsession-with-basketball-from-father-kim-jong-il/ |accessdate=14 February 2017 |work=The Washington Post |date=1 March 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170214180304/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2013/03/01/kim-jong-eun-inherited-an-eccentric-obsession-with-basketball-from-father-kim-jong-il/ |archivedate=14 February 2017 }}</ref> and was a fan of [[Jackie Chan]] action movies.<ref name=\"kimpersonality\"/>\n\nMost analysts agree that Kim Jong-un attended [[Kim Il-sung University]], a leading officer-training school in Pyongyang, from 2002 to 2007.<ref name=\"NYTProfile\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/15/world/asia/15kim.html?_r=0 |title=North Korea's Heir Apparent Remains a Mystery |author=Choe Sang-Hun and Martin Fackler |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=14 June 2009 |accessdate=2 April 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6MEoQ4wBe?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/15/world/asia/15kim.html?_r=0 |archivedate=29 December 2013 }}</ref> Kim obtained two degrees, one in physics at Kim Il-sung University and another as an Army officer at the [[Kim Il-sung Military University]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/world_now/2011/12/kim-jong-un-first-appearance.html|title=Kim Jong Un makes first appearance since father's death|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=20 December 2011|accessdate=8 January 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Powell2011\">{{cite journal|last=Powell |first=Bill |date=22 December 2011 |url=http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,2102985,00.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702154036/http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0%2C8599%2C2102985%2C00.html |url-status=live |archivedate= 2 July 2015 |title=The Generals Who Will Really Rule North Korea |journal=Time |location=New York |issn=0040-781X |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn late February 2018, [[Reuters]] reported that Kim and his father had used forged passports\u2014supposedly issued by [[Brazil]] and dated 26 February 1996\u2014to apply for visas in various countries. Both 10-year passports carry a stamp saying \"Embassy of Brazil in Prague\". Kim Jong-un's passport records the name \"Josef Pwag\" and a date of birth of 1 February 1983.<ref name=\"2018-02-28_Reuters\">[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-02-28/north-korea-kim-jong-un-father-used-fake-brazilian-passports/9494034 Kim Jong-un and father used fake Brazilian passports to apply for Western visas], [[Reuters]] per [[ABC News Online]]. 28 February 2018. Accessed on 12 April 2018.</ref>\n\nFor many years, only one confirmed photograph of him was known to exist outside North Korea, apparently taken in the mid-1990s, when he was eleven.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11389824 |title=Tales of starvation and death in North Korea |publisher=BBC |date=22 September 2010 |accessdate=28 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100930044845/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11389824 |archivedate=30 September 2010 }}</ref> Occasionally, other supposed images of him surfaced but were often disputed.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/8078562.stm Profile: Kim Jong-un] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090605160315/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/8078562.stm |date=5 June 2009 }}, BBC News, 2 June 2009<br/>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/world/asia/25succession.html |work=The New York Times |title=North Korea Appears to Tap Leader's Son as Enigmatic Heir |author=Martin Fackler |date=24 April 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701003019/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/world/asia/25succession.html |archivedate=1 July 2017 }}<br/>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2010/04/21/2010042100633.html |title=Confusion Over Photo of N. Korean Leader\u2011to\u2011Be |work=The Chosun Ilbo |accessdate=28 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100701171022/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2010/04/21/2010042100633.html |archivedate=1 July 2010 }}</ref> It was only in June 2010, shortly before he was given official posts and publicly introduced to the North Korean people, that more pictures were released of Kim, taken when he was attending school in Switzerland.<ref>{{Cite news|title=The son also rises |url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2921577 |newspaper=JoongAng Daily |date=9 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108060815/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2921577 |archivedate=8 January 2012 }}<br/>{{Cite news|author=Peter Foster |title=Rare photos of Kim Jong-il's youngest son, Kim Jong-un, released |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/7810203/Rare-photos-of-Kim-Jong-ils-youngest-son-Kim-Jong-un-released.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=8 June 2010 |location=London, UK |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611052037/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/7810203/Rare-photos-of-Kim-Jong-ils-youngest-son-Kim-Jong-un-released.html |archivedate=11 June 2010 }}</ref> The first official image of him as an adult was a group photograph released on 30 September 2010, at the end of the party conference that effectively anointed him, in which he is seated in the front row, two places from his father. This was followed by newsreel footage of him attending the conference.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11441504 New images of North Korea's heir apparent Kim Jong-un] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101001030218/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11441504 |date=1 October 2010 }}, BBC News, 30 September 2010.</ref>\n\n== Succession ==\n\n=== Pre-2010 Party Conference speculation ===\nKim Jong-un's eldest half-brother, [[Kim Jong-nam]], had been the favorite to succeed, but reportedly fell out of favor after 2001, when he was caught attempting to enter Japan on a [[fake passport]] to visit [[Tokyo Disneyland]].<ref name=concert>{{cite news|title=Kim Jong Il's Teen Grandson Spotted at Concert of S. Korean Pop Star|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/2009/07/18/kim-jong-il-teen-grandson-spotted-at-concert-s-korean-pop-star.html|accessdate=20 May 2017|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Fox News|date=18 July 2009}}</ref> Kim Jong-nam [[Assassination of Kim Jong-nam|was killed]] in Malaysia in 2017 by suspected North Korean agents.<ref name=\"independent\">{{cite news|title= Kim Jong-un's half-brother 'assassinated with poisoned needles at airport' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/kim-jong-un-half-brother-killed-kim-jong-nam-malaysia-north-korea-leader-a7579246.html|work=The Independent|date=14 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nKim Jong-il's former personal chef, [[Kenji Fujimoto]], revealed details regarding Kim Jong-un, with whom he had a good relationship,<ref>Lynn, Hyung Gu. (2007). ''Bipolar orders: the two Koreas since 1989.'' Zed Books. p. 122. {{ISBN|978-1-84277-743-5}}.</ref> stating that he was favored to be his father's successor. Fujimoto also said that Jong-un was favored by his father over his elder brother, Kim Jong-chul, reasoning that Jong-chul is too feminine in character, while Jong-un is \"exactly like his father\".<ref name=nyt>Sang-hun, Choe; Fackler, Martin. [https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/15/world/asia/15kim.html North Korea's Heir Apparent Remains a Mystery] {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6MEoQ4wBe?url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/15/world/asia/15kim.html?_r=0 |date=29 December 2013 }}. ''[[The New York Times]]''. 14 June 2009</ref> Furthermore, Fujimoto stated that \"if power is to be handed over then Jong-un is the best for it. He has superb physical gifts, is a big drinker and never admits defeat.\" Also, according to Fujimoto, Jong-un smokes [[Yves Saint Laurent (brand)|Yves Saint Laurent]] cigarettes, loves [[Johnnie Walker]] whisky and has a [[Mercedes-Benz 600]] luxury sedan.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2010/12/20/2010122001136.html|title=Kim Jong-un 'Loves Nukes, Computer Games and Johnny Walker'|date=20 December 2010|work=The Chosun Ilbo|access-date=30 November 2019|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160417065308/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2010/12/20/2010122001136.html|archive-date=17 April 2016}}</ref> When Jong-un was 18, Fujimoto described an episode where Jong-un once questioned his lavish lifestyle and asked, \"we are here, playing basketball, riding horses, riding jet skis, having fun together. But what of the lives of the average people?\"<ref name=nyt /> On 15 January 2009, the South Korean news agency [[Yonhap]] reported that Kim Jong-il had appointed Kim Jong-un to be his successor.<ref name=concert /><ref>[http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2009/01/22/62/0401000000AEN20090121007400325F.HTML North Korea Newsletter No. 38] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722135931/http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/northkorea/2009/01/22/62/0401000000AEN20090121007400325F.HTML |date=22 July 2011 }}. Yonhap. 22 January 2009.</ref>\n\nOn 8 March 2009, [[BBC News]] reported that Kim Jong-un was on the ballot for [[2009 North Korean parliamentary election|2009 elections]] to the [[Supreme People's Assembly]], the [[rubber stamp (politics)|rubber stamp parliament]] of North Korea.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7930775.stm \"N Korea holds parliamentary poll\"]. [[BBC News]]. Retrieved 8 March 2009.</ref> Subsequent reports indicated that his name did not appear on the list of lawmakers,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=20601086&sid=aFAm9ndQmJpI&refer=latin_america |title=Kim Jong Il's Son, Possible Successor, Isn't Named as Lawmaker |publisher=Bloomberg |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629121818/http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=aFAm9ndQmJpI&refer=latin_america |archive-date=29 June 2011 |url-status=dead |author=Heejin Koo |date=9 March 2009 |df= }}</ref> but he was later elevated to a mid-level position in the [[National Defense Commission]], which is a branch of the North Korean military.<ref name=\"Rosen2009\">{{cite web|first=James |last=Rosen |date=1 May 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504024115/http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/05/01/north-korea-kim-begins-shifting-power-military/ |archive-date= 4 May 2009 |title=In North Korea, Ailing Kim Begins Shifting Power to Military |publisher=Fox News Channel |url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/05/01/north-korea-ailing-kim-begins-shifting-power-military.html |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[File:The statues of Kim Il Sung and Kim Jong Il on Mansu Hill in Pyongyang (april 2012).jpg|thumb|260px|People paying homage<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/dec/17/north-korea-homage-kim-dynasty ''North Korea pays homage to the Kim dynasty, past, present (and future?).''] Justin McCurry. The Guardian. London. 17 December 2012. Accessed 18 August 2017.</ref> to the statues of [[Kim Il-sung]] and Kim Jong-il, April 2012]]\nFrom 2009, it was understood by foreign diplomatic services that Kim was to succeed his father Kim Jong-il as the head of the Korean Workers' Party and ''de facto'' leader of North Korea.<ref name=\"successor\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/8078324.stm |title=N Korea names Kim's successor named |publisher=BBC |date=2 June 2009 |accessdate=14 June 2009 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090608074810/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/8078324.stm |archivedate=8 June 2009 }}</ref> He has been named \"Y\u014fngmy\u014fng-han Tongji\" ({{Lang-ko|\uc601\uba85\ud55c \ub3d9\uc9c0|label=none}}), which loosely translates to \"Brilliant Comrade\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/06/13/north-korean-leader039s-son-039brilliant-comrade039.html|title=North Korean leader's son is 'Brilliant Comrade|work=[[The Jakarta Post]]|date=13 June 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303175033/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/06/13/north-korean-leader039s-son-039brilliant-comrade039.html|archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> His father had also asked embassy staff abroad to pledge loyalty to his son.<ref name=huff /> There have also been reports that citizens in North Korea were encouraged to sing a newly composed \"song of praise\" to Kim Jong-un, in a similar fashion to that of [[Song of General Kim Jong-il|praise songs relating to Kim Jong-il]] and [[Song of General Kim Il-sung|Kim Il-sung]].<ref name=\"Willacy2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/am/content/2009/s2632675.htm |title=North Koreans sing praises of dynastic dictatorship |work=AM |date=22 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090725031711/http://www.abc.net.au/am/content/2009/s2632675.htm |archivedate=25 July 2009 |url-status=live |first=Mark |last=Willacy |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |location=Sydney |df= }}</ref> Later, in June, Kim was reported to have visited [[China]] secretly to \"present himself\" to the Chinese leadership, who later warned against North Korea conducting another nuclear test.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6508436.ece|title=Kim Jong Il's son 'made secret visit to China'|last=Lewis|first=Leo|date=17 June 2009|work=The Times|access-date=30 November 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629113833/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/asia/article6508436.ece|archive-date=29 June 2011|last2=Reid|first2=Tim|location=UK}}</ref> The Chinese foreign ministry has strongly denied that this visit occurred.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2009/06/19/2009061900402.html|title=China Dismisses Reports of Kim Jong-un Visit|date=19 June 2009|work=The Chosun Ilbo|access-date=20 November 2019}}<br />{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/01/AR2009060103750.html|title=Son Named Heir to North Korea's Kim Studied in Switzerland, Reportedly Loves NBA|last=Harden|first=Blaine|date=3 June 2009|work=The Washington Post|access-date=1 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110204205420/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/06/01/AR2009060103750.html|archive-date=4 February 2011|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009, it was reported that Kim Jong-il had secured support for the succession plan, after a propaganda campaign.<ref name=\"Lim2009\">{{cite news|first=Chang-Won |last=Lim |date=6 September 2009 |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gvACCP7QGFdDDvwHxcbIph2Yw4pw |title={{not a typo|N|Korea}} backs Kim's succession plan: analysts |agency=Agence France-Presse |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219202429/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5gvACCP7QGFdDDvwHxcbIph2Yw4pw |archivedate=19 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> It is believed by some that Kim Jong-un was involved in the [[ROKS Cheonan sinking|''Cheonan'' sinking]]<ref name=\"Gayathri2011\">{{cite web|title=North Korean Propagandists Say Kim Jong\u2011il's Son Planned South Korea Attacks |work=International Business Times |date=24 December 2011 |url=http://www.ibtimes.com/north-korean-propagandists-say-kim-jong-ils-son-planned-south-korea-attacks-387228 |archivedate=26 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226192629/http://www.ibtimes.com/north-korean-propagandists-say-kim-jong-ils-son-planned-south-korea-attacks-387228 |url-status=live |first=Amrutha |last=Gayathri |df= }}</ref> and the [[bombardment of Yeonpyeong]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Kim Jong-un 'Masterminded Attacks on S. Korea' |work=The Chosun Ilbo |date=3 August 2011 |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/08/03/2011080300499.html |accessdate=13 January 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110912031953/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/08/03/2011080300499.html |archivedate=12 September 2011 }}</ref> to strengthen his military credentials and facilitate a successful transition of power from his father.<ref name=\"Chun2011\">{{cite web|title=Korean Peninsula: After Cheonan Warship Sinking and Yeonpyeong Incidents|last=Chun|first=Kwang Ho|year=2011|publisher=Jeju Peace Institute|url=http://jpi.or.kr/skyboard/download.sky?code=jpiworld&fid=3286&gid=5322|archive-date=26 December 2015|format=PDF|archive-url=https://webcitation.org/query?date=2015-12-26&url=http%3A%2F%2Fjpi.or.kr%2Fskyboard%2Fdownload.sky%3Fcode%3Djpiworld%26fid%3D3286%26gid%3D5322|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Vice Chairman of the Central Military Commission ===\nKim Jong-un was made a ''[[daejang]]'', the equivalent of a four-star [[General (United States)|general]] in the [[United States]],<ref name=BBCmodel>{{cite news|title=Is North Korea following the Chinese model? |publisher=BBC News |date=29 September 2010 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11432894 |accessdate=30 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100930040548/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11432894 |archivedate=30 September 2010 }}</ref> on 27 September 2010, a day ahead of a rare Workers' Party of Korea conference in Pyongyang, the first time North Korean media had mentioned him by name and despite him having no previous military experience.<ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea sets date for rare leadershipconference |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11378145 |accessdate=27 September 2010 |publisher=BBC News |date=21 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924075815/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11378145 |archivedate=24 September 2010 }}<br/>{{cite news|title=North Korean leader Kim Jong-il's son 'made a general' |publisher=BBC News |date=28 September 2010 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11417016 |accessdate=28 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928045127/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11417016 |archivedate=28 September 2010 }}<br/>{{cite news|title=North Korea's Kim paves way for family succession |publisher=BBC News |date=28 September 2010 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11426284 |accessdate=28 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929045116/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11426284 |archivedate=29 September 2010 }}</ref> Despite the promotion, no further details, including verifiable portraits of Kim, were released.<ref>{{cite web|author=Matt Negrin |url=http://www.politico.com/politico44/perm/0910/little_kim_rises_47f34787-5587-48fd-b2a4-c11fa6a56599.html |title=N. Korean leader promotes his son |publisher=Politico.com |date=28 September 2010 |accessdate=28 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113062741/http://www.politico.com/politico44/perm/0910/little_kim_rises_47f34787-5587-48fd-b2a4-c11fa6a56599.html |archivedate=13 January 2012 }}</ref> On 28 September 2010, he was named vice chairman of the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Military Commission]] and appointed to the [[Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Committee of the Workers' Party]], in an apparent nod to become the successor to Kim Jong-il.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11431415 |publisher=BBC News |title=North Korea leader's son given key party posts |date=28 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100929043702/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-pacific-11431415 |archivedate=29 September 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 October 2010, Kim Jong-un was alongside his father when he attended the ruling Workers' Party's 65th-anniversary celebration. This was seen as confirming his position as the next leader of the Workers' Party. Unprecedented international press access was granted to the event, further indicating the importance of Kim Jong-un's presence.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/10/world/asia/10korea.html|work=The New York Times|title=Kim Jong-il's Heir Attends Parade|date=9 October 2010|author=Mark McDonald}}</ref> In January 2011, the regime reportedly began purging around 200 prot\u00e9g\u00e9s of both Jong-un's uncle-in-law [[Jang Song-thaek]] and [[O Kuk-ryol]], the vice chairman of the National Defence Commission, by either detention or execution to further prevent either man from rivaling Jong-un.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/01/10/2011011000554.html |title=N.Korea 'Purging Proteges of the Old Guard' |work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]] |date=10 January 2011 |accessdate=19 December 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120110031142/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2011/01/10/2011011000554.html |archivedate=10 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\n== Leader of North Korea ==\n[[File:Festival Arirang 0001 06.JPG|thumb|Portraits of Kim Jong-un's father and grandfather ([[Arirang Festival]] mass games in Pyongyang)]]\n\n=== Assuming official titles ===\nOn 17 December 2011, Kim Jong-il died. Despite the elder Kim's plans, it was not immediately clear after his death whether Jong-un would in fact take full power, and what his exact role in a new government would be.<ref name=\"Branigan2011\">{{cite news|title=Kim Jong-il, North Korean leader, dies |first=Tania |last=Branigan |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/19/kim-jong-il-north-korean-leader-dies |work=The Guardian |date=19 December 2011 |archive-date=14 August 2015 |location=London, UK |issn=0261-3077 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814114449/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/19/kim-jong-il-north-korean-leader-dies |url-status=live |df= }}</ref> Some analysts had predicted that when Kim Jong-il died, Jang Song-thaek would act as [[regent]], as Jong-un was too inexperienced to immediately lead the country.<ref name=\"Wallace2013\">{{cite news|title=Kim Jong\u2011il's heir Kim Jong\u2011un made general |first1=Rick |last1=Wallace |first2=Michael |last2=Sainsbury |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/kim-jong-ils-heir-kim-jong-un-made-general/story-e6frg6so-1225931178505 |newspaper=The Australian |issn=1038-8761 |date=29 September 2010 |archive-date=25 December 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131225061032/http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/kim-jong-ils-heir-kim-jong-un-made-general/story-e6frg6so-1225931178505 |df= }}</ref><ref name=\"Shim2011\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-korea-north-power-idUSTRE7BO02I20111225 |title=North Korean power\u2011behind\u2011throne emerges as neighbors meet |agency=Reuters |date=25 December 2011 |archive-date= 7 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107225817/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-korea-north-power-idUSTRE7BO02I20111225 |url-status=live |first1=Sung-won |last1=Shim |first2=Kiyoshi |last2=Takenaka |first3=Chris |last3=Buckley |editor-first=Yoko |editor-last=Nishikawa |df= |newspaper=Reuters }}</ref>\n\nFollowing his father's death, Kim Jong-un was hailed as the \"great successor to the revolutionary cause of [[Juche]]\",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052970204791104577107350219610874.html|title=Kim Jong Il Has Died|author=Alastair Gale|date=18 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal Asia]]|accessdate=19 December 2011}}</ref> \"outstanding leader of the party, army and people\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2011/201112/news19/20111219-04ee.html |title=Notice to All Party Members, Servicepersons and People |publisher=Korean Central News Agency |date=19 December 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150311064222/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2011/201112/news19/20111219-04ee.html |archive-date=11 March 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and \"respected comrade who is identical to Supreme Commander Kim Jong-il\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2011/201112/news19/20111219-12ee.html |title=We Are under Respected Kim Jong Un |publisher=Korean Central News Agency |date=19 December 2011 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141012023229/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2011/201112/news19/20111219-12ee.html |archivedate=12 October 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and was made chairman of the Kim Jong-il funeral committee. The [[Korean Central News Agency]] described Kim Jong-un as \"a great person born of heaven\", a propaganda term only his father and grandfather had enjoyed.<ref>Associated Press (19 December 2011). [https://web.archive.org/web/20120113085114/http://www.chron.com/news/article/NKorea-grieves-Kim-Jong-Il-state-media-hails-son-2411026.php NKorea grieves Kim Jong Il, state media hails son], ''Houston Chronicle''. Retrieved 1 January 2012.</ref> And the ruling Workers' Party said in an editorial, \"We vow with bleeding tears to call Kim Jong-un our supreme commander, our leader.\"<ref name=\"Lee2011\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-12-24/north-korea-s-media-begins-referring-to-kim-jong-un-as-supreme-commander- |title=N. Korea Media Begins Calling Kim Jong Un Supreme Commander |publisher=Bloomberg |date=24 December 2011 |last=Lee |first=Jiyeun |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160410123745/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2011-12-24/north-korea-s-media-begins-referring-to-kim-jong-un-as-supreme-commander- |archivedate=10 April 2016 }}</ref>\n\nHe was publicly declared [[Supreme Commander of the Korean People's Army]] on 24 December 2011,<ref name=\"bbc24\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-16325390 |title=North Korea: Kim Jong-un hailed 'supreme commander' |date=24 December 2011 |accessdate=24 December 2011 |publisher=BBC News |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107065350/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-16325390 |archivedate=7 January 2014 }}</ref> and formally appointed to the position on 30 December 2011 when the Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party \"courteously proclaimed that the dear respected Kim Jong Un, vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission of the WPK, assumed the supreme commandership of the Korean People's Army\".<ref name=\"AFP2011\">{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jJYCeXinUm40ybUlJzb4_aOAiSAQ?docId=CNG.abd2d9a288a1831892829dfc484f077e.6a1|title=N.Korea declares Kim Jong-Un commander of military|date=30 December 2011|accessdate=30 December 2011|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140224223520/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5jJYCeXinUm40ybUlJzb4_aOAiSAQ?docId=CNG.abd2d9a288a1831892829dfc484f077e.6a1|archive-date=24 February 2014|agency=Agence France-Presse|df=}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Revolutionary Martyrs Cemetery 32.JPG|thumb|North Korean soldiers saluting at the [[Revolutionary Martyrs' Cemetery]] in Pyongyang, 2012]]\nOn 26 December 2011, the leading North Korean newspaper ''[[Rodong Sinmun]]'' reported that Kim Jong-un had been acting as chairman of the Central Military Commission,<ref name=autogenerated1>[http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/topics/2011/12/26/81/4603000000AEN20111226003700315F.HTML N. Korean newspaper refers to successor son as head of key party organ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526021309/http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/topics/2011/12/26/81/4603000000AEN20111226003700315F.HTML |date=26 May 2012 }} Yonhap News Agency, 26 December 2011.</ref> and Supreme Leader of the country, following his father's demise.<ref>{{cite news|author=Scott McDonald |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/story/2011-12-30/north-korea-leadership/52280412/1 |title=North Korea vows no softening toward South |date=30 December 2011 |work=USA Today |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230180135/http://www.usatoday.com/news/world/story/2011-12-30/north-korea-leadership/52280412/1 |archivedate=30 December 2011 }}</ref>\n\nOn 9 January 2012, a large rally was held by the Korean People's Army in front of the [[Kumsusan Palace of the Sun]] to honor Kim Jong-un and to demonstrate loyalty.<ref>{{cite web|title=Military Rallies in Keumsusan Square |author=So Yeol Kim |accessdate=10 January 2012 |url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01700&num=8664 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112211957/http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01700&num=8664 |archivedate=12 January 2012 |date=10 January 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March 2012, Kim was elected to the Fourth Conference of the Workers' Party of Korea. On 11 April, that conference wrote the post of general secretary out of the party charter and instead designated Kim Jong-il as the party's \"Eternal General Secretary\". The conference then elected Kim Jong-un as leader of the party under the newly created title of First Secretary. Kim Jong-un also took his father's post as Chairman of the Central Military Commission, as well as his father's old seat on the [[Presidium of the Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Politburo Presidium]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Kim Takes More Top Posts |author=Chris Green |accessdate=12 April 2012 |url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01700&num=9100 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415020037/http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01700&num=9100 |archivedate=15 April 2012 |date=12 April 2012 }}</ref> In a speech made prior to the Conference, Kim Jong-un declared that \"Imbuing the whole society with Kimilsungism-Kimjongilism is the highest programme of our Party\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Kim Jong-un|title=Let Us Brilliantly Accomplish the Revolutionary Cause of Juche, Holding Kim Jong Il in High Esteem as the Eternal General Secretary of Our Party: Talk to Senior Officials of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of Korea|url=http://www.korean-books.com.kp/en/packages/xnps/download.pg.php?122#.pdf|accessdate=9 May 2018|date=6 April 2012|publisher=Foreign Languages Publishing House|location=Pyongyang|oclc=988748608|page=6}}</ref> On 13 April 2012, the 5th Session of the 12th Supreme People's Assembly appointed Kim Jong-un [[Chairman of the National Defence Commission]].<ref>{{Cite web | title = Part II: The Kim Family Reigns: Preserving the Monarchy and Strengthening the Party-State | last = Mansourov | first = Alexandre  | work = 38 North | date = 19 December 2012 | accessdate = 9 May 2018 | url = https://www.38north.org/2012/12/amansourov121912/ }}</ref>\n\nOn 15 April 2012, during a military parade to commemorate Kim Il-sung's centenary, Kim Jong-un made his first public speech, ''[[Let Us March Forward Dynamically Towards Final Victory, Holding Higher the Banner of Songun]]''.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=BBC |accessdate=14 April 2012 |date=14 April 2012 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-17718011 |title=N Korea's Kim Jong-un speaks publicly for first time |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415181357/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-17718011 |archivedate=15 April 2012 }}</ref> That speech became the basis of a hymn dedicated to him, \"[[Onwards Toward the Final Victory]]\".<ref name=\"Branigan2012\">{{cite news|first=Tania |last=Branigan |title=North Korea's Kim Jong-un gets new official theme song |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jul/06/north-korea-kim-jong-un-song |archive-date= 2 August 2015 |work=The Guardian |date=6 July 2012 |issn=0261-3077 |location=London, UK |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150802102716/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/jul/06/north-korea-kim-jong-un-song |url-status=live |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012,<ref name=\"Green2012\" /> Kim Jong-un was promoted to [[Wonsu (North Korea)|wonsu]] (translated as [[marshal]]), the highest active rank in the military. The decision was jointly issued on by the Central Committee and the Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea, the National Defence Commission, and the [[Presidium]] of the Supreme People's Assembly, the [[Korean Central News Agency]] subsequently announced.<ref name=\"marshall\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18881524|title=North Korea's Kim Jong-un named 'marshal'|date=18 July 2012|accessdate=18 July 2012|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718074405/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18881524|archivedate=18 July 2012|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> The only higher rank is [[Dae Wonsu]] (roughly translated as [[Grand Marshal]] or [[Generalissimo]]) which was held by Kim's grandfather, Kim Il-sung, and which was awarded posthumously to his father, Kim Jong-il, in February 2012.<ref name=marshall /><ref name=\"Green2012\">{{cite news|last=Green |first=Chris |title=Kim Jong Eun Promoted to Marshal |url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01700&num=9533 |accessdate=18 July 2012 |work=Daily NK |date=18 July 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004213840/http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk01700&num=9533 |archivedate=4 October 2013 }}</ref> The promotion confirmed Kim's role as top leader of the North Korean military and came days after the replacement of Chief of General Staff [[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]] by [[Hyon Yong-chol]].<ref name=marshall />\n\n{{external image|image1=[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-20461822 Satellite imagery show the message \"Long Live General Kim Jong-un, the Shining Sun!\" in Korean on a hillside.]}}\nIn November 2012, satellite photos revealed a half-kilometer-long ({{convert|0.5|km|ft|disp=out}}) propaganda message carved into a hillside in [[Ryanggang Province]], reading, \"Long Live General Kim Jong-un, the Shining Sun!\"<ref name=\"NationalPost2012\">{{cite news |title=Half-kilometre long Kim Jong-un propaganda message visible from space |work=National Post |issn=1486-8008 |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/half-kilometre-long-kim-jong-un-propaganda-message-visible-from-space |date=23 November 2012 |df= |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20170419204737/http://news.nationalpost.com/news/half-kilometre-long-kim-jong-un-propaganda-message-visible-from-space |archivedate=19 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kim Jong Il Books (33012753981).jpg|thumb|upright|A selection of [[Kim Jong-un's works]]]]\nOn 30 November 2012, Kim met with [[Li Jianguo]], who \"briefed Kim on the [[18th National Congress of the Communist Party of China|18th National Congress]] of the [[Communist Party of China]]\", according to the state's official news agency, the [[Korean Central News Agency]].<ref name=\"letter Dec 3\">{{cite web|title=Kim Jong-un Gets Letter from China's New Leader |url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/12/03/2012120301309.html |publisher=Chosun.com |accessdate=6 December 2012 |date=3 December 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121206041056/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/12/03/2012120301309.html |archivedate=6 December 2012 }}</ref> A letter from [[Xi Jinping]], [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China]], was hand-delivered during the discussion.<ref name=\"letter Dec 3\" />\n\nOn 9 March 2014, Kim Jong-un was elected to a seat in the Supreme People's Assembly, the country's [[Unicameralism|unicameral]] [[legislature]]. He ran unopposed, but voters had the choice of voting yes or no. There was a record turnout of voters and, according to government officials, all voted \"yes\" in his home district of [[Mount Paekdu]].<ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea's Kim Jong-un elected to assembly without single vote against |agency=Associated Press |work=The Guardian |date=10 March 2014 |accessdate=4 August 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/mar/10/north-koreas-kim-jong-un-elected-assembly-vote-against |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826080442/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/mar/10/north-koreas-kim-jong-un-elected-assembly-vote-against |archivedate=26 August 2016 }}</ref> The Supreme People's Assembly subsequently elected him first chairman of the [[National Defence Commission]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Leader Tightens Hold on Power in North Korea |last=Sang-Hun |first=Choe |work=The New York Times |date=9 April 2014 |accessdate=4 August 2016 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/10/world/asia/kim-further-consolidates-power-as-north-koreas-leader.html |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920214043/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/04/10/world/asia/kim-further-consolidates-power-as-north-koreas-leader.html |archivedate=20 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\nKim became the Chairman of the Workers' Party of Korea on a party congress held on May 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-congress-kim-idUSKCN0Y015Y|title=North Korea leader Kim becomes chairman of ruling Workers' Party: NHK|date=9 May 2016|work=Reuters|access-date=6 January 2020|language=en}}</ref> On 29 June 2016, Kim became the [[Chairman of the State Affairs Commission]], after the [[State Affairs Commission]] replaced the National Defence Commission.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/dprk/ndc.htm|title=State Affairs Commission [ex National Defense Commission] - North Korea|website=www.globalsecurity.org|access-date=6 January 2020}}</ref> The office of the Supreme Commander of the armed forces was linked to this office because of the [[North Korean constitution|2019 constitutional amendment]].<ref name=\"CIC\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naenara.com.kp/en/politics/?rule+9|title=Socialist Constitution - Chairman of the State Affairs Commission - Article 102|website=[[Naenara]]|publisher=Government of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea}}</ref>\n\n=== Role in government ===\nOfficially, Kim Jong-un is part of a [[triumvirate]] heading the executive branch of the North Korean government along with Premier [[Kim Jae-ryong]] and parliament president [[Choe Ryong-hae]]. Each nominally holds powers equivalent to a third of a president's powers in most presidential systems. Kim Jong-un commands the armed forces, Kim Jae-ryong heads the government and handles domestic affairs, and Choe Ryong-hae handles foreign relations.{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} Indeed, a constitutional amendment enacted by his father explicitly named the NDC (first) chairman as \"the supreme leader of the Democratic People's Republic of North Korea\".<ref name=\"leon_DPRK\">{{cite web|title=DPRK has quietly amended its Constitution |last=Petrov |first=Leonid |work=Leonid Petrov's KOREA VISION |date=12 October 2009 |accessdate=12 September 2015 |url=https://leonidpetrov.wordpress.com/2009/10/12/dprk-has-quietly-amended-its-constitution/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151016015037/https://leonidpetrov.wordpress.com/2009/10/12/dprk-has-quietly-amended-its-constitution/ |archivedate=16 October 2015 }}<br/>{{cite book|series=Amended and supplemented on 1 April, Juche 102 (2013), at the Seventh Session of the Twelfth Supreme People's Assembly |title=Socialist Constitution of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea |chapter-url=http://www.naenara.com.kp/en/book/download.php?4+4047 |year=2014 |chapter-format=PDF |publisher=Foreign Languages Publishing House |location=Pyongyang |isbn=978-9946-0-1099-1 |page=22 |chapter=Article 100 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608030306/http://www.naenara.com.kp/en/book/download.php?4+4047 |archivedate=8 June 2016 }}</ref> However, analysts are divided about how much actual power Kim has.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/27/kim-jong-un-north-korea-supreme-leader-or-state-puppet|title=Kim Jong-un: North Korea's supreme leader or state puppet?|publisher=The Guardian|date=27 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2017/03/the-myth-of-kim-jong-uns-absolute-power/|title=The myth of Kim Jong Un's absolute power|first=Peter|last=Ward|publisher=NK News|date=20 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nKim Jong-un frequently performs symbolic acts that associate him with the [[North Korean cult of personality|personality cult]] of his father and grandfather.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.net.au/news/2019-10-16/north-korean-kim-jong-un-rides-horse-on-sacred-mountain/11608492|title=Kim Jong-un rides white horse on sacred North Korean mountain in fresh propaganda photos|publisher=ABC|date=16 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://qz.com/944973/photo-of-north-koreas-kim-jong-uns-shows-his-transformation-into-his-father-is-nearly-complete/|title=Kim Jong Un's transformation into his father is nearly complete|first=Johnny|last=Simon|publisher=Quartz|date=30 March 2017}}</ref> Like them, Kim Jong-un regularly tours the country, giving \"[[on-the-spot guidance]]\" at various sites.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/blogs-magazine-monitor-27116092|title=Why is Kim Jong-un always surrounded by people taking notes?|first=Kathryn|last=Westcott|publisher=BBC|date=25 April 2014}}</ref> North Korean state media often refers to him as Marshal Kim Jong-un, \"the Marshal\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tass.ru/en/world/764640|title=North Korean leader orders to turn armed forces into elite revolutionary army|date=2 December 2014|accessdate=28 December 2014|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150704075153/http://tass.ru/en/world/764640|archive-date=4 July 2015|agency=Information Telegraph Agency of Russia|df=}}<br />{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/10/kim-jong-un-north-korea-health-rumours|title=Kim Jong-un's latest no-show fuels further health rumours|date=10 October 2014|work=The Guardian|accessdate=28 December 2014|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141213222457/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/10/kim-jong-un-north-korea-health-rumours|archivedate=13 December 2014|location=London, UK|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> or \"Dear Respected.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/what-you-are-not-allowed-to-call-kim-jong-un-when-visiting-north-korea-a7019761.html|title=What you are not allowed to call Kim Jong-un when visiting North Korea|author1=Nicholas Wadhams|date=9 May 2016|newspaper=[[The Independent]]}}</ref>\n\n===New leadership style===\nIn July 2012, Kim Jong-un showed a change in cultural policy from his father by attending a [[Moranbong Band]] concert. The concert contained several elements of pop culture from [[Western culture|the West]], particularly the United States. Kim used this event to debut his wife to the public, an unprecedented move in North Korea.<ref>Lankov, Andrei (10 April 2013). The Real North Korea: Life and Politics in the Failed Stalinist Utopia (pp. 139\u2013141). Oxford University Press. Kindle Edition.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Kim Jong-il's personal chef Kenji Fujimoto visited North Korea and said, \"Stores in Pyongyang were brimming with products and people in the streets looked cheerful. North Korea has changed a lot since Kim Jong-un assumed power. All of this is because of leader Kim Jong-un.\"<ref name=\"McCurry2012\">{{cite web|first=Justin |last=McCurry |date=10 August 2012 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/aug/10/kim-jong-il-japan-chef |title=Kim Jong\u2011il's personal Japanese chef returns to land he fled |work=The Guardian |archivedate= 2 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702173449/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/aug/10/kim-jong-il-japan-chef |url-status=live |location=London, UK |issn=0261-3077 |df= }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Kim re-established his grandfather's style when he made his first New Year's address, a break from the approach of his father. Kim Jong-il never made televised addresses during his 17 years in power.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2013/01/01/world/asia/north-korea-kim-speech/index.html In first New Year speech, North Korea's Kim Jong Un calls for economic revamp] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131205121010/http://www.cnn.com/2013/01/01/world/asia/north-korea-kim-speech/index.html |date=5 December 2013 }}, CNN, 2 January 2013. Retrieved 23 April 2013.</ref> In lieu of delivering a speech, Kim Jong-il contributed to and approved a New Year's Day editorial, jointly published by ''Rodong Sinmun'' (the daily newspaper of the Korean Workers' Party), ''[[Joson Inmingun]]'' (the newspaper of the Korean People's Army), and ''[[Chongnyon Jonwi]]'' (the newspaper of the [[Kimilsungist-Kimjongilist Youth League]]).<ref>[http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/ \"KJU Delivers New Year's Day Address\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100608051801/http://nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com/ |date=8 June 2010 }}. Nkleadershipwatch.wordpress.com. Retrieved 23 April 2013.</ref> \n[[File:0921 - Nordkorea 2015 - Pj\u00f6ngjang - Public Viewing am Bahnhofsplatz (22584958809).jpg|thumb|230px|People in Pyongyang watch Kim Jong-un on [[Korean Central Television|North Korean TV]], 2015]]\n\nIn May 2014, following the collapse of an apartment building in Pyongyang, Kim Jong-un was said to be very upset at the loss of life that resulted. A statement issued by the country's official news agency the Korean Central News Agency used the rare expression \"profound consolation and apology\". An unnamed government official was quoted by the [[BBC]] as saying Kim Jong-un had \"sat up all night, feeling painful\".<ref>{{cite web|title=North Korea offers rare apology after apartment building collapses |last=Chasmar |first=Jessica |work=The Washingtion Times |date=18 May 2014 |accessdate=2 January 2015 |url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/may/18/north-korea-offers-rare-apology-after-apartment-bu/ |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150108201410/http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2014/may/18/north-korea-offers-rare-apology-after-apartment-bu/ |archivedate=8 January 2015 }}</ref> While the height of the building and the number of casualties was not released, media reports described it is a 23-story building and indicated that more than a hundred people may have died in the collapse.<ref>{{cite web|title=North Korea: Apology over Pyongyang building collapse |publisher=BBC News |date=18 May 2014 |accessdate=4 August 2016 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-27459186 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917041928/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-27459186 |archivedate=17 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\n=== Economic policies ===\nA set of comprehensive economic measures, the \"Socialist Corporate Responsible Management System\", were introduced in 2013.<ref name=\"IFES1\" /> The measures increase the autonomy of enterprises by granting them \"certain rights to engage in business activities autonomously and elevate the will to labor through appropriately implementing the socialist distribution system\". Another priority of economic policies that year was agriculture, where the ''pojon'' (vegetable garden) responsibility system was implemented. The system reportedly achieved a major increase in output in some collective farms.<ref name=\"IFES1\">{{cite web |url=http://ifes.kyungnam.ac.kr/eng/FRM/FRM_0101V.aspx?code=FRM150224_0001 |title=\"Socialist Enterprise Management System\" under Full Implementation |publisher=Institute for Far Eastern Studies |date=24 February 2015 |accessdate=28 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702134340/http://ifes.kyungnam.ac.kr/eng/FRM/FRM_0101V.aspx?code=FRM150224_0001 |archivedate=2 July 2015 }}</ref>\nNorth Korean media were describing the economy as a \"flexible collectivist system\" where enterprises were applying \"active and evolutionary actions\" to achieve economic development.<ref name=\"IFES2\" /> These reports reflect Kim's general economic policy of reforming management, increasing the autonomy and incentives for economic actors. This set of reforms known as the \"May 30th measures\" reaffirms both socialist ownership and \"objective economic laws in guidance and management\" to improve living standards. Other objectives of the measures are to increase the availability of domestically manufactured goods on markets, introduction of defence innovations into the civilian sector and boost international trade.<ref name=\"IFES2\">{{cite web |url=http://ifes.kyungnam.ac.kr/eng/FRM/FRM_0101V.aspx?code=FRM150115_0001 |title=Kim Jong Un Stresses the Principles of Market Economy through 'May 30th Measures' |publisher=Institute for Far Eastern Studies |date=15 January 2015 |accessdate=28 April 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702103857/http://ifes.kyungnam.ac.kr/eng/FRM/FRM_0101V.aspx?code=FRM150115_0001 |archivedate=2 July 2015 }}</ref>\n\nThere has been a construction boom in Pyongyang, bringing colour and creative architectural styles to the city. While in the past there was a concentration on building monuments, Kim Jong-un's government has constructed amusement parks, aquatic parks, skating rinks, a dolphinarium and a ski resort.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/asia/la-fg-north-korea-architecture-20160520-snap-story.html|title=North Korea is building something other than nukes: architecture with some zing|last=Makinen|first=Julie|date=20 May 2016|newspaper=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.atimes.com/article/going-native-in-the-hermit-kingdom/|title=Going native in the Hermit Kingdom|first=Andrew|last=Salmon|publisher=Asia Times|date=4 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Purges and executions ===\n{{See|List of officials purged and executed by Kim Jong-un}}\nAs with all reporting on North Korea, reports of purges and executions are difficult to verify.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Trianni |first1=Francesca |title=Did Kim Jong Un Really Execute His Uncle's Extended Family? |url=http://time.com/2087/did-kim-jong-un-really-execute-his-uncles-extended-family/ |accessdate=28 May 2016 |work=Time |date=27 January 2014 |location=1:04\u20131:10 in embedded video |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309222443/http://time.com/2087/did-kim-jong-un-really-execute-his-uncles-extended-family/ |archivedate=9 March 2016 }}</ref> In May 2016, analysts were surprised to find that General [[Ri Yong-gil]], reported by South Korea to have been executed earlier in the year, was, in fact, alive and well.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ri Yong-gil, North Korean general thought to be executed, is actually alive|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/may/10/ri-yong-gil-north-korean-general-thought-be-execut/?page=all|accessdate=28 May 2016|work=The Washingtion Times|date=10 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2013, Kim Jong-un's uncle Jang Song-thaek was arrested and executed for treachery.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21591581-kim-jong-un-has-managed-improbable-feat-making-north-korea-even-scarier-crying-uncle Crying uncle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212222959/http://www.economist.com/news/asia/21591581-kim-jong-un-has-managed-improbable-feat-making-north-korea-even-scarier-crying-uncle |date=12 December 2013 }} ''[[The Economist]]'', 14 December 2013.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nknews.org/2016/08/kim-jong-uns-executed-uncle-jang-song-thaek-reappears-on-n-korean-media/|title=Kim Jong Un's executed uncle Jang Song Thaek reappears on N.Korean media|last=Ahn|first=JH|date=10 August 2016|accessdate=23 January 2018|publisher=NKNews}}</ref> Jang is believed to have been executed by firing squad. [[Yonhap]] has stated that, according to multiple unnamed sources, Kim Jong-un has also put to death members of Jang's family, to completely destroy all traces of Jang's existence through \"extensive executions\" of his family, including the children and grandchildren of all close relatives. Those reportedly killed in Kim's purge include Jang's sister Jang Kye-sun, her husband and ambassador to Cuba, Jon Yong-jin, and Jang's nephew and ambassador to Malaysia, [[Jang Yong-chol]]. The nephew's two sons were also said to have been killed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com//news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20140127000056&cid=1101 |title=Jang Sung-taek's remaining family executed by Kim Jong-un |work=[[Want China Times]] |date=27 January 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705171755/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx/?id=20140127000056&cid=1101 |archivedate= 5 July 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}<br/>{{cite news|title=N Korea executes relatives of Kim Jong-Un's dead uncle: reports |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-01-27/north-korea-executes-family-of-uncle-of-kim-jong-un-reports-say/5221194 |accessdate=28 May 2016 |publisher=ABC News |date=27 January 2014 |language=en-AU |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160518023244/http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-01-27/north-korea-executes-family-of-uncle-of-kim-jong-un-reports-say/5221194 |archivedate=18 May 2016 }}</ref> At the time of Jang's removal, it was announced that \"the discovery and purge of the Jang group ... made our party and revolutionary ranks purer ...\"<ref>[http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/830936.shtml Kim's uncle stripped of all posts, expelled from WPK] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212112426/http://www.globaltimes.cn/content/830936.shtml |date=12 December 2013 }} ''[[Xinhua News Agency]]''</ref> and after his execution on 12 December 2013 state media warned that the army \"will never pardon all those who disobey the order of the Supreme Commander\".<ref>[http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/national/2013/12/13/12/0301000000AEN20131213002400315F.html N. Korea executes leader's uncle for 'treason': KCNA] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131222043735/http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/national/2013/12/13/12/0301000000AEN20131213002400315F.html |date=22 December 2013 }} ''[[Yonhap]]'' 13 December 2013.</ref>\n\nO Sang-hon ({{korean|\uc624\uc0c1\ud5cc|rr= O Sangheon|mr=O Sangh\u014fn|context=north}}) was a deputy security minister in the [[Ministry of People's Security]] in the government of North Korea who was reportedly killed in a political purge in 2014. According to the South Korean newspaper ''[[The Chosun Ilbo]]'', O was executed by [[flamethrower]] for his role in supporting Kim Jong-un's uncle Jang Song-taek.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10750082/North-Korean-official-executed-by-flame-thrower.html |title=North Korean official 'executed by flame-thrower' |author=Julian Ryall |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=7 April 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160426010236/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/northkorea/10750082/North-Korean-official-executed-by-flame-thrower.html |archivedate=26 April 2016 }}<br/>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2014/04/07/2014040700892.html |title=N.Korea Shuts Down Jang Song-taek's Department |work=Chosun Ilbo |date=7 April 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150507031034/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2014/04/07/2014040700892.html |archivedate=7 May 2015 }}</ref>\n\n=== Human rights violations ===\n{{See also|Human rights in North Korea}}\nThe 2013 report on the situation of human rights in North Korea<ref>{{cite web|title=Report of the Special Rapporteur on the situation of human rights in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, Marzuki Darusman |work=United Nations Human Rights Council |date=1 February 2013 |url=http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/Report%20of%20the%20Special%20Rapporteur%20on%20the%20situation%20of%20human%20rights%20in%20the%20Democratic%20People%E2%80%99s%20Republic%20of%20Korea%20A-HRC-22-57.pdf |accessdate=25 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004215248/http://reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/Report%20of%20the%20Special%20Rapporteur%20on%20the%20situation%20of%20human%20rights%20in%20the%20Democratic%20People%E2%80%99s%20Republic%20of%20Korea%20A-HRC-22-57.pdf |archivedate=4 October 2013 }}</ref> by [[United Nations Special Rapporteur]] [[Marzuki Darusman]] proposed a United Nations commission of inquiry<ref>{{cite web|title=North Korea human rights probe urged by UN |work=The Christian Science Monitor |date=5 February 2013 |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Latest-News-Wires/2013/0205/North-Korea-human-rights-probe-urged-by-UN |accessdate=25 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130225074501/http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Latest-News-Wires/2013/0205/North-Korea-human-rights-probe-urged-by-UN |archivedate=25 February 2013 }}</ref> to document the accountability of Kim Jong-un and other individuals in the North Korean government for alleged [[crimes against humanity]].<ref>{{cite news|title=U.N.'s Pillay says may be crimes against humanity in North Korea |agency=Reuters |date=14 January 2013 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/14/us-korea-north-rights-idUSBRE90D0DB20130114 |accessdate=25 February 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210235223/http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/14/us-korea-north-rights-idUSBRE90D0DB20130114 |archivedate=10 February 2013 }}</ref> The [[Report of the Commission of Inquiry on Human Rights in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea|report of the commission of inquiry]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Report of the Commission of Inquiry on Human Rights in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea |work=United Nations Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights |url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/CoIDPRK/Pages/ReportoftheCommissionofInquiryDPRK.aspx |author1=Michael Kirby |author2=Marzuki Darusman |author3=Sonja Biserko |date=17 February 2014 |accessdate=18 February 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140217224637/http://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/CoIDPRK/Pages/ReportoftheCommissionofInquiryDPRK.aspx |archivedate=17 February 2014 }}</ref> was published in February 2014 and recommends making him accountable for crimes against humanity at the [[International Criminal Court]].<ref>{{cite news|title=U.N. Panel Says North Korean Leader Could Face Trial |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/18/world/asia/un-panel-says-north-korean-leader-could-face-trial.html |author=Nick Cumming-Bruce |date=17 February 2014 |accessdate=18 February 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140218065002/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/18/world/asia/un-panel-says-north-korean-leader-could-face-trial.html |archivedate=18 February 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2016, the [[United States Department of the Treasury]] imposed personal sanctions on Kim. Although his involvement in human rights abuses was cited as the reason,<ref>{{cite news|title=Kim Jong-un placed on sanctions blacklist for the first time by US |agency=Agence France-Presse |work=The Guardian |date=6 July 2016 |accessdate=4 August 2016 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/06/north-korea-kim-jong-sanctions-blacklist |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812121754/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/06/north-korea-kim-jong-sanctions-blacklist |archivedate=12 August 2016 }}</ref> officials said the sanctions target the country's nuclear and missile programs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Solomon |first=Jay |title=U.S. Puts First Sanctions on North Korean Leader Kim Jong Un |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=6 July 2016 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-sanctions-north-korean-leader-kim-jong-un-for-first-time-1467825770 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161220123152/http://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-sanctions-north-korean-leader-kim-jong-un-for-first-time-1467825770 |archivedate=20 December 2016 }}</ref>\n\nIn June 2017, President Trump condemned Kim Jong-un's \"brutal\" regime and described Kim as a \"madman\" after the death of American student [[Otto Warmbier]] who had been imprisoned during a visit to North Korea.<ref>{{cite news |title=North Korea calls Donald Trump a 'psychopath' following death of Otto Warmbier |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/north-korea-donald-trump-psychopath-otto-warmbier-missile-strike-kim-jong-un-a7804491.html |work=The Independent |date=23 June 2017}}</ref> However, in 2019, U.S. President Trump said that he believed Kim was not responsible for Warmbier's death.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bosman|first=Julie|date=1 March 2019|title=Trump Faces Fury After Saying He Believes North Korean Leader on Student's Death|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/01/us/trump-otto-warmbier-north-korea.html|work=[[New York Times]]|location=|access-date=13 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313191956/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/01/us/trump-otto-warmbier-north-korea.html|archive-date=13 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Alleged assassination attempts===\nRevealed in 2014, in 2012 a machine gun was discovered beneath a juniper tree in Ryugyeongwon, located near a route that Kim was going to visit.  It was assumed this was part of an assassination attempt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sinonk.com/2014/11/17/under-the-juniper-tree-the-2012-assassination-attempt-on-kim-jong-un/|title=Under the Juniper Tree: The 2012 Assassination Attempt on Kim Jong-un|date=17 November 2014|website=Sino-NK|language=en-US|access-date=6 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, the North Korean government stated that the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) of the United States and the South Korean [[National Intelligence Service (South Korea)|National Intelligence Service]] (NIS) hired a North Korean [[lumberjack]] who worked in [[Russia]] to assassinate Kim with a \"biochemical weapon\" that was both [[radioactive]] and nano-poisonous, and whose effect would have been delayed by a few months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/05/asia/north-korea-kim-assassination/index.html |title=North Korea claims US 'biochemical' plot to kill Kim Jong Un |first=James |last=Griffiths |website=CNN |accessdate=20 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170519140041/http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/05/asia/north-korea-kim-assassination/index.html |archivedate=19 May 2017 }}</ref> North Korea said that it would seek extradition of anyone involved in the assassination attempt.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/05/11/north-korea-will-seek-extradition-anyone-involved-in-alleged-kim-assassination.html |title=North Korea will seek extradition of anyone involved in alleged Kim assassination |date=11 May 2017 |accessdate=20 May 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170511111128/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/05/11/north-korea-will-seek-extradition-anyone-involved-in-alleged-kim-assassination.html |archivedate=11 May 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== Nuclear weapons development ===\n{{See also|North Korea and weapons of mass destruction}}\n[[File:Unha-9 rocket model.jpg|thumb|right|Model of a [[Unha]]-9 rocket on display at a floral exhibition in Pyongyang, 30 August 2013]]\nUnder Kim Jong-un, North Korea has continued to develop nuclear weapons, testing bombs in February 2013, January and September 2016, and September 2017, and conducting over 80 missile tests.<ref name=\"Albert\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/north-koreas-military-capabilities|title=North Korea's Military Capabilities|first=Eleanor|last=Albert|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations|date=3 January 2018}}</ref> At a plenary meeting of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party held on 31 March 2013, he announced that North Korea would adopt \"a new strategic line on carrying out economic construction and building nuclear armed forces simultaneously\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Report on Plenary Meeting of WPK Central Committee |url=http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2013/201303/news31/20130331-24ee.html |publisher=[[Korean Central News Agency]] |archive-date= 3 April 2015 |date=31 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403171327/http://www.kcna.co.jp/item/2013/201303/news31/20130331-24ee.html |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nAccording to several analysts, North Korea sees the nuclear arsenal as vital to deter an attack, and it is unlikely that North Korea would launch a nuclear war.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/politics/north-korea-nuclear-bomb-war-south-atomic-ballistic-missile-test-a7578016.html |title=Should we really be so afraid of a nuclear North Korea? |first1=Markus |last1=Bell |first2=Marco |last2=Milani |work=The Independent |date=16 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170216012421/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/politics/north-korea-nuclear-bomb-war-south-atomic-ballistic-missile-test-a7578016.html |archivedate=16 February 2017 }}<br/>{{cite news|url=http://fpif.org/north-koreas-nuclear-ticket-survival/ |title=North Korea's Nuclear Ticket to Survival |first=Edward |last=Hunt |publisher=Foreign Policy in Focus |date=31 October 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170325112931/http://fpif.org/north-koreas-nuclear-ticket-survival/ |archivedate=25 March 2017 }}</ref> According to a [[RAND Corporation]] senior researcher, Kim Jong-un believes that nuclear weapons are his guarantee of regime survival.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cfr.org/backgrounder/north-koreas-military-capabilities|title=What's the Status of North Korea's Nuclear Program?|author=|date=|website=[[Council on Foreign Relations]]|accessdate=8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 7th [[Congress of the Workers' Party of Korea]] in 2016, Kim Jong-un stated that North Korea would \"not use nuclear weapons first unless aggressive hostile forces use nuclear weapons to invade on our sovereignty\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/north-korea-party-give-kim-jong-title-38948654 |title=Kim Jong Un Says Pyongyang Won't Use Nukes First; Associated Press |publisher=ABC |date=7 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508122147/http://abcnews.go.com/International/wireStory/north-korea-party-give-kim-jong-title-38948654 |archivedate=8 May 2016 }}</ref> However, on other occasions, North Korea has threatened [[Preemptive war|\"pre-emptive\" nuclear attacks]] against a US-led attack.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/06/asia/north-korea-preemptive-nuclear-strike-threat/ |title=North Korea threatens nuclear strike over U.S.-South Korean |publisher=CNN |date=7 March 2016 |accessdate=22 May 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524135322/http://www.cnn.com/2016/03/06/asia/north-korea-preemptive-nuclear-strike-threat/ |archivedate=24 May 2016 }}<br/>{{cite news|url=http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/03/07/17220065-un-passes-sanctions-despite-north-korea-threat-of-pre-emptive-nuclear-attack |title=UN passes sanctions despite North Korea threat of 'pre-emptive nuclear attack' |publisher=NBC News |date=7 March 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309191714/http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2013/03/07/17220065-un-passes-sanctions-despite-north-korea-threat-of-pre-emptive-nuclear-attack |archivedate=9 March 2013 }}</ref> In December 2015, Kim stated that his family \"turned the DPRK into a powerful nuclear weapons state ready to detonate a self-reliant A-bomb and H-bomb to reliably defend its sovereignty and the dignity of the nation\".<ref name=\"Kim has H-bomb?\">{{cite web|title=Kim Jong-Un claims North Korea has a hydrogen bomb |url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2015/12/10/kim-jong-un-claims-north-korea-has-hydrogen-bomb/ |publisher=Fox News Channel |accessdate=11 December 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151213060907/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2015/12/10/kim-jong-un-claims-north-korea-has-hydrogen-bomb/ |archivedate=13 December 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, estimates of North Korea's nuclear arsenal ranged between 15 and 60 bombs, probably including [[hydrogen bombs]]. In the opinion of analysts, the [[Hwasong-15]] missile is capable of striking anywhere in the United States.<ref name=\"Albert\"/>\n\nThe United Nations enacted a series of [[sanctions against North Korea]] for its nuclear program and missile tests.<ref>{{cite web|title=UN Security Council Resolutions on North Korea |url=https://www.armscontrol.org/factsheets/UN-Security-Council-Resolutions-on-North-Korea |publisher=[[Arms Control Association]] |accessdate=21 September 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170415112133/https://www.armscontrol.org/factsheets/UN-Security-Council-Resolutions-on-North-Korea |archivedate=15 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\n===International relations===\n[[File:2018 inter-Korean summit 01.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Kim and South Korean President [[Moon Jae-in]] shake hands during the [[April 2018 inter-Korean summit|2018 inter-Korean Summit]], April 2018]]\n[[File:Kim and Trump shaking hands at the red carpet during the DPRK\u2013USA Singapore Summit.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Kim and U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] shake hands at the start of the [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States Singapore Summit|2018 North Korea\u2013United States Summit]], June 2018]]\n[[File:Kim Jong-un and Vladimir Putin (2019-04-25) 05.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Kim and Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] shake hands during of the [[Kim\u2013Putin meetings|North Korea\u2013Russia Summit]], April 2019]]\n\nIn his 2018 New Year Speech, Kim announced that he was open to dialogue with [[South Korea]] with a view to take part in the [[North Korea at the 2018 Winter Olympics|upcoming Winter Olympics]] in the South.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kim Jong Un says he's 'open to dialogue' with South Korea so North Korea can compete in the Olympics \u2014 and Seoul wants to talk|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/kim-jong-un-north-korea-south-korea-talks-2018-1|work=Business Insider|accessdate=12 April 2018}}</ref> The [[Seoul\u2013Pyongyang hotline]] was reopened after almost two years.<ref>{{Cite web|title=North Korea reopens cross-border communication channel with South Korea|last=Kim |first=Hyung-Jin|work=Chicago Tribune|agency=AP|date=3 January 2018|accessdate=5 January 2018 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-south-korea-talks-north-20180102-story.html |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104221341/http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-south-korea-talks-north-20180102-story.html |archivedate=4 January 2018}}</ref> North and South Korea marched together in the Olympics opening ceremony, and fielded a [[Korea women's national ice hockey team|united women's ice hockey team]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://time.com/5142964/korea-hockey-olympics-winter-2018/|title='Cheer Up!' North Korean Cheerleaders Rally Unified Women's Hockey Team During 8\u20130 Loss|first1=Sean|last1=Gregory|location=Gangneug|magazine=Time|date=10 February 2018}}</ref> In addition to the athletes, Kim sent an unprecedented high-level delegation including his sister, Kim Yo-jong, and President of the Presidium, [[Kim Yong-nam]], and performers such as the [[Samjiyon Orchestra]].<ref name=Delegation>{{cite news |url=https://www.nknews.org/2018/02/delegation-visit-shows-n-korea-can-take-drastic-steps-to-improve-relations-mo|title=Delegation visit shows N. Korea can take \"drastic\" steps to improve relations: MOU|publisher=NK News|first=Dagyum|last=Ji|date=12 February 2018}}</ref> On 5 March, he had a meeting with South Korea's Chief of the National Security Office, Chung Eui-yong, in Pyongyang.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/07/world/asia/kim-jong-un-north-korea.html|title=Kim Jong-un, a Mystery to the World, Surprises in Diplomatic Debut|first=Choe|last=Sang-Hun|date=7 March 2018|accessdate=7 March 2018|work=[[The New York Times]] }}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, [[Kim\u2013Xi meetings|Kim visited Beijing]], meeting with General Secretary of the Communist Party of China, Xi Jinping,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xinhuanet.com/english/2018-03/28/c_137070598.htm|title=Xi Jinping, Kim Jong Un hold talks in Beijing \u2013 Xinhua|website=www.xinhuanet.com|access-date=28 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kcnawatch.co/newstream/287683/kim-jong-un-pays-unofficial-visit-to-china/|title=Kim Jong Un Pays Unofficial Visit to China|work=KCNA|access-date=2 April 2018}}</ref> marking his first foreign trip since assuming power.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/03/27/asia/north-korea-kim-jong-un-china-visit/index.html|title=North Korea's Kim Jong Un met Xi Jinping on surprise visit to China|author1=Steven Jiang |author2=Joshua Berlinger|publisher=CNN|access-date=28 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[April 2018 inter-Korean summit]], Kim and South Korean President [[Moon Jae-in]] signed the [[Panmunjom Declaration]], pledging to convert the [[Korean Armistice Agreement]] into a full peace treaty, formally ending the [[Korean War]], by the end of the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/ct-koreas-summit-20180426-story.html|title=Kim Jong Un makes historic walk across border to meet South Korea's Moon Jae-in|first=Foster|last=Klug|accessdate=3 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-43914208|title=Kim Jong-un crosses into South Korea|date=27 April 2018 |via=www.bbc.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Koreas make nuclear pledge after summit|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-43921385|accessdate=27 April 2018|work=BBC News|date=27 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nFrom 7\u20138 May, Kim made a second visit to China, meeting with Xi Jinping in [[Dalian]].<ref name=Surprise>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/08/world/asia/kim-jong-un-xi-jinping-china-north-korea.html|title=Kim's Second Surprise Visit to China Heightens Diplomatic Drama|date=8 May 2018|accessdate=26 May 2018|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May, Kim had a second and unannounced meeting in the North Korean side of [[Panmunjom]], meeting with Moon to discuss his proposed summit with [[President of the United States|US President]] [[Donald Trump]]  in Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kim Jong Un, South Korea's Moon Meet Amid Uncertainty Over U.S. Summit |date=26 May 2018 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/kim-jong-un-south-koreas-moon-meet-amid-uncertainty-over-u-s-summit-1527334020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/05/26/politics/north-and-south-korean-leaders-meet-again/index.html|title=North and South Korean leaders hold surprise meeting|author1=Jungeun Kim |author2=Theresa Waldrop|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 June, Kim arrived in [[Singapore]] and met with Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]].<ref name=Singapore>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-usa-kim/north-koreas-kim-lands-in-singapore-on-cusp-of-making-history-idUSKBN1J609X|title=Trump upbeat ahead of North Korean summit; Kim visits Singapore sites|first=Steve|last=Holland|website=reuters.com}}</ref> On 12 June, Kim held his [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States Singapore Summit|first summit]] with Trump and signed a declaration, affirming a commitment to peace, nuclear disarmament, and the repatriation of the remains of U.S. war dead.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |last1=Rosenfeld |first1=Everett |title=Document signed by Trump and Kim includes four main elements related to 'peace regime' |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/06/12/trump-and-kim-sign-agreement-document-after-summit-in-singapore.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=12 June 2018 |date=12 June 2018}}</ref> This marked the first-ever meeting between leaders of North Korea and the [[United States]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn September, Kim held another [[September 2018 inter-Korean summit|summit with Moon Jae-in]] in Pyongyang. Kim agreed to dismantle North Korea's nuclear weapons facilities if the United States took reciprocal action. The two governments also announced that they would establish buffer zones on their borders to prevent clashes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-09-19/north-korea-agrees-to-dismanlte-nuclear-test-site/10282040|title=North Korea agrees to dismantle nuclear complex if United States takes reciprocal action, South says|publisher=ABC|date=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Kim held [[2019 North Korea\u2013United States Hanoi Summit|another summit with Trump]] in [[Hanoi]], Vietnam, which Trump cut short on the second day without an agreement. The Trump administration said that the North Koreans wanted complete sanctions relief, while the North Koreans said that they were only asking for partial sanctions relief.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-and-kim-downplay-expectations-as-key-summit-talks-begin/2019/02/28/d77d752c-3ac5-11e9-aaae-69364b2ed137_story.html|title=North Korea's foreign minister says country seeks only partial sanctions relief, contradicting Trump|website=Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 April 2019, [[Kim\u2013Putin meetings|Kim held his first summit with]] [[President of Russia|Russian President]] [[Vladimir Putin]] in [[Vladivostok|Vladivostok, Russia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/asia/live-news/kim-jong-un-vladimir-putin-summit-intl/index.html|title=Vladimir Putin and Kim Jong Un hold first summit|last=Berlinger|first=Joshua|date=25 April 2019|publisher=CNN|language=en|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/kim-jong-vladimir-putin-share-warm-greeting-start/story?id=62617546|title=Kim Jong Un, Vladimir Putin share warm greeting at start of historic summit|last=Reevell|first=Patrick|date=25 April 2019|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 June 2019, in the Korean DMZ, Kim again met with Trump, shaking hands warmly and expressing hope for peace. Kim and Trump then joined Moon Jae-in for a brief chat.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-northkorea-usa/trump-sets-foot-in-north-korea-agrees-with-kim-to-resume-talks-idUSKCN1TV00R|title=Trump sets foot in north korea; Kim visits Freedom House|date=30 June 2019|language=en|website=reuters.com}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n\n=== Personality ===\nKenji Fujimoto, a Japanese chef who was Kim Jong-il's personal cook, described Kim Jong-un as \"a chip off the old block, a spitting image of his father in terms of face, body shape, and personality\".<ref name=\"McCurry2011\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/19/kim-jong-un-north-korea-leader |title=Kim Jong\u2011un, 'great successor' poised to lead North Korea |date=19 December 2011 |work=The Guardian |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703002350/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/dec/19/kim-jong-un-north-korea-leader |archivedate= 3 July 2015 |url-status=live |first=Justin |last=McCurry |location=London, UK |issn=0261-3077 |df= }}</ref> He said Jong-un was a big fan of [[The Beatles]] and [[Jean-Claude Van Damme]].{{cn|date=January 2020}} Kim is said to be a fan of the Chicago Bulls and [[Los Angeles Lakers]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Kim Jong Un wanted 'famous' US basketball players as part of denuclearization deal: Sources |url=https://abcnews.go.com/Politics/kim-jong-wanted-famous-us-basketball-players-part/story?id=62920773 |work=ABC News |date=9 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"kimpersonality\">{{cite news |title=How Did Kim Jong Un Become North Korea's Leader? 20 Little Known Facts About World's Youngest Leader |url=https://www.ibtimes.com/how-did-kim-jong-un-become-north-koreas-leader-20-little-known-facts-about-worlds-2494794 |work=International Business Times |date=20 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, ''[[Business Insider]]'' reported that there were \"{{bracket|s}}igns of a rise in luxury goods&nbsp;... creeping out of North Korea since Kim Jong-un took over\" and that his \"wife [[Ri Sol-ju]] (\ub9ac\uc124\uc8fc) was photographed holding what appeared to be an expensive [[Dior]] handbag, worth almost $1,594{{spnd}}an average year's salary in North Korea\".<ref name=\"Taylor2012\">{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/kim-jong-uns-love-for-luxury-2012-10|title=Kim Jong-un Has Massively Increased The Import of Luxury Goods into North Korea|work=Business Insider|date=5 October 2012|last=Taylor|first=Adam|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702083839/http://www.businessinsider.com/kim-jong-uns-love-for-luxury-2012-10|archivedate=2 July 2015|url-status=live|access-date=9 March 2013}}</ref> According to diplomatic sources, \"Kim Jong-un likes to drink and party all night like his father and ordered the [imported sauna] equipment to help him beat [[hangover]]s and fatigue.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2012/08/22/2012082201264.html|title=Kim Jong-un Inherits Father's Taste for Bling|date=22 August 2012|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February 2013, Kim Jong\u2011un met [[Dennis Rodman]],<ref>[http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/dennis-rodman-kim-jong-awesome-guy-article-1.1277017 Dennis Rodman: North Korea's Kim Jong Un is an 'awesome guy,' and his father and grandfather were 'great leaders'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130304071538/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/dennis-rodman-kim-jong-awesome-guy-article-1.1277017 |date=4 March 2013 }}. ''Daily News''. 1 March 2013.</ref> which led many reporters to speculate that Rodman was the first American that Kim had met.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=ABC News |title=Rodman Worms His Way into Kim Jong Un Meeting |date=28 February 2013 |url=https://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2013/02/rodman-worms-his-way-into-kim-jong-un-meeting |author=Joohee Cho |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Elyg6IRd?url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/headlines/2013/02/rodman-worms-his-way-into-kim-jong-un-meeting/ |archivedate=28 February 2013 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> During Rodman's trip, ''[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]'' magazine correspondent [[Ryan Duffy (correspondent)|Ryan Duffy]] said that \"the leader was 'socially awkward' and didn't make eye contact when shaking hands,\"<ref name=\"Vice 2013\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/vice-tracks-rodman-strange-days-north-korea-article-1.1357860 |title='Vice' season finale on HBO gives fresh look at Dennis Rodman's meeting with North Korea's Kim Jong-un |work=Daily News |location=New York |date=29 May 2013 |accessdate=16 July 2013 |last=Silverman |first=Justin Rocket |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608052205/http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/tv-movies/vice-tracks-rodman-strange-days-north-korea-article-1.1357860 |archivedate=8 June 2013 }}</ref> though [[Eye contact#Cultural differences|extended eye contact]] and [[Handshake#Modern customs|firm handshakes]] are generally less common in East Asian cultures.\n\nAccording to Cheong Seong-chang of the [[Sejong Institute]], Kim Jong-un has greater visible interest in the welfare of his people and engages in greater interaction with them than his father did.<ref>{{cite news|title=N.K. leader seen moving toward economic reform |url=http://view.koreaherald.com/kh/view.php?ud=20120627001074 |accessdate=28 June 2012 |newspaper=The Korea Herald |date=27 June 2012 |author=Song Sang-ho |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120703021456/http://view.koreaherald.com/kh/view.php?ud=20120627001074 |archivedate=3 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nSouth Koreans who saw Kim at the summit in April 2018 described him as straightforward, humorous, and attentive.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/east-asia/kim-jong-un-uncensored-what-does-footage-say-about-personality-of-reclusive-leader|title=Kim Jong Un uncensored: 7 impressions gleaned from historic summit|publisher=Straits Times|date=1 May 2018}}</ref> After meeting him, Donald Trump said, \"I learned he was a talented man. I also learned he loves his country very much.\" He added that Kim had a \"great personality\" and was \"very smart\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/news/politics/2018/06/12/five-things-president-trump-said-about-kim-jong-and-north-korea-that-have-critics-seething/eYd6Ei89ptewuWjQAPr9HN/story.html|title=Five things President Trump said about Kim Jong Un and North Korea that have critics seething|newspaper=Boston Globe|first=Jaclyn|last=Reiss|date=12 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Public image ===\n''[[Forbes]]'' magazine ranked Kim as the [[Forbes list of The World's Most Powerful People|36th most powerful person in the world]] in 2018, the highest amongst Koreans.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/powerful-people/list/|title=The World's Most Powerful People|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a research done by the Korean Research Center done in May 2018, 78% of respondents to a South Korean poll say they trusted Kim.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5262898/kim-jong-un-approval-rating/|title=Kim Jong Un Now Has An 80% Approval Rating... in South Korea|website=Time|language=en|access-date=6 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Wealth ===\nKim is said to have 17 luxury palaces around North Korea, a fleet of 100, mostly European, luxury cars, a private jet and a {{convert|100|ft|adj=on}} yacht.<ref name=\"Villasanta2019\">{{cite web|title=Kim Jong Un Net Worth: How Is North Korea's Leader Spending His Billions?\n |work=International Business Times |date=23 May 2019 |url=https://www.ibtimes.com/kim-jong-un-net-worth-how-north-koreas-leader-spending-his-billions-2794221 |first=Villasanta |last=Arthur |df= }}</ref> Rodman described his trip to Kim Jong-un's private island: \"It's like Hawaii or Ibiza, but he's the only one that lives there.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/02/dennis-rodman-north-korea-kim-jong-un |title=Dennis Rodman: North Korean leader Kim Jong-un is a 'good-hearted kid' |date=2 November 2013 |work=The Guardian |location=London, UK |issn=0261-3077 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161115035810/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/nov/02/dennis-rodman-north-korea-kim-jong-un |archivedate=15 November 2016 }}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nIn 2009, reports suggested that Kim Jong-un was a [[diabetic]] and suffered from [[hypertension]].<ref name=\"huff\">{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/06/01/kim-jongun-north-koreas-k_n_210065.html|title=Kim Jong-un: North Korea's Kim Anoints Youngest Son As Heir|last=Lee|first=Jean H.|date=2 June 2009|work=The Huffington Post|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304074646/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/06/01/kim-jongun-north-koreas-k_n_210065.html|archivedate=4 March 2016|access-date=30 November 2019}}</ref><ref name=gs>[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/dprk/kim-jong-woong.htm Kim Jong-un (Kim Jong Woon) \u2013 Leadership Succession] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225142111/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/world/dprk/kim-jong-woong.htm |date=25 February 2017 }}. Global Security.org. 3 July 2009</ref> He is also known to smoke cigarettes.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/09/asia/kim-jong-un-smoking/index.html|title=Kim Jong Un caught smoking during anti-smoking drive|last=Luu|first=Chieu|accessdate=10 June 2016|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160610062926/http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/09/asia/kim-jong-un-smoking/index.html|archivedate=10 June 2016|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nKim Jong-un did not appear in public for six weeks in September and October 2014. State media reported that he was suffering from an \"uncomfortable physical condition\". Previously he had been seen limping.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/26/north-korea-kim-jong-un-ill-health |author=Justin McCurry and Enjoli Liston |title=North Korea admits to Kim Jong-un's ill-health for first time |work=The Guardian |location=London, UK |issn=0261-3077 |date=26 September 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170217144641/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/26/north-korea-kim-jong-un-ill-health |archivedate=17 February 2017 }}</ref> When he reappeared, he was using a walking stick.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fifield |first1=Anna |title=North Korean media report that Kim Jong Un is back at work |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/north-korean-media-report-that-kim-jong-un-is-back/2014/10/13/b3545c63-0d8e-4edf-b9f5-06321d3da037_story.html |accessdate=13 October 2014 |work=The Washington Post |date=13 October 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014133600/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/north-korean-media-report-that-kim-jong-un-is-back/2014/10/13/b3545c63-0d8e-4edf-b9f5-06321d3da037_story.html |archivedate=14 October 2014 }}<br/>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/13/world/asia/north-korea-kim-jong-un/index.html |title=North Korea says leader has reappeared |publisher=CNN |date=13 October 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141014090047/http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/13/world/asia/north-korea-kim-jong-un/index.html |archivedate=14 October 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, the South Korean government commented that Kim appeared to have gained 30&nbsp;kg in body fat over the previous five years, reaching a total estimated body weight of {{convert|130|kg|lbs|abbr=on}}.<ref>[[Kyodo News]], \"Kim has gained 30&nbsp;kg, weighs 130 now: Seoul\", ''[[Japan Times]]'', 28 September 2015, p. 5</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, another period of absence from public appearances led to speculation around Kim's health.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/26/world/asia/kim-jong-un-absence-north-korea.html | title = Kim Jong-un\u2019s Absence and North Korea\u2019s Silence Keep Rumor Mill Churning | first = Choe | last = Sang-Hun | date = 26 April 2020 | accessdate = 26 April 2020 | work = [[The New York Times]] }}</ref> Kim had been absent on the [[Day of the Sun]], 15 April, celebrating the country's founding father, [[Kim Il Sung]], and was last seen four days prior at a government meeting.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://edition.cnn.com/2020/04/17/asia/north-korea-kim-jong-un-intl-hnk/index.html | title=  On North Korea's most important holiday, Kim Jong Un was nowhere to be seen | first1 =  Joshua | last1 =  Berlinger | first2= Yoonjung | last2 = Seo | date = 15 April 2020 | accessdate = 25 April 2020 | publisher = [[CNN]] }}</ref> ''[[Daily NK]]'' reported that Kim had gone to a hospital for a cardiovascular surgery on 12 April, but according to [[CNN]] reporting from U.S. agencies monitoring intelligence from North Korea, by 21 April Kim's state was in \"grave danger\" from the surgery.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/20/politics/kim-jong-un-north-korea/index.html|title=US source: North Korean leader in grave danger after surgery|publisher=CNN |date=20 April 2020 |accessdate=20 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> South Korea's [[Yonhap News Agency]] reported in response to these stories that there were \"no unusual signs detected\" in regards to Kim's health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200421003652325|title=No unusual signs about N.K. leader's health: government sources|last=Koh|first=Byung-joon|date=21 April 2020|website=Yonhap News Agency|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 April 2020}}</ref> ''[[Reuters]]'' reported that China had sent a team of doctors on 25 April to North Korea to monitor Kim's condition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/25/kim-jong-un-china-sends-doctors-to-advise-on-health-report|title=Kim Jong-un: China sends doctors to check on health|via=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=25 April 2020 |accessdate=25 April 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> South Korea's foreign policy advisor [[Moon Chung-in]] issued a statement on 26 April that \"Kim Jong Un is alive and well. He has been staying in the Wonsan area since April 13. No suspicious movements have so far been detected.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/26/asia/kim-jong-un-north-korea-health-intl/index.html | title = Amid mounting speculation, South Korea says Kim Jong Un is 'alive and well' | first1= Will | last1= Ripley | first2= Jake | last2 = Kwon | first3 = Sophie | last3 = Jeong | first4 = Tara | last4 = John | date = 26 April 2020 | accessdate = 26 April 2020 | publisher = [[CNN]] }}</ref>\n\n=== Family ===\n{{Main articles|Kim dynasty (North Korea)}}\n[[File:Chung Eui-yong and Kim Jong-un.jpg|thumb|Kim (holding envelope) with [[Chung Eui-yong]]. Kim's sister [[Kim Yo-jong]] (on the right) is said to be very close to him]]\nOn 25 July 2012, North Korean state media reported for the first time that Kim Jong-un is married to Ri Sol-ju.<ref name=\"marry\">{{cite news|title=North Korea leader Kim Jong-un married to Ri Sol-ju |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18986249 |publisher=BBC |accessdate=25 July 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725185615/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18986249 |archivedate=25 July 2012 }}</ref><ref name=\"fox\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2012/07/26/north-korea-leader-kim-jong-un-projects-new-image-by-showing-off-wife |title=North Korea leader Kim Jong Un projects new image by showing off wife |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Fox News Channel |date=26 July 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2012 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120726135344/http://www.foxnews.com/world/2012/07/26/north-korea-leader-kim-jong-un-projects-new-image-by-showing-off-wife/ |archivedate=26 July 2012 }}</ref> Ri, who was believed to be in her early 20s, had been accompanying Kim Jong-un to public appearances for several weeks prior to the announcement.<ref name=\"fox\" /> According to a South Korean analyst, Kim Jong-il had hastily arranged the marriage after suffering a stroke in 2008, the two married in 2009, and they had a child in 2010.<ref>{{cite news|title=North Korea leader Kim Jong-un married to Ri Sol-ju |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18986249 |publisher=BBC |date=25 July 2012 |accessdate=4 December 2013 |quote=Ms Ri is believed to have married Mr Kim in 2009 and given birth to a child the following year, analyst Cheong Seong-chang told the South Korean Korea Times newspaper. |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131107114949/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18986249 |archivedate=7 November 2013 }}</ref> Dennis Rodman, after visiting in 2013, reported that they had a daughter named Ju-ae.<ref name=\"NationalPost2013\">{{cite news|url=http://news.nationalpost.com/sports/nba/dennis-rodman-seems-to-let-it-slip-that-kim-jong-un-has-a-daughter |title=Dennis Rodman lets the world know Kim Jong-un has a daughter |agency=Associated Press |work=National Post |issn=1486-8008 |date=19 March 2013 |accessdate=23 March 2013 |df= }}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref name=\"Walker2013\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/09/dennis-rodman-north-korea-baby-name |title=Dennis Rodman gives away name of Kim Jong\u2011un's daughter |work=The Guardian |date=9 September 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150909205413/http://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/sep/09/dennis-rodman-north-korea-baby-name |archive-date= 9 September 2015 |url-status=live |first=Peter |last=Walker |location=London, UK |issn=0261-3077 |df= }}</ref> However, South Korean sources speculated that they could have many children.<ref name=chosunmarch20>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2013/03/20/2013032000553.html |title=Kim Jong-un 'Has a Little Daughter' |work=Chosun |date=20 March 2013 |accessdate=14 April 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130415034023/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2013/03/20/2013032000553.html |archivedate=15 April 2013 }}<br/>[http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2013/05/16/2013051600925.html Kim Jong-un 'Has 2 Daughters'] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130521020307/http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2013/05/16/2013051600925.html |date=21 May 2013 }}, Chosun.com, 16 May 2013.</ref>\n\nKim is sometimes accompanied by his younger sister Kim Yo-jong,<ref name=\"Lee2012\" /><ref name=\"Kim Yo Jong\" /> who is said to be instrumental in creating his public image and organising public events for him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/sister-helps-kim-strut-his-stuff-as-key-missile-test-looms-jjf8gdvzk|title=Sister helps Kim strut his stuff as key missile test looms|last=Sherwell|first=Phillip|date=8 January 2017|newspaper=The Times|access-date=15 February 2017|language=en}}</ref> According to Kim Yong-hyun, a professor of North Korean studies at [[Dongguk University]] in Seoul, and others, the promotion of Kim Yo-jong and others is a sign that \"the Kim Jong-un regime has ended its co-existence with the remnants of the previous Kim Jong-il regime by carrying out a generational replacement in the party's key elite posts\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/09/kim-yo-jong-sister-brains-behind-kim-jong-uns-image|title=Meet Kim Yo-jong, the sister who is the brains behind Kim Jong-un's image|last=McCurry|first=Justin|date=9 October 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=8 January 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 February 2017, Kim Jong-nam, the exiled half-brother of Kim Jong-un, was assassinated with the [[VX (nerve agent)|nerve agent VX]] while walking through Terminal 2 at [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-39073389 |title=Kim Jong-nam killing: VX nerve agent 'found on his face' |publisher=BBC News |date=24 February 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170224021724/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-39073389 |archivedate=24 February 2017 }}</ref> Jong-un is widely believed to have ordered the assassination.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/15/world/asia/kim-jong-nam-dna-malaysia.html DNA Confirms Assassination Victim Was Half Brother of Kim Jong-un, Malaysia Says] New York Times. By Russell Goldman. 5 March 2017. Downloaded 6 May 2017.</ref><ref name=\"delusional\">[http://m.koreatimes.co.kr/phone/news/view.jsp?req_newsidx=224020 Kim Jong-un risks vital ties with China] Korea Times. By Jun Ji-hye. 16 February 2017.  Downloaded 6 May 2017.</ref> \n{{Kim Jong-il family}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|North Korea|Politics}}\n* [[Inter-Korean summit]]\n* [[Kim dynasty (North Korea)]]\n* [[Kim Jong-un bibliography]]\n* [[Residences of North Korean leaders]]\n* [[Kim\u2013Xi meetings]]\n* [[Kim\u2013Putin meetings]]\n* [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States Singapore Summit]]\n* [[2019 North Korea\u2013United States Hanoi Summit]]\n* [[2019 Koreas\u2013United States DMZ Summit]]\n* [[List of international trips made by Kim Jong-un]]\n* [[Kim (Korean surname)#Jeonju|Jeongju Gim (Kim)]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist|group=efn}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Bechtol|first=Bruce E., Jr.|title=North Korea and Regional Security in the Kim Jong-un Era: A New International Security Dilemma|year=2014|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-137-40007-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=French|first=Paul|title=Our Supreme Leader: The Making of Kim Jong-un|year=2016|publisher=Zed Books|location=London|isbn=978-1-78360-900-0}}\n*{{cite book|last=Fifield|first=Anna|title=The Great Successor: The Divinely Perfect Destiny of Brilliant Comrade Kim Jong Un|year=2019|publisher=PublicAffairs|isbn=978-1541742482}}\n*{{cite book|title=Kim Jong Un Aphorisms |volume=1|url=http://www.naenara.com.kp/en/book/download.php?4+4061#.pdf |date=2016 |publisher=Foreign Languages Publishing House |location=Pyongyang |isbn=978-9946-0-1430-2}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=Kyo-Duk|last2=Lim|first2=Soon-Hee|last3=Cho|first3=Jeong-Ah|last4=Song|first4=Joung-Ho|title=Study on the Power Elite of the Kim Jong Un Regime|url=http://repo.kinu.or.kr/bitstream/2015.oak/2240/1/0001458996.pdf|series=Study Series 13-01|year=2013|publisher=Korea Institute for National Unification|location=Seoul|isbn=978-89-8479-708-6}}\n*{{cite book |editor1=Thak Song-il |editor2=An Su-yong |title=Supreme Leader Kim Jong Un in the Year 2012 |url=http://www.naenara.com.kp/en/book/download.php?4+4051#.pdf |date=January 2014 |publisher=Foreign Languages Publishing House |location=Pyongyang |isbn=978-9946-0-1192-9}}\n*{{cite book |editor=An Chol-gang |title=Supreme Leader Kim Jong Un in the Year 2013 |url=http://www.naenara.com.kp/en/book/download.php?4+4056#.pdf |date=November 2014 |publisher=Foreign Languages Publishing House |location=Pyongyang |isbn=978-9946-0-1192-9}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Thak Son-il|author2=An Su-yong|title=Anecdotes of Kim Jong Un's Life|year=2017|publisher=Foreign Languages Publishing House|location=Pyongyang|isbn=978-9946-0-1530-9}}\n*{{cite book|translator1=Mun Myong-song|translator2=Jong Myong-jin|editor=Thak Song-il|title=Son of the People|url=http://www.korean-books.com.kp/en/packages/xnps/download.pg.php?388#.pdf|year=2018|publisher=Foreign Languages Publishing House|location=Pyongyang|isbn=978-9946-0-1719-8}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikinews category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Wikisource author}}\n* {{Britannica|1549482|Kim Jong-Un}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101201161408/http://video.nytimes.com/video/2010/09/30/world/asia/1248069113905/north-korea-s-young-leader-on-show.html North Korea's Young Leader on Show]&nbsp;\u2013 video report by ''[[The New York Times]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130411010330/http://nsarchive.wordpress.com/2011/12/19/document-friday-kim-jong-il-the-%E2%80%9Cgreat-successor%E2%80%9D/ NSA Archive Kim Jong-Il: The \"Great Successor\"]\n* [http://www.naenara.com.kp/en/politics/?leader3 Official short biography] at [[Naenara]]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170729133349/http://www.korean-books.com.kp/en/search/?page=work-leader3 Kim Jong-un's works] at Publications of the DPRK\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kim Jong-il]]|rows=3}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chairman of the Workers' Party of Korea|Chairman]] of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]<br />{{small|[[First Secretary of the Workers' Party of Korea|First Secretary]]: 2012\u20132016}}|years=2016\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc|rows=3}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=Chairman of the [[Central Military Commission of the Workers' Party of Korea|Central Military Commission]]<br />{{small|Acting: 2011\u20132012}}|years=2012\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Leader of the Workers' Party of Korea|Leader]] of the [[Presidium of the Politburo of the Workers' Party of Korea|Presidium of the Politburo]]<br /> of the [[Workers' Party of Korea]]<br />{{small|Acting: 2011\u20132012}}|years=2012\u2013present}}\n|-\n{{s-new|office}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice Chairman of the<br />[[Central Military Commission (North Korea)|Central Military Commission]]|alongside=[[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]]|years=2010\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Choe Ryong-hae]]<br /> & [[Ri Yong-ho (general)|Ri Yong-ho]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Kim Kyong-hui]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Director of the <br /> [[Organization and Guidance Department]]|years=2012\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Choe Ryong-hae]