{"title_page": "Clete Roberts", "text_new": "{{no footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Clete Roberts\n| image       = Alan Alda Clete Roberts MASH 1976.JPG\n| caption     = From TV series ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'':<br>Clete Roberts and [[Alan Alda]] (1976)\n| birthname   = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1912|2|1}}\n| birth_place = [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1984|9|30|1912|2|1}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| education   = \n| occupation  = [[Journalist]]<br />[[News presenter|Anchor]]\n| years_active = 1950s &ndash; 1980s\n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| credits     = [[KCBS-TV]], [[KTLA]] Channel 5, [[KCET]]\n}}\n'''Clete Roberts''' (1 February 1912 \u2013 30 November 1984) was an [[Americans|America]]n [[broadcast journalism|broadcast journalist]] and film and television actor.\n\n==Career==\n\n===KNXT Channel 2===\nAfter serving as a [[war correspondent]] in [[World War II]] and [[Korean War|Korea]], Roberts settled in the Los Angeles area and became a respected radio news [[reporter]], eventually turning to television in the mid-1950s at KNXT Channel 2 (now [[KCBS-TV]]), the local CBS [[Owned-and-operated station|owned-and-operated]] station. He [[news presenter|anchored]] a nightly newscast and occasionally ventured to far-flung locations to report on national and international stories, taking with him his own [[Bell and Howell]] movie camera with which he shot his own news footage. With him on KNXT's newscasts in that time were three other Los Angeles television stalwarts, anchor and reporter [[Bill Stout]], weather forecaster [[Bill Keene]] and sports reporter [[Gil Stratton]] (who at the time also doubled as a radio, television and movie actor).\n\n===KTLA Channel 5===\nRoberts left KNXT in 1959 and joined Los Angeles station [[KTLA]] Channel 5 as news director and primary anchor, along with news producer/director Julian Macdonald, virtually remaking that independent station's news operation. The newscast Roberts and Macdonald oversaw included such respected figures as Stout (who followed Roberts to KTLA in 1960), sports reporter and former football star [[Tom Harmon]], and veteran reporter [[Stan Chambers]] (who retired on August 11, 2010 on his 87th birthday, marking 63 years as a reporter at KTLA). Roberts' signature conclusion to the early news broadcast was \"I bid you a pleasant evening\"; for the late news it was \"I bid you goodnight.\"\n\n===\"The Big News\"===\nIn 1966, Roberts returned to KNXT, joining the station's highly esteemed 6 p.m. \"The Big News\" broadcast and its late-night companion \"The Eleven O'Clock Report.\" Roberts joined a staff that included anchor [[Jerry Dunphy]], [[Maury Green]], [[Ralph Story]], Keene, and Stratton. Roberts contributed news and feature reports and anchored the weekend newscasts. Early in 1974 he once again left KNXT for KTLA and took over the station's hour-long 10 p.m. newscasts. After two years Roberts decided to step back from nightly television news and left KTLA; after a hiatus he joined then-[[PBS]] member television station [[KCET]], contributing feature reports and commentaries. His long tenure in Los Angeles comprised reports and travels ranging from offbeat local stories to the war in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]. According to the book Helter Skelter, the young son of a neighbor of Roberts found what turned out to be the .22 Buntline revolver wielded by Manson Family member Tex Watson the night of actress Sharon Tate's and her houseguests' murders, and it was turned over to the police.  As details of the crime came out in the weeks that followed, the boy's father made several calls to the police, suggesting that the missing murder weapon was the same broken, long-barreled gun his son had found. Finally, fed up with months of being ignored by the LAPD, he asked Clete Roberts to intervene in December 1969. The book does not say whether the call from Roberts finally did the trick.\n\n===Acting career===\nRoberts also carried his polish and expertise onto the \"silver screen\" and television as well, most notably in select episodes of ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', in which he played himself, a war correspondent.\n\nRoberts appeared as himself in the lengthy introduction to the crime syndicate expose film ''[[The Phenix City Story]]'' in 1955. He interviewed on camera several of the actual townspeople of [[Phenix City, Alabama]], who had been witness to the events there in the 1930s, '40s and early '50s.\n\nRoberts portrayed reporters in various productions, among them, ''[[Meteor (film)|Meteor]]''  from 1979, the 1983 NBC miniseries ''[[V (1983 miniseries)|V]]'', as well a San Francisco television newsman in the 1983 nuclear war film ''[[Testament (1983 film)|Testament]]''.\n\n== Honors and awards ==\nThe [[Associated Press Television and Radio Association]] of [[California]], [[Nevada]], and [[Hawaii]] has established a $1,500 scholarship in Roberts' memory.{{cn|date=September 2015}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IMDb name|0730950}}\n* {{Find a Grave|1365}}\n\n{{Vietnam War correspondents}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberts, Clete}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:American radio reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American war correspondents]]\n[[Category:American war correspondents of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Television anchors from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:Burials at Valley Oaks Memorial Park]]\n", "text_old": "{{no footnotes|date=March 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Clete Roberts\n| image       = Alan Alda Clete Roberts MASH 1976.JPG\n| caption     = From TV series ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'':<br>Clete Roberts and [[Alan Alda]] (1976)\n| birthname   = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1912|2|1}}\n| birth_place = [[Portland, Oregon]]\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1984|9|30|1912|2|1}}\n| death_place = [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| education   = \n| occupation  = [[Journalist]]<br />[[News presenter|Anchor]]\n| years_active = 1950s &ndash; 1980s\n| spouse      = \n| children    = \n| credits     = [[KCBS-TV]], [[KTLA]] Channel 5, [[KCET]]\n}}\n'''Clete Roberts''' (1 February 1912 \u2013 30 November 1984) was an [[Americans|America]]n [[broadcast journalism|broadcast journalist]] and film and television actor.\n\n==Career==\n\n===KNXT Channel 2===\nAfter serving as a [[war correspondent]] in [[World War II]] and [[Korean War|Korea]], Roberts settled in the Los Angeles area and became a respected radio news [[reporter]], eventually turning to television in the mid-1950s at KNXT Channel 2 (now [[KCBS-TV]]), the local CBS [[Owned-and-operated station|owned-and-operated]] station. He [[news presenter|anchored]] a nightly newscast and occasionally ventured to far-flung locations to report on national and international stories, taking with him his own [[Bell and Howell]] movie camera with which he shot his own news footage. With him on KNXT's newscasts in that time were three other Los Angeles television stalwarts, anchor and reporter [[Bill Stout]], weather forecaster [[Bill Keene]] and sports reporter [[Gil Stratton]] (who at the time also doubled as a radio, television and movie actor).\n\n===KTLA Channel 5===\nRoberts left KNXT in 1959 and joined Los Angeles station [[KTLA]] Channel 5 as news director and primary anchor, along with news producer/director Julian Macdonald, virtually remaking that independent station's news operation. The newscast Roberts and Macdonald oversaw included such respected figures as Stout (who followed Roberts to KTLA in 1960), sports reporter and former football star [[Tom Harmon]], and veteran reporter [[Stan Chambers]] (who retired on August 11, 2010 on his 87th birthday, marking 63 years as a reporter at KTLA). Roberts' signature conclusion to the early news broadcast was \"I bid you a pleasant evening\"; for the late news it was \"I bid you goodnight.\"\n\n===\"The Big News\"===\nIn 1966, Roberts returned to KNXT, joining the station's highly-esteemed 6 p.m. \"The Big News\" broadcast and its late-night companion \"The Eleven O'Clock Report.\" Roberts joined a staff that included anchor [[Jerry Dunphy]], [[Maury Green]], [[Ralph Story]], Keene, and Stratton. Roberts contributed news and feature reports and anchored the weekend newscasts. Early in 1974 he once again left KNXT for KTLA and took over the station's hour-long 10 p.m. newscasts. After two years Roberts decided to step back from nightly television news and left KTLA; after a hiatus he joined then-[[PBS]] member television station [[KCET]], contributing feature reports and commentaries. His long tenure in Los Angeles comprised reports and travels ranging from offbeat local stories to the war in [[Vietnam War|Vietnam]]. According to the book Helter Skelter, the young son of a neighbor of Roberts found what turned out to be the .22 Buntline revolver wielded by Manson Family member Tex Watson the night of actress Sharon Tate's and her houseguests' murders, and it was turned over to the police.  As details of the crime came out in the weeks that followed, the boy's father made several calls to the police, suggesting that the missing murder weapon was the same broken, long-barreled gun his son had found. Finally, fed up with months of being ignored by the LAPD, he asked Clete Roberts to intervene in December 1969. The book does not say whether the call from Roberts finally did the trick.\n\n===Acting career===\nRoberts also carried his polish and expertise onto the \"silver screen\" and television as well, most notably in select episodes of ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'', in which he played himself, a war correspondent.\n\nRoberts appeared as himself in the lengthy introduction to the crime syndicate expose film ''[[The Phenix City Story]]'' in 1955. He interviewed on camera several of the actual townspeople of [[Phenix City, Alabama]], who had been witness to the events there in the 1930s, '40s and early '50s.\n\nRoberts portrayed reporters in various productions, among them, ''[[Meteor (film)|Meteor]]''  from 1979, the 1983 NBC miniseries ''[[V (1983 miniseries)|V]]'', as well a San Francisco television newsman in the 1983 nuclear war film ''[[Testament (1983 film)|Testament]]''.\n\n== Honors and awards ==\nThe [[Associated Press Television and Radio Association]] of [[California]], [[Nevada]], and [[Hawaii]] has established a $1,500 scholarship in Roberts' memory.{{cn|date=September 2015}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n* {{IMDb name|0730950}}\n* {{Find a Grave|1365}}\n\n{{Vietnam War correspondents}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roberts, Clete}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:American radio reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American television reporters and correspondents]]\n[[Category:American war correspondents]]\n[[Category:American war correspondents of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Portland, Oregon]]\n[[Category:Television anchors from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:Burials at Valley Oaks Memorial Park]]\n", "name_user": "Grammarspellchecker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e\"The Big News\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clete_Roberts"}
{"title_page": "Tucker Carlson", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American conservative political commentator}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tucker Carlson\n| image              = Tucker Carlson 2013 cropped noise rem lighting color correction.jpg\n| caption            = Carlson in 2013\n| birth_name         = Tucker McNear Carlson<ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VGZJ-QSS|title=Person Details for Tucker M Carlson, \"California Birth Index, 1905\u20131995\"|publisher=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=February 3, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311073401/https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VGZJ-QSS|archive-date=March 11, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1969|5|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| home_town          = [[La Jolla]], [[San Diego]], California, U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| occupation         = [[Talk show host]], [[political commentator|commentator]], [[columnist]]\n| employer           = [[CNN]] (2000\u20132005)<br>[[MSNBC]] (2005\u20132008)<br>[[Fox News]] (2009\u2013present)\n| movement           = [[Conservatism]]\n| party              = \n| spouse             = Susan Andrews\n| children           = 4\n| relatives          = [[Dick Carlson]] (father)\n}}\n{{Conservatism in the United States}}\n'''Tucker Swanson McNear Carlson''' (born May 16, 1969) is an American [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] journalist, author, and political commentator who has hosted the nightly political talk show ''[[Tucker Carlson Tonight]]'' on [[Fox News]] since 2016.\n\nCarlson became a print journalist in the 1990s, writing for the magazine ''[[The Weekly Standard]]''. He was a commentator on [[CNN]] from 2000 to 2005 and co-hosted the primetime news debate program ''[[Crossfire (U.S. TV program)|Crossfire]]''. Carlson then hosted the nightly program ''[[Tucker (2005 TV program)|Tucker]]'' on [[MSNBC]] from 2005 to 2008. He has been a political analyst for Fox News since 2009, appearing as guest or guest host on various programs before the launch of his current show. In 2010, Carlson co-founded and served as the initial editor-in-chief of the conservative news and opinion website ''[[The Daily Caller]]''.\n\nCarlson has written two books, the memoir ''Politicians, Partisans and Parasites: My Adventures in Cable News'' (2003) and ''[[Ship of Fools (book)|Ship of Fools: How a Selfish Ruling Class is Bringing America to the Brink of Revolution]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life and education==\nCarlson was born Tucker McNear Carlson in [[San Francisco]], [[California]]. He is the elder son of [[Dick Carlson|Richard Warner Carlson]], a former \"[[Gonzo journalism|gonzo reporter]]\"<ref name=Dick/> who became the director of the [[Voice of America]], the president of the [[Corporation for Public Broadcasting]] and the [[List of ambassadors of the United States to Seychelles|U.S. Ambassador to the Seychelles]].<ref name=\":102\">Lenz, Lyz (September 5, 2018). [https://www.cjr.org/the_profile/tucker-carlson.php \"The mystery of Tucker Carlson\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908093046/https://www.cjr.org/the_profile/tucker-carlson.php |date=September 8, 2018 }}, ''Columbia Journalism Review''.</ref> Carlson's paternal grandparents were Richard Boynton and Dorothy Anderson, teenagers who placed his father in an [[orphanage]] where he was adopted when he was two years old by the Carlsons. Richard Carlson's adoptive father was a wool broker.<ref name=Boynton>{{cite news|author=Tony Knight|title=Hoping for a runoff|publisher=Times-Advocate|location=Escondido, California|date=27 May 1984}}</ref><ref name=Dick>{{cite news|author=Scott Harris|title=Carlson Takes on Embattled Mayor|publisher=Los Angeles Times|location=Los Angeles, California|date=6 May 1984}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/politicswithprin00mich/page/47 <!-- quote=father richard carlson boynton. --> Politics with Principle: Ten Characters with Character] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110120123/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=furNVPTV-wMC&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=father+richard+carlson+boynton&source=bl&ots=FLin8F_daJ&sig=7ea6pViQVWdC9BJgxBc4iPbbyYo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-y5WS0cjeAhWMA8AKHXXHAsAQ6AEwD3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=father%20richard%20carlson%20boynton&f=false |date=November 10, 2018 }} \u2013 By Michael J. Kerrigan.</ref>\n\nCarlson's mother was artist Lisa McNear (n\u00e9e Lombardi). He also has a brother, Buckley Peck Carlson (later, Buckley Swanson Peck Carlson), who is nearly two years younger and was born two months premature.<ref name=Brother>{{cite news|author=Albert Morch|title=Albert Morch [Column]|publisher=The San Francisco Examiner|date=15 Feb 1971}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, Carlson's parents divorced after the nine-year marriage reportedly \"turned sour.\"<ref name=Brother/><ref name=Divorce>{{cite news|author=Center for Health Statistics, California Department of Health Services|title=California Divorce Index, 1966-1984|publisher=State of California|location=Sacramento, California}}</ref> Carlson's father was granted custody of him and his brother. Carlson's mother left the family when he was six, wanting to pursue a \"[[Bohemianism|bohemian]]\" lifestyle.<ref>''National Social Directory'', National Social Register Company, 1959, page 86.</ref><ref name=\":102\"/> She eventually split her time between [[Beaufort County, South Carolina]] and [[Cazac, Haute-Garonne|Cazac, France]], where she had little contact with Carlson's family and later married artist Michael Vaughn.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/04/10/tucker-carlsons-fighting-words|title=Tucker Carlson's Fighting Words|work=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=August 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830041835/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/04/10/tucker-carlsons-fighting-words|archive-date=August 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Obit>{{cite web|title=Obituary: Lisa Lombardi-Vaughan|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/sfgate/obituary.aspx?n=lisa-lombardi-vaughan&pid=154563219|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle|date=13 Nov 2011}}</ref><ref name=lawsuit>{{cite web|title=IN RE ESTATE OF VAUGHN|url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/incaco20190606085|publisher=Leagle|date=4 Jun 2019}}</ref><ref name=lawsuit2>{{cite web|title=Bickel v. Carlson (In re Estate of Vaughan)|url=https://casetext.com/case/bickel-v-carlson-in-re-estate-of-vaughan|publisher=Casetext|date=4 Jun 2019}}</ref>\n\nDick Carlson was said to be an active father who had a specific outlook in raising his sons:\n\n{{Quote|\"I want them to be self-disciplined to the degree that I think is necessary to find satisfaction{{nbsp}}... you measure a person on how far they go, on how far they've sprung. My parents, the Carlsons, they instilled a modesty in me that, at times, gets in my way{{nbsp}}... I know it's immodest of me to say it, but it's difficult sometimes when you want to beat your own drum and say what you really think.\"}}\n\nIn 1979, Carlson's father married divorc\u00e9e Patricia Caroline Swanson, an heiress to [[Swanson]] Enterprises. Swanson is the daughter of Gilbert Carl Swanson and the niece of [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[J. William Fulbright]].<ref name=\":102\"/><ref name=Patty>{{cite news|author=David Harris|title=SWANSON SAGA: END OF A DREAM|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/09/09/archives/swanson-saga-end-of-a-dream-they-were-the-pride-of-omaha-but-today.html|publisher=The New York Times|date=9 Sep 1979}}</ref> This was the third marriage for Swanson, who legally adopted Carlson and his brother.<ref name=lawsuit/><ref name=Patty/>\n\nWhen Carlson was in first grade, his father moved him and his brother to [[La Jolla]], [[California]] and raised them there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://observer.com/2018/01/fox-new-tucker-carlson-immigrant-bashing-is-toxic/|title=Tucker Carlson's Xenophobia Is Horribly Effective|date=January 24, 2018|access-date=August 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806072343/https://observer.com/2018/01/fox-new-tucker-carlson-immigrant-bashing-is-toxic/|archive-date=August 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"peoplemag\">{{cite news |url= http://people.com/archive/meet-mister-right-vol-54-no-19/ |title= Meet Mister Right |volume= 54 |number= 19 |date= November 6, 2000 |work= [[People (magazine)|People]] |first= Steve |last= Dougherty |access-date= January 5, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170106011519/http://people.com/archive/meet-mister-right-vol-54-no-19/ |archive-date= January 6, 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> In La Jolla, Carlson attended [[La Jolla Country Day School]] and grew up in a home overlooking the [[La Jolla Beach and Tennis Club]].<ref name=Proven>{{cite news|author=Gerry Braun|title=Rites of Passage: Dick Carlson says he has proven himself|publisher=Times-Advocate|location=Escondido, California|date=21 Oct 1984}}</ref> His father owned property in Nevada, Vermont, and islands in Maine and Nova Scotia.<ref name=Proven/><ref name=Dick/>\n\nCarlson attained his secondary education at [[St. George's School, Newport|St. George's School]], a [[boarding school]] in [[Middletown, Rhode Island]]. He then went to [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]] in [[Hartford, Connecticut]], where he graduated in 1991 with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in history.<ref name=\":102\"/> After college, Carlson tried to join the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], but his application was denied, after which he decided to pursue a career in journalism with the encouragement of his father.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jeva Lange |url=https://theweek.com/speedreads-amp/689969/tucker-carlson-tried-join-cia |title=Tucker Carlson tried to join the CIA |publisher=Theweek.com |date=2017-04-03 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>https://www.cjr.org/the_profile/tucker-carlson.php</ref>\n\n==Television career==\nCarlson began his [[journalism]] career as a fact-checker for ''[[Policy Review]]'',<ref name=\":102\"/> a national [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] journal then published by [[The Heritage Foundation]] and since acquired by the [[Hoover Institution]]. He later worked as a reporter at the ''[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette]]'' newspaper in [[Little Rock, Arkansas]], before joining ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'' newsmagazine in 1995.<ref name=\":102\"/>\n\nAs a magazine and newspaper journalist, Carlson has reported from around the world. He has been a columnist for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' and ''[[Reader's Digest]]''. He also wrote for ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'', ''[[The New Republic]]'', ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', and ''[[The Daily Beast]]''.<ref name=\":102\"/>\n\n===CNN (2000\u20132005)===\n[[File:CPAC 2012 &#039;Fight Club&#039; Debate with Paul Begala and Tucker Carlson, Thomas McDevitt, President, The Washington Times is the Moderator. (6859927507).jpg|thumb|right|Paul Begala, Thomas McDevitt, and Carlson, 2012]]\nIn 2000, Carlson co-hosted the short-lived show ''The Spin Room''.<ref name=\":102\"/> In 2001, Carlson was appointed co-host of ''[[Crossfire (U.S. TV program)|Crossfire]].'' On the show, Carlson and [[Robert Novak]] represented the political [[right-wing politics|right]] (alternating on different nights), while [[James Carville]] and [[Paul Begala]], also alternating as hosts, represented the left.<ref name=\":102\"/> During the same period, he also hosted a weekly public affairs program on [[PBS]], ''Tucker Carlson: Unfiltered''.\n\nIn October 2004, comedian [[Jon Stewart]], host of ''[[The Daily Show]]'' on [[Comedy Central]], appeared on ''Crossfire'', ostensibly to promote his book ''[[America (The Book)]]'', but instead launching into a critique of ''Crossfire'', saying that the show was harmful to political discourse in the United States.<ref name=\":102\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Watch Jon Stewart Call Tucker Carlson a \"Dick\" in Epic 2004 'Crossfire' Takedown |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jon-stewart-takes-down-tucker-carlson-crossfire-video-961127 |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719234728/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jon-stewart-takes-down-tucker-carlson-crossfire-video-961127 |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carlson represented the right-wing side on that episode, and Stewart singled him out for criticism, with Carlson in turn criticizing Stewart for being biased toward the left.<ref name=\":102\"/> Carlson later recalled that Stewart had stayed at CNN for hours after the show to discuss the issues he had raised on the air. \"It was heartfelt,\" Carlson said, \"He [Stewart] needed to do this.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Cave |first=Damien |url=http://msl1.mit.edu/furdlog/docs/nytimes/2004-10-24_nytimes_damien_cave.pdf |format=PDF |title=A Week in Review: If You Interview Kissinger, Are You Still a Comedian? |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 24, 2004 |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |via=Msl1.mit.edu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405064722/http://msl1.mit.edu/furdlog/docs/nytimes/2004-10-24_nytimes_damien_cave.pdf |archive-date=April 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' referred to Stewart's \"on-air dressing-down\" of Carlson as an \"ignominious career [moment]\" for Carlson.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/05/business/media/tucker-carlson-megyn-kelly-fox.html|title=Megyn Kelly Being Replaced by Tucker Carlson at Fox|last=Grynbaum|first=Michael M.|date=2017-01-05|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2018-12-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124539/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/05/business/media/tucker-carlson-megyn-kelly-fox.html|archive-date=December 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the view of ''The New York Times'', Stewart's criticism led to the cancellation of the show.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nIn January 2005, CNN announced they were ending their relationship with Carlson and would soon cancel ''Crossfire''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://politicalhumor.about.com/b/2005/01/07/jon-stewarts-wish-fulfilled-crossfire-to-stop-hurting-america.htm |title=Jon Stewart's Wish Fulfilled; 'Crossfire' to Stop 'Hurting America' |publisher=Political Humor |date=January 7, 2005 |accessdate=August 5, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090501190911/http://politicalhumor.about.com/b/2005/01/07/jon-stewarts-wish-fulfilled-crossfire-to-stop-hurting-america.htm |archive-date=May 1, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Cancel\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/06/business/media/06crossfire.html?_r=1 |title=CNN Will Cancel 'Crossfire' and Cut Ties to Commentator|author1=Carter, Bill |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422204302/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/06/business/media/06crossfire.html?_r=1 |archivedate=April 22, 2012 |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 6, 2005|accessdate=March 16, 2009|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> CNN chief [[Jonathan Klein (CNN)|Jonathan Klein]] told Carlson on January 4, 2005, that the network had decided not to renew his contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/story/2005/01/05/tucker050105.html |publisher=[[CBC.ca]] |date=January 6, 2005 |title=CNN lets Tucker Carlson go |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509183431/http://www.cbc.ca/arts/story/2005/01/05/tucker050105.html |archivedate=May 9, 2007}}</ref> Carlson has said that he had already resigned from CNN and ''Crossfire'' long before Stewart was booked as a guest, telling host [[Patricia Duff]]: \"I resigned from ''Crossfire'' in April [2004], many months before Jon Stewart came on our show, because I didn't like the partisanship, and I thought in some ways it was kind of a pointless conversation{{nbsp}}... each side coming out, you know, 'Here's my argument', and no one listening to anyone else. [CNN] was a frustrating place to work.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tvweek.com/in-depth/2005/01/tucker-carlson-leaving-cnn-cro/ |title=Tucker Carlson Leaving CNN; \u2018Crossfire\u2019s\u2019 Demise Likely|date=5 January 2005|work=TV Week| accessdate=August 17, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===MSNBC (2005\u20132008)===\n{{Main|Tucker (2005 TV program)}}\nCarlson's early evening show, ''Tucker'' (originally titled ''The Situation With Tucker Carlson'') premiered on June 13, 2005, on [[MSNBC]]. He also hosted a late afternoon weekday wrap-up for MSNBC during the [[2006 Winter Olympics]], during which he attempted to learn how to play various Olympic sports. In July 2006, he reported live for ''Tucker'' from [[Haifa]], [[Israel]], during the [[2006 Lebanon War]] between Israel and [[Hezbollah]] in southern Lebanon. While in the [[Middle East]], he also hosted ''MSNBC Special Report: Mideast Crisis''. He appeared regularly on ''[[Verdict with Dan Abrams]]'' as a panelist in political discussions.\n\n''Tucker'' was cancelled by the network on March 10, 2008, due to low ratings,<ref>{{cite news|title=David Gregory Replaces Tucker Carlson on MSNBC Evening Shift|date=March 10, 2008|agency=Associated Press|publisher=[[Fox News]]|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,336470,00.html|access-date=December 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025110901/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,336470,00.html|archive-date=October 25, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the final episode aired on March 14, 2008. [[Brian Stelter]] of ''The New York Times'' wrote that \"during Mr. Carlson's tenure, MSNBC's evening programming moved gradually to the left. His former time slots, 6{{nbsp}}and 9{{nbsp}}p.m., were then occupied by two liberals, [[Ed Schultz]] and [[Rachel Maddow]].\" Carlson said the network had changed a lot and \"they didn't have a role for me.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Stelter|first=Brian|title=Tucker Carlson turns 40, moves to Fox News|url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/05/15/tucker-carlson-turns-40-moves-to-fox-news/|accessdate=March 4, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 15, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130404232029/http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/05/15/tucker-carlson-turns-40-moves-to-fox-news/|archive-date=April 4, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Fox News Channel (2009\u2013present)===\nIn May 2009, Fox News announced that Carlson was being hired as a Fox News contributor. He was a frequent guest panelist on Fox's late-night satire show ''[[Red Eye w/Greg Gutfeld]],'' made frequent appearances on the All-Star Panel segment of ''[[Special Report with Bret Baier]]'', was a substitute host of ''[[Hannity]]'' in Sean Hannity's absence, and produced a Fox News special entitled ''Fighting for Our Children's Minds''.\n\nIn April 2013, Carlson replaced [[Dave Briggs (journalist)|Dave Briggs]] as a co-host of [[Fox & Friends Weekend]], joining Alisyn Camerota and Clayton Morris on Saturday and Sunday mornings.<ref>{{cite news|last=Byers|first=Dylan|title=Tucker Carlson to Fox & Friends Weekends|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/03/tucker-carlson-to-cohost-fox-friends-weekends-160334.html|work=[[Politico]]|access-date=March 27, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330091112/http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/03/tucker-carlson-to-cohost-fox-friends-weekends-160334.html|archive-date=March 30, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' (2016\u2013present)====\n{{Main|Tucker Carlson Tonight}}\n\nOn November 14, 2016, Carlson started hosting ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' on Fox News. ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' was created to replace the show ''[[On the Record (Fox News TV series)|On the Record]]''.<ref name=\"NewsHoundEllen\">{{cite news|url=https://crooksandliars.com/2016/09/greta-van-susteren-abruptly-leaves-fox|title=Greta Van Susteren Abruptly Leaves Fox News|author=News Hound Ellen|date=September 7, 2016|work=[[Crooks and Liars]]|accessdate=November 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119055501/http://crooksandliars.com/2016/09/greta-van-susteren-abruptly-leaves-fox|archive-date=November 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The show debuted as \"the network's most watched telecast of the year in the time slot\".<ref name=\"DarcyBusinessInsider\">{{cite news |first=Oliver |last=Darcy |title=Tucker Carlson's Fox News show debuts to phenomenal ratings, beats both CNN and MSNBC combined |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-fox-news-show-ratings-2016-11 |website=[[Business Insider]] |accessdate=December 22, 2016 |date=November 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223063726/http://www.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-fox-news-show-ratings-2016-11 |archive-date=December 23, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The program's premiere episode, viewed by 3.7{{nbsp}}million,<ref name=\"DarcyBusinessInsider\" /> was rated higher than previous editions of ''On the Record''.\n\n''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' aired at 7{{nbsp}}p.m. ET each weeknight until January 9, 2017, when Carlson's show replaced [[Megyn Kelly]] at the 9{{nbsp}}p.m. ET time slot after she left Fox News. In January 2017, ''[[Forbes]]'' reported that the show had \"scored consistently high ratings, averaging 2.8{{nbsp}}million viewers per night and ranking as the number two cable news program behind The O'Reilly Factor in December [2016].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maddieberg/2017/01/05/tucker-carlson-to-replace-megyn-kelly-at-fox-news-keeping-the-network-conservative/#7c745789672e|title='Right' Move For Fox News As Tucker Carlson To Replace Megyn Kelly in Prime Time|last=Berg|first=Madeline|date=January 5, 2017|access-date=October 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014165941/https://www.forbes.com/sites/maddieberg/2017/01/05/tucker-carlson-to-replace-megyn-kelly-at-fox-news-keeping-the-network-conservative/#7c745789672e|archive-date=October 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2017, ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' was the most watched cable program in the 9{{nbsp}}p.m. time slot.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nOn April 19, 2017, it was announced that ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' would air at 8{{nbsp}}p.m. following the cancellation of ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fox-news-tucker-carlson-bill-oreilly-1202313557/|title=Fox News Will Replace Bill O'Reilly With Tucker Carlson|first=Brian|last=Steinberg|date=April 19, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=December 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201094626/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fox-news-tucker-carlson-bill-oreilly-1202313557/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' was the third-highest-rated cable news show as of March 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/385492-carlsons-ratings-on-fox-closing-in-on-oreillys|title=Carlson's ratings on Fox closing in on O'Reilly's|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|last=Concha|first=Joe|date=April 30, 2018|access-date=September 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913040121/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/385492-carlsons-ratings-on-fox-closing-in-on-oreillys|archive-date=September 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' was the second-highest rated cable news show in prime time, after ''The Sean Hannity Show'' with [[Sean Hannity]], with 3.2{{nbsp}}million nightly viewers.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=October 31, 2018 |first=Joe |last=Concha |title=Fox News tops CNN and MSNBC combined in October cable news ratings |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/414005-fox-news-tops-cnn-and-msnbc-combined-in-october-cable-news-ratings |access-date=November 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122172137/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/414005-fox-news-tops-cnn-and-msnbc-combined-in-october-cable-news-ratings |archive-date=November 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> By the end of 2018, the show had begun to be boycotted by at least 20 advertisers after Carlson said U.S. immigration makes the country \"poorer, dirtier and more divided\". According to Fox News, the advertisers only moved their ad buys to other programs.<ref name=Katz-181220>{{cite news | url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/20-plus-brands-have-stopped-advertising-on-tucker-carlson-tonight-after-immigration-comments/ | title=20-Plus Brands Have Stopped Advertising on Tucker Carlson Tonight After Immigration Comments | work=[[Adweek]] | date=December 20, 2018 | accessdate=March 24, 2019 | last=Katz | first=A.J. | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324123518/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/20-plus-brands-have-stopped-advertising-on-tucker-carlson-tonight-after-immigration-comments/ | archive-date=March 24, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy January 2019, his show dropped to third with 2.8 million nightly viewers, down six percent from the previous year.<ref name=Katz-190324>{{cite news | url=https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/the-top-cable-news-programs-of-january-2019-were/392622 | title=RATINGS The Top Cable News Programs of January 2019 Were{{nbsp}}... | work=[[Adweek]] | date=March 24, 2019 | accessdate=March 24, 2019 | first=A.J. | last=Katz | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324123139/https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/the-top-cable-news-programs-of-january-2019-were/392622 | archive-date=March 24, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The show had lost at least 26 advertisers.<ref name=Brunley>{{cite news | url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a26911984/tucker-carlson-fox-news-advertiser-boycott/ | title=If Tucker Carlson Keeps Hemorrhaging Advertisers He Might Soon Be Down to Just 'My Pillow' | work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] | date=March 22, 2019 | accessdate=March 24, 2019 | first=Gabrielle | last=Brunley | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324061142/https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a26911984/tucker-carlson-fox-news-advertiser-boycott/ | archive-date=March 24, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Barr-190322>{{cite news | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/major-sponsors-tucker-carlsons-show-leans-fox-news-house-ads-1196257 | title=Without Major Sponsors, Tucker Carlson's Show Leans on Ads for Fox Programming | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=March 22, 2019 | accessdate=March 24, 2019 | first=Jeremy | last=Barr | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324003930/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/major-sponsors-tucker-carlsons-show-leans-fox-news-house-ads-1196257 | archive-date=March 24, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> There were calls to fire Carlson from Fox News, but his ratings had risen 8 percent despite the boycotts.<ref name=\"Tucker Carlson\u2019s Weekly TV Ratings Rise Despite Boycotts\">{{cite web |last1=Tony |first1=Maglio |title=Tucker Carlson\u2019s Weekly TV Ratings Rise Despite Boycotts |url=https://www.thewrap.com/tucker-carlson-ratings-rise-despite-boycotts/ |website=The Wrap |publisher=The Wrap |accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> By August 2019, [[Media Matters]] calculated that some companies had fulfilled their media buy contracts and advertising inventory for the time slot and had now begun their purchases for other time slots on Fox News.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/tucker-carlson/tucker-carlson-returns-fox-news-advertisers-are-staying-away|title=Tucker Carlson returns to Fox News -- but advertisers are staying away|first=Jordan|last=Uhl|website=Media Matters for America|access-date=August 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820185209/https://www.mediamatters.org/tucker-carlson/tucker-carlson-returns-fox-news-advertisers-are-staying-away|archive-date=August 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/tucker-carlson/tucker-carlson-tonight-loses-advertisers-after-remarks-about-hoax-white-supremacy|title=Tucker Carlson Tonight loses advertisers after remarks about \"hoax\" of white supremacy|first=Jordan|last=Uhl|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref>\n\nAs of the close of 2019, Fox News had it highest ratings in the company's 23-year history, its ratings up 2 percent from 2018 while other competing networks were down 2 percent ([[CNN]] and [[MSNBC]]). According to [[Nielsen Ratings]], Carlson's ratings among all viewers 25-54 placed him second overall only to Fox's ''The Sean Hannity Show.'' [[Rachael Maddow]] of ''The Rachael Maddow Show'' on [[MSNBC]] placed third, and another Fox News journalist, [[Laura Ingraham]] of ''The Laura Ingraham Show'' placed fourth.  Ratings for all three of the networks were down compared to 2018, with Fox News showing the least of the decline at 16 percent, MSNBC down 20 percent and CNN down 21 percent overall.<ref name=\"Fox News Ends 2019 With Biggest Prime Time Ratings Ever\" group=\"\">{{cite web |last1=Joyellaq |first1=Mark |title=Fox News Ends 2019 with Highest Rated Prime Time Ratings Ever |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markjoyella/2019/12/11/fox-news-ends-2019-with-highest-rated-prime-time-ratings-ever/#31cb86923347 |website=Forbes.com |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''The Daily Caller'' (2010\u2013present)===\n{{Main|The Daily Caller}}\n\nOn January 11, 2010, Carlson and former vice president [[Dick Cheney]] aide [[Neil Patel (political advisor)|Neil Patel]] launched a political news website titled ''[[The Daily Caller]]''. Carlson served as editor-in-chief, and occasionally wrote opinion pieces with Patel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://dailycaller.com/author/carlsonandpatel/|title=Tucker Carlson and Neil Patel Author Page|work=[[The Daily Caller]]|accessdate=March 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107030311/http://dailycaller.com/author/carlsonandpatel/|archive-date=January 7, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The website was funded by the conservative activist [[Foster Friess|Foster Freiss]].<ref name=\":102\"/> By February ''The Daily Caller'' was part of the White House rotating press pool.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/michaelcalderone/0210/Daily_Caller_joins_WH_pool.html|title=Daily Caller joins W.H. pool|last=Calderone|first=Michael|date=February 1, 2010|work=[[Politico]]|accessdate=July 8, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620011410/http://www.politico.com/blogs/michaelcalderone/0210/Daily_Caller_joins_WH_pool.html|archive-date=June 20, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Politico]]'', Carlson said ''The Daily Caller'' would not be tied to ideology but rather will be \"breaking stories of importance\". In a ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' article, Carlson added, \"We're not enforcing any kind of ideological orthodoxy on anyone.\" Columnist [[Mickey Kaus]] quit after Carlson refused to run a column critical of [[Fox News]]'s coverage of the immigration policy debate due to his contractual obligations to Fox News.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2015/03/mickey-kaus-quits-daily-caller-after-tucker-carlson-204135.html|title=Mickey Kaus quits Daily Caller after Tucker Carlson pulls critical Fox News column|last1=Byers|first1=Dylan|date=March 17, 2015|work=[[Politico]]|access-date=April 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401091337/http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2015/03/mickey-kaus-quits-daily-caller-after-tucker-carlson-204135.html|archive-date=April 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/03/18/daily-callers-tucker-carlson-takes-a-stand-for-censorship/|title=Daily Caller's Tucker Carlson takes a stand for censorship|last1=Wemple|first1=Erik|date=March 18, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=September 17, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812141953/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/03/18/daily-callers-tucker-carlson-takes-a-stand-for-censorship/|archive-date=August 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":102\"/>\n\n===''Dancing with the Stars''===\nCarlson was a contestant on [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 3)|season 3]] of the [[reality show]] ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', which aired in 2006; he was paired with professional dancer [[Elena Grinenko]]. Carlson took four-hour-a-day [[ballroom dance]] classes in preparation for the competition. In an interview a month before the show began, he lamented that he would miss classes during a two-week-long MSNBC assignment in Lebanon, noting that \"It's hard for me to remember the moves.\"<ref name=\"AR2006081401091.html\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/14/AR2006081401091.html|title=Names & Faces|date=August 15, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2009|work=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107134310/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/14/AR2006081401091.html|archive-date=November 7, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Carlson said he accepted ABC's invitation to perform because \"I don't do things that I'm not good at very often. I'm psyched to get to do that.\"<ref name=\"AR2006081401091.html\" /> Carlson was the first contestant eliminated, on September 13, 2006.<ref name=\":102\"/>\n\n==Writings==\nIn 2003, Carlson authored the memoir ''Politicians, Partisans and Parasites: My Adventures in Cable News'', about his television news experiences; the publisher was [[Warner Books]].<ref name=adventures>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonian.com/bookreviews/currentaffairs/politicians-partisans-and-parasites-my-adventures-in-cable-news.php|title=Politicians, Partisans, and Parasites: My Adventures in Cable News|work=[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]]|access-date=April 2, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120064449/http://www.washingtonian.com/bookreviews/currentaffairs/politicians-partisans-and-parasites-my-adventures-in-cable-news.php|archive-date=November 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the book's revelations was Carlson's description of being falsely accused of [[rape]] by a woman he did not know who suffered from severe [[mental illness]] and displayed [[stalking|stalker]]-like behavior. Carlson wrote in the book that the incident was emotionally [[Psychological trauma|traumatic]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Politicians, Partisans, and Parasites: My Adventures in Cable News|last=Carlson|first=Tucker|date=2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3JoFL9epFbcC&pg=PT103&dq=Tucker+Carlson+rape&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2M47U_maMYjSsAT6uIGADg&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Tucker%20Carlson%20rape&f=false|access-date=October 13, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704044010/http://books.google.com/books?id=3JoFL9epFbcC&pg=PT103&dq=Tucker+Carlson+rape&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2M47U_maMYjSsAT6uIGADg&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Tucker%20Carlson%20rape&f=false|archive-date=July 4, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, ''The Daily Caller'' published an \"investigative series\" of articles co-authored by Carlson, purporting to be an insiders' expos\u00e9 of [[Media Matters for America]] (MMfA), a liberal watchdog group that monitors and scrutinizes conservative media outlets, and its founder [[David Brock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailycaller.com/2012/02/12/inside-media-matters-sources-memos-reveal-erratic-behavior-close-coordination-with-white-house-and-news-organizations/|title=Inside Media Matters: Sources, memos reveal erratic behavior, close coordination with White House and news organizations|website=Inside Media Matters: Sources, memos reveal erratic behavior, close coordination with White House and news organizations|access-date=August 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621140251/https://dailycaller.com/2012/02/12/inside-media-matters-sources-memos-reveal-erratic-behavior-close-coordination-with-white-house-and-news-organizations/|archive-date=June 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Citing \"current and former\" MMfA employees, \"friends\" of Brock's and a \"prominent liberal\" \u2014 none of whom are named \u2014 the article characterized MMfA as having \"an atmosphere of tension and paranoia\" and portraying Brock as \"erratic, unstable and disturbing,\" who \"struggles with mental illness,\" in fear of \"right-wing assassins,\" a regular cocaine user and would \"close [local bars] and party till six in the morning.\" [[Reuters]] media critic and libertarian [[Jack Shafer]], while noting \"I've never thought much of Media Matters' style of watchdogging or Brock's journalism,\" nevertheless sharply criticized ''The Daily Caller'' piece as \"anonymously sourced crap,\" adding \"''Daily Caller'' is attacking Media Matters with bad journalism and lame propaganda.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/jackshafer/2012/02/15/media-madders/|title=Media Madders|first=Jack|last=Shafer|date=February 15, 2012|access-date=August 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727212205/http://blogs.reuters.com/jackshafer/2012/02/15/media-madders/|archive-date=July 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Carlson, represented by the literary and creative agency [[Javelin (company)|Javelin]], signed an eight-figure, two-book deal with [[Simon & Schuster]]'s [[Threshold Editions]].<ref>{{cite news |date=May 2, 2017 |title=Tucker Carlson Gets Two-Book, Eight-Figure Deal |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/bookmark/tucker-carlson-gets-two-book-eight-figure-deal-999704 |agency=AP |access-date=August 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811012346/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/bookmark/tucker-carlson-gets-two-book-eight-figure-deal-999704 |archive-date=August 11, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> His first book in the series, ''[[Ship of Fools (book)|Ship of Fools: How a Selfish Ruling Class is Bringing America to the Brink of Revolution]]'', was released in October 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fox News star Tucker Carlson exposes 'elites' in new book |url=https://www.naplesnews.com/story/entertainment/books/2018/10/02/when-tucker-carlson-book-signing-naples-ship-fools/1454117002/ |first=Dave |last=Osborn |date=October 2, 2018 |work=[[Naples Daily News]] |access-date=January 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121014016/https://www.naplesnews.com/story/entertainment/books/2018/10/02/when-tucker-carlson-book-signing-naples-ship-fools/1454117002/ |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It debuted at No.{{nbsp}}1 on [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tucker Carlson's new book topples Woodward from No.{{nbsp}}1 on New York Times best-seller list |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/410912-tucker-carlsons-new-book-topples-woodward-from-1-on-new-york-times-bestseller |first=Joe |last=Concha |date=October 11, 2018 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=October 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016032645/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/410912-tucker-carlsons-new-book-topples-woodward-from-1-on-new-york-times-bestseller |archive-date=October 16, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nCarlson is generally described as a [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/06/business/media/cnn-will-cancel-crossfire-and-cut-ties-to-commentator.html|title=CNN Will Cancel 'Crossfire' and Cut Ties to Commentator|last=Carter|first=Bill|date=January 6, 2005|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808071252/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/06/business/media/cnn-will-cancel-crossfire-and-cut-ties-to-commentator.html|archive-date=2017-08-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/19/business/media/life-after-bill-oreilly-for-fox-news-to-include-tucker-carlson.html|title=For Fox News, Life After Bill O'Reilly Will Feature Tucker Carlson|last=Grynbaum|first=Michael M.|date=April 19, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 22, 2017|last2=Koblin|first2=John|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504235538/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/19/business/media/life-after-bill-oreilly-for-fox-news-to-include-tucker-carlson.html|archive-date=2017-05-04|url-status=live}}</ref> or [[paleoconservatism|paleoconservative]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Raimondo |first=Justin |url=https://isi.org/modern-age/tucker-carlson-a-buckley-for-our-time/ |title=Tucker Carlson: A Buckley for Our Time? - Intercollegiate Studies Institute: Think. Live Free |publisher=Isi.org |date=2019-01-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2019/06/19/president-trump-got-talked-out-of-war-with-iran-by-fox-news-host-tucker-carlson_partner/ |title=President Trump got talked out of war with Iran by Fox News host Tucker Carlson: report |publisher=Salon.com |date=2019-06-19 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Writing for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'''s Intelligencer, Park MacDougald called Carlson a \"Middle American radical\", which he described as someone who holds [[populist]] economic beliefs, hostililty to [[corporatocracy]], fervent positions on nationalism, race and immigration, and a preference for [[Strongman (politics)|strongmen]] in political authority. MacDouglad identified this form of radicalism as the ideological core of \"[[Political positions of Donald Trump|Trumpism]].\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Park MacDougald|title=Is Tucker Carlson the Most Important Pundit in America?|publisher=New York Magazine|url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/is-tucker-carlson-the-most-important-pundit-in-america.html|date=17 Sep 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Economics===\n[[File:TuckerRonPaul.jpg|thumb|2007 [[Ron Paul]] event]]\nEarly in his career, Carlson espoused a [[libertarian]] view of economics. He supported [[Ron Paul|Ron Paul's]] 1988 presidential candidacy, when Paul ran the candidate for the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]], along with [[Ron Paul 2008 presidential campaign|Paul's 2008 presidential candidacy]], when Paul ran as a Republican.<ref name=Paul88>{{cite news|author=Associated Press|title=Tucker Carlson thinks libertarians run the economy. That's news to Ron Paul|publisher=Washington Examiner|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/tucker-carlson-thinks-libertarians-run-the-economy-thats-news-to-ron-paul|date=7 Jun 2019}}</ref><ref name=Paul08>{{cite news|author=Associated Press|title=Ron Paul Endorsed by Nevada Brothel Owner|publisher=NBC News|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21973236/ns/politics-decision_08/t/ron-paul-endorsed-nevada-brothel-owner/#.XXOveC2ZPUI|date=26 Nov 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Carlson became a senior fellow at libertarian think tank, the [[Cato Institute]].<ref name=Cato>{{cite web|title=Tucker Carlson Joins the Cato Institute|url=https://www.cato.org/news-releases/2009/2/23/tucker-carlson-joins-cato-institute|publisher=Cato Institute|date=23 Feb 2009}}</ref> As of 2017, he is no longer affiliated with the organization.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tucker Carlson- Former Senior Fellow |url=https://www.cato.org/people/tucker-carlson |publisher=Cato Institute}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Carlson began to promote a more [[economic populism|populist]] view of economics,<ref name=Mystery>{{cite web|author=Lyz Lenz|title=The mystery of Tucker Carlson|url=https://www.cjr.org/the_profile/tucker-carlson.php|publisher=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|date=5 Sep 2018}}</ref> attacking libertarianism and saying \"market capitalism is not a religion.\"<ref name=Debate>{{cite web|author=Coaston|title=Tucker Carlson has sparked the most interesting debate in conservative politics|url=https://www.vox.com/2019/1/10/18171912/tucker-carlson-fox-news-populism-conservatism-trump-gop|publisher=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|date=10 Jan 2019}}</ref>\nIn an interview, he warned that economic and technological change that occurs too quickly can cause widespread social and political upheaval, and stated his belief that a model to follow is that of President [[Political positions of Theodore Roosevelt|Theodore Roosevelt]], whose interventionist role in the economy in the early 1900s may have, in Carlson's view, prevented a [[communist revolution]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bh8vqof9hAk&t=1966s|title=Sunday Special Ep 26: Tucker Carlson|work=[[The Ben Shapiro Show]]|publisher=[[The Daily Wire]]|via=YouTube|date=November 4, 2018|access-date=November 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129200743/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bh8vqof9hAk&t=1966s|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, in his monologue on ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'', Carlson said America's \"ruling class\" are, in effect, the \"mercenaries\" behind the decline of the American middle class:\n\n{{Quote|\"[A]ny economic system that weakens and destroys families is not worth having. A system like that is the enemy of a healthy society\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilcox|first1=W. Bradford|last2=Hammond|first2=Samuel|date=January 9, 2019|title=What Tucker Carlson Gets Right|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/01/tucker-carlson-was-right-about-working-class-family/579754/|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113054611/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/01/tucker-carlson-was-right-about-working-class-family/579754/|archive-date=2019-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\nHe also criticized what he called the \"[[private equity]] model\" of capitalism, using the example of [[Bain Capital]] to describe a pattern of corporate behavior in such organizations:\n\n{{Quote|\"Take over an existing company for a short period of time, cut costs by firing employees, run up the debt, extract the wealth and move on, sometimes leaving retirees without their earned pensions{{nbsp}}... Meanwhile, a remarkable number of the companies are now bankrupt or extinct.\"<ref name=romney />}}\n\nHe attacked [[payday lender]]s for \"loan[ing] people money they can't possibly repay{{nbsp}}... [and] charg[ing] them interest that impoverishes them.\"<ref name=romney />\n\nCarlson has also praised Democratic presidential candidate [[Elizabeth Warren]]'s economic plan, and her book, ''[[The Two-Income Trap|The Two Income Trap]]'', as \"one of the best books I've ever read on Economics.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://politi.co/2IjrbC6|title=Fox News host says Warren 'sounds like Donald Trump at his best'|first=Matthew|last=Choi|website=POLITICO}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AXGoWtK1NnY&t=2428|title=Tucker Carlson at National Conservatism Conference: Big Business Hates Your Family|work=National Conservatism Conference|via=YouTube|date=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Environment===\nCarlson has argued that the extent to which humans contribute to [[climate change]] is \"an open question\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/682862/fox-news-tucker-carlson-bill-nye-got-into-heated-debate-about-humans-contribution-climate-change|title=Fox News' Tucker Carlson and Bill Nye got into a heated debate about humans' contribution to climate change|date=2017-02-28|website=theweek.com|author1=Stanek, Becca |accessdate=2019-04-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402144833/https://theweek.com/speedreads/682862/fox-news-tucker-carlson-bill-nye-got-into-heated-debate-about-humans-contribution-climate-change|archivedate=April 2, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"not settled\"<ref name=\"vs_Bill_Nye\">{{cite news |last1=Matyszczyk |first1=Chris |title=Bill Nye appears on Fox News and it doesn't go well |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/bill-nye-tucker-carlson-fox-news-climate-change/ |work=CNet |date=28 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realclearenergy.org/video/2017/02/28/tucker_vs_bill_nye_the_science_guy.html|title=Tucker vs. Bill Nye the Science Guy {{!}} Video {{!}} RealClearEnergy|last=|date=February 28, 2017|first2= |website=www.realclearenergy.org|accessdate=2019-06-07|last3=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607143537/https://www.realclearenergy.org/video/2017/02/28/tucker_vs_bill_nye_the_science_guy.html|archivedate=June 7, 2019|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and \"unknowable.\"<ref name=\":63\">{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/142260/bill-nye-not-right-guy-lead-climate-fight|title=Bill Nye Is Not the Right Guy to Lead the Climate Fight|last=Atkin|first=Emily|date=2017-04-27|work=The New Republic|access-date=2019-04-02|issn=0028-6583|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713052902/https://newrepublic.com/article/142260/bill-nye-not-right-guy-lead-climate-fight|archive-date=July 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn his show, Carlson frequently hosts guests who downplay the [[scientific consensus on climate change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/fox-news-republican-viewers-reject-climate-change-science-2019-3|title=Only 12% of Republican Fox News viewers believe climate change is man-made|last=Shamsian |first=Jacob|website=Business Insider|date=March 22, 2019|accessdate=2019-06-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607143538/https://www.businessinsider.com/fox-news-republican-viewers-reject-climate-change-science-2019-3|archivedate=June 7, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Views on Republicans and Democrats===\n[[File:Tucker Carlson &amp; Charlie Kirk (32618423398).jpg|thumb|Carlson & [[Turning Point USA|Charlie Kirk]], 2018]]\nCarlson did not vote in the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 election]], citing his disgust with the [[Iraq War]], his disillusionment with the once [[small government|small-government]] [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and his disappointment with President [[George W. Bush]] along with likeminded conservatives:<ref name=\"A39712-2004Aug27.html\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A39712-2004Aug27.html |title=Republican Convention: Tucker Carlson |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=August 30, 2004 |accessdate=August 5, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104110031/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A39712-2004Aug27.html |archive-date=2012-11-04 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"I don't know what you consider conservative, but I'm not much of a '[[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]],' at least as the word is currently defined. For instance, I'm utterly opposed to [[abortion]], which I think is horrible and cruel. I think [[affirmative action]] is wrong. I'd like to slow [[Immigration to the United States|immigration]] pretty dramatically. I hate all [[nanny-state]] regulations, such as seat belt laws and smoking bans. I'm not for [[big government]]. I think the U.S. ought to hesitate before intervening abroad. I think these are conservative impulses. So by my criteria, Bush isn't much of a conservative.<ref name=\"A39712-2004Aug27.html\"/></blockquote>\n\nIn 2003, speaking about [[John McCain]] and his failed 2000 presidential bid, Carlson stated:\n\n{{Quote|\"I liked McCain. And I would have voted for McCain for president happily, not because I agree with his politics; I never took McCain's politics seriously enough even to have strong feelings about them. I don't think McCain has very strong politics. He's interested in ideas almost as little as George W. Bush is. McCain isn't intellectual and doesn't have a strong ideology at all. He's wound up sort of as a liberal Republican because he's mad at other Republicans, not because he's a liberal.\"<ref name=\"salon 20030913\">{{cite news |last=Lauerman |first=Kerry |url=http://dir.salon.com/story/books/feature/2003/09/13/carlson/index.html |title=\"You burn out fast when you demagogue\" |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=September 13, 2003 |accessdate=August 5, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090512193301/http://dir.salon.com/story/books/feature/2003/09/13/carlson/index.html |archivedate=May 12, 2009}}</ref>}}}}\n\nIn January 2019, Carlson used an [[op-ed]] by [[Mitt Romney]], in ''The Washington Post'', to criticize what he described as the \"mainstream Republican\" worldview, consisting of \"unwavering support for a finance-based economy and an internationalist foreign policy,\" which he argued was also supported by the bulk of Democrats.<ref name=romney>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/tucker-carlson-mitt-romney-supports-the-status-quo-but-for-everyone-else-its-infuriating |title=Tucker Carlson: Mitt Romney supports the status quo. But for everyone else, it's infuriating |last=Carlson |first=Tucker |date=3 January 2019 |website=[[FOXNews.com]] |access-date=27 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127001302/https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/tucker-carlson-mitt-romney-supports-the-status-quo-but-for-everyone-else-its-infuriating |archive-date=2019-01-27 |url-status=live }}</ref> He cited parallels, in regard to economic and social problems which had befallen inner cities and rural areas, despite cultural and demographic differences between their respective populations, as evidence that the \"[[culture of poverty]]\", which had been cited by conservatives as the cause of [[Urban decay|urban decline]], \"wasn't the whole story\":\n\n{{Quote|\"[Both parties] miss the obvious point: Culture and economics are inseparably intertwined. Certain economic systems allow families to thrive. Thriving families make market economies possible.\"<ref name=romney/>}}\n\nCarlson is a registered member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] in Washington D.C.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/04/10/tucker-carlson-registered-democrat/|title=Tucker Carlson, registered Democrat|last=Wemple|first=Eric|date=April 10, 2015|accessdate=December 6, 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064324/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/04/10/tucker-carlson-registered-democrat/|archive-date=2019-01-21|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, Carlson said he registered for the Democratic Party to gain the right to vote in mayoral elections in the district and that he \"always votes for the more corrupt candidate over the idealist.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-fox-news-democrat-ignition-mayor-most-corrupt-candidate-2017-12|title=Fox News' Tucker Carlson \u2013 a registered Democrat \u2013 explains why he always votes for the most corrupt mayoral candidate|date=December 1, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2018|last=Lee|first=Nathaniel|work=[[Business Insider]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630031421/http://uk.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-fox-news-democrat-ignition-mayor-most-corrupt-candidate-2017-12|archive-date=2018-06-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Robert Mueller===\nIn May 2019, after [[Robert Mueller]] gave a statement saying the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel investigation on Russian interference]] in the 2016 election did not exonerate Trump of obstruction of justice, Carlson said Mueller was \"sleazy and dishonest.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/fox-news-mueller-hannity-carlson-ingraham_n_5cef781ce4b0888f89d0e91d|title=Fox News Hosts Freak Out Over 'Mean Girl' Robert Mueller: 'Full Of Crap'|last=Moran|first=Lee|date=2019-05-30|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605233826/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/fox-news-mueller-hannity-carlson-ingraham_n_5cef781ce4b0888f89d0e91d|archive-date=June 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\n[[File:Tucker Carlson (46491104471).jpg|thumb|[[Turning Point USA|Student Action Summit]], 2018]]\nCarlson is skeptical of foreign intervention, and has stated that he thinks \"the U.S. ought to hesitate before intervening abroad.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nationalinterest.org/feature/tucker-carlson-goes-war-against-the-neocons-21545?page=show|title=Tucker Carlson Goes to War Against the Neocons|first=Curt|last=Mills|work=[[The National Interest]]|access-date=2019-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723111323/https://nationalinterest.org/feature/tucker-carlson-goes-war-against-the-neocons-21545?page=show|archive-date=2018-07-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenewamerican.com/usnews/item/25081-change-from-kelly-to-carlson-may-give-fox-viewers-a-new-perspective|title=Change from Kelly to Carlson May Give Fox Viewers a New Perspective|work=[[The New American]]|access-date=2019-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012122717/https://www.thenewamerican.com/usnews/item/25081-change-from-kelly-to-carlson-may-give-fox-viewers-a-new-perspective|archive-date=2018-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Iraq====\nCarlson initially supported the [[Iraq War]]. However, a year after the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]], he began criticizing the war, telling ''[[The New York Observer]]'':\n\n{{Quote|\"I think it's a total nightmare and disaster, and I'm ashamed that I went against my own instincts in supporting it.[...] It's something I'll never do again. Never. I got convinced by a friend of mine who's smarter than I am, and I shouldn't have done that. No. I want things to work out, but I'm enraged by it, actually.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Hagan|first=Joe|url=https://observer.com/2004/05/newly-dovish-tucker-carlson-goes-publickimmel-writer-ribs-times/|title=Newly Dovish, Tucker Carlson Goes Public\u2026Kimmel Writer Ribs Times|work=[[The New York Observer]] |date=May 17, 2004 |accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\nIn June 2019, Carlson remained critical of the war, stating:\n\n{{quote|\"We killed hundreds of thousands of people, lost thousands of our own troops, spent more than $1 trillion \u2014 all to eliminate a [[Iraq and weapons of mass destruction|WMD threat]] that, despite [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]]'s assurances, never existed in the first place.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Fox News' Tucker Carlson Advised Trump Not to Bomb Iran \u2014 Then Roasted John Bolton on Air |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/fox-news-tucker-carlson-reportedly-at-center-of-trump-s-decision-not-to-bomb-iran-1.7403783 |work=Haaretz |date=June 24, 2019 |access-date=June 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190625005733/https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/fox-news-tucker-carlson-reportedly-at-center-of-trump-s-decision-not-to-bomb-iran-1.7403783 |archive-date=June 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n\n====Iran====\nIn July 2017, Carlson said that \"[w]e actually don't face any domestic threat from [[Iran]].\" He asked [[Max Boot]] to \"tell me how many Americans in the United States have been murdered by terrorists backed by Iran since 9/11?\"<ref name=\":1\" /> According to ''The New York Times'', Carlson played an influential role in dissuading Trump from launching military strikes against Iran in response to the [[2019 Iranian shoot-down of American drone|shooting down of an American drone]] in June 2019. Carlson reportedly told Trump that if he listened to his hawkish advisors and went ahead with the strikes, he would not win re-election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/21/us/politics/trump-iran-strike.html|title=Urged to Launch an Attack, Trump Listened to the Skeptics Who Said It Would Be a Costly Mistake|last=Baker|first=Peter|date=2019-06-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-22|last2=Haberman|first2=Maggie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Gibbons-Neff|first3=Thomas|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622135242/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/21/us/politics/trump-iran-strike.html|archive-date=June 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCarlson referred to the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|2020 assassination]] of [[Qasem Soleimani]] as a \"quagmire.\" He criticized the \"chest-beaters\" who promote foreign interventions, particularly Senator [[Ben Sasse]] (R-NE), and asked, \"By the way, if we're still in Afghanistan, 19 years, sad years, later, what makes us think there's a quick way out of Iran?\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/04/media/fox-news-iran-soleimani/index.html |title=Fox's Tucker Carlson breaks with colleagues and criticizes Trump's strike on Iranian general |last=Stelter |first=Brian |date=4 January 2020 |publisher=CNN }}</ref>\n\n====Mexico====\nCarlson supported the proposed expansion of the [[Mexico\u2013United States barrier]] \u2013 citing the [[Israeli West Bank barrier]] as an example. Carlson argued: \"The estimated cost of a border wall is about $25 billion. That is estimated so let's say it is twice that. That is still a tiny fraction of the price of the pointless stalemate we're now waging in Afghanistan. That costs about $45 billion every year, not including the human cost. Compare that to $25 billion needed to restore sovereignty with the wall.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Fox's Tucker Carlson: Why Is Congress Paying for Walls in Israel, but Not the U.S. |url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/fox-s-tucker-carlson-why-is-congress-paying-for-walls-in-israel-but-no-the-u-s-1.6761078 |work=Haaretz |date=December 18, 2018 |access-date=June 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190317143226/https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/fox-s-tucker-carlson-why-is-congress-paying-for-walls-in-israel-but-no-the-u-s-1.6761078 |archive-date=March 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a July 2018 interview about Russian involvement in U.S. elections, Carlson said [[Mexico]] has interfered in U.S. elections \"more successfully\" than Russia by \"packing our electorate\" through [[Immigration to the United States|mass immigration]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/397329-tucker-carlson-mexico-has-interfered-in-us-elections-more-successfully-than|title=Tucker Carlson: Mexico has interfered in US elections 'more successfully' than Russia|last=Greenwood|first=Max|date=July 16, 2018|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|access-date=October 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008214131/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/397329-tucker-carlson-mexico-has-interfered-in-us-elections-more-successfully-than|archive-date=2018-10-08|url-status=live}}</ref> This assertion was disputed by journalist Philip Bump, who wrote that the number of Mexicans in the U.S. had decreased since 2009 and asked rhetorically: \"What good has it done Mexico to have a number of its citizens move to the United States and gain the right to vote?\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2018/07/17/tucker-carlson-identifies-the-actual-threat-to-american-democracy-hispanic-voters/|title=Analysis {{!}} Tucker Carlson identifies the actual threat to American democracy: Hispanic voters|website=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=October 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008214110/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2018/07/17/tucker-carlson-identifies-the-actual-threat-to-american-democracy-hispanic-voters/|archive-date=2018-10-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Carlson defended Trump's decision to place tariffs on Mexico unless Mexico stopped illegal immigration to the United States. Carlson said, \"When the United States is attacked by a hostile foreign power it must strike back, and make no mistake Mexico is a hostile foreign power.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlson-america-must-strike-back-against-mexico|title=Tucker Carlson: America 'Must Strike Back' Against Mexico|last=Messer|first=Olivia|date=2019-06-01|website=The Daily Beast|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602054123/https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlson-america-must-strike-back-against-mexico|archive-date=June 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Russia====\nCarlson has said he does not consider [[Russia]] a serious threat.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/07/tucker-carlson-is-doing-something-extraordinary/533586/|title=Tucker Carlson Is Doing Something Extraordinary|last=Beinart|first=Peter|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=July 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715055655/https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/07/tucker-carlson-is-doing-something-extraordinary/533586/|archive-date=2017-07-15|url-status=live}}</ref> Carlson has called for the United States to work with Russia in the [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War]] against a common enemy like the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIS).<ref>{{cite news |title=Tucker Carlson interview goes sideways when guest accuses him of defending Putin |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-putin-hitler-ralph-peters-interview-fox-news-2017-7 |work=Business Insider |date=July 12, 2017 |access-date=June 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125171406/https://www.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-putin-hitler-ralph-peters-interview-fox-news-2017-7 |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/democracy-post/wp/2017/07/12/why-two-talking-heads-on-fox-news-just-rehashed-the-debates-of-1938/|title=Why two talking heads on Fox News just rehashed the debates of 1938|last=Heilbrunn|first=Jacob|date=July 12, 2017|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=July 22, 2017|last2=Heilbrunn|first2=Jacob|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717212044/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/democracy-post/wp/2017/07/12/why-two-talking-heads-on-fox-news-just-rehashed-the-debates-of-1938/|archive-date=2017-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Peter Beinart]] of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' said Carlson has been an \"apologist for [[Donald Trump]] on the [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russia scandal]]\".<ref name=\":1\" /> Carlson described the controversy in the wake of revelations that [[Donald Trump Jr.]] was [[Trump Tower meeting|willing to accept]] anti-Clinton information from a Russian government official as a \"new level of hysteria\" and said that Trump Jr. had only been \"gossiping with foreigners\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAt the beginning of December 2019, Carlson stated \"the irony, of course, is that Putin, for all his faults, does not hate America as much as many of these people do\" meaning liberals. \"They really dislike our country. And they call other people traitors, because they\u2019re mouthing the talking points of Putin.\" He was criticized by [[Michael McFaul]] former US ambassador during the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]], \"You are wrong Mr. Carlson. Putin does hate America\" urging him to \"Stop attacking Americans & defending Putin.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Rozsa|first=Matthew|url=https://www.salon.com/2019/12/03/barack-obamas-ambassador-to-russia-calls-out-fox-news-host-tucker-carlson-for-defending-putin/|title=Barack Obama's ambassador to Russia calls out Fox News host Tucker Carlson for defending Putin|date=December 4, 2019|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pengelly|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/dec/03/tucker-carlson-putin-nbc-chuck-todd-msnbc|title=Fox News host Tucker Carlson: Putin does not hate America like liberals do|work=The Guardian|date=December 3, 2019|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Syria====\nCarlson opposes overthrowing Syrian President [[Bashar al-Assad]].<ref name=\":1\" /> In April 2018, Carlson questioned whether Assad was responsible for the [[Douma chemical attack]] that had occurred a few days earlier and killed dozens.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/syria/fox-news-host-u-s-bombing-syria-could-lead-to-genocide-of-christian-1.5990560|title=Fox News Host: We Tolerate Saudi Atrocities in Yemen, So Why Not Assad's in Syria?|date=April 11, 2018|work=[[Haaretz]]|access-date=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412130428/https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/syria/fox-news-host-u-s-bombing-syria-could-lead-to-genocide-of-christian-1.5990560|archive-date=April 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Jason|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/apr/13/syria-intervention-conservative-rightwing-opposition-trump|title=Why is the far right so against US intervention in Syria?|work=The Guardian|date=April 13, 2018|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref> In November 2019, Carlson repeated this claim and queried whether the attack had actually happened at all.<ref>{{cite news|last=Malaea|first=Marika|url=https://www.newsweek.com/tucker-carlson-claims-theres-no-evidence-assad-was-behind-deadly-chemical-attack-syria-that-it-1474278|title=Tucker Carlson Claims There's 'No Evidence' Assad Was Behind Deadly Chemical Attack in Syria or That it Even Happened|work=Newsweek|date=November 27, 2019|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCarlson suggested that a similar attack that occurred the year before (the [[Khan Shaykhun chemical attack]]), which was attributed to Assad's forces and which the [[OPCW-UN Joint Investigative Mechanism|OPCW JIM]] indicated was carried out with sarin that bore the regime's signature, was a [[False flag|false flag attack]] perpetrated to falsely implicate the Assad government. Carlson compared Assad's war crimes during the [[Syrian Civil War]] to [[Saudi Arabia]]'s [[Human rights violations during the Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|war crimes in Yemen]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n====North Korea====\nWhen [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] met [[Kim Jong-un|Supreme Leader Kim Jong-un]] at the Korean border in June 2019, Carlson told ''Fox & Friends'' said that although \"there's no defending the North Korean regime, it\u2019s the last real Stalinist regime in the world. It\u2019s a disgusting place obviously{{nbsp}}... you've got to be honest about what it means to lead a country, it means killing people.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Fox News' Tucker Carlson is right: Governments kill people |url=https://theweek.com/articles/850557/fox-news-tucker-carlson-right-governments-kill-people |work=The Week |date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Carlson went on to argue that although \"not on the scale that the North Koreans do, but a lot of countries commit atrocities, including a number that [the United States] are closely allied with.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/tucker-carlson-defends-trump-liking-kim-jong-un-north-korea-monstrous-lead-country-means-1446733|title=Tucker Carlson defends Trump for liking Kim Jong-un: North Korea is 'monstrous' but 'to lead a country' means 'killing people'|date=2019-06-30|website=[[Newsweek]]|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701021651/https://www.newsweek.com/tucker-carlson-defends-trump-liking-kim-jong-un-north-korea-monstrous-lead-country-means-1446733|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/tucker-carlson-north-korea-donald-trump-fox-kim-joing-un-kill-people-a8981621.html|title=Fox host Tucker Carlson defends North Korean regime: 'Leading a country means killing people'|last=Rahim|first=Zamira|work=[[The Independent]]|date=2019-06-30|access-date=2019-07-01|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701022134/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/tucker-carlson-north-korea-donald-trump-fox-kim-joing-un-kill-people-a8981621.html|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/30/tucker-carlson-defends-trumps-praise-kim-jong-un/1612478001/|title=Leading a country 'means killing people': Tucker Carlson defends Trump friendship with Kim Jong Un|last=Cummings|first=William|date=2019-06-30|website=[[USA Today]]|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701015702/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/30/tucker-carlson-defends-trumps-praise-kim-jong-un/1612478001/|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/850289/foxs-tucker-carlson-trumps-meeting-kim-end-what-matters-whats-good-united-states|title=Fox's Tucker Carlson on Trump's meeting with Kim: 'In the end, what matters is what's good for the United States'|date=2019-06-30|website=theweek.com|access-date=2019-06-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630181558/https://theweek.com/speedreads/850289/foxs-tucker-carlson-trumps-meeting-kim-end-what-matters-whats-good-united-states|archive-date=June 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====China====\nCarlson criticized [[LeBron James]] for speaking out against [[Daryl Morey]], who had tweeted in support of the [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tucker Carlson and Laura Ingraham blast LeBron James over support of China |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/tucker-carlson-and-laura-ingraham-blast-le-bron-james-over-support-of-china-061428613.html |work=Yahoo News |date=October 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dennis Rodman defends LeBron James and confuses Tucker Carlson |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/dennis-rodman-defends-lebron-james-051402747.html |work=Yahoo News |date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration and race===\n[[File:Tucker carlson cropped.jpg|thumb|Immigrants' Rights Rally in [[National Mall|Washington Mall]], 2006]]\nCarlson is a frequent critic of [[immigration]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/12/15/tucker-carlson-suggested-immigrants-make-us-dirtier-it-cost-fox-news-an-advertiser/|title=Tucker Carlson suggested immigrants make the U.S. 'dirtier' \u2013 and it cost Fox News an advertiser|date=2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228040820/https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/12/15/tucker-carlson-suggested-immigrants-make-us-dirtier-it-cost-fox-news-an-advertiser/|archive-date=2018-12-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Carlson has been accused by [[Erik Wemple]] of ''The Washington Post'' and by writers for ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' of demonizing immigrants, both legal and illegal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/videos/2017/7/21/16008190/strikethrough-white-supremacists-love-tucker-carlson|title=Why white supremacists love Tucker Carlson|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=July 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831094912/https://www.vox.com/videos/2017/7/21/16008190/strikethrough-white-supremacists-love-tucker-carlson|archive-date=2017-08-31|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/07/20/in-his-quest-to-demonize-immigrants-fox-newss-tucker-carlson-misses-a-good-story/ |title=In his quest to demonize immigrants, Fox News's Tucker Carlson misses a good story |last=Wemple |first=Erik |date=July 20, 2017 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=July 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720194837/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/07/20/in-his-quest-to-demonize-immigrants-fox-newss-tucker-carlson-misses-a-good-story/ |archive-date=2017-07-20 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/05/08/fox-newss-tucker-carlson-demagogued-a-rape-case-involving-immigrants-then-they-were-cleared/ |title=Fox News's Tucker Carlson demagogued a rape case involving immigrants. Then they were cleared. |last=Wemple |first=Erik |date=May 8, 2017 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=July 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829170124/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/05/08/fox-newss-tucker-carlson-demagogued-a-rape-case-involving-immigrants-then-they-were-cleared/ |archive-date=2017-08-29 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/3/21/17146866/tucker-carlson-demographics-immigration-fox-news|title=Watch: Tucker Carlson rails against America's demographic changes|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=March 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321175631/https://www.vox.com/2018/3/21/17146866/tucker-carlson-demographics-immigration-fox-news|archive-date=2018-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> He has opposed [[Demography of the United States|demographic changes]] in the United States, writing that the demographic change seen in [[Hazleton, Pennsylvania]], which saw Hispanics go from a small minority to a majority over a 15-year period, is \"more change than human beings are designed to digest\".<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2018, Carlson suggested that mass immigration makes the United States \"dirtier\", \"poorer\" and \"more divided\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/421474-pacific-life-pulls-advertisements-from-tucker-carlsons-show-after-he-says|title=Pacific Life pulls ads from Tucker Carlson's show after 'poorer and dirtier' immigration comment|last=Daugherty|first=Owen|date=2018-12-14|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|access-date=2018-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215015100/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/421474-pacific-life-pulls-advertisements-from-tucker-carlsons-show-after-he-says|archive-date=2018-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pacific-life-will-pause-ads-tucker-carlsons-show-reevaluate-fox-news-relationship-1169574|title=Pacific Life Insurance Will Pause Ads on Tucker Carlson's Fox News Show, \"Reevaluate\" Relationship|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=2018-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214231413/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pacific-life-will-pause-ads-tucker-carlsons-show-reevaluate-fox-news-relationship-1169574|archive-date=2018-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref> In response to criticism of this, he has said that \"we're not intimidated\" and \"we plan to try to say what's true until the last day. And the truth is, unregulated mass immigration has badly hurt this country's natural landscape\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/tucker-carlson-advertisers-depart-over-poorer-and-dirtier-immigration-comments/|title=Tucker Carlson's show loses advertisers over immigration comments|publisher=[[CBS News]]|access-date=2018-12-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219011018/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/tucker-carlson-advertisers-depart-over-poorer-and-dirtier-immigration-comments/|archive-date=2018-12-19|url-status=live}}</ref> Of illegal immigration, Carlson said in May 2019, \"The flood of illegal workers into the United States has damaged our communities, ruined our schools, burdened our healthcare system and fractured our national unity.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> In December 2019, he falsely claimed that immigrants were responsible for making the Potomac River \"dirtier and dirtier\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/punditfact/statements/2019/dec/18/tucker-carlson/carlson-falsely-claims-immigrants-are-dirtying-pot/|title=Tucker Carlson wrong about Potomac River litter|website=@politifact|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/dec/17/tucker-carlson-potomac-river-immigrants-litter-racist-remarks|title=Clean water group denounces Tucker Carlson's 'racist' litter comments|last=Pilkington|first=Ed|date=2019-12-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nHeidi Beirich of the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] said that \"Carlson probably has been the No.{{nbsp}}1 commentator mainstreaming bedrock principles of white nationalism in [the US],\" and accused him of promoting the [[white genocide conspiracy theory]], the idea that white people are under attack by minorities and immigrants.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.salon.com/2018/08/15/tucker-carlson-claims-theres-no-white-nationalism-his-shows-obsessive-racism-suggests-otherwise/ |title=Tucker Carlson claims there's no white nationalism. His show's obsessive racism suggests otherwise |date=August 15, 2018 |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |access-date=2019-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102011741/https://www.salon.com/2018/08/15/tucker-carlson-claims-theres-no-white-nationalism-his-shows-obsessive-racism-suggests-otherwise/ |archive-date=2019-01-02 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Anti-Defamation League]]'s Jessica Reaves has compared Carlson's defense of the [[nuclear family]] to white supremacist anti-immigrant rhetoric.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Weill |first1=Kelly |title=Tucker Carlson's Immigration Rants Sound a Lot Like White Nationalism, Experts Say |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlsons-immigration-rants-sound-a-lot-like-white-nationalism-experts-say |website=The Daily Beast |accessdate=March 14, 2019 |language=en |date=June 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330194238/https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlsons-immigration-rants-sound-a-lot-like-white-nationalism-experts-say |archive-date=March 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[CNN]], ''[[Business Insider]]'', ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'', and ''[[GQ]]'', Carlson's show has promoted and echoed white supremacist discourse.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/28/media/fox-news-laura-ingraham-tucker-carlson-white-nationalism/index.html|title=White anxiety finds a home at Fox News|last1=Kludt|first1=Tom|last2=Stelter|first2=Brian|publisher=[[CNN Business]]|access-date=September 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005200259/https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/28/media/fox-news-laura-ingraham-tucker-carlson-white-nationalism/index.html|archive-date=October 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/trump-promotes-white-supremacist-narrative-about-south-africa-2018-8 |title=White supremacists celebrate Trump's promotion of false narrative of white persecution in South Africa |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=August 23, 2018 |first=Eliza |last=Relman |access-date=September 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/story/tucker-carlson-white-nationalist-diversity-terrible|title=Tucker Carlson Proves He's Not a White Nationalist by Doubling Down on How Terrible Diversity Is|last=Darby|first=Luke|date=September 10, 2018|work=[[GQ]]|access-date=September 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929233216/https://www.gq.com/story/tucker-carlson-white-nationalist-diversity-terrible|archive-date=September 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/3/21/17146866/tucker-carlson-demographics-immigration-fox-news|title=Watch: Tucker Carlson rails against America's demographic changes|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=September 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321175631/https://www.vox.com/2018/3/21/17146866/tucker-carlson-demographics-immigration-fox-news|archive-date=March 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Neoconservative]] pundit [[Bill Kristol]] described the views Carlson expressed on his show as \"ethno-nationalism of some kind\";<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/24/bill-kristol-takes-on-fox-news-tucker-carlson.html|title=Bill Kristol hits Fox News, Tucker Carlson for 'dumbing down' coverage, pushing 'ethno-nationalism'|last=Harwood|first=John|date=January 25, 2018|publisher=[[CNBC]]|access-date=March 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319161614/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/24/bill-kristol-takes-on-fox-news-tucker-carlson.html|archive-date=March 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Carlson responded that Kristol had \"discredited himself years ago.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/tucker-fires-back-at-bill-kristol-former-intellectual-who-now-exists-primarily-on-twitter/|title=Tucker Fires Back at Bill Kristol: 'Former Intellectual Who Now Exists Primarily on Twitter'|publisher=[[Mediaite]]|access-date=March 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321063046/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/tucker-fires-back-at-bill-kristol-former-intellectual-who-now-exists-primarily-on-twitter/|archive-date=March 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Carlson has denied being a racist and has said he hates racism.<ref name=\":102\"/>\n\nIn call-in segments Carlson made from 2006 to 2008 on the radio show ''[[Bubba the Love Sponge]]'', Carlson said Iraq was not worth invading because it was a country made up of \"semiliterate primitive monkeys\" who \"don't use toilet paper or forks.\" He also criticized \"lunatic Muslims who are behaving like animals\", and said that any presidential candidate who vowed to \"kill as many of them as [they] can\" would be \"elected king\". Recordings of these segments were released online on March 2019 by the progressive Media Matters for America. ''[[The Washington Post]]'' labelled these comments racist.<ref name=\"WaPo recordings\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/03/12/new-tucker-carlson-audio-released-this-time-using-racist-homophobic-language/|title=Fox News host Tucker Carlson uses racist, homophobic language in second set of recordings|date=March 11, 2019|website=The Washington Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319225139/https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/03/12/new-tucker-carlson-audio-released-this-time-using-racist-homophobic-language/|archive-date=March 19, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> Carlson also made demeaning remarks towards women, argued against the 2007 conviction of [[Warren Jeffs]], and used homophobic slurs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/03/11/fox-tucker-carlson-bubba-love-sponge-comments-spark-uproar/3127666002/|title=Tucker Carlson refuses to apologize amid uproar over past comments on 'extremely primitive' women|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728053203/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/03/11/fox-tucker-carlson-bubba-love-sponge-comments-spark-uproar/3127666002/|archive-date=July 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"WaPo recordings\" /> Carlson declined to apologize for his comments.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/5549523/audio-tucker-carlson-racist-iraq/|title=Report Says Tucker Carlson Called Iraqis 'Primitive Monkeys'|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331141919/http://time.com/5549523/audio-tucker-carlson-racist-iraq/|archive-date=March 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen Mitt Romney condemned then-candidate Donald Trump after Trump evaded questions about [[David Duke]]'s support,<ref>{{cite news |title=Huckabee, Rep. King talk Trump's KKK controversy; Carson vows he's not dropping out of race |url=https://www.foxnews.com/transcript/huckabee-rep-king-talk-trumps-kkk-controversy-carson-vows-hes-not-dropping-out-of-race |work=Fox News |date=January 23, 2017 |access-date=June 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626101216/https://www.foxnews.com/transcript/huckabee-rep-king-talk-trumps-kkk-controversy-carson-vows-hes-not-dropping-out-of-race |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> saying it was a \"disqualifying and disgusting response [...],\" Carlson criticized Romney. Carlson said \"Obama could have written\" that.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://press.princeton.edu/titles/11084.html |title=Identity Crisis |first=John |last=Sides |first2=Michael |last2=Tesler |first3=Lynn |last3=Vavreck |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |page=88 |access-date=2018-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012182250/https://press.princeton.edu/titles/11084.html |archive-date=2018-10-12 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCarlson concluded his July 9, 2019 ''[[Tucker Carlson Tonight]]'' episode with a 3-minute monologue about Rep. [[Ilhan Omar]] (D-MN); he criticized Omar for being ungrateful to the United States, where she had been granted asylum, and called her \"living proof that the way we practice immigration has become dangerous to this country.\" His monologue was described by ''The Guardian'' as \"scathing\", \"racially loaded\", and \"full of anti-immigrant rhetoric\".<ref name=\"theguardian_20190710\">{{Cite news| issn = 0261-3077| last = Bryant| first = Miranda| title = Ilhan Omar calls Tucker Carlson a 'racist fool' after his scathing attack on air| work = The Guardian| access-date = July 10, 2019| date = July 10, 2019| url = https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jul/10/ilhan-omar-tucker-carlson-fox-news-host-racist-fool| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190710165113/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jul/10/ilhan-omar-tucker-carlson-fox-news-host-racist-fool| archive-date = July 10, 2019| url-status = live}}</ref> Congresswoman Omar responded on [[Twitter]], saying that \"advertisers should not be underwriting this kind of dangerous, hateful rhetoric.\"<ref name=\"huffpost_20190710\">{{Cite news| title = Ilhan Omar Calls Tucker Carlson 'Racist Fool' After He Claimed She Hated America| first = Jenna| last = Amatulli| work = HuffPost Canada| access-date = July 10, 2019| date = July 10, 2019| url = https://www.huffpost.com/entry/rep-ilhan-omar-tucker-carlson_n_5d255d05e4b0583e482902d7| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190710115948/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/rep-ilhan-omar-tucker-carlson_n_5d255d05e4b0583e482902d7| archive-date = July 10, 2019| url-status = live}}</ref> In their July 10 article on the incident, ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' commented that, mainly because of \"right-wing attacks that have then been amplified by members of Congress and the president\", Omar has been receiving death threats since she was elected to Congress.<ref name=\"thedailybeast_Baragona_20190710\">{{Cite news| last = Baragona| first = Justin| title = Tucker Carlson: Ilhan Omar Is 'Living Proof' Our Immigration Laws Are 'Dangerous'| access-date = July 10, 2019| date = July 10, 2019| url = https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlson-ilhan-omar-is-living-proof-our-immigration-laws-are-dangerous| work = [[The Daily Beast]]| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190711093102/https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlson-ilhan-omar-is-living-proof-our-immigration-laws-are-dangerous| archive-date = July 11, 2019| url-status = live}}</ref> According to the article, while Carlson \"has devoted numerous segments\" of his show to criticizing her, this time Carlson \"took his anti-Omar stance even further.\"<ref name=\"thedailybeast_Baragona_20190710\"/>\n\nDays after the [[2019 El Paso shooting]] which was committed by a man who released an anti-immigrant manifesto complaining of a \"Hispanic invasion\", Carlson described white supremacy as a \"hoax\" and \"a conspiracy theory used to divide the country and keep a hold on power\". He asked rhetorically, \"the combined membership of every white supremacist group in America - would they be able to fit inside a college football stadium?\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Tucker Carlson: White Supremacy Is a 'Hoax' and 'Not a Real Problem in America' |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QW-T1_Nf-pc |publisher=YouTube |work=Tucker Carlson Tonight |date=August 6, 2019 |access-date=August 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807170312/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QW-T1_Nf-pc&hl=en&gl=US&has_verified=1&disable_polymer=true&bpctr=9999999999 |archive-date=August 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/aug/07/tucker-carlson-white-supremacy-fox-news-hoax|title=Fox News host Tucker Carlson dismisses white supremacy as 'a hoax'|last=Helmore|first=Edward|date=2019-08-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807135834/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/aug/07/tucker-carlson-white-supremacy-fox-news-hoax|archive-date=August 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/us-news/2019/08/tucker-carlson-white-supremacists-are-a-hoax-not-a-real-problem.html|title=Tucker Carlson: White supremacists are a hoax, 'not a real problem'|last=Herbert|first=Geoff|date=2019-08-07|website=syracuse.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807135834/https://www.syracuse.com/us-news/2019/08/tucker-carlson-white-supremacists-are-a-hoax-not-a-real-problem.html|archive-date=August 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to ''The Washington Post'', \"Carlson's argument is belied by many experts and seemingly contradicted by a recent wave of deadly attacks by men motivated by those views.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/08/07/tucker-carlson-white-supremacy-hoax-lie-not-real-problem/|title='It's not actually a real problem in America': Tucker Carlson calls white supremacy a 'hoax'|date=2019|work=The Washington Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807140424/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/08/07/tucker-carlson-white-supremacy-hoax-lie-not-real-problem/|archive-date=August 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====South Africa====\nIn August 2018, Carlson ran a segment in which he alleged that the South African government was targeting [[White South Africans|white farmers]] during its ongoing [[Land reform in South Africa|land reform efforts]] due to anti-white racism.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/23/now-trump-is-having-a-twitter-spat-with-south-africa-over-land-reforms.html|title=Trump hypes fringe talking point about South African government 'seizing land from white farmers'|last=Ellyatt|first=Holly|date=August 23, 2018|publisher=[[CNBC]]|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828001737/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/23/now-trump-is-having-a-twitter-spat-with-south-africa-over-land-reforms.html|archive-date=2018-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/23/world/africa/trump-south-africa-white-farmers.html|title=Trump Cites False Claims of Widespread Attacks on White Farmers in South Africa|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827021629/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/23/world/africa/trump-south-africa-white-farmers.html|archive-date=2018-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-45282088|title=SA rejects Trump tweet on farmer killings|date=August 23, 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826201956/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-45282088|archive-date=2018-08-26|url-status=live}}</ref> He interviewed Marian Tupy, an analyst at the Cato Institute, who likened South African farmers facing land seizures to white farmers in [[Zimbabwe]] who lost their farms in a controversial [[Land reform in Zimbabwe|land reform policy]] under the President [[Robert Mugabe]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Expropriation without compensation: Fact-checking Tucker Carlson and Donald Trump |url=https://www.news24.com/Analysis/expropriation-without-compensation-fact-checking-tucker-carlson-and-donald-trump-20180823 |work=News24 |date=23 August 2018 |access-date=June 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020153353/https://www.news24.com/Analysis/expropriation-without-compensation-fact-checking-tucker-carlson-and-donald-trump-20180823 |archive-date=October 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the segment, Carlson criticized \"elites\" who were purportedly concerned about racism \"paying no attention\" to the \"racist government of South Africa\".<ref name=\":0\" /> He accused South African President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] of changing the country's constitution to enable land theft of whites, and without compensation, because \"they are the wrong skin color.\"<ref name=\":72\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/69edd18af846491fa2c27b5bd3d483d4|title=Fox's Carlson stunned by reaction to stories on South Africa|agency=Associated Press|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828035602/https://apnews.com/69edd18af846491fa2c27b5bd3d483d4|archive-date=2018-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[CBS News]], [[Associated Press]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' described Carlson's segment on South Africa's [[Reparations (transitional justice)|corrective reparations]] as false or misleading. In addition to presenting statistics that [[South African farm attacks|violence against farmers]] had reached an all-time low, they noted that the reforms had yet to pass and were primarily aimed at land that had fallen into disuse.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-tweet-on-south-african-land-reform-draws-governments-ire-1535017460|title=Trump Tweet on South African Land Overhaul Draws Government's Ire|last=Steinhauser|first=Gabriele|date=August 23, 2018|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827002821/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-tweet-on-south-african-land-reform-draws-governments-ire-1535017460|archive-date=2018-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":62\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/south-africa-hits-back-at-trump-over-land-seizure-tweet/|title=South Africa hits back at Trump over land seizure tweet|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827024600/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/south-africa-hits-back-at-trump-over-land-seizure-tweet/|archive-date=2018-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":72\"/><ref name=\":82\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2018/aug/24/donald-trump/trump-tweets-incorrect-south-african-land-seizures/|title=Trump tweets incorrect on S.A. land seizures, farmers|publisher=[[PolitiFact]]|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828035531/https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2018/aug/24/donald-trump/trump-tweets-incorrect-south-african-land-seizures/|archive-date=2018-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/ap-fact-check-trumps-claim-on-south-african-farms-off-mark/2018/08/23/242fa3e2-a6ea-11e8-ad6f-080770dcddc2_story.html|title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump's claim on South African farms off mark|website=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828001725/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/ap-fact-check-trumps-claim-on-south-african-farms-off-mark/2018/08/23/242fa3e2-a6ea-11e8-ad6f-080770dcddc2_story.html|archive-date=2018-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nFollowing the Carlson segment, President Trump tweeted that he had instructed Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] to \"closely study the South Africa land and farm seizure and large scale killing of farmers.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Trump's tweet was denounced as \"'misinformed'\" by the South African government, which stated that it would address the matter through diplomatic channels.<ref name=\":5\" /> The [[White Nationalist]] South African group, [[AfriForum]], took credit for Carlson and Trump's statements, saying it believed that its campaign to influence American politics had succeeded.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe evening following the segment, Carlson corrected the statements he had made about the South African land reform, though he did not admit to having made errors. He said the proposed constitutional amendment was still being debated in South Africa and added that no farms had yet been expropriated.<ref name=\":72\"/> Carlson later stated in an interview that he \"doesn't believe anyone should be rewarded or punished based upon characteristics they can't control\" and added that his South Africa segment made \"an argument against tribalism\".<ref name=\":72\"/>\n\n===COVID-19 pandemic===\nCarlson has criticized government officials and other media for not taking the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]] seriously enough, while blaming China for causing the pandemic.<ref name=\"USN-Pandemic\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chiu |first1=Allyson |title='China has blood on its hands': Fox News hosts join Trump in blame-shifting |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/03/19/coronavirus-fox-news-china/ |work=Washington Post |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, 2020, Carlson opened his show by saying, \"People you trust, people you probably voted for, have spent weeks minimizing what is clearly a very serious problem. ... But they're wrong. It's definitely not just the flu.\"<ref name=\"wpcovid\">{{cite news |last1=Costa |first1=Robert |title=As much of America takes drastic action, some Republicans remain skeptical of the severity of the coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/as-much-of-america-takes-drastic-action-some-republicans-remain-skeptical-of-the-severity-of-the-coronavirus-pandemic/2020/03/17/f8b199c8-6786-11ea-b313-df458622c2cc_story.html |work=Washington Post |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Two anonymous sources in the White House told the ''Washington Post'' that Carlson's statements had caused President Donald Trump to reconsider his position.<ref name=\"wpcovid\" /> Carlson also told ''Vanity Fair'' that he spoke to Trump and encouraged him to take the coronavirus outbreak seriously.<ref name=\"vanityfair-carlson\">{{cite news |title=\"Dishonesty...Is Always an Indicator of Weakness\": Tucker Carlson on How He Brought His Coronavirus Message to Mar-a-Lago |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/03/tucker-carlson-on-how-he-brought-coronavirus-message-to-mar-a-lago |work=Vanity Fair |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"USN-Pandemic\">{{cite news |title=Tucker Carlson says he felt an obligation to meet with Trump on seriousness of coronavirus |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/entertainment/articles/2020-03-18/carlson-says-he-felt-obligation-to-meet-with-trump-on-virus |work=U.S. News |agency=The Associated Press |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCarlson is married to Susan Carlson (n\u00e9e Andrews).<ref name=\":102\"/> They met while in high school at St. George's School and were married in 1991 in the high school chapel.<ref name=Wife>{{cite news|title=Weddings/East: Andrews-Carlson|publisher=Detroit Free Press|date=28 Aug 1991}}</ref> They have three daughters and one son, including Lillie (b. 1995), Buckley (b. 1997), Hopie (b. 1999), and Dorothy.<ref name=\"peoplemag\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/15/travel/tmagazine/15T-FISH.html?pagewanted=print&position=&_r=|title=Off the Hook|last=Carlson|first=Tucker|date=May 15, 2005|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nCarlson is an [[Episcopal Church USA|Episcopalian]] and \"loves the liturgy, though [he] abhors the liberals who run the denomination\".<ref name=\"Fighting-Words\">{{cite news |first=Kelefa |last=Sanneh |title=Tucker Carlson's Fighting Words |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/04/10/tucker-carlsons-fighting-words |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=April 10, 2017 |accessdate=April 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303224152/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/04/10/tucker-carlsons-fighting-words |archive-date=March 3, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCarlson quit drinking alcohol in 2002, \"having decided that neither the pleasant nights nor the unpleasant mornings were improving his life\".<ref name=\"Fighting-Words\" /> Years earlier, he had quit smoking and replaced cigarettes with nicotine gum, which he buys in bulk from New Zealand and \"chews constantly\".<ref name=\"Fighting-Words\" />\n\nCarlson is a [[Deadhead]] (a fan of the rock band the [[Grateful Dead]]), and said in a 2005 interview that he had attended more than 50 of their concerts.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The New York Sun]] |date=August 9, 2005 |first=John P. |last=Avlon |title=Jerry Garcia's Conservative Children |url=https://www.nysun.com/opinion/jerry-garcias-conservative-children/18288/ |access-date=December 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206235312/https://www.nysun.com/opinion/jerry-garcias-conservative-children/18288/ |archive-date=December 6, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also good friends with the Nevada [[brothel]] owner [[Dennis Hof]].<ref name=Paul08/>\n\nCarlson's estranged mother, Lisa Vaughn, died in October 2011. Vaughn was thought to have died intestate, and in 2012, Carlson and his brother, Buckley, filed a lawsuit to determine succession of her oil and gas royalties in several counties in California, initially valued at over $125,000<ref name=lawsuit/><ref name=lawsuit2/> but later found to be over $2.5 million. However, in 2013 a one-page handwritten will was discovered in which Vaughn explicitly stated that she wished her estate to go solely to her husband and left one dollar each for Carlson and his brother.<ref name=lawsuit/><ref name=lawsuit2/> As of March 2019, the lawsuit was still under appeal.<ref name=lawsuit/><ref name=lawsuit2/>\n\nIn 2018, a group of about 20 activists from Smash Racism D.C. protested outside Carlson's [[Washington, D.C.]], home.<ref name=WaPo.Threatening>{{cite news |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=November 8, 2018 |first=Allyson |last=Chiu |title='They were threatening me and my family': Tucker Carlson's home targeted by protesters |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2018/11/08/they-were-threatening-me-my-family-tucker-carlsons-home-targeted-by-protesters/ |access-date=2019-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229143955/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2018/11/08/they-were-threatening-me-my-family-tucker-carlsons-home-targeted-by-protesters/ |archive-date=2018-12-29 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carlson's driveway was vandalized with a spray-painted [[Anarchist symbolism|anarchist symbol]]. Police responded within minutes and the protesters were dispersed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/all/antifa-group-chants-outside-vandalizes-fox-commentator-tucker-carlson-s-n934131|title=Antifa group chants outside, vandalizes Fox commentator Tucker Carlson's home|last1=Fieldstadt|first1=Elisha|access-date=2019-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126153143/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/all/antifa-group-chants-outside-vandalizes-fox-commentator-tucker-carlson-s-n934131|archive-date=2018-11-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Lenz, Lyz. [https://www.cjr.org/the_profile/tucker-carlson.php \"The Mystery of Tucker Carlson,\"] ''Columbia Journalism Review,'' September 5, 2018.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tucker Carlson}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|1227121}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Tucker Carlson}}\n\n{{Fox News Personalities}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carlson, Tucker}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American broadcast news analysts]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political journalists]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Cato Institute people]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:Fox News people]]\n[[Category:Free speech activists]]\n[[Category:The Heritage Foundation]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:MSNBC people]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Opinion journalists]]\n[[Category:People from Carlsbad, California]]\n[[Category:People from La Jolla, San Diego]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:St. George's School, Newport alumni]]\n[[Category:Television personalities from California]]\n[[Category:Trinity College (Connecticut) alumni]]\n[[Category:The Weekly Standard people]]\n[[Category:Writers from California]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United States]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013illegal immigration activists]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-protected|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American conservative political commentator}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tucker Carlson\n| image              = Tucker Carlson 2013 cropped noise rem lighting color correction.jpg\n| caption            = Carlson in 2013\n| birth_name         = Tucker McNear Carlson<ref>{{cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VGZJ-QSS|title=Person Details for Tucker M Carlson, \"California Birth Index, 1905\u20131995\"|publisher=[[FamilySearch]]|accessdate=February 3, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311073401/https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VGZJ-QSS|archive-date=March 11, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1969|5|16}}\n| birth_place        = [[San Francisco]], [[California]], [[United States|U.S.]]\n| home_town          = [[La Jolla]], [[San Diego]], California, U.S.\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| education          = [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n| occupation         = [[Talk show host]], [[political commentator|commentator]], [[columnist]]\n| employer           = [[CNN]] (2000\u20132005)<br>[[MSNBC]] (2005\u20132008)<br>[[Fox News]] (2009\u2013present)\n| movement           = [[Conservatism]]\n| party              = \n| spouse             = Susan Andrews\n| children           = 4\n| relatives          = [[Dick Carlson]] (father)\n}}\n{{Conservatism in the United States}}\n'''Tucker Swanson McNear Carlson''' (born May 16, 1969) is an American [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] journalist, author, and political commentator who has hosted the nightly political talk show ''[[Tucker Carlson Tonight]]'' on [[Fox News]] since 2016.\n\nCarlson became a print journalist in the 1990s, writing for the magazine ''[[The Weekly Standard]]''. He was a commentator on [[CNN]] from 2000 to 2005 and co-hosted the primetime news debate program ''[[Crossfire (U.S. TV program)|Crossfire]]''. Carlson then hosted the nightly program ''[[Tucker (2005 TV program)|Tucker]]'' on [[MSNBC]] from 2005 to 2008. He has been a political analyst for Fox News since 2009, appearing as guest or guest host on various programs before the launch of his current show. In 2010, Carlson co-founded and served as the initial editor-in-chief of the conservative news and opinion website ''[[The Daily Caller]]''.\n\nCarlson has written two books, the memoir ''Politicians, Partisans and Parasites: My Adventures in Cable News'' (2003) and ''[[Ship of Fools (book)|Ship of Fools: How a Selfish Ruling Class is Bringing America to the Brink of Revolution]]'' (2018).\n\n==Early life and education==\nCarlson was born Tucker McNear Carlson in [[San Francisco]], [[California]]. He is the elder son of [[Dick Carlson|Richard Warner Carlson]], a former \"[[Gonzo journalism|gonzo reporter]]\"<ref name=Dick/> who became the director of the [[Voice of America]], the president of the [[Corporation for Public Broadcasting]] and the [[List of ambassadors of the United States to Seychelles|U.S. Ambassador to the Seychelles]].<ref name=\":102\">Lenz, Lyz (September 5, 2018). [https://www.cjr.org/the_profile/tucker-carlson.php \"The mystery of Tucker Carlson\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180908093046/https://www.cjr.org/the_profile/tucker-carlson.php |date=September 8, 2018 }}, ''Columbia Journalism Review''.</ref> Carlson's paternal grandparents were Richard Boynton and Dorothy Anderson, teenagers who placed his father in an [[orphanage]] where he was adopted when he was two years old by the Carlsons. Richard Carlson's adoptive father was a wool broker.<ref name=Boynton>{{cite news|author=Tony Knight|title=Hoping for a runoff|publisher=Times-Advocate|location=Escondido, California|date=27 May 1984}}</ref><ref name=Dick>{{cite news|author=Scott Harris|title=Carlson Takes on Embattled Mayor|publisher=Los Angeles Times|location=Los Angeles, California|date=6 May 1984}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/politicswithprin00mich/page/47 <!-- quote=father richard carlson boynton. --> Politics with Principle: Ten Characters with Character] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181110120123/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=furNVPTV-wMC&pg=PA47&lpg=PA47&dq=father+richard+carlson+boynton&source=bl&ots=FLin8F_daJ&sig=7ea6pViQVWdC9BJgxBc4iPbbyYo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwj-y5WS0cjeAhWMA8AKHXXHAsAQ6AEwD3oECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=father%20richard%20carlson%20boynton&f=false |date=November 10, 2018 }} \u2013 By Michael J. Kerrigan.</ref>\n\nCarlson's mother was artist Lisa McNear (n\u00e9e Lombardi). He also has a brother, Buckley Peck Carlson (later, Buckley Swanson Peck Carlson), who is nearly two years younger and was born two months premature.<ref name=Brother>{{cite news|author=Albert Morch|title=Albert Morch [Column]|publisher=The San Francisco Examiner|date=15 Feb 1971}}</ref>\n\nIn 1976, Carlson's parents divorced after the nine-year marriage reportedly \"turned sour.\"<ref name=Brother/><ref name=Divorce>{{cite news|author=Center for Health Statistics, California Department of Health Services|title=California Divorce Index, 1966-1984|publisher=State of California|location=Sacramento, California}}</ref> Carlson's father was granted custody of him and his brother. Carlson's mother left the family when he was six, wanting to pursue a \"[[Bohemianism|bohemian]]\" lifestyle.<ref>''National Social Directory'', National Social Register Company, 1959, page 86.</ref><ref name=\":102\"/> She eventually split her time between [[Beaufort County, South Carolina]] and [[Cazac, Haute-Garonne|Cazac, France]], where she had little contact with Carlson's family and later married artist Michael Vaughn.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/04/10/tucker-carlsons-fighting-words|title=Tucker Carlson's Fighting Words|work=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=August 10, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830041835/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/04/10/tucker-carlsons-fighting-words|archive-date=August 30, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Obit>{{cite web|title=Obituary: Lisa Lombardi-Vaughan|url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/sfgate/obituary.aspx?n=lisa-lombardi-vaughan&pid=154563219|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle|date=13 Nov 2011}}</ref><ref name=lawsuit>{{cite web|title=IN RE ESTATE OF VAUGHN|url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/incaco20190606085|publisher=Leagle|date=4 Jun 2019}}</ref><ref name=lawsuit2>{{cite web|title=Bickel v. Carlson (In re Estate of Vaughan)|url=https://casetext.com/case/bickel-v-carlson-in-re-estate-of-vaughan|publisher=Casetext|date=4 Jun 2019}}</ref>\n\nDick Carlson was said to be an active father who had a specific outlook in raising his sons:\n\n{{Quote|\"I want them to be self-disciplined to the degree that I think is necessary to find satisfaction{{nbsp}}... you measure a person on how far they go, on how far they've sprung. My parents, the Carlsons, they instilled a modesty in me that, at times, gets in my way{{nbsp}}... I know it's immodest of me to say it, but it's difficult sometimes when you want to beat your own drum and say what you really think.\"}}\n\nIn 1979, Carlson's father married divorc\u00e9e Patricia Caroline Swanson, an heiress to [[Swanson]] Enterprises. Swanson is the daughter of Gilbert Carl Swanson and the niece of [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[J. William Fulbright]].<ref name=\":102\"/><ref name=Patty>{{cite news|author=David Harris|title=SWANSON SAGA: END OF A DREAM|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/09/09/archives/swanson-saga-end-of-a-dream-they-were-the-pride-of-omaha-but-today.html|publisher=The New York Times|date=9 Sep 1979}}</ref> This was the third marriage for Swanson, who legally adopted Carlson and his brother.<ref name=lawsuit/><ref name=Patty/>\n\nWhen Carlson was in first grade, his father moved him and his brother to [[La Jolla]], [[California]] and raised them there.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://observer.com/2018/01/fox-new-tucker-carlson-immigrant-bashing-is-toxic/|title=Tucker Carlson's Xenophobia Is Horribly Effective|date=January 24, 2018|access-date=August 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806072343/https://observer.com/2018/01/fox-new-tucker-carlson-immigrant-bashing-is-toxic/|archive-date=August 6, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"peoplemag\">{{cite news |url= http://people.com/archive/meet-mister-right-vol-54-no-19/ |title= Meet Mister Right |volume= 54 |number= 19 |date= November 6, 2000 |work= [[People (magazine)|People]] |first= Steve |last= Dougherty |access-date= January 5, 2017 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170106011519/http://people.com/archive/meet-mister-right-vol-54-no-19/ |archive-date= January 6, 2017 |url-status= live }}</ref> In La Jolla, Carlson attended [[La Jolla Country Day School]] and grew up in a home overlooking the [[La Jolla Beach and Tennis Club]].<ref name=Proven>{{cite news|author=Gerry Braun|title=Rites of Passage: Dick Carlson says he has proven himself|publisher=Times-Advocate|location=Escondido, California|date=21 Oct 1984}}</ref> His father owned property in Nevada, Vermont, and islands in Maine and Nova Scotia.<ref name=Proven/><ref name=Dick/>\n\nCarlson attained his secondary education at [[St. George's School, Newport|St. George's School]], a [[boarding school]] in [[Middletown, Rhode Island]]. He then went to [[Trinity College (Connecticut)|Trinity College]] in [[Hartford, Connecticut]], where he graduated in 1991 with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in history.<ref name=\":102\"/> After college, Carlson tried to join the [[Central Intelligence Agency]], but his application was denied, after which he decided to pursue a career in journalism with the encouragement of his father.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jeva Lange |url=https://theweek.com/speedreads-amp/689969/tucker-carlson-tried-join-cia |title=Tucker Carlson tried to join the CIA |publisher=Theweek.com |date=2017-04-03 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>https://www.cjr.org/the_profile/tucker-carlson.php</ref>\n\n==Television career==\nCarlson began his [[journalism]] career as a fact-checker for ''[[Policy Review]]'',<ref name=\":102\"/> a national [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]] journal then published by [[The Heritage Foundation]] and since acquired by the [[Hoover Institution]]. He later worked as a reporter at the ''[[Arkansas Democrat-Gazette]]'' newspaper in [[Little Rock, Arkansas]], before joining ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'' newsmagazine in 1995.<ref name=\":102\"/>\n\nAs a magazine and newspaper journalist, Carlson has reported from around the world. He has been a columnist for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' and ''[[Reader's Digest]]''. He also wrote for ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]'', ''[[The Weekly Standard]]'', ''[[The New Republic]]'', ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', and ''[[The Daily Beast]]''.<ref name=\":102\"/>\n\n===CNN (2000\u20132005)===\n[[File:CPAC 2012 &#039;Fight Club&#039; Debate with Paul Begala and Tucker Carlson, Thomas McDevitt, President, The Washington Times is the Moderator. (6859927507).jpg|thumb|right|Paul Begala, Thomas McDevitt, and Carlson, 2012]]\nIn 2000, Carlson co-hosted the short-lived show ''The Spin Room''.<ref name=\":102\"/> In 2001, Carlson was appointed co-host of ''[[Crossfire (U.S. TV program)|Crossfire]].'' On the show, Carlson and [[Robert Novak]] represented the political [[right-wing politics|right]] (alternating on different nights), while [[James Carville]] and [[Paul Begala]], also alternating as hosts, represented the left.<ref name=\":102\"/> During the same period, he also hosted a weekly public affairs program on [[PBS]], ''Tucker Carlson: Unfiltered''.\n\nIn October 2004, comedian [[Jon Stewart]], host of ''[[The Daily Show]]'' on [[Comedy Central]], appeared on ''Crossfire'', ostensibly to promote his book ''[[America (The Book)]]'', but instead launching into a critique of ''Crossfire'', saying that the show was harmful to political discourse in the United States.<ref name=\":102\"/><ref>{{cite news |title=Watch Jon Stewart Call Tucker Carlson a \"Dick\" in Epic 2004 'Crossfire' Takedown |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jon-stewart-takes-down-tucker-carlson-crossfire-video-961127 |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=January 5, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719234728/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/jon-stewart-takes-down-tucker-carlson-crossfire-video-961127 |archive-date=July 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carlson represented the right-wing side on that episode, and Stewart singled him out for criticism, with Carlson in turn criticizing Stewart for being biased toward the left.<ref name=\":102\"/> Carlson later recalled that Stewart had stayed at CNN for hours after the show to discuss the issues he had raised on the air. \"It was heartfelt,\" Carlson said, \"He [Stewart] needed to do this.\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Cave |first=Damien |url=http://msl1.mit.edu/furdlog/docs/nytimes/2004-10-24_nytimes_damien_cave.pdf |format=PDF |title=A Week in Review: If You Interview Kissinger, Are You Still a Comedian? |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 24, 2004 |accessdate=July 19, 2018 |via=Msl1.mit.edu |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130405064722/http://msl1.mit.edu/furdlog/docs/nytimes/2004-10-24_nytimes_damien_cave.pdf |archive-date=April 5, 2013 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> In 2017, ''[[The New York Times]]'' referred to Stewart's \"on-air dressing-down\" of Carlson as an \"ignominious career [moment]\" for Carlson.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/05/business/media/tucker-carlson-megyn-kelly-fox.html|title=Megyn Kelly Being Replaced by Tucker Carlson at Fox|last=Grynbaum|first=Michael M.|date=2017-01-05|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2018-12-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181209124539/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/01/05/business/media/tucker-carlson-megyn-kelly-fox.html|archive-date=December 9, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In the view of ''The New York Times'', Stewart's criticism led to the cancellation of the show.<ref name=\":02\" />\n\nIn January 2005, CNN announced they were ending their relationship with Carlson and would soon cancel ''Crossfire''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://politicalhumor.about.com/b/2005/01/07/jon-stewarts-wish-fulfilled-crossfire-to-stop-hurting-america.htm |title=Jon Stewart's Wish Fulfilled; 'Crossfire' to Stop 'Hurting America' |publisher=Political Humor |date=January 7, 2005 |accessdate=August 5, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090501190911/http://politicalhumor.about.com/b/2005/01/07/jon-stewarts-wish-fulfilled-crossfire-to-stop-hurting-america.htm |archive-date=May 1, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"Cancel\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/06/business/media/06crossfire.html?_r=1 |title=CNN Will Cancel 'Crossfire' and Cut Ties to Commentator|author1=Carter, Bill |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422204302/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/06/business/media/06crossfire.html?_r=1 |archivedate=April 22, 2012 |work=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 6, 2005|accessdate=March 16, 2009|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> CNN chief [[Jonathan Klein (CNN)|Jonathan Klein]] told Carlson on January 4, 2005, that the network had decided not to renew his contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/arts/story/2005/01/05/tucker050105.html |publisher=[[CBC.ca]] |date=January 6, 2005 |title=CNN lets Tucker Carlson go |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509183431/http://www.cbc.ca/arts/story/2005/01/05/tucker050105.html |archivedate=May 9, 2007}}</ref> Carlson has said that he had already resigned from CNN and ''Crossfire'' long before Stewart was booked as a guest, telling host [[Patricia Duff]]: \"I resigned from ''Crossfire'' in April [2004], many months before Jon Stewart came on our show, because I didn't like the partisanship, and I thought in some ways it was kind of a pointless conversation{{nbsp}}... each side coming out, you know, 'Here's my argument', and no one listening to anyone else. [CNN] was a frustrating place to work.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tvweek.com/in-depth/2005/01/tucker-carlson-leaving-cnn-cro/ |title=Tucker Carlson Leaving CNN; \u2018Crossfire\u2019s\u2019 Demise Likely|date=5 January 2005|work=TV Week| accessdate=August 17, 2006|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===MSNBC (2005\u20132008)===\n{{Main|Tucker (2005 TV program)}}\nCarlson's early evening show, ''Tucker'' (originally titled ''The Situation With Tucker Carlson'') premiered on June 13, 2005, on [[MSNBC]]. He also hosted a late afternoon weekday wrap-up for MSNBC during the [[2006 Winter Olympics]], during which he attempted to learn how to play various Olympic sports. In July 2006, he reported live for ''Tucker'' from [[Haifa]], [[Israel]], during the [[2006 Lebanon War]] between Israel and [[Hezbollah]] in southern Lebanon. While in the [[Middle East]], he also hosted ''MSNBC Special Report: Mideast Crisis''. He appeared regularly on ''[[Verdict with Dan Abrams]]'' as a panelist in political discussions.\n\n''Tucker'' was cancelled by the network on March 10, 2008, due to low ratings,<ref>{{cite news|title=David Gregory Replaces Tucker Carlson on MSNBC Evening Shift|date=March 10, 2008|agency=Associated Press|publisher=[[Fox News]]|url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,336470,00.html|access-date=December 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025110901/http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,336470,00.html|archive-date=October 25, 2012|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the final episode aired on March 14, 2008. [[Brian Stelter]] of ''The New York Times'' wrote that \"during Mr. Carlson's tenure, MSNBC's evening programming moved gradually to the left. His former time slots, 6{{nbsp}}and 9{{nbsp}}p.m., were then occupied by two liberals, [[Ed Schultz]] and [[Rachel Maddow]].\" Carlson said the network had changed a lot and \"they didn't have a role for me.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Stelter|first=Brian|title=Tucker Carlson turns 40, moves to Fox News|url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/05/15/tucker-carlson-turns-40-moves-to-fox-news/|accessdate=March 4, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=May 15, 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130404232029/http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/05/15/tucker-carlson-turns-40-moves-to-fox-news/|archive-date=April 4, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Fox News Channel (2009\u2013present)===\nIn May 2009, Fox News announced that Carlson was being hired as a Fox News contributor. He was a frequent guest panelist on Fox's late-night satire show ''[[Red Eye w/Greg Gutfeld]],'' made frequent appearances on the All-Star Panel segment of ''[[Special Report with Bret Baier]]'', was a substitute host of ''[[Hannity]]'' in Sean Hannity's absence, and produced a Fox News special entitled ''Fighting for Our Children's Minds''.\n\nIn April 2013, Carlson replaced [[Dave Briggs (journalist)|Dave Briggs]] as a co-host of [[Fox & Friends Weekend]], joining Alisyn Camerota and Clayton Morris on Saturday and Sunday mornings.<ref>{{cite news|last=Byers|first=Dylan|title=Tucker Carlson to Fox & Friends Weekends|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/03/tucker-carlson-to-cohost-fox-friends-weekends-160334.html|work=[[Politico]]|access-date=March 27, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130330091112/http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2013/03/tucker-carlson-to-cohost-fox-friends-weekends-160334.html|archive-date=March 30, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' (2016\u2013present)====\n{{Main|Tucker Carlson Tonight}}\n\nOn November 14, 2016, Carlson started hosting ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' on Fox News. ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' was created to replace the show ''[[On the Record (Fox News TV series)|On the Record]]''.<ref name=\"NewsHoundEllen\">{{cite news|url=https://crooksandliars.com/2016/09/greta-van-susteren-abruptly-leaves-fox|title=Greta Van Susteren Abruptly Leaves Fox News|author=News Hound Ellen|date=September 7, 2016|work=[[Crooks and Liars]]|accessdate=November 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161119055501/http://crooksandliars.com/2016/09/greta-van-susteren-abruptly-leaves-fox|archive-date=November 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> The show debuted as \"the network's most watched telecast of the year in the time slot\".<ref name=\"DarcyBusinessInsider\">{{cite news |first=Oliver |last=Darcy |title=Tucker Carlson's Fox News show debuts to phenomenal ratings, beats both CNN and MSNBC combined |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-fox-news-show-ratings-2016-11 |website=[[Business Insider]] |accessdate=December 22, 2016 |date=November 15, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223063726/http://www.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-fox-news-show-ratings-2016-11 |archive-date=December 23, 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref> The program's premiere episode, viewed by 3.7{{nbsp}}million,<ref name=\"DarcyBusinessInsider\" /> was rated higher than previous editions of ''On the Record''.\n\n''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' aired at 7{{nbsp}}p.m. ET each weeknight until January 9, 2017, when Carlson's show replaced [[Megyn Kelly]] at the 9{{nbsp}}p.m. ET time slot after she left Fox News. In January 2017, ''[[Forbes]]'' reported that the show had \"scored consistently high ratings, averaging 2.8{{nbsp}}million viewers per night and ranking as the number two cable news program behind The O'Reilly Factor in December [2016].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/maddieberg/2017/01/05/tucker-carlson-to-replace-megyn-kelly-at-fox-news-keeping-the-network-conservative/#7c745789672e|title='Right' Move For Fox News As Tucker Carlson To Replace Megyn Kelly in Prime Time|last=Berg|first=Madeline|date=January 5, 2017|access-date=October 14, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181014165941/https://www.forbes.com/sites/maddieberg/2017/01/05/tucker-carlson-to-replace-megyn-kelly-at-fox-news-keeping-the-network-conservative/#7c745789672e|archive-date=October 14, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> In March 2017, ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' was the most watched cable program in the 9{{nbsp}}p.m. time slot.{{citation needed|date=June 2019}}\n\nOn April 19, 2017, it was announced that ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' would air at 8{{nbsp}}p.m. following the cancellation of ''[[The O'Reilly Factor]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fox-news-tucker-carlson-bill-oreilly-1202313557/|title=Fox News Will Replace Bill O'Reilly With Tucker Carlson|first=Brian|last=Steinberg|date=April 19, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|access-date=December 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201094626/http://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fox-news-tucker-carlson-bill-oreilly-1202313557/|archive-date=December 1, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' was the third-highest-rated cable news show as of March 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/385492-carlsons-ratings-on-fox-closing-in-on-oreillys|title=Carlson's ratings on Fox closing in on O'Reilly's|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|last=Concha|first=Joe|date=April 30, 2018|access-date=September 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180913040121/http://thehill.com/homenews/media/385492-carlsons-ratings-on-fox-closing-in-on-oreillys|archive-date=September 13, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'' was the second-highest rated cable news show in prime time, after ''The Sean Hannity Show'' with [[Sean Hannity]], with 3.2{{nbsp}}million nightly viewers.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |date=October 31, 2018 |first=Joe |last=Concha |title=Fox News tops CNN and MSNBC combined in October cable news ratings |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/414005-fox-news-tops-cnn-and-msnbc-combined-in-october-cable-news-ratings |access-date=November 22, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122172137/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/414005-fox-news-tops-cnn-and-msnbc-combined-in-october-cable-news-ratings |archive-date=November 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> By the end of 2018, the show had begun to be boycotted by at least 20 advertisers after Carlson said U.S. immigration makes the country \"poorer, dirtier and more divided\". According to Fox News, the advertisers only moved their ad buys to other programs.<ref name=Katz-181220>{{cite news | url=https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/20-plus-brands-have-stopped-advertising-on-tucker-carlson-tonight-after-immigration-comments/ | title=20-Plus Brands Have Stopped Advertising on Tucker Carlson Tonight After Immigration Comments | work=[[Adweek]] | date=December 20, 2018 | accessdate=March 24, 2019 | last=Katz | first=A.J. | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324123518/https://www.adweek.com/tv-video/20-plus-brands-have-stopped-advertising-on-tucker-carlson-tonight-after-immigration-comments/ | archive-date=March 24, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy January 2019, his show dropped to third with 2.8 million nightly viewers, down six percent from the previous year.<ref name=Katz-190324>{{cite news | url=https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/the-top-cable-news-programs-of-january-2019-were/392622 | title=RATINGS The Top Cable News Programs of January 2019 Were{{nbsp}}... | work=[[Adweek]] | date=March 24, 2019 | accessdate=March 24, 2019 | first=A.J. | last=Katz | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324123139/https://www.adweek.com/tvnewser/the-top-cable-news-programs-of-january-2019-were/392622 | archive-date=March 24, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The show had lost at least 26 advertisers.<ref name=Brunley>{{cite news | url=https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a26911984/tucker-carlson-fox-news-advertiser-boycott/ | title=If Tucker Carlson Keeps Hemorrhaging Advertisers He Might Soon Be Down to Just 'My Pillow' | work=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] | date=March 22, 2019 | accessdate=March 24, 2019 | first=Gabrielle | last=Brunley | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324061142/https://www.esquire.com/news-politics/a26911984/tucker-carlson-fox-news-advertiser-boycott/ | archive-date=March 24, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=Barr-190322>{{cite news | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/major-sponsors-tucker-carlsons-show-leans-fox-news-house-ads-1196257 | title=Without Major Sponsors, Tucker Carlson's Show Leans on Ads for Fox Programming | work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date=March 22, 2019 | accessdate=March 24, 2019 | first=Jeremy | last=Barr | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324003930/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/major-sponsors-tucker-carlsons-show-leans-fox-news-house-ads-1196257 | archive-date=March 24, 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> There were calls to fire Carlson from Fox News, but his ratings had risen 8 percent despite the boycotts.<ref name=\"Tucker Carlson\u2019s Weekly TV Ratings Rise Despite Boycotts\">{{cite web |last1=Tony |first1=Maglio |title=Tucker Carlson\u2019s Weekly TV Ratings Rise Despite Boycotts |url=https://www.thewrap.com/tucker-carlson-ratings-rise-despite-boycotts/ |website=The Wrap |publisher=The Wrap |accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref> By August 2019, [[Media Matters]] calculated that some companies had fulfilled their media buy contracts and advertising inventory for the time slot and had now begun their purchases for other time slots on Fox News.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/tucker-carlson/tucker-carlson-returns-fox-news-advertisers-are-staying-away|title=Tucker Carlson returns to Fox News -- but advertisers are staying away|first=Jordan|last=Uhl|website=Media Matters for America|access-date=August 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190820185209/https://www.mediamatters.org/tucker-carlson/tucker-carlson-returns-fox-news-advertisers-are-staying-away|archive-date=August 20, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediamatters.org/tucker-carlson/tucker-carlson-tonight-loses-advertisers-after-remarks-about-hoax-white-supremacy|title=Tucker Carlson Tonight loses advertisers after remarks about \"hoax\" of white supremacy|first=Jordan|last=Uhl|website=Media Matters for America}}</ref>\n\nAs of the close of 2019, Fox News had it highest ratings in the company's 23-year history, its ratings up 2 percent from 2018 while other competing networks were down 2 percent ([[CNN]] and [[MSNBC]]). According to [[Nielsen Ratings]], Carlson's ratings among all viewers 25-54 placed him second overall only to Fox's ''The Sean Hannity Show.'' [[Rachael Maddow]] of ''The Rachael Maddow Show'' on [[MSNBC]] placed third, and another Fox News journalist, [[Laura Ingraham]] of ''The Laura Ingraham Show'' placed fourth.  Ratings for all three of the networks were down compared to 2018, with Fox News showing the least of the decline at 16 percent, MSNBC down 20 percent and CNN down 21 percent overall.<ref name=\"Fox News Ends 2019 With Biggest Prime Time Ratings Ever\" group=\"\">{{cite web |last1=Joyellaq |first1=Mark |title=Fox News Ends 2019 with Highest Rated Prime Time Ratings Ever |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/markjoyella/2019/12/11/fox-news-ends-2019-with-highest-rated-prime-time-ratings-ever/#31cb86923347 |website=Forbes.com |publisher=Forbes |accessdate=February 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===''The Daily Caller'' (2010\u2013present)===\n{{Main|The Daily Caller}}\n\nOn January 11, 2010, Carlson and former vice president [[Dick Cheney]] aide [[Neil Patel (political advisor)|Neil Patel]] launched a political news website titled ''[[The Daily Caller]]''. Carlson served as editor-in-chief, and occasionally wrote opinion pieces with Patel.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://dailycaller.com/author/carlsonandpatel/|title=Tucker Carlson and Neil Patel Author Page|work=[[The Daily Caller]]|accessdate=March 4, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130107030311/http://dailycaller.com/author/carlsonandpatel/|archive-date=January 7, 2013|url-status=live}}</ref> The website was funded by the conservative activist [[Foster Friess|Foster Freiss]].<ref name=\":102\"/> By February ''The Daily Caller'' was part of the White House rotating press pool.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/michaelcalderone/0210/Daily_Caller_joins_WH_pool.html|title=Daily Caller joins W.H. pool|last=Calderone|first=Michael|date=February 1, 2010|work=[[Politico]]|accessdate=July 8, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100620011410/http://www.politico.com/blogs/michaelcalderone/0210/Daily_Caller_joins_WH_pool.html|archive-date=June 20, 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''[[Politico]]'', Carlson said ''The Daily Caller'' would not be tied to ideology but rather will be \"breaking stories of importance\". In a ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'' article, Carlson added, \"We're not enforcing any kind of ideological orthodoxy on anyone.\" Columnist [[Mickey Kaus]] quit after Carlson refused to run a column critical of [[Fox News]]'s coverage of the immigration policy debate due to his contractual obligations to Fox News.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2015/03/mickey-kaus-quits-daily-caller-after-tucker-carlson-204135.html|title=Mickey Kaus quits Daily Caller after Tucker Carlson pulls critical Fox News column|last1=Byers|first1=Dylan|date=March 17, 2015|work=[[Politico]]|access-date=April 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150401091337/http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2015/03/mickey-kaus-quits-daily-caller-after-tucker-carlson-204135.html|archive-date=April 1, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/03/18/daily-callers-tucker-carlson-takes-a-stand-for-censorship/|title=Daily Caller's Tucker Carlson takes a stand for censorship|last1=Wemple|first1=Erik|date=March 18, 2015|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=September 17, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170812141953/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/03/18/daily-callers-tucker-carlson-takes-a-stand-for-censorship/|archive-date=August 12, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":102\"/>\n\n===''Dancing with the Stars''===\nCarlson was a contestant on [[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. season 3)|season 3]] of the [[reality show]] ''[[Dancing with the Stars (U.S. TV series)|Dancing with the Stars]]'', which aired in 2006; he was paired with professional dancer [[Elena Grinenko]]. Carlson took four-hour-a-day [[ballroom dance]] classes in preparation for the competition. In an interview a month before the show began, he lamented that he would miss classes during a two-week-long MSNBC assignment in Lebanon, noting that \"It's hard for me to remember the moves.\"<ref name=\"AR2006081401091.html\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/14/AR2006081401091.html|title=Names & Faces|date=August 15, 2006|accessdate=August 5, 2009|work=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107134310/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/08/14/AR2006081401091.html|archive-date=November 7, 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Carlson said he accepted ABC's invitation to perform because \"I don't do things that I'm not good at very often. I'm psyched to get to do that.\"<ref name=\"AR2006081401091.html\" /> Carlson was the first contestant eliminated, on September 13, 2006.<ref name=\":102\"/>\n\n==Writings==\nIn 2003, Carlson authored the memoir ''Politicians, Partisans and Parasites: My Adventures in Cable News'', about his television news experiences; the publisher was [[Warner Books]].<ref name=adventures>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonian.com/bookreviews/currentaffairs/politicians-partisans-and-parasites-my-adventures-in-cable-news.php|title=Politicians, Partisans, and Parasites: My Adventures in Cable News|work=[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]]|access-date=April 2, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120064449/http://www.washingtonian.com/bookreviews/currentaffairs/politicians-partisans-and-parasites-my-adventures-in-cable-news.php|archive-date=November 20, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the book's revelations was Carlson's description of being falsely accused of [[rape]] by a woman he did not know who suffered from severe [[mental illness]] and displayed [[stalking|stalker]]-like behavior. Carlson wrote in the book that the incident was emotionally [[Psychological trauma|traumatic]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Politicians, Partisans, and Parasites: My Adventures in Cable News|last=Carlson|first=Tucker|date=2003|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3JoFL9epFbcC&pg=PT103&dq=Tucker+Carlson+rape&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2M47U_maMYjSsAT6uIGADg&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Tucker%20Carlson%20rape&f=false|access-date=October 13, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140704044010/http://books.google.com/books?id=3JoFL9epFbcC&pg=PT103&dq=Tucker+Carlson+rape&hl=en&sa=X&ei=2M47U_maMYjSsAT6uIGADg&ved=0CEUQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=Tucker%20Carlson%20rape&f=false|archive-date=July 4, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, ''The Daily Caller'' published an \"investigative series\" of articles co-authored by Carlson, purporting to be an insiders' expos\u00e9 of [[Media Matters for America]] (MMfA), a liberal watchdog group that monitors and scrutinizes conservative media outlets, and its founder [[David Brock]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailycaller.com/2012/02/12/inside-media-matters-sources-memos-reveal-erratic-behavior-close-coordination-with-white-house-and-news-organizations/|title=Inside Media Matters: Sources, memos reveal erratic behavior, close coordination with White House and news organizations|website=Inside Media Matters: Sources, memos reveal erratic behavior, close coordination with White House and news organizations|access-date=August 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621140251/https://dailycaller.com/2012/02/12/inside-media-matters-sources-memos-reveal-erratic-behavior-close-coordination-with-white-house-and-news-organizations/|archive-date=June 21, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Citing \"current and former\" MMfA employees, \"friends\" of Brock's and a \"prominent liberal\" \u2014 none of whom are named \u2014 the article characterized MMfA as having \"an atmosphere of tension and paranoia\" and portraying Brock as \"erratic, unstable and disturbing,\" who \"struggles with mental illness,\" in fear of \"right-wing assassins,\" a regular cocaine user and would \"close [local bars] and party till six in the morning.\" [[Reuters]] media critic and libertarian [[Jack Shafer]], while noting \"I've never thought much of Media Matters' style of watchdogging or Brock's journalism,\" nevertheless sharply criticized ''The Daily Caller'' piece as \"anonymously sourced crap,\" adding \"''Daily Caller'' is attacking Media Matters with bad journalism and lame propaganda.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.reuters.com/jackshafer/2012/02/15/media-madders/|title=Media Madders|first=Jack|last=Shafer|date=February 15, 2012|access-date=August 21, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727212205/http://blogs.reuters.com/jackshafer/2012/02/15/media-madders/|archive-date=July 27, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2017, Carlson, represented by the literary and creative agency [[Javelin (company)|Javelin]], signed an eight-figure, two-book deal with [[Simon & Schuster]]'s [[Threshold Editions]].<ref>{{cite news |date=May 2, 2017 |title=Tucker Carlson Gets Two-Book, Eight-Figure Deal |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/bookmark/tucker-carlson-gets-two-book-eight-figure-deal-999704 |agency=AP |access-date=August 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811012346/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/bookmark/tucker-carlson-gets-two-book-eight-figure-deal-999704 |archive-date=August 11, 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> His first book in the series, ''[[Ship of Fools (book)|Ship of Fools: How a Selfish Ruling Class is Bringing America to the Brink of Revolution]]'', was released in October 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fox News star Tucker Carlson exposes 'elites' in new book |url=https://www.naplesnews.com/story/entertainment/books/2018/10/02/when-tucker-carlson-book-signing-naples-ship-fools/1454117002/ |first=Dave |last=Osborn |date=October 2, 2018 |work=[[Naples Daily News]] |access-date=January 20, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121014016/https://www.naplesnews.com/story/entertainment/books/2018/10/02/when-tucker-carlson-book-signing-naples-ship-fools/1454117002/ |archive-date=January 21, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> It debuted at No.{{nbsp}}1 on [[The New York Times Best Seller list|''The New York Times'' Best Seller list]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tucker Carlson's new book topples Woodward from No.{{nbsp}}1 on New York Times best-seller list |url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/410912-tucker-carlsons-new-book-topples-woodward-from-1-on-new-york-times-bestseller |first=Joe |last=Concha |date=October 11, 2018 |work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]] |access-date=October 15, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181016032645/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/410912-tucker-carlsons-new-book-topples-woodward-from-1-on-new-york-times-bestseller |archive-date=October 16, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nCarlson is generally described as a [[Conservatism in the United States|conservative]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/06/business/media/cnn-will-cancel-crossfire-and-cut-ties-to-commentator.html|title=CNN Will Cancel 'Crossfire' and Cut Ties to Commentator|last=Carter|first=Bill|date=January 6, 2005|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170808071252/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/06/business/media/cnn-will-cancel-crossfire-and-cut-ties-to-commentator.html|archive-date=2017-08-08|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/19/business/media/life-after-bill-oreilly-for-fox-news-to-include-tucker-carlson.html|title=For Fox News, Life After Bill O'Reilly Will Feature Tucker Carlson|last=Grynbaum|first=Michael M.|date=April 19, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=July 22, 2017|last2=Koblin|first2=John|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170504235538/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/19/business/media/life-after-bill-oreilly-for-fox-news-to-include-tucker-carlson.html|archive-date=2017-05-04|url-status=live}}</ref> or [[paleoconservatism|paleoconservative]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Raimondo |first=Justin |url=https://isi.org/modern-age/tucker-carlson-a-buckley-for-our-time/ |title=Tucker Carlson: A Buckley for Our Time? - Intercollegiate Studies Institute: Think. Live Free |publisher=Isi.org |date=2019-01-24 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.salon.com/2019/06/19/president-trump-got-talked-out-of-war-with-iran-by-fox-news-host-tucker-carlson_partner/ |title=President Trump got talked out of war with Iran by Fox News host Tucker Carlson: report |publisher=Salon.com |date=2019-06-19 |accessdate=2020-04-08}}</ref> Writing for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'''s Intelligencer, Park MacDougald called Carlson a \"Middle American radical\", which he described as someone who holds [[populist]] economic beliefs, hostililty to [[corporatocracy]], fervent positions on nationalism, race and immigration, and a preference for [[Strongman (politics)|strongmen]] in political authority. MacDouglad identified this form of radicalism as the ideological core of \"[[Political positions of Donald Trump|Trumpism]].\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Park MacDougald|title=Is Tucker Carlson the Most Important Pundit in America?|publisher=New York Magazine|url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2019/09/is-tucker-carlson-the-most-important-pundit-in-america.html|date=17 Sep 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Economics===\n[[File:TuckerRonPaul.jpg|thumb|2007 [[Ron Paul]] event]]\nEarly in his career, Carlson espoused a [[libertarian]] view of economics. He supported [[Ron Paul|Ron Paul's]] 1988 presidential candidacy, when Paul ran the candidate for the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]], along with [[Ron Paul 2008 presidential campaign|Paul's 2008 presidential candidacy]], when Paul ran as a Republican.<ref name=Paul88>{{cite news|author=Associated Press|title=Tucker Carlson thinks libertarians run the economy. That's news to Ron Paul|publisher=Washington Examiner|url=https://www.washingtonexaminer.com/opinion/tucker-carlson-thinks-libertarians-run-the-economy-thats-news-to-ron-paul|date=7 Jun 2019}}</ref><ref name=Paul08>{{cite news|author=Associated Press|title=Ron Paul Endorsed by Nevada Brothel Owner|publisher=NBC News|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21973236/ns/politics-decision_08/t/ron-paul-endorsed-nevada-brothel-owner/#.XXOveC2ZPUI|date=26 Nov 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Carlson became a senior fellow at libertarian think tank, the [[Cato Institute]].<ref name=Cato>{{cite web|title=Tucker Carlson Joins the Cato Institute|url=https://www.cato.org/news-releases/2009/2/23/tucker-carlson-joins-cato-institute|publisher=Cato Institute|date=23 Feb 2009}}</ref> As of 2017, he is no longer affiliated with the organization.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tucker Carlson- Former Senior Fellow |url=https://www.cato.org/people/tucker-carlson |publisher=Cato Institute}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Carlson began to promote a more [[economic populism|populist]] view of economics,<ref name=Mystery>{{cite web|author=Lyz Lenz|title=The mystery of Tucker Carlson|url=https://www.cjr.org/the_profile/tucker-carlson.php|publisher=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|date=5 Sep 2018}}</ref> attacking libertarianism and saying \"market capitalism is not a religion.\"<ref name=Debate>{{cite web|author=Coaston|title=Tucker Carlson has sparked the most interesting debate in conservative politics|url=https://www.vox.com/2019/1/10/18171912/tucker-carlson-fox-news-populism-conservatism-trump-gop|publisher=[[Columbia Journalism Review]]|date=10 Jan 2019}}</ref>\nIn an interview, he warned that economic and technological change that occurs too quickly can cause widespread social and political upheaval, and stated his belief that a model to follow is that of President [[Political positions of Theodore Roosevelt|Theodore Roosevelt]], whose interventionist role in the economy in the early 1900s may have, in Carlson's view, prevented a [[communist revolution]] in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bh8vqof9hAk&t=1966s|title=Sunday Special Ep 26: Tucker Carlson|work=[[The Ben Shapiro Show]]|publisher=[[The Daily Wire]]|via=YouTube|date=November 4, 2018|access-date=November 9, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129200743/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bh8vqof9hAk&t=1966s|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, in his monologue on ''Tucker Carlson Tonight'', Carlson said America's \"ruling class\" are, in effect, the \"mercenaries\" behind the decline of the American middle class:\n\n{{Quote|\"[A]ny economic system that weakens and destroys families is not worth having. A system like that is the enemy of a healthy society\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilcox|first1=W. Bradford|last2=Hammond|first2=Samuel|date=January 9, 2019|title=What Tucker Carlson Gets Right|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/01/tucker-carlson-was-right-about-working-class-family/579754/|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=January 13, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190113054611/https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/01/tucker-carlson-was-right-about-working-class-family/579754/|archive-date=2019-01-13|url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\nHe also criticized what he called the \"[[private equity]] model\" of capitalism, using the example of [[Bain Capital]] to describe a pattern of corporate behavior in such organizations:\n\n{{Quote|\"Take over an existing company for a short period of time, cut costs by firing employees, run up the debt, extract the wealth and move on, sometimes leaving retirees without their earned pensions{{nbsp}}... Meanwhile, a remarkable number of the companies are now bankrupt or extinct.\"<ref name=romney />}}\n\nHe attacked [[payday lender]]s for \"loan[ing] people money they can't possibly repay{{nbsp}}... [and] charg[ing] them interest that impoverishes them.\"<ref name=romney />\n\nCarlson has also praised Democratic presidential candidate [[Elizabeth Warren]]'s economic plan, and her book, ''[[The Two-Income Trap|The Two Income Trap]]'', as \"one of the best books I've ever read on Economics.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://politi.co/2IjrbC6|title=Fox News host says Warren 'sounds like Donald Trump at his best'|first=Matthew|last=Choi|website=POLITICO}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AXGoWtK1NnY&t=2428|title=Tucker Carlson at National Conservatism Conference: Big Business Hates Your Family|work=National Conservatism Conference|via=YouTube|date=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Environment===\nCarlson has argued that the extent to which humans contribute to [[climate change]] is \"an open question\",<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/682862/fox-news-tucker-carlson-bill-nye-got-into-heated-debate-about-humans-contribution-climate-change|title=Fox News' Tucker Carlson and Bill Nye got into a heated debate about humans' contribution to climate change|date=2017-02-28|website=theweek.com|author1=Stanek, Becca |accessdate=2019-04-02|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190402144833/https://theweek.com/speedreads/682862/fox-news-tucker-carlson-bill-nye-got-into-heated-debate-about-humans-contribution-climate-change|archivedate=April 2, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \"not settled\"<ref name=\"vs_Bill_Nye\">{{cite news |last1=Matyszczyk |first1=Chris |title=Bill Nye appears on Fox News and it doesn't go well |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/bill-nye-tucker-carlson-fox-news-climate-change/ |work=CNet |date=28 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.realclearenergy.org/video/2017/02/28/tucker_vs_bill_nye_the_science_guy.html|title=Tucker vs. Bill Nye the Science Guy {{!}} Video {{!}} RealClearEnergy|last=|date=February 28, 2017|first2= |website=www.realclearenergy.org|accessdate=2019-06-07|last3=|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607143537/https://www.realclearenergy.org/video/2017/02/28/tucker_vs_bill_nye_the_science_guy.html|archivedate=June 7, 2019|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> and \"unknowable.\"<ref name=\":63\">{{Cite news|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/142260/bill-nye-not-right-guy-lead-climate-fight|title=Bill Nye Is Not the Right Guy to Lead the Climate Fight|last=Atkin|first=Emily|date=2017-04-27|work=The New Republic|access-date=2019-04-02|issn=0028-6583|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170713052902/https://newrepublic.com/article/142260/bill-nye-not-right-guy-lead-climate-fight|archive-date=July 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn his show, Carlson frequently hosts guests who downplay the [[scientific consensus on climate change]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/fox-news-republican-viewers-reject-climate-change-science-2019-3|title=Only 12% of Republican Fox News viewers believe climate change is man-made|last=Shamsian |first=Jacob|website=Business Insider|date=March 22, 2019|accessdate=2019-06-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607143538/https://www.businessinsider.com/fox-news-republican-viewers-reject-climate-change-science-2019-3|archivedate=June 7, 2019|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Views on Republicans and Democrats===\n[[File:Tucker Carlson &amp; Charlie Kirk (32618423398).jpg|thumb|Carlson & [[Turning Point USA|Charlie Kirk]], 2018]]\nCarlson did not vote in the [[2004 United States presidential election|2004 election]], citing his disgust with the [[Iraq War]], his disillusionment with the once [[small government|small-government]] [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] and his disappointment with President [[George W. Bush]] along with likeminded conservatives:<ref name=\"A39712-2004Aug27.html\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A39712-2004Aug27.html |title=Republican Convention: Tucker Carlson |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=August 30, 2004 |accessdate=August 5, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121104110031/http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A39712-2004Aug27.html |archive-date=2012-11-04 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|\"I don't know what you consider conservative, but I'm not much of a '[[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]],' at least as the word is currently defined. For instance, I'm utterly opposed to [[abortion]], which I think is horrible and cruel. I think [[affirmative action]] is wrong. I'd like to slow [[Immigration to the United States|immigration]] pretty dramatically. I hate all [[nanny-state]] regulations, such as seat belt laws and smoking bans. I'm not for [[big government]]. I think the U.S. ought to hesitate before intervening abroad. I think these are conservative impulses. So by my criteria, Bush isn't much of a conservative.<ref name=\"A39712-2004Aug27.html\"/></blockquote>\n\nIn 2003, speaking about [[John McCain]] and his failed 2000 presidential bid, Carlson stated:\n\n{{Quote|\"I liked McCain. And I would have voted for McCain for president happily, not because I agree with his politics; I never took McCain's politics seriously enough even to have strong feelings about them. I don't think McCain has very strong politics. He's interested in ideas almost as little as George W. Bush is. McCain isn't intellectual and doesn't have a strong ideology at all. He's wound up sort of as a liberal Republican because he's mad at other Republicans, not because he's a liberal.\"<ref name=\"salon 20030913\">{{cite news |last=Lauerman |first=Kerry |url=http://dir.salon.com/story/books/feature/2003/09/13/carlson/index.html |title=\"You burn out fast when you demagogue\" |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |date=September 13, 2003 |accessdate=August 5, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090512193301/http://dir.salon.com/story/books/feature/2003/09/13/carlson/index.html |archivedate=May 12, 2009}}</ref>}}}}\n\nIn January 2019, Carlson used an [[op-ed]] by [[Mitt Romney]], in ''The Washington Post'', to criticize what he described as the \"mainstream Republican\" worldview, consisting of \"unwavering support for a finance-based economy and an internationalist foreign policy,\" which he argued was also supported by the bulk of Democrats.<ref name=romney>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/tucker-carlson-mitt-romney-supports-the-status-quo-but-for-everyone-else-its-infuriating |title=Tucker Carlson: Mitt Romney supports the status quo. But for everyone else, it's infuriating |last=Carlson |first=Tucker |date=3 January 2019 |website=[[FOXNews.com]] |access-date=27 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190127001302/https://www.foxnews.com/opinion/tucker-carlson-mitt-romney-supports-the-status-quo-but-for-everyone-else-its-infuriating |archive-date=2019-01-27 |url-status=live }}</ref> He cited parallels, in regard to economic and social problems which had befallen inner cities and rural areas, despite cultural and demographic differences between their respective populations, as evidence that the \"[[culture of poverty]]\", which had been cited by conservatives as the cause of [[Urban decay|urban decline]], \"wasn't the whole story\":\n\n{{Quote|\"[Both parties] miss the obvious point: Culture and economics are inseparably intertwined. Certain economic systems allow families to thrive. Thriving families make market economies possible.\"<ref name=romney/>}}\n\nCarlson is a registered member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] in Washington D.C.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/04/10/tucker-carlson-registered-democrat/|title=Tucker Carlson, registered Democrat|last=Wemple|first=Eric|date=April 10, 2015|accessdate=December 6, 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121064324/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2015/04/10/tucker-carlson-registered-democrat/|archive-date=2019-01-21|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2017, Carlson said he registered for the Democratic Party to gain the right to vote in mayoral elections in the district and that he \"always votes for the more corrupt candidate over the idealist.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-fox-news-democrat-ignition-mayor-most-corrupt-candidate-2017-12|title=Fox News' Tucker Carlson \u2013 a registered Democrat \u2013 explains why he always votes for the most corrupt mayoral candidate|date=December 1, 2017|accessdate=December 6, 2018|last=Lee|first=Nathaniel|work=[[Business Insider]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180630031421/http://uk.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-fox-news-democrat-ignition-mayor-most-corrupt-candidate-2017-12|archive-date=2018-06-30|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Robert Mueller===\nIn May 2019, after [[Robert Mueller]] gave a statement saying the [[Special Counsel investigation (2017\u20132019)|Special Counsel investigation on Russian interference]] in the 2016 election did not exonerate Trump of obstruction of justice, Carlson said Mueller was \"sleazy and dishonest.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/fox-news-mueller-hannity-carlson-ingraham_n_5cef781ce4b0888f89d0e91d|title=Fox News Hosts Freak Out Over 'Mean Girl' Robert Mueller: 'Full Of Crap'|last=Moran|first=Lee|date=2019-05-30|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605233826/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/fox-news-mueller-hannity-carlson-ingraham_n_5cef781ce4b0888f89d0e91d|archive-date=June 5, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Foreign policy===\n[[File:Tucker Carlson (46491104471).jpg|thumb|[[Turning Point USA|Student Action Summit]], 2018]]\nCarlson is skeptical of foreign intervention, and has stated that he thinks \"the U.S. ought to hesitate before intervening abroad.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://nationalinterest.org/feature/tucker-carlson-goes-war-against-the-neocons-21545?page=show|title=Tucker Carlson Goes to War Against the Neocons|first=Curt|last=Mills|work=[[The National Interest]]|access-date=2019-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180723111323/https://nationalinterest.org/feature/tucker-carlson-goes-war-against-the-neocons-21545?page=show|archive-date=2018-07-23|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thenewamerican.com/usnews/item/25081-change-from-kelly-to-carlson-may-give-fox-viewers-a-new-perspective|title=Change from Kelly to Carlson May Give Fox Viewers a New Perspective|work=[[The New American]]|access-date=2019-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012122717/https://www.thenewamerican.com/usnews/item/25081-change-from-kelly-to-carlson-may-give-fox-viewers-a-new-perspective|archive-date=2018-10-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Iraq====\nCarlson initially supported the [[Iraq War]]. However, a year after the [[2003 invasion of Iraq|invasion of Iraq]], he began criticizing the war, telling ''[[The New York Observer]]'':\n\n{{Quote|\"I think it's a total nightmare and disaster, and I'm ashamed that I went against my own instincts in supporting it.[...] It's something I'll never do again. Never. I got convinced by a friend of mine who's smarter than I am, and I shouldn't have done that. No. I want things to work out, but I'm enraged by it, actually.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Hagan|first=Joe|url=https://observer.com/2004/05/newly-dovish-tucker-carlson-goes-publickimmel-writer-ribs-times/|title=Newly Dovish, Tucker Carlson Goes Public\u2026Kimmel Writer Ribs Times|work=[[The New York Observer]] |date=May 17, 2004 |accessdate=January 23, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\nIn June 2019, Carlson remained critical of the war, stating:\n\n{{quote|\"We killed hundreds of thousands of people, lost thousands of our own troops, spent more than $1 trillion \u2014 all to eliminate a [[Iraq and weapons of mass destruction|WMD threat]] that, despite [[John R. Bolton|John Bolton]]'s assurances, never existed in the first place.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Fox News' Tucker Carlson Advised Trump Not to Bomb Iran \u2014 Then Roasted John Bolton on Air |url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/fox-news-tucker-carlson-reportedly-at-center-of-trump-s-decision-not-to-bomb-iran-1.7403783 |work=Haaretz |date=June 24, 2019 |access-date=June 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190625005733/https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/fox-news-tucker-carlson-reportedly-at-center-of-trump-s-decision-not-to-bomb-iran-1.7403783 |archive-date=June 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>}}\n\n====Iran====\nIn July 2017, Carlson said that \"[w]e actually don't face any domestic threat from [[Iran]].\" He asked [[Max Boot]] to \"tell me how many Americans in the United States have been murdered by terrorists backed by Iran since 9/11?\"<ref name=\":1\" /> According to ''The New York Times'', Carlson played an influential role in dissuading Trump from launching military strikes against Iran in response to the [[2019 Iranian shoot-down of American drone|shooting down of an American drone]] in June 2019. Carlson reportedly told Trump that if he listened to his hawkish advisors and went ahead with the strikes, he would not win re-election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/21/us/politics/trump-iran-strike.html|title=Urged to Launch an Attack, Trump Listened to the Skeptics Who Said It Would Be a Costly Mistake|last=Baker|first=Peter|date=2019-06-21|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-22|last2=Haberman|first2=Maggie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Gibbons-Neff|first3=Thomas|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190622135242/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/21/us/politics/trump-iran-strike.html|archive-date=June 22, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nCarlson referred to the [[2020 Baghdad International Airport airstrike|2020 assassination]] of [[Qasem Soleimani]] as a \"quagmire.\" He criticized the \"chest-beaters\" who promote foreign interventions, particularly Senator [[Ben Sasse]] (R-NE), and asked, \"By the way, if we're still in Afghanistan, 19 years, sad years, later, what makes us think there's a quick way out of Iran?\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/01/04/media/fox-news-iran-soleimani/index.html |title=Fox's Tucker Carlson breaks with colleagues and criticizes Trump's strike on Iranian general |last=Stelter |first=Brian |date=4 January 2020 |publisher=CNN }}</ref>\n\n====Mexico====\nCarlson supported the proposed expansion of the [[Mexico\u2013United States barrier]] \u2013 citing the [[Israeli West Bank barrier]] as an example. Carlson argued: \"The estimated cost of a border wall is about $25 billion. That is estimated so let's say it is twice that. That is still a tiny fraction of the price of the pointless stalemate we're now waging in Afghanistan. That costs about $45 billion every year, not including the human cost. Compare that to $25 billion needed to restore sovereignty with the wall.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Fox's Tucker Carlson: Why Is Congress Paying for Walls in Israel, but Not the U.S. |url=https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/fox-s-tucker-carlson-why-is-congress-paying-for-walls-in-israel-but-no-the-u-s-1.6761078 |work=Haaretz |date=December 18, 2018 |access-date=June 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190317143226/https://www.haaretz.com/us-news/fox-s-tucker-carlson-why-is-congress-paying-for-walls-in-israel-but-no-the-u-s-1.6761078 |archive-date=March 17, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIn a July 2018 interview about Russian involvement in U.S. elections, Carlson said [[Mexico]] has interfered in U.S. elections \"more successfully\" than Russia by \"packing our electorate\" through [[Immigration to the United States|mass immigration]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/397329-tucker-carlson-mexico-has-interfered-in-us-elections-more-successfully-than|title=Tucker Carlson: Mexico has interfered in US elections 'more successfully' than Russia|last=Greenwood|first=Max|date=July 16, 2018|work=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|access-date=October 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008214131/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/397329-tucker-carlson-mexico-has-interfered-in-us-elections-more-successfully-than|archive-date=2018-10-08|url-status=live}}</ref> This assertion was disputed by journalist Philip Bump, who wrote that the number of Mexicans in the U.S. had decreased since 2009 and asked rhetorically: \"What good has it done Mexico to have a number of its citizens move to the United States and gain the right to vote?\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2018/07/17/tucker-carlson-identifies-the-actual-threat-to-american-democracy-hispanic-voters/|title=Analysis {{!}} Tucker Carlson identifies the actual threat to American democracy: Hispanic voters|website=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=October 8, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008214110/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2018/07/17/tucker-carlson-identifies-the-actual-threat-to-american-democracy-hispanic-voters/|archive-date=2018-10-08|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Carlson defended Trump's decision to place tariffs on Mexico unless Mexico stopped illegal immigration to the United States. Carlson said, \"When the United States is attacked by a hostile foreign power it must strike back, and make no mistake Mexico is a hostile foreign power.\"<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlson-america-must-strike-back-against-mexico|title=Tucker Carlson: America 'Must Strike Back' Against Mexico|last=Messer|first=Olivia|date=2019-06-01|website=The Daily Beast|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190602054123/https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlson-america-must-strike-back-against-mexico|archive-date=June 2, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Russia====\nCarlson has said he does not consider [[Russia]] a serious threat.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/07/tucker-carlson-is-doing-something-extraordinary/533586/|title=Tucker Carlson Is Doing Something Extraordinary|last=Beinart|first=Peter|work=[[The Atlantic]]|access-date=July 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715055655/https://www.theatlantic.com/international/archive/2017/07/tucker-carlson-is-doing-something-extraordinary/533586/|archive-date=2017-07-15|url-status=live}}</ref> Carlson has called for the United States to work with Russia in the [[American-led intervention in the Syrian Civil War]] against a common enemy like the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] (ISIS).<ref>{{cite news |title=Tucker Carlson interview goes sideways when guest accuses him of defending Putin |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-putin-hitler-ralph-peters-interview-fox-news-2017-7 |work=Business Insider |date=July 12, 2017 |access-date=June 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125171406/https://www.businessinsider.com/tucker-carlson-putin-hitler-ralph-peters-interview-fox-news-2017-7 |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/democracy-post/wp/2017/07/12/why-two-talking-heads-on-fox-news-just-rehashed-the-debates-of-1938/|title=Why two talking heads on Fox News just rehashed the debates of 1938|last=Heilbrunn|first=Jacob|date=July 12, 2017|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=July 22, 2017|last2=Heilbrunn|first2=Jacob|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170717212044/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/democracy-post/wp/2017/07/12/why-two-talking-heads-on-fox-news-just-rehashed-the-debates-of-1938/|archive-date=2017-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Peter Beinart]] of ''[[The Atlantic]]'' said Carlson has been an \"apologist for [[Donald Trump]] on the [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|Russia scandal]]\".<ref name=\":1\" /> Carlson described the controversy in the wake of revelations that [[Donald Trump Jr.]] was [[Trump Tower meeting|willing to accept]] anti-Clinton information from a Russian government official as a \"new level of hysteria\" and said that Trump Jr. had only been \"gossiping with foreigners\".<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAt the beginning of December 2019, Carlson stated \"the irony, of course, is that Putin, for all his faults, does not hate America as much as many of these people do\" meaning liberals. \"They really dislike our country. And they call other people traitors, because they\u2019re mouthing the talking points of Putin.\" He was criticized by [[Michael McFaul]] former US ambassador during the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama administration]], \"You are wrong Mr. Carlson. Putin does hate America\" urging him to \"Stop attacking Americans & defending Putin.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=Rozsa|first=Matthew|url=https://www.salon.com/2019/12/03/barack-obamas-ambassador-to-russia-calls-out-fox-news-host-tucker-carlson-for-defending-putin/|title=Barack Obama's ambassador to Russia calls out Fox News host Tucker Carlson for defending Putin|date=December 4, 2019|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pengelly|first=Martin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/dec/03/tucker-carlson-putin-nbc-chuck-todd-msnbc|title=Fox News host Tucker Carlson: Putin does not hate America like liberals do|work=The Guardian|date=December 3, 2019|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Syria====\nCarlson opposes overthrowing Syrian President [[Bashar al-Assad]].<ref name=\":1\" /> In April 2018, Carlson questioned whether Assad was responsible for the [[Douma chemical attack]] that had occurred a few days earlier and killed dozens.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/syria/fox-news-host-u-s-bombing-syria-could-lead-to-genocide-of-christian-1.5990560|title=Fox News Host: We Tolerate Saudi Atrocities in Yemen, So Why Not Assad's in Syria?|date=April 11, 2018|work=[[Haaretz]]|access-date=April 13, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180412130428/https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/syria/fox-news-host-u-s-bombing-syria-could-lead-to-genocide-of-christian-1.5990560|archive-date=April 12, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Jason|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2018/apr/13/syria-intervention-conservative-rightwing-opposition-trump|title=Why is the far right so against US intervention in Syria?|work=The Guardian|date=April 13, 2018|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref> In November 2019, Carlson repeated this claim and queried whether the attack had actually happened at all.<ref>{{cite news|last=Malaea|first=Marika|url=https://www.newsweek.com/tucker-carlson-claims-theres-no-evidence-assad-was-behind-deadly-chemical-attack-syria-that-it-1474278|title=Tucker Carlson Claims There's 'No Evidence' Assad Was Behind Deadly Chemical Attack in Syria or That it Even Happened|work=Newsweek|date=November 27, 2019|access-date=January 23, 2020}}</ref>\n\nCarlson suggested that a similar attack that occurred the year before (the [[Khan Shaykhun chemical attack]]), which was attributed to Assad's forces and which the [[OPCW-UN Joint Investigative Mechanism|OPCW JIM]] indicated was carried out with sarin that bore the regime's signature, was a [[False flag|false flag attack]] perpetrated to falsely implicate the Assad government. Carlson compared Assad's war crimes during the [[Syrian Civil War]] to [[Saudi Arabia]]'s [[Human rights violations during the Yemeni Civil War (2015\u2013present)|war crimes in Yemen]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n====North Korea====\nWhen [[Donald Trump|President Trump]] met [[Kim Jong-un|Supreme Leader Kim Jong-un]] at the Korean border in June 2019, Carlson told ''Fox & Friends'' said that although \"there's no defending the North Korean regime, it\u2019s the last real Stalinist regime in the world. It\u2019s a disgusting place obviously{{nbsp}}... you've got to be honest about what it means to lead a country, it means killing people.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Fox News' Tucker Carlson is right: Governments kill people |url=https://theweek.com/articles/850557/fox-news-tucker-carlson-right-governments-kill-people |work=The Week |date=July 2, 2019}}</ref> Carlson went on to argue that although \"not on the scale that the North Koreans do, but a lot of countries commit atrocities, including a number that [the United States] are closely allied with.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/tucker-carlson-defends-trump-liking-kim-jong-un-north-korea-monstrous-lead-country-means-1446733|title=Tucker Carlson defends Trump for liking Kim Jong-un: North Korea is 'monstrous' but 'to lead a country' means 'killing people'|date=2019-06-30|website=[[Newsweek]]|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701021651/https://www.newsweek.com/tucker-carlson-defends-trump-liking-kim-jong-un-north-korea-monstrous-lead-country-means-1446733|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/tucker-carlson-north-korea-donald-trump-fox-kim-joing-un-kill-people-a8981621.html|title=Fox host Tucker Carlson defends North Korean regime: 'Leading a country means killing people'|last=Rahim|first=Zamira|work=[[The Independent]]|date=2019-06-30|access-date=2019-07-01|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701022134/https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/tucker-carlson-north-korea-donald-trump-fox-kim-joing-un-kill-people-a8981621.html|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/30/tucker-carlson-defends-trumps-praise-kim-jong-un/1612478001/|title=Leading a country 'means killing people': Tucker Carlson defends Trump friendship with Kim Jong Un|last=Cummings|first=William|date=2019-06-30|website=[[USA Today]]|language=en|access-date=2019-07-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701015702/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/06/30/tucker-carlson-defends-trumps-praise-kim-jong-un/1612478001/|archive-date=July 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theweek.com/speedreads/850289/foxs-tucker-carlson-trumps-meeting-kim-end-what-matters-whats-good-united-states|title=Fox's Tucker Carlson on Trump's meeting with Kim: 'In the end, what matters is what's good for the United States'|date=2019-06-30|website=theweek.com|access-date=2019-06-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190630181558/https://theweek.com/speedreads/850289/foxs-tucker-carlson-trumps-meeting-kim-end-what-matters-whats-good-united-states|archive-date=June 30, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====China====\nCarlson criticized [[LeBron James]] for speaking out against [[Daryl Morey]], who had tweeted in support of the [[2019\u201320 Hong Kong protests]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tucker Carlson and Laura Ingraham blast LeBron James over support of China |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/tucker-carlson-and-laura-ingraham-blast-le-bron-james-over-support-of-china-061428613.html |work=Yahoo News |date=October 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dennis Rodman defends LeBron James and confuses Tucker Carlson |url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/dennis-rodman-defends-lebron-james-051402747.html |work=Yahoo News |date=October 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Immigration and race===\n[[File:Tucker carlson cropped.jpg|thumb|Immigrants' Rights Rally in [[National Mall|Washington Mall]], 2006]]\nCarlson is a frequent critic of [[immigration]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/12/15/tucker-carlson-suggested-immigrants-make-us-dirtier-it-cost-fox-news-an-advertiser/|title=Tucker Carlson suggested immigrants make the U.S. 'dirtier' \u2013 and it cost Fox News an advertiser|date=2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181228040820/https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2018/12/15/tucker-carlson-suggested-immigrants-make-us-dirtier-it-cost-fox-news-an-advertiser/|archive-date=2018-12-28|url-status=live}}</ref> Carlson has been accused by [[Erik Wemple]] of ''The Washington Post'' and by writers for ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'' of demonizing immigrants, both legal and illegal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/videos/2017/7/21/16008190/strikethrough-white-supremacists-love-tucker-carlson|title=Why white supremacists love Tucker Carlson|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=July 22, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831094912/https://www.vox.com/videos/2017/7/21/16008190/strikethrough-white-supremacists-love-tucker-carlson|archive-date=2017-08-31|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/07/20/in-his-quest-to-demonize-immigrants-fox-newss-tucker-carlson-misses-a-good-story/ |title=In his quest to demonize immigrants, Fox News's Tucker Carlson misses a good story |last=Wemple |first=Erik |date=July 20, 2017 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=July 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170720194837/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/07/20/in-his-quest-to-demonize-immigrants-fox-newss-tucker-carlson-misses-a-good-story/ |archive-date=2017-07-20 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/05/08/fox-newss-tucker-carlson-demagogued-a-rape-case-involving-immigrants-then-they-were-cleared/ |title=Fox News's Tucker Carlson demagogued a rape case involving immigrants. Then they were cleared. |last=Wemple |first=Erik |date=May 8, 2017 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=July 22, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829170124/https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/erik-wemple/wp/2017/05/08/fox-newss-tucker-carlson-demagogued-a-rape-case-involving-immigrants-then-they-were-cleared/ |archive-date=2017-08-29 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/3/21/17146866/tucker-carlson-demographics-immigration-fox-news|title=Watch: Tucker Carlson rails against America's demographic changes|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=March 21, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321175631/https://www.vox.com/2018/3/21/17146866/tucker-carlson-demographics-immigration-fox-news|archive-date=2018-03-21|url-status=live}}</ref> He has opposed [[Demography of the United States|demographic changes]] in the United States, writing that the demographic change seen in [[Hazleton, Pennsylvania]], which saw Hispanics go from a small minority to a majority over a 15-year period, is \"more change than human beings are designed to digest\".<ref name=\":2\" /> In 2018, Carlson suggested that mass immigration makes the United States \"dirtier\", \"poorer\" and \"more divided\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/media/421474-pacific-life-pulls-advertisements-from-tucker-carlsons-show-after-he-says|title=Pacific Life pulls ads from Tucker Carlson's show after 'poorer and dirtier' immigration comment|last=Daugherty|first=Owen|date=2018-12-14|website=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|access-date=2018-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181215015100/https://thehill.com/homenews/media/421474-pacific-life-pulls-advertisements-from-tucker-carlsons-show-after-he-says|archive-date=2018-12-15|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pacific-life-will-pause-ads-tucker-carlsons-show-reevaluate-fox-news-relationship-1169574|title=Pacific Life Insurance Will Pause Ads on Tucker Carlson's Fox News Show, \"Reevaluate\" Relationship|website=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|access-date=2018-12-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181214231413/https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pacific-life-will-pause-ads-tucker-carlsons-show-reevaluate-fox-news-relationship-1169574|archive-date=2018-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref> In response to criticism of this, he has said that \"we're not intimidated\" and \"we plan to try to say what's true until the last day. And the truth is, unregulated mass immigration has badly hurt this country's natural landscape\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/tucker-carlson-advertisers-depart-over-poorer-and-dirtier-immigration-comments/|title=Tucker Carlson's show loses advertisers over immigration comments|publisher=[[CBS News]]|access-date=2018-12-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181219011018/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/tucker-carlson-advertisers-depart-over-poorer-and-dirtier-immigration-comments/|archive-date=2018-12-19|url-status=live}}</ref> Of illegal immigration, Carlson said in May 2019, \"The flood of illegal workers into the United States has damaged our communities, ruined our schools, burdened our healthcare system and fractured our national unity.\"<ref name=\":6\" /> In December 2019, he falsely claimed that immigrants were responsible for making the Potomac River \"dirtier and dirtier\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politifact.com/punditfact/statements/2019/dec/18/tucker-carlson/carlson-falsely-claims-immigrants-are-dirtying-pot/|title=Tucker Carlson wrong about Potomac River litter|website=@politifact|language=en|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2019/dec/17/tucker-carlson-potomac-river-immigrants-litter-racist-remarks|title=Clean water group denounces Tucker Carlson's 'racist' litter comments|last=Pilkington|first=Ed|date=2019-12-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nHeidi Beirich of the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]] said that \"Carlson probably has been the No.{{nbsp}}1 commentator mainstreaming bedrock principles of white nationalism in [the US],\" and accused him of promoting the [[white genocide conspiracy theory]], the idea that white people are under attack by minorities and immigrants.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.salon.com/2018/08/15/tucker-carlson-claims-theres-no-white-nationalism-his-shows-obsessive-racism-suggests-otherwise/ |title=Tucker Carlson claims there's no white nationalism. His show's obsessive racism suggests otherwise |date=August 15, 2018 |work=[[Salon (website)|Salon]] |access-date=2019-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190102011741/https://www.salon.com/2018/08/15/tucker-carlson-claims-theres-no-white-nationalism-his-shows-obsessive-racism-suggests-otherwise/ |archive-date=2019-01-02 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Anti-Defamation League]]'s Jessica Reaves has compared Carlson's defense of the [[nuclear family]] to white supremacist anti-immigrant rhetoric.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Weill |first1=Kelly |title=Tucker Carlson's Immigration Rants Sound a Lot Like White Nationalism, Experts Say |url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlsons-immigration-rants-sound-a-lot-like-white-nationalism-experts-say |website=The Daily Beast |accessdate=March 14, 2019 |language=en |date=June 19, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190330194238/https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlsons-immigration-rants-sound-a-lot-like-white-nationalism-experts-say |archive-date=March 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[CNN]], ''[[Business Insider]]'', ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'', and ''[[GQ]]'', Carlson's show has promoted and echoed white supremacist discourse.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/28/media/fox-news-laura-ingraham-tucker-carlson-white-nationalism/index.html|title=White anxiety finds a home at Fox News|last1=Kludt|first1=Tom|last2=Stelter|first2=Brian|publisher=[[CNN Business]]|access-date=September 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181005200259/https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/28/media/fox-news-laura-ingraham-tucker-carlson-white-nationalism/index.html|archive-date=October 5, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/trump-promotes-white-supremacist-narrative-about-south-africa-2018-8 |title=White supremacists celebrate Trump's promotion of false narrative of white persecution in South Africa |work=[[Business Insider]] |date=August 23, 2018 |first=Eliza |last=Relman |access-date=September 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gq.com/story/tucker-carlson-white-nationalist-diversity-terrible|title=Tucker Carlson Proves He's Not a White Nationalist by Doubling Down on How Terrible Diversity Is|last=Darby|first=Luke|date=September 10, 2018|work=[[GQ]]|access-date=September 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180929233216/https://www.gq.com/story/tucker-carlson-white-nationalist-diversity-terrible|archive-date=September 29, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2018/3/21/17146866/tucker-carlson-demographics-immigration-fox-news|title=Watch: Tucker Carlson rails against America's demographic changes|work=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|access-date=September 29, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321175631/https://www.vox.com/2018/3/21/17146866/tucker-carlson-demographics-immigration-fox-news|archive-date=March 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Neoconservative]] pundit [[Bill Kristol]] described the views Carlson expressed on his show as \"ethno-nationalism of some kind\";<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/24/bill-kristol-takes-on-fox-news-tucker-carlson.html|title=Bill Kristol hits Fox News, Tucker Carlson for 'dumbing down' coverage, pushing 'ethno-nationalism'|last=Harwood|first=John|date=January 25, 2018|publisher=[[CNBC]]|access-date=March 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180319161614/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/01/24/bill-kristol-takes-on-fox-news-tucker-carlson.html|archive-date=March 19, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Carlson responded that Kristol had \"discredited himself years ago.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mediaite.com/tv/tucker-fires-back-at-bill-kristol-former-intellectual-who-now-exists-primarily-on-twitter/|title=Tucker Fires Back at Bill Kristol: 'Former Intellectual Who Now Exists Primarily on Twitter'|publisher=[[Mediaite]]|access-date=March 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180321063046/https://www.mediaite.com/tv/tucker-fires-back-at-bill-kristol-former-intellectual-who-now-exists-primarily-on-twitter/|archive-date=March 21, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Carlson has denied being a racist and has said he hates racism.<ref name=\":102\"/>\n\nIn call-in segments Carlson made from 2006 to 2008 on the radio show ''[[Bubba the Love Sponge]]'', Carlson said Iraq was not worth invading because it was a country made up of \"semiliterate primitive monkeys\" who \"don't use toilet paper or forks.\" He also criticized \"lunatic Muslims who are behaving like animals\", and said that any presidential candidate who vowed to \"kill as many of them as [they] can\" would be \"elected king\". Recordings of these segments were released online on March 2019 by the progressive Media Matters for America. ''[[The Washington Post]]'' labelled these comments racist.<ref name=\"WaPo recordings\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/03/12/new-tucker-carlson-audio-released-this-time-using-racist-homophobic-language/|title=Fox News host Tucker Carlson uses racist, homophobic language in second set of recordings|date=March 11, 2019|website=The Washington Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190319225139/https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/03/12/new-tucker-carlson-audio-released-this-time-using-racist-homophobic-language/|archive-date=March 19, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> Carlson also made demeaning remarks towards women, argued against the 2007 conviction of [[Warren Jeffs]], and used homophobic slurs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/03/11/fox-tucker-carlson-bubba-love-sponge-comments-spark-uproar/3127666002/|title=Tucker Carlson refuses to apologize amid uproar over past comments on 'extremely primitive' women|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190728053203/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2019/03/11/fox-tucker-carlson-bubba-love-sponge-comments-spark-uproar/3127666002/|archive-date=July 28, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"WaPo recordings\" /> Carlson declined to apologize for his comments.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/5549523/audio-tucker-carlson-racist-iraq/|title=Report Says Tucker Carlson Called Iraqis 'Primitive Monkeys'|website=Time|language=en|access-date=2019-03-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331141919/http://time.com/5549523/audio-tucker-carlson-racist-iraq/|archive-date=March 31, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWhen Mitt Romney condemned then-candidate Donald Trump after Trump evaded questions about [[David Duke]]'s support,<ref>{{cite news |title=Huckabee, Rep. King talk Trump's KKK controversy; Carson vows he's not dropping out of race |url=https://www.foxnews.com/transcript/huckabee-rep-king-talk-trumps-kkk-controversy-carson-vows-hes-not-dropping-out-of-race |work=Fox News |date=January 23, 2017 |access-date=June 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190626101216/https://www.foxnews.com/transcript/huckabee-rep-king-talk-trumps-kkk-controversy-carson-vows-hes-not-dropping-out-of-race |archive-date=June 26, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> saying it was a \"disqualifying and disgusting response [...],\" Carlson criticized Romney. Carlson said \"Obama could have written\" that.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://press.princeton.edu/titles/11084.html |title=Identity Crisis |first=John |last=Sides |first2=Michael |last2=Tesler |first3=Lynn |last3=Vavreck |publisher=[[Princeton University Press]] |page=88 |access-date=2018-10-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181012182250/https://press.princeton.edu/titles/11084.html |archive-date=2018-10-12 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCarlson concluded his July 9, 2019 ''[[Tucker Carlson Tonight]]'' episode with a 3-minute monologue about Rep. [[Ilhan Omar]] (D-MN); he criticized Omar for being ungrateful to the United States, where she had been granted asylum, and called her \"living proof that the way we practice immigration has become dangerous to this country.\" His monologue was described by ''The Guardian'' as \"scathing\", \"racially loaded\", and \"full of anti-immigrant rhetoric\".<ref name=\"theguardian_20190710\">{{Cite news| issn = 0261-3077| last = Bryant| first = Miranda| title = Ilhan Omar calls Tucker Carlson a 'racist fool' after his scathing attack on air| work = The Guardian| access-date = July 10, 2019| date = July 10, 2019| url = https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jul/10/ilhan-omar-tucker-carlson-fox-news-host-racist-fool| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190710165113/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2019/jul/10/ilhan-omar-tucker-carlson-fox-news-host-racist-fool| archive-date = July 10, 2019| url-status = live}}</ref> Congresswoman Omar responded on [[Twitter]], saying that \"advertisers should not be underwriting this kind of dangerous, hateful rhetoric.\"<ref name=\"huffpost_20190710\">{{Cite news| title = Ilhan Omar Calls Tucker Carlson 'Racist Fool' After He Claimed She Hated America| first = Jenna| last = Amatulli| work = HuffPost Canada| access-date = July 10, 2019| date = July 10, 2019| url = https://www.huffpost.com/entry/rep-ilhan-omar-tucker-carlson_n_5d255d05e4b0583e482902d7| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190710115948/https://www.huffpost.com/entry/rep-ilhan-omar-tucker-carlson_n_5d255d05e4b0583e482902d7| archive-date = July 10, 2019| url-status = live}}</ref> In their July 10 article on the incident, ''[[The Daily Beast]]'' commented that, mainly because of \"right-wing attacks that have then been amplified by members of Congress and the president\", Omar has been receiving death threats since she was elected to Congress.<ref name=\"thedailybeast_Baragona_20190710\">{{Cite news| last = Baragona| first = Justin| title = Tucker Carlson: Ilhan Omar Is 'Living Proof' Our Immigration Laws Are 'Dangerous'| access-date = July 10, 2019| date = July 10, 2019| url = https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlson-ilhan-omar-is-living-proof-our-immigration-laws-are-dangerous| work = [[The Daily Beast]]| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190711093102/https://www.thedailybeast.com/tucker-carlson-ilhan-omar-is-living-proof-our-immigration-laws-are-dangerous| archive-date = July 11, 2019| url-status = live}}</ref> According to the article, while Carlson \"has devoted numerous segments\" of his show to criticizing her, this time Carlson \"took his anti-Omar stance even further.\"<ref name=\"thedailybeast_Baragona_20190710\"/>\n\nDays after the [[2019 El Paso shooting]] which was committed by a man who released an anti-immigrant manifesto complaining of a \"Hispanic invasion\", Carlson described white supremacy as a \"hoax\" and \"a conspiracy theory used to divide the country and keep a hold on power\". He asked rhetorically, \"the combined membership of every white supremacist group in America - would they be able to fit inside a college football stadium?\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Tucker Carlson: White Supremacy Is a 'Hoax' and 'Not a Real Problem in America' |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QW-T1_Nf-pc |publisher=YouTube |work=Tucker Carlson Tonight |date=August 6, 2019 |access-date=August 7, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807170312/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QW-T1_Nf-pc&hl=en&gl=US&has_verified=1&disable_polymer=true&bpctr=9999999999 |archive-date=August 7, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/aug/07/tucker-carlson-white-supremacy-fox-news-hoax|title=Fox News host Tucker Carlson dismisses white supremacy as 'a hoax'|last=Helmore|first=Edward|date=2019-08-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-07|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807135834/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2019/aug/07/tucker-carlson-white-supremacy-fox-news-hoax|archive-date=August 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.syracuse.com/us-news/2019/08/tucker-carlson-white-supremacists-are-a-hoax-not-a-real-problem.html|title=Tucker Carlson: White supremacists are a hoax, 'not a real problem'|last=Herbert|first=Geoff|date=2019-08-07|website=syracuse.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807135834/https://www.syracuse.com/us-news/2019/08/tucker-carlson-white-supremacists-are-a-hoax-not-a-real-problem.html|archive-date=August 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> According to ''The Washington Post'', \"Carlson's argument is belied by many experts and seemingly contradicted by a recent wave of deadly attacks by men motivated by those views.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/08/07/tucker-carlson-white-supremacy-hoax-lie-not-real-problem/|title='It's not actually a real problem in America': Tucker Carlson calls white supremacy a 'hoax'|date=2019|work=The Washington Post|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190807140424/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2019/08/07/tucker-carlson-white-supremacy-hoax-lie-not-real-problem/|archive-date=August 7, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====''South Africa''====\nIn August 2018, Carlson ran a segment in which he alleged that the South African government was targeting [[White South Africans|white farmers]] during its ongoing [[Land reform in South Africa|land reform efforts]] due to anti-white racism.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/23/now-trump-is-having-a-twitter-spat-with-south-africa-over-land-reforms.html|title=Trump hypes fringe talking point about South African government 'seizing land from white farmers'|last=Ellyatt|first=Holly|date=August 23, 2018|publisher=[[CNBC]]|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828001737/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/23/now-trump-is-having-a-twitter-spat-with-south-africa-over-land-reforms.html|archive-date=2018-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/23/world/africa/trump-south-africa-white-farmers.html|title=Trump Cites False Claims of Widespread Attacks on White Farmers in South Africa|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827021629/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/23/world/africa/trump-south-africa-white-farmers.html|archive-date=2018-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-45282088|title=SA rejects Trump tweet on farmer killings|date=August 23, 2018|publisher=BBC News|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180826201956/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-45282088|archive-date=2018-08-26|url-status=live}}</ref> He interviewed Marian Tupy, an analyst at the Cato Institute, who likened South African farmers facing land seizures to white farmers in [[Zimbabwe]] who lost their farms in a controversial [[Land reform in Zimbabwe|land reform policy]] under the President [[Robert Mugabe]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Expropriation without compensation: Fact-checking Tucker Carlson and Donald Trump |url=https://www.news24.com/Analysis/expropriation-without-compensation-fact-checking-tucker-carlson-and-donald-trump-20180823 |work=News24 |date=23 August 2018 |access-date=June 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181020153353/https://www.news24.com/Analysis/expropriation-without-compensation-fact-checking-tucker-carlson-and-donald-trump-20180823 |archive-date=October 20, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the segment, Carlson criticized \"elites\" who were purportedly concerned about racism \"paying no attention\" to the \"racist government of South Africa\".<ref name=\":0\" /> He accused South African President [[Cyril Ramaphosa]] of changing the country's constitution to enable land theft of whites, and without compensation, because \"they are the wrong skin color.\"<ref name=\":72\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/69edd18af846491fa2c27b5bd3d483d4|title=Fox's Carlson stunned by reaction to stories on South Africa|agency=Associated Press|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828035602/https://apnews.com/69edd18af846491fa2c27b5bd3d483d4|archive-date=2018-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[CBS News]], [[Associated Press]], ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' described Carlson's segment on South Africa's [[Reparations (transitional justice)|corrective reparations]] as false or misleading. In addition to presenting statistics that [[South African farm attacks|violence against farmers]] had reached an all-time low, they noted that the reforms had yet to pass and were primarily aimed at land that had fallen into disuse.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-tweet-on-south-african-land-reform-draws-governments-ire-1535017460|title=Trump Tweet on South African Land Overhaul Draws Government's Ire|last=Steinhauser|first=Gabriele|date=August 23, 2018|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827002821/https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-tweet-on-south-african-land-reform-draws-governments-ire-1535017460|archive-date=2018-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":62\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/south-africa-hits-back-at-trump-over-land-seizure-tweet/|title=South Africa hits back at Trump over land seizure tweet|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180827024600/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/south-africa-hits-back-at-trump-over-land-seizure-tweet/|archive-date=2018-08-27|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":72\"/><ref name=\":82\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2018/aug/24/donald-trump/trump-tweets-incorrect-south-african-land-seizures/|title=Trump tweets incorrect on S.A. land seizures, farmers|publisher=[[PolitiFact]]|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828035531/https://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2018/aug/24/donald-trump/trump-tweets-incorrect-south-african-land-seizures/|archive-date=2018-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/ap-fact-check-trumps-claim-on-south-african-farms-off-mark/2018/08/23/242fa3e2-a6ea-11e8-ad6f-080770dcddc2_story.html|title=AP FACT CHECK: Trump's claim on South African farms off mark|website=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=August 27, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180828001725/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/ap-fact-check-trumps-claim-on-south-african-farms-off-mark/2018/08/23/242fa3e2-a6ea-11e8-ad6f-080770dcddc2_story.html|archive-date=2018-08-28|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" />\n\nFollowing the Carlson segment, President Trump tweeted that he had instructed Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] to \"closely study the South Africa land and farm seizure and large scale killing of farmers.\"<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Trump's tweet was denounced as \"'misinformed'\" by the South African government, which stated that it would address the matter through diplomatic channels.<ref name=\":5\" /> The [[White Nationalist]] South African group, [[AfriForum]], took credit for Carlson and Trump's statements, saying it believed that its campaign to influence American politics had succeeded.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nThe evening following the segment, Carlson corrected the statements he had made about the South African land reform, though he did not admit to having made errors. He said the proposed constitutional amendment was still being debated in South Africa and added that no farms had yet been expropriated.<ref name=\":72\"/> Carlson later stated in an interview that he \"doesn't believe anyone should be rewarded or punished based upon characteristics they can't control\" and added that his South Africa segment made \"an argument against tribalism\".<ref name=\":72\"/>\n\n===COVID-19 pandemic===\nCarlson has criticized government officials and other media for not taking the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]] seriously enough, while blaming China for causing the pandemic.<ref name=\"USN-Pandemic\"/><ref>{{cite news |last1=Chiu |first1=Allyson |title='China has blood on its hands': Fox News hosts join Trump in blame-shifting |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2020/03/19/coronavirus-fox-news-china/ |work=Washington Post |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> On March 9, 2020, Carlson opened his show by saying, \"People you trust, people you probably voted for, have spent weeks minimizing what is clearly a very serious problem. ... But they're wrong. It's definitely not just the flu.\"<ref name=\"wpcovid\">{{cite news |last1=Costa |first1=Robert |title=As much of America takes drastic action, some Republicans remain skeptical of the severity of the coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/as-much-of-america-takes-drastic-action-some-republicans-remain-skeptical-of-the-severity-of-the-coronavirus-pandemic/2020/03/17/f8b199c8-6786-11ea-b313-df458622c2cc_story.html |work=Washington Post |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Two anonymous sources in the White House told the ''Washington Post'' that Carlson's statements had caused President Donald Trump to reconsider his position.<ref name=\"wpcovid\" /> Carlson also told ''Vanity Fair'' that he spoke to Trump and encouraged him to take the coronavirus outbreak seriously.<ref name=\"vanityfair-carlson\">{{cite news |title=\"Dishonesty...Is Always an Indicator of Weakness\": Tucker Carlson on How He Brought His Coronavirus Message to Mar-a-Lago |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2020/03/tucker-carlson-on-how-he-brought-coronavirus-message-to-mar-a-lago |work=Vanity Fair |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"USN-Pandemic\">{{cite news |title=Tucker Carlson says he felt an obligation to meet with Trump on seriousness of coronavirus |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/entertainment/articles/2020-03-18/carlson-says-he-felt-obligation-to-meet-with-trump-on-virus |work=U.S. News |agency=The Associated Press |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nCarlson is married to Susan Carlson (n\u00e9e Andrews).<ref name=\":102\"/> They met while in high school at St. George's School and were married in 1991 in the high school chapel.<ref name=Wife>{{cite news|title=Weddings/East: Andrews-Carlson|publisher=Detroit Free Press|date=28 Aug 1991}}</ref> They have three daughters and one son, including Lillie (b. 1995), Buckley (b. 1997), Hopie (b. 1999), and Dorothy.<ref name=\"peoplemag\" /><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/15/travel/tmagazine/15T-FISH.html?pagewanted=print&position=&_r=|title=Off the Hook|last=Carlson|first=Tucker|date=May 15, 2005|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref>\n\nCarlson is an [[Episcopal Church USA|Episcopalian]] and \"loves the liturgy, though [he] abhors the liberals who run the denomination\".<ref name=\"Fighting-Words\">{{cite news |first=Kelefa |last=Sanneh |title=Tucker Carlson's Fighting Words |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/04/10/tucker-carlsons-fighting-words |work=[[The New Yorker]] |date=April 10, 2017 |accessdate=April 12, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180303224152/https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/04/10/tucker-carlsons-fighting-words |archive-date=March 3, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nCarlson quit drinking alcohol in 2002, \"having decided that neither the pleasant nights nor the unpleasant mornings were improving his life\".<ref name=\"Fighting-Words\" /> Years earlier, he had quit smoking and replaced cigarettes with nicotine gum, which he buys in bulk from New Zealand and \"chews constantly\".<ref name=\"Fighting-Words\" />\n\nCarlson is a [[Deadhead]] (a fan of the rock band the [[Grateful Dead]]), and said in a 2005 interview that he had attended more than 50 of their concerts.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[The New York Sun]] |date=August 9, 2005 |first=John P. |last=Avlon |title=Jerry Garcia's Conservative Children |url=https://www.nysun.com/opinion/jerry-garcias-conservative-children/18288/ |access-date=December 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181206235312/https://www.nysun.com/opinion/jerry-garcias-conservative-children/18288/ |archive-date=December 6, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was also good friends with the Nevada [[brothel]] owner [[Dennis Hof]].<ref name=Paul08/>\n\nCarlson's estranged mother, Lisa Vaughn, died in October 2011. Vaughn was thought to have died intestate, and in 2012, Carlson and his brother, Buckley, filed a lawsuit to determine succession of her oil and gas royalties in several counties in California, initially valued at over $125,000<ref name=lawsuit/><ref name=lawsuit2/> but later found to be over $2.5 million. However, in 2013 a one-page handwritten will was discovered in which Vaughn explicitly stated that she wished her estate to go solely to her husband and left one dollar each for Carlson and his brother.<ref name=lawsuit/><ref name=lawsuit2/> As of March 2019, the lawsuit was still under appeal.<ref name=lawsuit/><ref name=lawsuit2/>\n\nIn 2018, a group of about 20 activists from Smash Racism D.C. protested outside Carlson's [[Washington, D.C.]], home.<ref name=WaPo.Threatening>{{cite news |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=November 8, 2018 |first=Allyson |last=Chiu |title='They were threatening me and my family': Tucker Carlson's home targeted by protesters |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2018/11/08/they-were-threatening-me-my-family-tucker-carlsons-home-targeted-by-protesters/ |access-date=2019-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181229143955/https://www.washingtonpost.com/nation/2018/11/08/they-were-threatening-me-my-family-tucker-carlsons-home-targeted-by-protesters/ |archive-date=2018-12-29 |url-status=live }}</ref> Carlson's driveway was vandalized with a spray-painted [[Anarchist symbolism|anarchist symbol]]. Police responded within minutes and the protesters were dispersed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/all/antifa-group-chants-outside-vandalizes-fox-commentator-tucker-carlson-s-n934131|title=Antifa group chants outside, vandalizes Fox commentator Tucker Carlson's home|last1=Fieldstadt|first1=Elisha|access-date=2019-01-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181126153143/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/all/antifa-group-chants-outside-vandalizes-fox-commentator-tucker-carlson-s-n934131|archive-date=2018-11-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Lenz, Lyz. [https://www.cjr.org/the_profile/tucker-carlson.php \"The Mystery of Tucker Carlson,\"] ''Columbia Journalism Review,'' September 5, 2018.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Tucker Carlson}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{IMDb name|1227121}}\n* {{C-SPAN|Tucker Carlson}}\n\n{{Fox News Personalities}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carlson, Tucker}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American Episcopalians]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American broadcast news analysts]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:American people of English descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Swiss descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political journalists]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Cato Institute people]]\n[[Category:CNN people]]\n[[Category:Fox News people]]\n[[Category:Free speech activists]]\n[[Category:The Heritage Foundation]]\n[[Category:Journalists from California]]\n[[Category:Journalists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:MSNBC people]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Opinion journalists]]\n[[Category:People from Carlsbad, California]]\n[[Category:People from La Jolla, San Diego]]\n[[Category:People from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:St. George's School, Newport alumni]]\n[[Category:Television personalities from California]]\n[[Category:Trinity College (Connecticut) alumni]]\n[[Category:The Weekly Standard people]]\n[[Category:Writers from California]]\n[[Category:Conservatism in the United States]]\n[[Category:American anti\u2013illegal immigration activists]]\n", "name_user": "MyPreferredUsernameWasTaken", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSouth Africa", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tucker_Carlson"}
{"title_page": "Andrew Breitbart", "text_new": "{{short description|Conservative writer and publisher}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Andrew Breitbart\n| image              = Andrew Breitbart by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption            = Breitbart at [[Conservative Political Action Conference|CPAC]] in 2012, 3 weeks before his death\n| birth_name         = Andrew James Breitbart\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1969|02|01}}\n| birth_place        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2012|03|01|1969|02|01}}\n| death_place        = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| resting_place      = [[Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n| party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| occupation         = Writer, columnist, journalist, publisher\n| alma_mater         = [[Tulane University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Susannah Bean|1997}}\n| children           = 4\n| website            = {{URL|http://www.breitbart.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew James Breitbart''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|r|a\u026a|t|b|\u0251r|t}}; February 1, 1969 \u2013 March 1, 2012) was an American [[conservatism in the United States|conservative]] journalist,<ref name=\"c-span\"/> writer, and commentator who was the founder of [[Breitbart News]].\n\nAfter helping in the early stages of ''[[HuffPost]]''<ref name=\"huff\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/Breitbart.com-has-Drudge-to-thank-for-its-success---page-2/2100-1025_3-5976096-2.html |title=Breitbart.com has Drudge to thank for its success |accessdate=July 29, 2009 |publisher=Cnet news |date=November 2005}}</ref> and the ''[[Drudge Report]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Ng|first=Christina|title=Publisher and Author Andrew Breitbart Dead|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/andrew-breitbart-publisher-author-dead/story?id=15824337#.UCsmqJZSTsY|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref> Breitbart created ''[[Breitbart News]]'', a news and right-wing opinion website, along with multiple other \"BIG\" sites - BIGHollywood, BIGGovernment, BIGJournalism. He played central roles in the [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandals|Anthony Weiner sexting scandal]], the [[firing of Shirley Sherrod]], and the [[ACORN 2009 undercover videos controversy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.alternet.org/story/154463/what_really_killed_andrew_breitbart_the_likely_cause_of_death_the_mainstream_media_ignored|title=What Really Killed Andrew Breitbart? The Likely Cause of Death The Mainstream Media Ignored|last=Roshan|first=Maer|date=March 8, 2012|work=AlterNet|access-date=August 22, 2017|last2=Slayton|first2=Hunter R.}}</ref> Commenters such as [[Nick Gillespie]] and [[Conor Friedersdorf]] have credited Breitbart with changing how people wrote about politics by \"show[ing] how the Internet could be used to route around information bottlenecks imposed by official spokesmen and legacy news outlets\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/03/01/opinion/gillespie-breitbart/index.html|title=How Andrew Breitbart changed the news|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=March 2, 2012|first=Nick|last=Gillespie}}</ref><ref name=Atlantic1>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2012/03/andrew-breitbarts-legacy-credit-and-blame-where-its-due/253953/ | title=Andrew Breitbart's Legacy: Credit and Blame Where It's Due | publisher=Atlantic Media | work=Politics | date=March 8, 2012 | accessdate=January 13, 2015 | author=Friedersdorf, Connor}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBreitbart was born in [[Los Angeles]] on February 1, 1969.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/us/andrew-breitbart-conservative-blogger-dies-at-43.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Andrew Breitbart, Conservative Blogger, Dies at 43|last1=Peters |first1=Jeremy W.|date=March 1, 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> He was the adopted son of Gerald and Arlene Breitbart, a restaurant owner and banker respectively, and grew up in the affluent neighborhood of [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]].<ref name=\"WAPO20120301\" /> He was adopted at three weeks old and raised [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/940/000203331/#FN1|title=Andrew Breitbart|publisher=NNDB|page=1|language=English|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> His biological parents had been [[Irish American]].<ref name=\"WAPO20120301\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/andrew-breitbart-built-internet-empire-by-combining-new-media-old-fashioned-pranks/2012/03/01/gIQA7vc9kR_story.html|title=Andrew Breitbart built Internet empire by combining new media, partisan slant|last=Farhi|first=Paul|date=March 1, 2012|publisher=The Washington Post|language=English|accessdate=August 16, 2017|location=United States}}</ref> He said that his birth certificate indicated his biological father was a folk singer. His adoptive mother had [[Conversion to Judaism|converted]] to Judaism when marrying his adoptive father.<ref name=\"family\">{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2010/03/what_is_andrew_breitbart_thinking.single.html |title=Big Breitbart: Andrew Breitbart is messing with you | author= Christopher Beam |journal =Slate Magazine |accessdate=March 17, 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100322191051/http://www.slate.com/id/2247593| archivedate= March 22, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704471504574451703003340362?mod=WSJ_hpp_sections_opinion |title=The Weekend Interview With Andrew Breitbart: Taking On the 'Democrat-Media Complex' |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=October 18, 2009 | first=James | last=Taranto | date=October 16, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091020224720/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704471504574451703003340362.html?mod=WSJ_hpp_sections_opinion| archivedate= October 20, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Breitbart studied at [[Hebrew school]] and had a [[Bar Mitzvah]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Breitbart, Republican Jewish media mogul, is dead at 43|first=Jonah|last=Lowenfeld|date=March 1, 2012|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/thenon-prophet/item/andrew_breitbart_republican_jewish_media_mogul_is_dead_at_43_20120301}}</ref> Theologically he was an agnostic.<ref name=\"family\"/>\n\nBreitbart attended [[Brentwood School (Los Angeles)|Brentwood School]], one of the country's top private schools, but did not distinguish himself, saying: \"My sense of humor saved me\".<ref name=\"family\"/> However, he discovered that he loved writing, publishing his first comedic piece in the school newspaper, the ''Brentwood Eagle'', analyzing the inequality in his high school's senior and junior parking lots: \"One had Mercedes and BMWs, the other Sciroccos and GTIs.\"\"<ref name=\"family\"/> Breitbart remembers his upbringing as [[apolitical]], except in one instance: when the family's rabbi tried to defend [[Jesse Jackson]] against charges of antisemitism after his \"[[Hymietown]]\" comment, his parents left the synagogue in protest.<ref name=\"family\"/>\n\nBreitbart would remain \"proudly and playfully Jewish\" throughout his life, although not always religiously observant. He would sing Hebrew songs at work while also teasing his Orthodox Jewish colleagues for keeping a kosher diet.<ref name=\"jpost.com\">[http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-Features/Comment-Andrew-Breitbart-Israel-and-Judaism \"Comment: Andrew Breitbart, Israel and Judaism\"] By Benjamin Weinthal, ''Jerusalem Post'', April 3, 2012</ref> [[Joel Pollak]] wrote: \"He carried his faith as he carried all his convictions: with a lighthearted touch but a deep commitment.\"<ref name=\"jpost.com\"/> Breitbart later said of his profession: \"I'm glad I've become a journalist because I'd like to fight on behalf of the Israeli people... And the Israeli people, I adore and I love.\"<ref name=\"jpost.com\"/><ref>[http://www.jewishjournal.com/politics/article/andrew_breitbart_the_unabashedly_biased_journalist_20110613/ \"Andrew Breitbart, the unabashedly 'biased journalist'\u201d] by Jonah Lowenfeld, June 13, 2011, ''Jewish Journal''</ref>\n\nWhile in high school, Breitbart worked as a [[pizza delivery]] driver; he sometimes delivered to celebrities such as [[Judge Reinhold]].<ref>''Righteous Indignation'', page 17</ref> He earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in [[American studies]] from [[Tulane University]] in 1991, graduating with \"no sense of [his] future whatsoever.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/may/29/20070529-111812-9136r/print/|title='News addict' gets his fix|last=McCain|first=Robert Stacy|date=May 29, 2007|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=July 27, 2009}}</ref> His early jobs included a stint at [[cable television|cable]] channel [[E! Entertainment Television]], working for the company's [[blog|online magazine]], and some time in film production.<ref name=\"wsj\"/> He was a Lincoln Fellow at [[Claremont Institute|The Claremont Institute]] in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|last=DeVore|first=Chuck|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2012/mar/01/andrew-breitbart-most-important-conservative|title=The most important conservative of our time never to hold office {{!}} Chuck DeVore|date=2012-03-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.claremont.org/page/fellowships/lincoln-fellowship/former-lincoln-fellows/|title=Lincoln Fellowship Alumni|website=www.claremont.org|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nPreviously left-leaning in his politics, Breitbart changed his political views after experiencing \"an [[epiphany (feeling)|epiphany]]\" while watching the late 1991 [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination|confirmation hearings]] for Supreme Court justice [[Clarence Thomas]], due to what he considered unfounded attacks on the part of liberals based on former employee [[Anita Hill]]'s sexual harassment accusations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aim.org/podcast/take-aim-andrew-breitbart/|title= Take AIM: Andrew Breitbart }}</ref> Breitbart later described himself as \"a [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]] conservative\" with [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] sympathies.<ref name=\"c-span\"/>\n\nListening to radio hosts such as [[Rush Limbaugh]] helped Breitbart refine his political and philosophical positions, igniting an interest in learning that he had suppressed as a result of his distaste for the \"nihilistic musings of dead [[critical theory|critical theorists]]\"<ref name=\"Righteous Indignation, p. 36\">Righteous Indignation, p. 36</ref> that had dominated his studies at Tulane. In this era, Breitbart also read [[Camille Paglia]]'s book ''[[Sexual Personae]]'' (1990), a massive survey of Western art, literature and culture from ancient Egypt to the 20th century, which, he wrote, \"made me realize how little I really had learned in college.\"<ref name=\"Righteous Indignation, p. 36\"/>\n\n==Public life==\n\n===Authorship, research, and reporting===\nBreitbart has been lauded for his role in the \"evolution of pioneering websites\" including ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' and ''[[Drudge Report|The Drudge Report]]'', and later his \"Big\" sites. Journalists such as Nick Gillespie and Conor Friedersdorf have credited Breitbart with bringing new voices to debates about politics and culture. Breitbart told ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' in 2004 that after feeling ignored by existing outlets, \"We decided to go out and create our media.\" Described as \"a series of do-it-yourself demonstration projects\" and \"conversation pits\", the Breitbart websites have been both criticized and praised for their role in various political issues.<ref name=Atlantic1 /><ref name=\"Gillespie\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/03/01/opinion/gillespie-breitbart/index.html|title=How Andrew Breitbart changed the news|date=March 2, 2012|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=January 4, 2015|author=Gillespie, Nick}}</ref> Breitbart has been recognized for adopting an inclusive stance with regard to LGBT participation in the conservative movement. He has also been credited with helping to derail [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|conspiracy theories about Barack Obama's citizenship]].<ref name=Atlantic1 />\n\nIn 1995, Breitbart saw ''The Drudge Report'' and was so impressed that he e-mailed [[Matt Drudge]]. Breitbart said, \"I thought what he was doing was by far the coolest thing on the Internet. And I still do.\"<ref name=\"huff\" /> Breitbart described himself as \"Matt Drudge's [[bitch (insult)#In reference to men|bitch]]\"<ref name=\"biyatch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reason.com/news/show/122048.html|title=Lists: What's Your Source for That? Where Andrew Breitbart gets his information.|accessdate=October 1, 2008|publisher=ReasonOnline.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080919111403/http://www.reason.com/news/show/122048.html| archivedate= September 19, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> and selected and posted links to other news wire sources. Later, Drudge introduced him to a then still-[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Arianna Huffington]]<ref name=\"wsj\" /> and Breitbart subsequently assisted in the creation of ''The Huffington Post''.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Andrew Breitbart Helped Launch Huffington Post|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/buzzfeedpolitics/how-andrew-breitbart-helped-launch-huffington-post|publisher=Buzzfeed|accessdate=April 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBreitbart wrote a weekly column for ''[[The Washington Times]]'', which also appeared at [[Real Clear Politics]]. Breitbart also co-wrote the book ''[[Hollywood, Interrupted|Hollywood, Interrupted: Insanity Chic in Babylon]]'' with [[Mark Ebner]], a book that is highly critical of U.S. [[celebrity culture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0471450510.html |title=Wiley: Hollywood, Interrupted: Insanity Chic in Babylon \u2013 The Case Against Celebrity \u2013 Andrew Breitbart, Mark Ebner |work=wiley.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705051111/http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0471450510.html |archivedate=July 5, 2009 }}</ref> On January 19, 2011, the [[LGBT conservatism|conservative gay rights]] group [[GOProud]] announced Breitbart had joined its Advisory Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goproud.org/conservative-media-mogul-andrew-breitbart-to-join-goproud%E2%80%99s-advisory-council/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110803200215/http://www.goproud.org/conservative-media-mogul-andrew-breitbart-to-join-goproud%e2%80%99s-advisory-council/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 3, 2011 |title=Conservative Media Mogul Andrew Breitbart to Join GOProud's Advisory Council |publisher=Goproud.org |date=January 21, 2011 |accessdate=September 20, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, Grand Central Publishing released Breitbart's book ''Righteous Indignation: Excuse Me While I Save the World'', in which he discussed his own political evolution and the part he took in the rise of [[new media]], most notably at the Drudge Report and ''The Huffington Post''.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\nIn June 2011, Breitbart's websites broke the story that congressman [[Anthony Weiner]] was [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandal|sending women revealing photographs of himself]].<ref>Daly, Corbett D. [http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20069298-503544.html \"Conservative website posts private pictures of Anthony Weiner.\"] [[CBS News]]. June 6, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Breitbart.com===\n{{main|Breitbart News Network}}\nBreitbart launched his first website as a news site; it is often linked to by the ''[[Drudge Report]]'' and other websites. It has wire stories from the [[Associated Press]], [[Reuters]], [[Agence France-Presse]], [[Fox News]], [[PR Newswire]], and [[U.S. Newswire]], as well as direct links to a number of major international newspapers. Its political viewpoint as well as its audience runs to the [[right-wing|right]] within the U.S. political spectrum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.org/interactives/media-polarization/outlet/breitbart/|title=Where Breitbart's Audience Fits on the Political Spectrum |date=October 21, 2014|work=Pew Research Center's Journalism Project}}</ref> In 2007, Breitbart launched a video blog, Breitbart.tv.<ref>[[Rob Owen (journalist)|Owen, Rob]]. [http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07075/769897-96.stm The next wave: Ex-WTAE anchor Scott Baker changes channel to run Web news site], ''[[Post-Gazette]]''</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Breitbart and one of his editors [[Larry O'Connor (radio host)|Larry O'Connor]] were sued for [[defamation]] by [[Shirley Sherrod]], who had been [[Firing of Shirley Sherrod|fired]] after Breitbart posted a video of a speech given by Sherrod. The video had been selectively edited to suggest that she had purposely discriminated against a white farmer, while in reality the unedited video told the story of how she had helped that farmer.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Zeleny| first = Jeff|author2=  Wheaton, Sarah| title = At Gathering, Ron Paul Is No. 1 for 2012| newspaper = [[The New York Times]]| pages = A21 | date = February 13, 2011| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/13/us/politics/13cpac.html?_r=1&emc=eta1 | accessdate =February 14, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Gerstein\" /> Breitbart himself maintained that he stated this in his article about it, and that the purpose of the video was to show the crowd's positive reaction to Sherrod's statements about discriminating against the white farmer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/128436-andrew-breitbart/ |title= Breitbart on ACORN, Sherrod, and 'Gotcha' Journalism |author=Stephen Reader |date= May 11, 2011}}</ref> In July 2015, it was reported that Sherrod and Breitbart's estate had reached a tentative settlement.<ref name=\"Gerstein\">{{cite news|last1=Gerstein|first1=Josh|title=Breitbart, Sherrod near libel settlement|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/07/breitbart-sherrod-near-libel-settlement-209824.html|accessdate=August 18, 2015|publisher=Politico|date=July 1, 2015}}</ref> It was reported October 1, 2016, that the lawsuit was settled.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://talkingpointsmemo.com/muckraker/sherrod-breitbart-lawsuit-settle |title= Ex-USDA Official Settles Her Lawsuit Over Breitbart Video That Got Her Fired |work= [[Talking Points Memo]] |author= Tierney Sneed |date= October 1, 2015 |accessdate= October 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Commentaries===\nIn 2009, Breitbart appeared as a commentator on ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]'' and ''[[Dennis Miller]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=BREITBART: 'My Real Time With Bill Maher'|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/mar/16/my-real-time-with-bill-maher/?page=all|accessdate=January 6, 2016|publisher=Washington Times|date=March 16, 2009}}</ref> In 2004, he was a guest commentator on [[Fox News Channel|Fox News Channel's]] morning show and frequently appeared as a guest panelist on [[Fox News]]'s late night program, ''[[Red Eye (TV series)|Red Eye w/ Greg Gutfeld]]''. Breitbart also appeared as a commentator in the 2004 documentary ''[[Michael Moore Hates America]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/212271/michael-wilson-loves-america/andrew-leigh |title=National Review Online|publisher=nationalreview.com |accessdate=November 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2009, Breitbart appeared on the [[C-SPAN]] program ''[[Washington Journal]]''. He gave his opinions on the mainstream media, Hollywood, the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama Administration]] and his personal political views, having heated debates with several callers.<ref name=\"c-span\">[http://www.c-spanarchives.org/program/289587-8 Andrew Breitbart, Breitbart.com Publisher] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002155759/http://www.c-spanarchives.org/program/289587-8 |date=October 2, 2012 }} [[C-SPAN]], October 22, 2009. Breitbart referred to the \"Democrat-media complex\" several times...</ref>\n\nIn the hours immediately following Senator [[Ted Kennedy]]'s death, Breitbart called Kennedy a \"villain\", a \"duplicitous bastard\", a \"prick\"<ref name=\"politico\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0809/26475.html|title=Not all Kennedy critics hold fire|accessdate=August 26, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090827091650/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0809/26475.html| archivedate= August 27, 2009| url-status= live}}</ref> and \"a special pile of human excrement,\" adding, \"Sorry, he destroyed lives. And he knew it,\" referring to Kennedy's actions during the [[Chappaquiddick incident]], the [[Robert Bork Supreme Court nomination]], and the [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination]].<ref>\"[http://www.pennlive.com/editorials/index.ssf/2009/08/compromise_what_pennsylvania_l.html Compromise: what Pennsylvania lawmakers could learn from Ted Kennedy]\" (editorial), ''[[The Patriot-News]]'' (Pennsylvania), August 28, 2009. Retrieved September 24, 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/278320 |title=Opinion: Ted Kennedy, the liberal adversary to the conservative movement |publisher=digitaljournal.com |accessdate=September 24, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091003110202/http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/278320| archivedate= October 3, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Breitbart received the [[Reed Irvine]] [[Accuracy in Media]] Award during the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] in Washington, D.C. During his acceptance speech, he responded directly to accusations by ''[[The New York Times]]'' reporter Kate Zernike that [[Jason Mattera]], a young conservative activist, had been using \"racial tones\" in his [[allusions]] to President [[Barack Obama]], and had spoken in a \"[[Chris Rock]] voice\". From the podium, Breitbart called Zernike \"a despicable human being\" for having made such allegations about what, according to him, was just Mattera's Brooklyn accent.<ref>Beam, Christopher, [http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2010/03/what_is_andrew_breitbart_thinking.html \"'Media Is Everything. It's Everything.' Slate's 2010 profile of Andrew Breitbart\"], ''Slate.com'', March 15, 2010.</ref> At the same conference, Breitbart was also filmed saying to journalist [[Max Blumenthal]] that he found him to be \"a jerk\" and \"a despicable human being\" over a blog entry in which Blumenthal accused Breitbart of employing a racist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MIeByOeERpY |title=Max Blumenthal confronted by Andrew Breitbart and Larry O'Connor/Stage right at CPAC 10 |publisher=YouTube |date=February 20, 2010 |accessdate=March 1, 2012}}</ref> Blumenthal was referring to [[James O'Keefe]] over his having attended a [[Georgetown Law Center]] discussion on race featuring Kevin Martin, [[John Derbyshire]], and [[Jared Taylor]], the last of whom founded ''[[American Renaissance (magazine)|American Renaissance]]'', an online magazine often considered white supremacist. Neither O'Keefe nor Breitbart endorsed Taylor's views.\n\nIn 2011, Breitbart said that \"of course\" [[Donald Trump]] was not a conservative, adding:\n\n<blockquote>But this is a message to those candidates who are languishing at 2 percent and 3 percent within the Republican Party who are brand names in Washington, but the rest of the country don't know ... celebrity is everything in this country. And if these guys don't learn how to play the media the way that Barack Obama played the media last election cycle and the way that Donald Trump is playing the election cycle, we're going to probably get a celebrity candidate.<ref name=\"WP.Aug.7.16\">{{cite news|last1=Weigel|first1=David|title=Five things to know about Breitbart, the new force in the Trump campaign|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/17/five-things-to-know-about-breitbart-the-new-force-in-the-trump-campaign/|accessdate=March 18, 2017|work=Washington Post|date=August 17, 2016}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nThese comments resurfaced after the controversy of Donald Trump hiring [[Breitbart News]]' executive chairman [[Steve Bannon]] to be his [[White House Chief Strategist]].<ref name=\"WP.Aug.7.16\" />\n\n===Activism===\n{{See also|Tea party movement#Reports of slurs at health care reform protests|l1=Tea Party movement}}\nBreitbart often appeared as a speaker at [[Tea Party movement]] events across the U.S. For example, Breitbart was a speaker at the first National Tea Party Convention at Gaylord Opryland Hotel in Nashville on February 6, 2010.<ref>\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_D2YLnaTr6w/ Breitbart Keynote Part 1 of 4, Nashville, February 2010]{{dead link|date=March 2012 | Breitbart Keynote Part 1 of 4, Nashville, January]\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N3os3js4B0/ Part 2]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3t6XSeR5GEw/ Part 3]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jJZmKGE6tdE/ Part 4]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}</ref> Breitbart later involved himself in a controversy over allegations of [[homophobia|homophobic]] and [[racism|racial]] slurs being used at a March 20, 2010, rally at the [[United States Capitol]] in Washington, D.C., by asserting that slurs were never used, and that \"it was a set-up\" by [[Nancy Pelosi]] and the Democratic Party. Breitbart offered to donate $100,000 to the [[United Negro College Fund]] \"for any audio/video footage of the [[nigger|N-word]] being hurled,\" claiming that the several Congressmen made it up. Breitbart insisted Congressman [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]] and several other witnesses were forced to lie, concluding that \"Nancy Pelosi did a great disservice to a great civil rights icon by thrusting him out there to perform this mischievous task. His reputation is now on the line as a result of her desperation to take down the Tea Party movement.\"<ref name=\"AB-100402\">{{cite web |url=http://bigjournalism.com/abreitbart/2010/04/02/barack-obamas-helter-skelter-insane-clown-posse-alinsky-planes-to-deconstruct-america/ |title=Barack Obama's Helter-Skelter, Insane Clown Posse, Alinsky Plans to 'Deconstruct' America |first=Andrew |last=Breitbart |publisher=Big Journalism |date=April 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302143429/http://bigjournalism.com/abreitbart/2010/04/02/barack-obamas-helter-skelter-insane-clown-posse-alinsky-planes-to-deconstruct-america/ |archivedate=March 2, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"WPost Omb\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/04/09/AR2010040903716.html|title=Allegations of spitting and slurs at Capitol protest merit more reporting|date=April 11, 2010|work=Washington Post|accessdate=April 14, 2010| first=Andrew |last=Alexander}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, a [[YouTube]] video showed Breitbart yelling at [[Occupy D.C.]] protesters outside a Washington hotel hosting a [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC). The video showed security escorting Breitbart back to the hotel while he told the protesters to \"behave yourself\", and alluding to reported assaults of women at Occupy encampments, he repeatedly yelled, \"Stop raping people\", and called the protestors \"filthy, filthy, raping, murdering freaks!\" David Carr said with the incident Breitbart had caused his last \"viral storm on the Web.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/15/business/media/the-life-and-death-of-andrew-breitbart.html?pagewanted=all |work=The New York Times |first=David |last=Carr |title=The Life and Death of Andrew Breitbart |date=April 13, 2012}}</ref><ref name=CPAC>Sources that describe the confrontation with Occupy protesters at CPAC 2012:\n* [http://www.theatlanticwire.com/politics/2012/02/web-talking-about-andrew-breitbarts-occupy-DC-freakout/48598/ The Web is Talking About Andrew Breitbart's Occupy D.C. Freakout], by Seth Abramovitch, ''[[The Atlantic]]'', February 12, 2012\n* [http://www.slate.com/blogs/weigel/2012/02/11/eighty_seven_seconds_of_andrew_breitbart_yelling.html Eighty-Seven Seconds of Andrew Breitbart Yelling], by David Weigel, ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', February 11, 2012\n* [http://articles.businessinsider.com/2012-03-06/politics/31125723_1_andrew-breitbart-cpac-bloggers WATCH: Andrew Breitbart LOSES It On Occupy Wall Street Protesters]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121212021939/http://articles.businessinsider.com/2012-03-06/politics/31125723_1_andrew-breitbart-cpac-bloggers |date=December 12, 2012 }}, by Grace Wyler, ''[[Business Insider]]'', March 6, 2012\n* [http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/03/01/andrew-breitbart-dies-most-controversial-moments-video.html Andrew Breitbart Dies: Most Controversial Moments (Video)], by ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', March 1, 2012\n* [http://www.observer.com/2012/03/andrew-breitbart-dead-03012012/ Andrew Breitbart Dead at 43], by Kat Stoeffel and Hunter Walker, ''[[The New York Observer]]'', January 3, 2012\n* [http://campusprogress.org/articles/exclusive_video_andrew_breitbart_to_occupiers_stop_raping_people/ EXCLUSIVE VIDEO: Blogger Andrew Breitbart to Occupiers: 'Stop Raping People!']   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419075311/http://campusprogress.org/articles/exclusive_video_andrew_breitbart_to_occupiers_stop_raping_people/ |date=April 19, 2012 }}, by Emily Crockett, ''[[Campus Progress]]'', February 10, 2012\n* [http://www.mediaite.com/tv/andrew-breitbart-confronts-occupy-crowd-at-cpac-demands-they-stop-raping-people/ Andrew Breitbart Confronts Occupy Crowd At CPAC, Demands They 'Stop Raping People'], by Frances Martel, ''[[Mediaite]]'', March 1, 2012\n* [http://dcist.com/2012/02/andrew_breitbart_flips_out_at_occup.php Right-Wing Blog Mogul Andrew Breitbart Flips Out at Occupy D.C. Outside CPAC]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212061609/http://dcist.com/2012/02/andrew_breitbart_flips_out_at_occup.php |date=February 12, 2012 }}, by Benjamin R. Freed, ''[[DCist]]'', February 10, 2012\n* [http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2012/02/occupiers_berat.php Occupiers Berated By Breitbart; ''Times'' Looks At Movement's Next Moves] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413053517/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2012/02/occupiers_berat.php |date=April 13, 2012 }}, by Esther Zuckerman, ''[[The Village Voice]]'', February 11, 2012</ref>\n\nBreitbart appeared posthumously in ''[[Occupy Unmasked]]'', a documentary film by [[Steve Bannon]] that contends that the [[Occupy movement|Occupy Wall Street movement]] of \"largely na\u00efve students and legitimately concerned citizens looking for answers\" is actually orchestrated by sinister, violent, and organized leaders with the purpose of not just changing, but destroying the American government.<ref>{{cite web|title=Occupyunmasked.com|url=http://www.occupyunmasked.com/about.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nBreitbart was married to Susannah Bean, the daughter of actor [[Orson Bean]] and fashion designer Carolyn Maxwell, and had four children.<ref name=\"huff\"/><ref name=\"Saad\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-orson-bean-2050-story.html |first1=Nardine |last1=Saad |date=February 8, 2020 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |title=OBITUARIES Actor Orson Bean, local theater mainstay who rose to fame as a 1950s TV personality, dies |accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"AP\"> {{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/actor-comedian-orson-bean-91-114135652.html |title=Celebrity Actor-comedian Orson Bean, 91, hit and killed by car in LA |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 8, 2020|via=[[Yahoo!]]}}</ref>\n\nOn the night of February 29, 2012, Breitbart collapsed suddenly while walking in [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]]. He was rushed to [[Ronald Reagan UCLA Medical Center]], where he was pronounced dead just after midnight, March 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/15/business/media/the-life-and-death-of-andrew-breitbart.html |title=The Provocateur | publisher =New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autopsyfiles.org/reports/Celebs/breitbart,%20andrew_report.pdf |title=Andrew Breitbart autopsy report | publisher =Autopsyfile.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/andrew-breitbart-publisher-author-dead/story?id=15824337\n |title=Publisher and Author Andrew Breitbart Dead\n |first=Christina |last=Ng |date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> He was 43 years old. An [[autopsy]] by the [[Los Angeles County Coroner's Office]] showed that he had [[hypertrophic cardiomyopathy]], with focal coronary [[atherosclerosis]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/05/commentator-and-editor-andrew-breitbart-died-of-heart-failure-and-hard-up-to-a-60-narrowing-of-a-major-artery-and-was-unde.html|title=Andrew Breitbart died of heart failure, narrowing of artery, coroner finds|first=Andrew|last=Blankstein|work=L.A. Times|publisher=L.A. Times|date=May 16, 2012}}</ref> and died of a [[heart attack]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/us/andrew-breitbart-conservative-blogger-dies-at-43.html|title=Andrew Breitbart, Conservative Blogger, Dies at 43|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|date=2012-03-01|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref> His burial was in the Jewish cemetery [[Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery|Hillside Memorial Park]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Andrew James Breitbart |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/86040288/andrew-james-breitbart |website=Find A Grave\u2122 |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn remembrance, Republican presidential candidates [[Rick Santorum]], [[Mitt Romney]], and [[Newt Gingrich]] praised Breitbart.<ref name=\"media star\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nwherald.com/2012/03/06/limbaugh-and-the-gop-the-media-stars-and-politics/agdmwrt/?page=3|title=Limbaugh and the GOP: The media stars and politics|author=Beth Fouhey|author2=Philip Elliott|work=Associated Press|date=March 6, 2012|accessdate=March 6, 2012}}</ref> Santorum called Breitbart's death \"a huge loss\" that strongly affected him.<ref name=\"media star\"/><ref>{{cite video |date=March 1, 2012 |title=CBS News|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/andrew-breitbart-death-shocks-santorum-100/2012/03/01/gIQAqm8qkR_video.html}}</ref> Romney praised Breitbart as a \"fearless conservative,\" while Gingrich remembered him as \"the most innovative pioneer in conservative activist social media in America\".<ref name=\"media star\" /> A special episode of ''[[Red Eye (TV series)|Red Eye w/ Greg Gutfeld]]'' aired the day after his death as the host and panelists paid their tributes and showed clips from his appearances on the show.<ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CLqEPe9emsU |title=Red Eye Remembers Andrew Breitbart |accessdate= September 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book|title = Righteous Indignation: Excuse Me While I Save the World|publisher = [[Grand Central Publishing]]|date = April 15, 2011|isbn = 978-0-446-57282-8|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/righteousindigna0000brei|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|first = Mark C.|last =  Ebner|authorlink = Mark Ebner |author2=Andrew Breitbart |title = [[Hollywood, Interrupted]]: Insanity Chic in Babylon \u2013 The Case Against Celebrity|publisher = [[John Wiley & Sons|Wiley]]|date = March 10, 2005|isbn = 978-0-471-70624-3}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q503917|q=Andrew Breitbart|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no|c=category:Andrew Breitbart}}\n* {{IMDb name|1620485}}\n* {{C-SPAN|andrewbreitbart}}\n* {{Worldcat id|id=lccn-no2004-14171}}\n* {{Find a Grave|86040288}}\n\n{{Andrew Breitbart|state=expanded}}\n{{Portalbar|Biography|California|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breitbart, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n[[Category:American alternative journalists]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American online journalists]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:Breitbart News people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:HuffPost]]\n[[Category:Jewish American journalists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish agnostics]]\n[[Category:National Review people]]\n[[Category:People from Brentwood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:The Washington Times people]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Conservative writer and publisher}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Andrew Breitbart\n| image              = Andrew Breitbart by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg\n| caption            = Breitbart at [[Conservative Political Action Conference|CPAC]] in 2012, 3 weeks before his death\n| birth_name         = Andrew James Breitbart\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|1969|02|01}}\n| birth_place        = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2012|03|01|1969|02|01}}\n| death_place        = Los Angeles, California, U.S.\n| resting_place      = [[Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n| party              = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| occupation         = Writer, columnist, journalist, publisher\n| alma_mater         = [[Tulane University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Susannah Bean|1997}}\n| children           = 4\n| website            = {{URL|http://www.breitbart.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Andrew James Breitbart''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|r|a\u026a|t|b|\u0251r|t}}; February 1, 1969 \u2013 March 1, 2012) was an American [[conservatism in the United States|conservative]] journalist,<ref name=\"c-span\"/> writer, and commentator who was the founder of [[Breitbart News]].\n\nAfter helping in the early stages of ''[[HuffPost]]''<ref name=\"huff\">{{cite web|url=http://news.cnet.com/Breitbart.com-has-Drudge-to-thank-for-its-success---page-2/2100-1025_3-5976096-2.html |title=Breitbart.com has Drudge to thank for its success |accessdate=July 29, 2009 |publisher=Cnet news |date=November 2005}}</ref> and the ''[[Drudge Report]]'',<ref>{{cite news|last=Ng|first=Christina|title=Publisher and Author Andrew Breitbart Dead|url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/andrew-breitbart-publisher-author-dead/story?id=15824337#.UCsmqJZSTsY|publisher=ABC News|accessdate=August 15, 2012}}</ref> Breitbart created ''[[Breitbart News]]'', a news and right-wing opinion website, along with multiple other \"BIG\" sites - BIGHollywood, BIGGovernment, BIGJournalism. He played central roles in the [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandals|Anthony Weiner sexting scandal]], the [[firing of Shirley Sherrod]], and the [[ACORN 2009 undercover videos controversy]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.alternet.org/story/154463/what_really_killed_andrew_breitbart_the_likely_cause_of_death_the_mainstream_media_ignored|title=What Really Killed Andrew Breitbart? The Likely Cause of Death The Mainstream Media Ignored|last=Roshan|first=Maer|date=March 8, 2012|work=AlterNet|access-date=August 22, 2017|last2=Slayton|first2=Hunter R.}}</ref> Commenters such as [[Nick Gillespie]] and [[Conor Friedersdorf]] have credited Breitbart with changing how people wrote about politics by \"show[ing] how the Internet could be used to route around information bottlenecks imposed by official spokesmen and legacy news outlets\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/03/01/opinion/gillespie-breitbart/index.html|title=How Andrew Breitbart changed the news|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=March 2, 2012|first=Nick|last=Gillespie}}</ref> .<ref name=Atlantic1>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2012/03/andrew-breitbarts-legacy-credit-and-blame-where-its-due/253953/ | title=Andrew Breitbart's Legacy: Credit and Blame Where It's Due | publisher=Atlantic Media | work=Politics | date=March 8, 2012 | accessdate=January 13, 2015 | author=Friedersdorf, Connor}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nBreitbart was born in [[Los Angeles]] on February 1, 1969.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/us/andrew-breitbart-conservative-blogger-dies-at-43.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0|title=Andrew Breitbart, Conservative Blogger, Dies at 43|last1=Peters |first1=Jeremy W.|date=March 1, 2012|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> He was the adopted son of Gerald and Arlene Breitbart, a restaurant owner and banker respectively, and grew up in the affluent neighborhood of [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]].<ref name=\"WAPO20120301\" /> He was adopted at three weeks old and raised [[Jewish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nndb.com/people/940/000203331/#FN1|title=Andrew Breitbart|publisher=NNDB|page=1|language=English|accessdate=August 29, 2017}}</ref> His biological parents had been [[Irish American]].<ref name=\"WAPO20120301\">{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/andrew-breitbart-built-internet-empire-by-combining-new-media-old-fashioned-pranks/2012/03/01/gIQA7vc9kR_story.html|title=Andrew Breitbart built Internet empire by combining new media, partisan slant|last=Farhi|first=Paul|date=March 1, 2012|publisher=The Washington Post|language=English|accessdate=August 16, 2017|location=United States}}</ref> He said that his birth certificate indicated his biological father was a folk singer. His adoptive mother had [[Conversion to Judaism|converted]] to Judaism when marrying his adoptive father.<ref name=\"family\">{{cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2010/03/what_is_andrew_breitbart_thinking.single.html |title=Big Breitbart: Andrew Breitbart is messing with you | author= Christopher Beam |journal =Slate Magazine |accessdate=March 17, 2010 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100322191051/http://www.slate.com/id/2247593| archivedate= March 22, 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704471504574451703003340362?mod=WSJ_hpp_sections_opinion |title=The Weekend Interview With Andrew Breitbart: Taking On the 'Democrat-Media Complex' |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=October 18, 2009 | first=James | last=Taranto | date=October 16, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091020224720/http://online.wsj.com/article/SB10001424052748704471504574451703003340362.html?mod=WSJ_hpp_sections_opinion| archivedate= October 20, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Breitbart studied at [[Hebrew school]] and had a [[Bar Mitzvah]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Andrew Breitbart, Republican Jewish media mogul, is dead at 43|first=Jonah|last=Lowenfeld|date=March 1, 2012|work=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]]|url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/thenon-prophet/item/andrew_breitbart_republican_jewish_media_mogul_is_dead_at_43_20120301}}</ref> Theologically he was an agnostic.<ref name=\"family\"/>\n\nBreitbart attended [[Brentwood School (Los Angeles)|Brentwood School]], one of the country's top private schools, but did not distinguish himself, saying: \"My sense of humor saved me\".<ref name=\"family\"/> However, he discovered that he loved writing, publishing his first comedic piece in the school newspaper, the ''Brentwood Eagle'', analyzing the inequality in his high school's senior and junior parking lots: \"One had Mercedes and BMWs, the other Sciroccos and GTIs.\"\"<ref name=\"family\"/> Breitbart remembers his upbringing as [[apolitical]], except in one instance: when the family's rabbi tried to defend [[Jesse Jackson]] against charges of antisemitism after his \"[[Hymietown]]\" comment, his parents left the synagogue in protest.<ref name=\"family\"/>\n\nBreitbart would remain \"proudly and playfully Jewish\" throughout his life, although not always religiously observant. He would sing Hebrew songs at work while also teasing his Orthodox Jewish colleagues for keeping a kosher diet.<ref name=\"jpost.com\">[http://www.jpost.com/Jewish-World/Jewish-Features/Comment-Andrew-Breitbart-Israel-and-Judaism \"Comment: Andrew Breitbart, Israel and Judaism\"] By Benjamin Weinthal, ''Jerusalem Post'', April 3, 2012</ref> [[Joel Pollak]] wrote: \"He carried his faith as he carried all his convictions: with a lighthearted touch but a deep commitment.\"<ref name=\"jpost.com\"/> Breitbart later said of his profession: \"I'm glad I've become a journalist because I'd like to fight on behalf of the Israeli people... And the Israeli people, I adore and I love.\"<ref name=\"jpost.com\"/><ref>[http://www.jewishjournal.com/politics/article/andrew_breitbart_the_unabashedly_biased_journalist_20110613/ \"Andrew Breitbart, the unabashedly 'biased journalist'\u201d] by Jonah Lowenfeld, June 13, 2011, ''Jewish Journal''</ref>\n\nWhile in high school, Breitbart worked as a [[pizza delivery]] driver; he sometimes delivered to celebrities such as [[Judge Reinhold]].<ref>''Righteous Indignation'', page 17</ref> He earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in [[American studies]] from [[Tulane University]] in 1991, graduating with \"no sense of [his] future whatsoever.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2007/may/29/20070529-111812-9136r/print/|title='News addict' gets his fix|last=McCain|first=Robert Stacy|date=May 29, 2007|work=The Washington Times|accessdate=July 27, 2009}}</ref> His early jobs included a stint at [[cable television|cable]] channel [[E! Entertainment Television]], working for the company's [[blog|online magazine]], and some time in film production.<ref name=\"wsj\"/> He was a Lincoln Fellow at [[Claremont Institute|The Claremont Institute]] in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|last=DeVore|first=Chuck|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/cifamerica/2012/mar/01/andrew-breitbart-most-important-conservative|title=The most important conservative of our time never to hold office {{!}} Chuck DeVore|date=2012-03-01|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-11|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.claremont.org/page/fellowships/lincoln-fellowship/former-lincoln-fellows/|title=Lincoln Fellowship Alumni|website=www.claremont.org|access-date=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n\nPreviously left-leaning in his politics, Breitbart changed his political views after experiencing \"an [[epiphany (feeling)|epiphany]]\" while watching the late 1991 [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination|confirmation hearings]] for Supreme Court justice [[Clarence Thomas]], due to what he considered unfounded attacks on the part of liberals based on former employee [[Anita Hill]]'s sexual harassment accusations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aim.org/podcast/take-aim-andrew-breitbart/|title= Take AIM: Andrew Breitbart }}</ref> Breitbart later described himself as \"a [[Ronald Reagan|Reagan]] conservative\" with [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] sympathies.<ref name=\"c-span\"/>\n\nListening to radio hosts such as [[Rush Limbaugh]] helped Breitbart refine his political and philosophical positions, igniting an interest in learning that he had suppressed as a result of his distaste for the \"nihilistic musings of dead [[critical theory|critical theorists]]\"<ref name=\"Righteous Indignation, p. 36\">Righteous Indignation, p. 36</ref> that had dominated his studies at Tulane. In this era, Breitbart also read [[Camille Paglia]]'s book ''[[Sexual Personae]]'' (1990), a massive survey of Western art, literature and culture from ancient Egypt to the 20th century, which, he wrote, \"made me realize how little I really had learned in college.\"<ref name=\"Righteous Indignation, p. 36\"/>\n\n==Public life==\n\n===Authorship, research, and reporting===\nBreitbart has been lauded for his role in the \"evolution of pioneering websites\" including ''[[The Huffington Post]]'' and ''[[Drudge Report|The Drudge Report]]'', and later his \"Big\" sites. Journalists such as Nick Gillespie and Conor Friedersdorf have credited Breitbart with bringing new voices to debates about politics and culture. Breitbart told ''[[Reason (magazine)|Reason]]'' in 2004 that after feeling ignored by existing outlets, \"We decided to go out and create our media.\" Described as \"a series of do-it-yourself demonstration projects\" and \"conversation pits\", the Breitbart websites have been both criticized and praised for their role in various political issues.<ref name=Atlantic1 /><ref name=\"Gillespie\">{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/03/01/opinion/gillespie-breitbart/index.html|title=How Andrew Breitbart changed the news|date=March 2, 2012|work=[[CNN]]|accessdate=January 4, 2015|author=Gillespie, Nick}}</ref> Breitbart has been recognized for adopting an inclusive stance with regard to LGBT participation in the conservative movement. He has also been credited with helping to derail [[Barack Obama citizenship conspiracy theories|conspiracy theories about Barack Obama's citizenship]].<ref name=Atlantic1 />\n\nIn 1995, Breitbart saw ''The Drudge Report'' and was so impressed that he e-mailed [[Matt Drudge]]. Breitbart said, \"I thought what he was doing was by far the coolest thing on the Internet. And I still do.\"<ref name=\"huff\" /> Breitbart described himself as \"Matt Drudge's [[bitch (insult)#In reference to men|bitch]]\"<ref name=\"biyatch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.reason.com/news/show/122048.html|title=Lists: What's Your Source for That? Where Andrew Breitbart gets his information.|accessdate=October 1, 2008|publisher=ReasonOnline.com| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080919111403/http://www.reason.com/news/show/122048.html| archivedate= September 19, 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> and selected and posted links to other news wire sources. Later, Drudge introduced him to a then still-[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Arianna Huffington]]<ref name=\"wsj\" /> and Breitbart subsequently assisted in the creation of ''The Huffington Post''.<ref>{{cite web|title=How Andrew Breitbart Helped Launch Huffington Post|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/buzzfeedpolitics/how-andrew-breitbart-helped-launch-huffington-post|publisher=Buzzfeed|accessdate=April 24, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBreitbart wrote a weekly column for ''[[The Washington Times]]'', which also appeared at [[Real Clear Politics]]. Breitbart also co-wrote the book ''[[Hollywood, Interrupted|Hollywood, Interrupted: Insanity Chic in Babylon]]'' with [[Mark Ebner]], a book that is highly critical of U.S. [[celebrity culture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0471450510.html |title=Wiley: Hollywood, Interrupted: Insanity Chic in Babylon \u2013 The Case Against Celebrity \u2013 Andrew Breitbart, Mark Ebner |work=wiley.com |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090705051111/http://www.wiley.com/WileyCDA/WileyTitle/productCd-0471450510.html |archivedate=July 5, 2009 }}</ref> On January 19, 2011, the [[LGBT conservatism|conservative gay rights]] group [[GOProud]] announced Breitbart had joined its Advisory Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goproud.org/conservative-media-mogul-andrew-breitbart-to-join-goproud%E2%80%99s-advisory-council/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110803200215/http://www.goproud.org/conservative-media-mogul-andrew-breitbart-to-join-goproud%e2%80%99s-advisory-council/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 3, 2011 |title=Conservative Media Mogul Andrew Breitbart to Join GOProud's Advisory Council |publisher=Goproud.org |date=January 21, 2011 |accessdate=September 20, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, Grand Central Publishing released Breitbart's book ''Righteous Indignation: Excuse Me While I Save the World'', in which he discussed his own political evolution and the part he took in the rise of [[new media]], most notably at the Drudge Report and ''The Huffington Post''.{{citation needed|date=February 2017}}\n\nIn June 2011, Breitbart's websites broke the story that congressman [[Anthony Weiner]] was [[Anthony Weiner sexting scandal|sending women revealing photographs of himself]].<ref>Daly, Corbett D. [http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-20069298-503544.html \"Conservative website posts private pictures of Anthony Weiner.\"] [[CBS News]]. June 6, 2011.</ref>\n\n===Breitbart.com===\n{{main|Breitbart News Network}}\nBreitbart launched his first website as a news site; it is often linked to by the ''[[Drudge Report]]'' and other websites. It has wire stories from the [[Associated Press]], [[Reuters]], [[Agence France-Presse]], [[Fox News]], [[PR Newswire]], and [[U.S. Newswire]], as well as direct links to a number of major international newspapers. Its political viewpoint as well as its audience runs to the [[right-wing|right]] within the U.S. political spectrum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.org/interactives/media-polarization/outlet/breitbart/|title=Where Breitbart's Audience Fits on the Political Spectrum |date=October 21, 2014|work=Pew Research Center's Journalism Project}}</ref> In 2007, Breitbart launched a video blog, Breitbart.tv.<ref>[[Rob Owen (journalist)|Owen, Rob]]. [http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/07075/769897-96.stm The next wave: Ex-WTAE anchor Scott Baker changes channel to run Web news site], ''[[Post-Gazette]]''</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Breitbart and one of his editors [[Larry O'Connor (radio host)|Larry O'Connor]] were sued for [[defamation]] by [[Shirley Sherrod]], who had been [[Firing of Shirley Sherrod|fired]] after Breitbart posted a video of a speech given by Sherrod. The video had been selectively edited to suggest that she had purposely discriminated against a white farmer, while in reality the unedited video told the story of how she had helped that farmer.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Zeleny| first = Jeff|author2=  Wheaton, Sarah| title = At Gathering, Ron Paul Is No. 1 for 2012| newspaper = [[The New York Times]]| pages = A21 | date = February 13, 2011| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/13/us/politics/13cpac.html?_r=1&emc=eta1 | accessdate =February 14, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"Gerstein\" /> Breitbart himself maintained that he stated this in his article about it, and that the purpose of the video was to show the crowd's positive reaction to Sherrod's statements about discriminating against the white farmer.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wnyc.org/story/128436-andrew-breitbart/ |title= Breitbart on ACORN, Sherrod, and 'Gotcha' Journalism |author=Stephen Reader |date= May 11, 2011}}</ref> In July 2015, it was reported that Sherrod and Breitbart's estate had reached a tentative settlement.<ref name=\"Gerstein\">{{cite news|last1=Gerstein|first1=Josh|title=Breitbart, Sherrod near libel settlement|url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/under-the-radar/2015/07/breitbart-sherrod-near-libel-settlement-209824.html|accessdate=August 18, 2015|publisher=Politico|date=July 1, 2015}}</ref> It was reported October 1, 2016, that the lawsuit was settled.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://talkingpointsmemo.com/muckraker/sherrod-breitbart-lawsuit-settle |title= Ex-USDA Official Settles Her Lawsuit Over Breitbart Video That Got Her Fired |work= [[Talking Points Memo]] |author= Tierney Sneed |date= October 1, 2015 |accessdate= October 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Commentaries===\nIn 2009, Breitbart appeared as a commentator on ''[[Real Time with Bill Maher]]'' and ''[[Dennis Miller]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=BREITBART: 'My Real Time With Bill Maher'|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/mar/16/my-real-time-with-bill-maher/?page=all|accessdate=January 6, 2016|publisher=Washington Times|date=March 16, 2009}}</ref> In 2004, he was a guest commentator on [[Fox News Channel|Fox News Channel's]] morning show and frequently appeared as a guest panelist on [[Fox News]]'s late night program, ''[[Red Eye (TV series)|Red Eye w/ Greg Gutfeld]]''. Breitbart also appeared as a commentator in the 2004 documentary ''[[Michael Moore Hates America]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/212271/michael-wilson-loves-america/andrew-leigh |title=National Review Online|publisher=nationalreview.com |accessdate=November 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nOn October 22, 2009, Breitbart appeared on the [[C-SPAN]] program ''[[Washington Journal]]''. He gave his opinions on the mainstream media, Hollywood, the [[Presidency of Barack Obama|Obama Administration]] and his personal political views, having heated debates with several callers.<ref name=\"c-span\">[http://www.c-spanarchives.org/program/289587-8 Andrew Breitbart, Breitbart.com Publisher] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002155759/http://www.c-spanarchives.org/program/289587-8 |date=October 2, 2012 }} [[C-SPAN]], October 22, 2009. Breitbart referred to the \"Democrat-media complex\" several times...</ref>\n\nIn the hours immediately following Senator [[Ted Kennedy]]'s death, Breitbart called Kennedy a \"villain\", a \"duplicitous bastard\", a \"prick\"<ref name=\"politico\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0809/26475.html|title=Not all Kennedy critics hold fire|accessdate=August 26, 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090827091650/http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0809/26475.html| archivedate= August 27, 2009| url-status= live}}</ref> and \"a special pile of human excrement,\" adding, \"Sorry, he destroyed lives. And he knew it,\" referring to Kennedy's actions during the [[Chappaquiddick incident]], the [[Robert Bork Supreme Court nomination]], and the [[Clarence Thomas Supreme Court nomination]].<ref>\"[http://www.pennlive.com/editorials/index.ssf/2009/08/compromise_what_pennsylvania_l.html Compromise: what Pennsylvania lawmakers could learn from Ted Kennedy]\" (editorial), ''[[The Patriot-News]]'' (Pennsylvania), August 28, 2009. Retrieved September 24, 2009.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/278320 |title=Opinion: Ted Kennedy, the liberal adversary to the conservative movement |publisher=digitaljournal.com |accessdate=September 24, 2009 | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091003110202/http://www.digitaljournal.com/article/278320| archivedate= October 3, 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2010, Breitbart received the [[Reed Irvine]] [[Accuracy in Media]] Award during the [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] in Washington, D.C. During his acceptance speech, he responded directly to accusations by ''[[The New York Times]]'' reporter Kate Zernike that [[Jason Mattera]], a young conservative activist, had been using \"racial tones\" in his [[allusions]] to President [[Barack Obama]], and had spoken in a \"[[Chris Rock]] voice\". From the podium, Breitbart called Zernike \"a despicable human being\" for having made such allegations about what, according to him, was just Mattera's Brooklyn accent.<ref>Beam, Christopher, [http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/politics/2010/03/what_is_andrew_breitbart_thinking.html \"'Media Is Everything. It's Everything.' Slate's 2010 profile of Andrew Breitbart\"], ''Slate.com'', March 15, 2010.</ref> At the same conference, Breitbart was also filmed saying to journalist [[Max Blumenthal]] that he found him to be \"a jerk\" and \"a despicable human being\" over a blog entry in which Blumenthal accused Breitbart of employing a racist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MIeByOeERpY |title=Max Blumenthal confronted by Andrew Breitbart and Larry O'Connor/Stage right at CPAC 10 |publisher=YouTube |date=February 20, 2010 |accessdate=March 1, 2012}}</ref> Blumenthal was referring to [[James O'Keefe]] over his having attended a [[Georgetown Law Center]] discussion on race featuring Kevin Martin, [[John Derbyshire]], and [[Jared Taylor]], the last of whom founded ''[[American Renaissance (magazine)|American Renaissance]]'', an online magazine often considered white supremacist. Neither O'Keefe nor Breitbart endorsed Taylor's views.\n\nIn 2011, Breitbart said that \"of course\" [[Donald Trump]] was not a conservative, adding:\n\n<blockquote>But this is a message to those candidates who are languishing at 2 percent and 3 percent within the Republican Party who are brand names in Washington, but the rest of the country don't know ... celebrity is everything in this country. And if these guys don't learn how to play the media the way that Barack Obama played the media last election cycle and the way that Donald Trump is playing the election cycle, we're going to probably get a celebrity candidate.<ref name=\"WP.Aug.7.16\">{{cite news|last1=Weigel|first1=David|title=Five things to know about Breitbart, the new force in the Trump campaign|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2016/08/17/five-things-to-know-about-breitbart-the-new-force-in-the-trump-campaign/|accessdate=March 18, 2017|work=Washington Post|date=August 17, 2016}}</ref> </blockquote>\n\nThese comments resurfaced after the controversy of Donald Trump hiring [[Breitbart News]]' executive chairman [[Steve Bannon]] to be his [[White House Chief Strategist]].<ref name=\"WP.Aug.7.16\" />\n\n===Activism===\n{{See also|Tea party movement#Reports of slurs at health care reform protests|l1=Tea Party movement}}\nBreitbart often appeared as a speaker at [[Tea Party movement]] events across the U.S. For example, Breitbart was a speaker at the first National Tea Party Convention at Gaylord Opryland Hotel in Nashville on February 6, 2010.<ref>\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_D2YLnaTr6w/ Breitbart Keynote Part 1 of 4, Nashville, February 2010]{{dead link|date=March 2012 | Breitbart Keynote Part 1 of 4, Nashville, January]\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3N3os3js4B0/ Part 2]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3t6XSeR5GEw/ Part 3]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}\n[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jJZmKGE6tdE/ Part 4]{{dead link|date=March 2012}}</ref> Breitbart later involved himself in a controversy over allegations of [[homophobia|homophobic]] and [[racism|racial]] slurs being used at a March 20, 2010, rally at the [[United States Capitol]] in Washington, D.C., by asserting that slurs were never used, and that \"it was a set-up\" by [[Nancy Pelosi]] and the Democratic Party. Breitbart offered to donate $100,000 to the [[United Negro College Fund]] \"for any audio/video footage of the [[nigger|N-word]] being hurled,\" claiming that the several Congressmen made it up. Breitbart insisted Congressman [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]] and several other witnesses were forced to lie, concluding that \"Nancy Pelosi did a great disservice to a great civil rights icon by thrusting him out there to perform this mischievous task. His reputation is now on the line as a result of her desperation to take down the Tea Party movement.\"<ref name=\"AB-100402\">{{cite web |url=http://bigjournalism.com/abreitbart/2010/04/02/barack-obamas-helter-skelter-insane-clown-posse-alinsky-planes-to-deconstruct-america/ |title=Barack Obama's Helter-Skelter, Insane Clown Posse, Alinsky Plans to 'Deconstruct' America |first=Andrew |last=Breitbart |publisher=Big Journalism |date=April 2, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120302143429/http://bigjournalism.com/abreitbart/2010/04/02/barack-obamas-helter-skelter-insane-clown-posse-alinsky-planes-to-deconstruct-america/ |archivedate=March 2, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref><ref name=\"WPost Omb\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/04/09/AR2010040903716.html|title=Allegations of spitting and slurs at Capitol protest merit more reporting|date=April 11, 2010|work=Washington Post|accessdate=April 14, 2010| first=Andrew |last=Alexander}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, a [[YouTube]] video showed Breitbart yelling at [[Occupy D.C.]] protesters outside a Washington hotel hosting a [[Conservative Political Action Conference]] (CPAC). The video showed security escorting Breitbart back to the hotel while he told the protesters to \"behave yourself\", and alluding to reported assaults of women at Occupy encampments, he repeatedly yelled, \"Stop raping people\", and called the protestors \"filthy, filthy, raping, murdering freaks!\" David Carr said with the incident Breitbart had caused his last \"viral storm on the Web.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/15/business/media/the-life-and-death-of-andrew-breitbart.html?pagewanted=all |work=The New York Times |first=David |last=Carr |title=The Life and Death of Andrew Breitbart |date=April 13, 2012}}</ref><ref name=CPAC>Sources that describe the confrontation with Occupy protesters at CPAC 2012:\n* [http://www.theatlanticwire.com/politics/2012/02/web-talking-about-andrew-breitbarts-occupy-DC-freakout/48598/ The Web is Talking About Andrew Breitbart's Occupy D.C. Freakout], by Seth Abramovitch, ''[[The Atlantic]]'', February 12, 2012\n* [http://www.slate.com/blogs/weigel/2012/02/11/eighty_seven_seconds_of_andrew_breitbart_yelling.html Eighty-Seven Seconds of Andrew Breitbart Yelling], by David Weigel, ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'', February 11, 2012\n* [http://articles.businessinsider.com/2012-03-06/politics/31125723_1_andrew-breitbart-cpac-bloggers WATCH: Andrew Breitbart LOSES It On Occupy Wall Street Protesters]   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121212021939/http://articles.businessinsider.com/2012-03-06/politics/31125723_1_andrew-breitbart-cpac-bloggers |date=December 12, 2012 }}, by Grace Wyler, ''[[Business Insider]]'', March 6, 2012\n* [http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2012/03/01/andrew-breitbart-dies-most-controversial-moments-video.html Andrew Breitbart Dies: Most Controversial Moments (Video)], by ''[[The Daily Beast]]'', March 1, 2012\n* [http://www.observer.com/2012/03/andrew-breitbart-dead-03012012/ Andrew Breitbart Dead at 43], by Kat Stoeffel and Hunter Walker, ''[[The New York Observer]]'', January 3, 2012\n* [http://campusprogress.org/articles/exclusive_video_andrew_breitbart_to_occupiers_stop_raping_people/ EXCLUSIVE VIDEO: Blogger Andrew Breitbart to Occupiers: 'Stop Raping People!']   {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120419075311/http://campusprogress.org/articles/exclusive_video_andrew_breitbart_to_occupiers_stop_raping_people/ |date=April 19, 2012 }}, by Emily Crockett, ''[[Campus Progress]]'', February 10, 2012\n* [http://www.mediaite.com/tv/andrew-breitbart-confronts-occupy-crowd-at-cpac-demands-they-stop-raping-people/ Andrew Breitbart Confronts Occupy Crowd At CPAC, Demands They 'Stop Raping People'], by Frances Martel, ''[[Mediaite]]'', March 1, 2012\n* [http://dcist.com/2012/02/andrew_breitbart_flips_out_at_occup.php Right-Wing Blog Mogul Andrew Breitbart Flips Out at Occupy D.C. Outside CPAC]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212061609/http://dcist.com/2012/02/andrew_breitbart_flips_out_at_occup.php |date=February 12, 2012 }}, by Benjamin R. Freed, ''[[DCist]]'', February 10, 2012\n* [http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2012/02/occupiers_berat.php Occupiers Berated By Breitbart; ''Times'' Looks At Movement's Next Moves] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120413053517/http://blogs.villagevoice.com/runninscared/2012/02/occupiers_berat.php |date=April 13, 2012 }}, by Esther Zuckerman, ''[[The Village Voice]]'', February 11, 2012</ref>\n\nBreitbart appeared posthumously in ''[[Occupy Unmasked]]'', a documentary film by [[Steve Bannon]] that contends that the [[Occupy movement|Occupy Wall Street movement]] of \"largely na\u00efve students and legitimately concerned citizens looking for answers\" is actually orchestrated by sinister, violent, and organized leaders with the purpose of not just changing, but destroying the American government.<ref>{{cite web|title=Occupyunmasked.com|url=http://www.occupyunmasked.com/about.aspx}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\nBreitbart was married to Susannah Bean, the daughter of actor [[Orson Bean]] and fashion designer Carolyn Maxwell, and had four children.<ref name=\"huff\"/><ref name=\"Saad\">{{cite news |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-orson-bean-2050-story.html |first1=Nardine |last1=Saad |date=February 8, 2020 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |title=OBITUARIES Actor Orson Bean, local theater mainstay who rose to fame as a 1950s TV personality, dies |accessdate=February 9, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"AP\"> {{cite news |url=https://www.yahoo.com/news/actor-comedian-orson-bean-91-114135652.html |title=Celebrity Actor-comedian Orson Bean, 91, hit and killed by car in LA |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=February 8, 2020|via=[[Yahoo!]]}}</ref>\n\nOn the night of February 29, 2012, Breitbart collapsed suddenly while walking in [[Brentwood, Los Angeles|Brentwood]]. He was rushed to [[Ronald Reagan UCLA Medical Center]], where he was pronounced dead just after midnight, March 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/15/business/media/the-life-and-death-of-andrew-breitbart.html |title=The Provocateur | publisher =New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.autopsyfiles.org/reports/Celebs/breitbart,%20andrew_report.pdf |title=Andrew Breitbart autopsy report | publisher =Autopsyfile.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/andrew-breitbart-publisher-author-dead/story?id=15824337\n |title=Publisher and Author Andrew Breitbart Dead\n |first=Christina |last=Ng |date=March 1, 2012}}</ref> He was 43 years old. An [[autopsy]] by the [[Los Angeles County Coroner's Office]] showed that he had [[hypertrophic cardiomyopathy]], with focal coronary [[atherosclerosis]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/lanow/2012/05/commentator-and-editor-andrew-breitbart-died-of-heart-failure-and-hard-up-to-a-60-narrowing-of-a-major-artery-and-was-unde.html|title=Andrew Breitbart died of heart failure, narrowing of artery, coroner finds|first=Andrew|last=Blankstein|work=L.A. Times|publisher=L.A. Times|date=May 16, 2012}}</ref> and died of a [[heart attack]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/us/andrew-breitbart-conservative-blogger-dies-at-43.html|title=Andrew Breitbart, Conservative Blogger, Dies at 43|last=Peters|first=Jeremy W.|date=2012-03-01|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref> His burial was in the Jewish cemetery [[Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery|Hillside Memorial Park]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Andrew James Breitbart |url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/86040288/andrew-james-breitbart |website=Find A Grave\u2122 |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn remembrance, Republican presidential candidates [[Rick Santorum]], [[Mitt Romney]], and [[Newt Gingrich]] praised Breitbart.<ref name=\"media star\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nwherald.com/2012/03/06/limbaugh-and-the-gop-the-media-stars-and-politics/agdmwrt/?page=3|title=Limbaugh and the GOP: The media stars and politics|author=Beth Fouhey|author2=Philip Elliott|work=Associated Press|date=March 6, 2012|accessdate=March 6, 2012}}</ref> Santorum called Breitbart's death \"a huge loss\" that strongly affected him.<ref name=\"media star\"/><ref>{{cite video |date=March 1, 2012 |title=CBS News|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/andrew-breitbart-death-shocks-santorum-100/2012/03/01/gIQAqm8qkR_video.html}}</ref> Romney praised Breitbart as a \"fearless conservative,\" while Gingrich remembered him as \"the most innovative pioneer in conservative activist social media in America\".<ref name=\"media star\" /> A special episode of ''[[Red Eye (TV series)|Red Eye w/ Greg Gutfeld]]'' aired the day after his death as the host and panelists paid their tributes and showed clips from his appearances on the show.<ref>{{cite video |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CLqEPe9emsU |title=Red Eye Remembers Andrew Breitbart |accessdate= September 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book|title = Righteous Indignation: Excuse Me While I Save the World|publisher = [[Grand Central Publishing]]|date = April 15, 2011|isbn = 978-0-446-57282-8|url-access = registration|url = https://archive.org/details/righteousindigna0000brei|via=[[Internet Archive]]}}\n* {{cite book|first = Mark C.|last =  Ebner|authorlink = Mark Ebner |author2=Andrew Breitbart |title = [[Hollywood, Interrupted]]: Insanity Chic in Babylon \u2013 The Case Against Celebrity|publisher = [[John Wiley & Sons|Wiley]]|date = March 10, 2005|isbn = 978-0-471-70624-3}}\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q503917|q=Andrew Breitbart|n=no|b=no|v=no|voy=no|m=no|mw=no|wikt=no|s=no|species=no|c=category:Andrew Breitbart}}\n* {{IMDb name|1620485}}\n* {{C-SPAN|andrewbreitbart}}\n* {{Worldcat id|id=lccn-no2004-14171}}\n* {{Find a Grave|86040288}}\n\n{{Andrew Breitbart|state=expanded}}\n{{Portalbar|Biography|California|Politics}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Breitbart, Andrew}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2012 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Activists from California]]\n[[Category:American adoptees]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n[[Category:American alternative journalists]]\n[[Category:American bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n[[Category:American male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:American online journalists]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:Breitbart News people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Hillside Memorial Park Cemetery]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n[[Category:HuffPost]]\n[[Category:Jewish American journalists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish agnostics]]\n[[Category:National Review people]]\n[[Category:People from Brentwood, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Tea Party movement activists]]\n[[Category:The Washington Times people]]\n[[Category:Tulane University alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Procyonidae", "label": "safe", "comment": "formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Breitbart"}
{"title_page": "Ministry of Culture (France)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox official post\n|post                     = Minister of Culture\n|native_name              = ''{{lang|fr|Ministre de la Culture}}''\n|insignia                 = \n|insigniasize             = \n|insigniacaption          = \n|image                    = Franck Riester 2019 (cropped).jpg\n|incumbent                = [[Franck Riester]]\n|incumbentsince           = 16 October 2018\n|style                    = Mister the Minister\n|member_of                = [[Government of France|Council of Ministers]]\n|reports_to               = [[President of France|President of the Republic]]<br/>and to [[French Parliament|Parliament]]\n|residence                = [[Palais-Royal]]\n|seat                     = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n|appointer                = [[President of France|President of the Republic]]\n|termlength               = No fixed term\n|termlength_qualified     = Remains in office while commanding the confidence of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] and the [[President of France|President of the Republic]]\n|constituting_instrument  = [[Constitution of France|Constitution of 4 October 1958]] \n|precursor                = \n|formation                = 8 January 1959\n|first                    = [[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]]\n|salary                   = \u20ac9,940 per month\n|website                  = {{URL|http://www.economie.gouv.fr/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Ministry of Culture''' ({{lang-fr|Minist\u00e8re de la Culture}}) is the [[Ministry (government department)|ministry]] of the [[Government of France]] in charge of [[List of museums in France|national museums]] and the ''[[Monument historique|monuments historiques]]''. Its goal is to maintain the French identity through the promotion and protection of the arts (visual, plastic, theatrical, musical, dance, architectural, literary, televisual and cinematographic) on national soil and abroad. Its budget is mainly dedicated to the management of the [[Archives Nationales (France)|Archives Nationales]] (six national sites and hundred decentralised storage facilities) and the regional ''Maisons de la culture'' (culture centres).\n\nIts main office is in the [[Palais-Royal]] in the [[1st arrondissement of Paris]] on the [[Rue de Valois]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culturecommunication.gouv.fr/ |title=Accueil |website=Minist\u00e8re de la Culture |language=fr |access-date=7 May 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511161520/http://www.culturecommunication.gouv.fr/ |archive-date=11 May 2016 |quote=Nous contacter: 3, rue de Valois, 75001 Paris}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00085993 |title=Monuments historiques: \u00e9difice / site: Domaine national du Palais-Royal (ancien Palais Cardinal), comprenant Conseil d'Etat, Conseil Constitutionnel, Minist\u00e8re de la Culture, th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Com\u00e9die Fran\u00e7aise |website=[[Base M\u00e9rim\u00e9e]] |language=fr |access-date=7 May 2016 |quote=place du Palais-Royal ; 1 \u00e0 7 rue de Valois ; 2 \u00e0 8 rue de Montpensier ; place Colette.}}</ref> It is headed by the Minister of Culture, a cabinet member. The current officeholder has been [[Franck Riester]] since 16 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publishingperspectives.com/2018/10/publisher-francoise-nyssen-out-as-french-minister-of-culture/ |title=Publisher Fran\u00e7oise Nyssen Is Out as France's Minister of Culture |last=Snaije |first=Olivia |date=16 October 2018 |website=Publishing Perspectives |access-date=18 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Palais Royal @ Paris (34375405432).jpg|thumb|left|The [[Palais-Royal]] in [[Paris]] houses the ministry's head office as well as the [[Constitutional Council (France)|Constitutional Council]]]]\n\nDeriving from the [[Italian Renaissance|Italian]] and [[Duchy of Burgundy|Burgundian]] courts of the [[Renaissance]], the notion that the state had a key role to play in the sponsoring of artistic production and that the arts were linked to national prestige was found in France from at least the 16th century on. During the pre-revolutionary period, these ideas are apparent in such things as the creation of the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]], the [[Acad\u00e9mie de peinture et de sculpture]] and other state-sponsored institutions of artistic production, and through the cultural policies of [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]]'s minister [[Jean-Baptiste Colbert]].\n\nThe modern post of Minister of Culture was created by [[Charles de Gaulle]] in 1959 and the first officeholders was the writer [[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]]. Malraux was responsible for realising the goals of the ''droit \u00e0 la culture'' (\"right to culture\"), an idea which had been incorporated in the [[Constitution of France]] and the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] (1948), by democratising access to culture, while also achieving the [[Gaullism|Gaullist]] aim of elevating the \"grandeur\" (\"greatness\") of post-war France.  To this end, he created numerous regional cultural centres throughout France and actively sponsored the arts. Malraux's artistic tastes included the modern arts and the avant-garde, but on the whole he remained conservative.\n\n[[File:Archives nationales Pierrefitte 1.jpg|thumb|left|One of France's six National Archives sites operated by the Ministry of Culture, in [[Pierrefitte-sur-Seine]]]]\nUnder President [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]] the Minister of Culture was [[Jack Lang (French politician)|Jack Lang]] who showed himself to be far more open to popular cultural production, including [[jazz]], [[rock and roll]], [[rap music]], [[graffiti]], [[cartoon]]s, [[comic books]], [[fashion]] and [[food]]. His famous phrase \"\u00e9conomie et culture, m\u00eame combat\" (\"economy and culture: it's the same fight\") is representative of his commitment to cultural democracy and to active national sponsorship and participation in cultural production. In addition to the creation of the ''[[F\u00eate de la Musique]]'' and overseeing the French Revolution bicentennial (1989), he was in charge of the [[Grands Projets of Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand|massive architectural program]] of the [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]] years (the so-called ''Grands travaux'' or \"Great Works\") that gave permission for the building of the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale]], the new [[Louvre]], the [[Arab World Institute]], the [[Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]], the [[Op\u00e9ra-Bastille]], the \"[[Grande Arche]]\" of [[La D\u00e9fense]] (the Parisian business quarter), the new seat of the [[French Ministry for the Economy and Finance]], the [[Jean-Marie Tjibaou Cultural Centre]], and the [[Cit\u00e9 des Sciences et de l'Industrie]] and [[Cit\u00e9 de la Musique]], both in the [[Parc de la Villette]].\n\nThe Ministry of [[Jacques Toubon]] was notable for a number of laws (the \"[[Toubon Law]]s\") enacted for the preservation of the [[French language]], both in advertisements (all ads must include a French translation of foreign words) and on the radio (35% of songs on French radio stations must be in French), ostensibly in reaction to the presence of English.\n{{-}}\n==Ministros de Cultura==\nLas siguientes personas fueron nombradas Ministro de Cultura de Francia:\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* Febrero 1959: [[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]]\n* Junio 1969: [[Edmond Michelet]]\n* Octubre 1970: [[Andr\u00e9 Bettencourt]]\n* Enero 1971: {{ill|Jacques Duhamel|fr}}\n* Abril 1973: [[Maurice Druon]]\n* Marzo 1974: [[Alain Peyrefitte]]\n* Junio 1974: {{ill|Michel Guy|fr}}\n* Agosto 1976: [[Fran\u00e7oise Giroud]]\n* Marzo 1977: [[Michel d'Ornano]]\n* Abril 1978: [[Jean-Philippe Lecat]]\n* Marzo 1981: [[Michel d'Ornano]]\n* Mayo 1981: [[Jack Lang (French politician)|Jack Lang]]\n* Marzo 1986: [[Fran\u00e7ois L\u00e9otard]]\n* Mayo 1988: [[Jack Lang (French politician)|Jack Lang]]\n* Marzo 1993: [[Jacques Toubon]]\n* Mayo 1995: [[Philippe Douste-Blazy]]\n* Junio 1997: [[Catherine Trautmann]]\n* Marzo 2000: [[Catherine Tasca]]\n* Mayo 2002: [[Jean-Jacques Aillagon]]\n* Marzo 2004: [[Renaud Donnedieu de Vabres]]\n* Mayo 2007: [[Christine Albanel]]\n* Junio 2009: [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Mitterrand]]\n* Mayo 2012: [[Aur\u00e9lie Filippetti]]\n* Agosto 2014: [[Fleur Pellerin]]\n* Febrero 2016: [[Audrey Azoulay]]\n* Mayo 2017: [[Fran\u00e7oise Nyssen]]\n* Octubre 2018: [[Franck Riester]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Names of the Ministry of Culture==\nSince the French constitution does not identify specific ministers (merely speaking of \"the minister in charge of\" this or that), each government may label each ministry as they wish, or even have a broader ministry in charge of several governmental sectors. Hence, the ministry has gone through a number of different names:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break|width=50%}}\n* 1959: ''Minist\u00e8re des Affaires culturelles''\n* 1974: ''Minist\u00e8re des Affaires culturelles et de l'Environnement''\n* 1974: ''Secr\u00e9tariat d'\u00c9tat \u00e0 la Culture''\n* 1976: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de l'Environnement''\n* 1978: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de la Communication''\n* 1981: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture''\n* 1986: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de la Communication''\n* 1988: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture, de la Communication, des Grands Travaux et du Bicentenaire''\n{{col-break}}\n* 1991: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de la Communication''\n* 1992: ''Minist\u00e8re de l'\u00c9ducation nationale et de la Culture''\n* 1993: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de la Francophonie''\n* 1995: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture''\n* 1997: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de la Communication''\n* 2017: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture''\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Organisation==\n\n=== Central administration===\nThe Ministry of Culture is made up of a variety of internal divisions, including:\n* ''Direction de l'administration g\u00e9n\u00e9rale'' (DAG)\n* ''Direction de l'architecture et du patrimoine'' (DAPA) in charge of national monuments and heritage\n** ''Inventaire g\u00e9n\u00e9ral du patrimoine culturel'' maintains extensive databases of historical sites and objects via the [[Base M\u00e9rim\u00e9e]] and ''[[monument historique]]'' status.\n* ''Direction des archives de France'' (DAF) in charge of the [[Archives nationales (France)|National Archives]]\n* ''Direction du livre et de la lecture'' (DLL) in charge of [[French literature]] and the book trade\n* ''Direction de la musique, de la danse, du th\u00e9\u00e2tre et des spectacles'' (DMDTS) in charge of [[French culture|music, dance and theater]]\n* ''Direction des Mus\u00e9es de France'' (DMF) in charge of national museums\n\nThe Ministry has access to one inter-ministerial division:\n* ''Direction du d\u00e9veloppement des m\u00e9dias'' (DDM) in charge of developing and expanding the [[Media of France|French media]] (although French public television is run through the public-service company [[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]])\n\nThe Ministry also runs three \"delegations\" (administrative boards):\n* ''D\u00e9l\u00e9gation aux arts plastiques'' (DAP) in charge of the visual and sculptural arts\n* ''D\u00e9l\u00e9gation au d\u00e9veloppement et aux affaires internationales'' (DDAI) in charge of international affairs and French art\n* ''D\u00e9l\u00e9gation g\u00e9n\u00e9rale \u00e0 la langue fran\u00e7aise et aux langues de France'' (DGLFLF) in charge of the [[French language]] and [[languages of France]]\n\nFinally, the Ministry shares in the management of the National Centre of [[French cinema|Cinema]] (Centre national de la cin\u00e9matographie), a public institution.<ref>Go to their link [http://www.cnc.fr here].</ref>\n\nThe [[Alliance fran\u00e7aise]] is run by the [[Ministry of Europe and Foreign Affairs]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051210074418/http://www.culture.gouv.fr/culture/min/index-min.htm Ministry of Culture]</ref>\n\n===Other services===\nOn the national level, the Ministry also runs:\n* [[R\u00e9gion in France|Regional]] Cultural Affairs (Direction r\u00e9gionale des affaires culturelles, DRAC)\n* [[D\u00e9partement in France|Department]]al Architecture and Monuments (Services d\u00e9partementaux de l'architecture et du patrimoine, SDAP)\n* [[D\u00e9partement in France|Department]]al Archives under the direction of the [[Departmental councils (France)|departmental councils]]\n* [[Centre National de la Danse]], institution for the study and preservation of dance<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnd.fr/en/page/21-missions |title=Missions |website=Centre national de la danse |access-date=18 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural activities==\nThe Ministry of Culture is responsible for, or a major sponsor of, a number of annual cultural activities, including the ''[[F\u00eate de la Musique]]'', the [[Maison de la culture de Grenoble]], the ''[[Festival d'Avignon]]'', the [[Public Establishment of the Palace, Museum and National Estate of Versailles]], the [[Joconde]] (online database of objects in French museums), the [[Base M\u00e9rim\u00e9e]] (database of listed heritage monuments), and the [[Ma\u00eetre d'art]] program.\n\n==Further reading==\n* Nancy Marmer, \"The New Culture: France '82,\" ''Art in America,'' December 1982, pp.&nbsp;115\u2013123, 181-189.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n{{Portal|France|Society|Politics}}\n*{{official|http://www.culture.gouv.fr/ }} {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.culture.fr/en/sections/ Culture Portal of the Ministry of Culture] (Page index in English, documents in French)\n*[http://culture.fr Culture Portal of the Ministry of Culture] {{in lang|fr}}\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.culture.fr/cgi-bin/cookie-test-en English pages] (Archive)\n\n{{Ministers of Culture of France}}\n{{French Government}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Minister Of Culture (France)}}\n[[Category:French Ministers of Culture| ]]\n[[Category:French culture]]\n[[Category:Culture ministers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Infobox official post\n|post                     = Minister of Culture\n|native_name              = ''{{lang|fr|Ministre de la Culture}}''\n|insignia                 = \n|insigniasize             = \n|insigniacaption          = \n|image                    = Franck Riester 2019 (cropped).jpg\n|incumbent                = [[Franck Riester]]\n|incumbentsince           = 16 October 2018\n|style                    = Mister the Minister\n|member_of                = [[Government of France|Council of Ministers]]\n|reports_to               = [[President of France|President of the Republic]]<br/>and to [[French Parliament|Parliament]]\n|residence                = [[Palais-Royal]]\n|seat                     = [[Paris]], [[France]]\n|appointer                = [[President of France|President of the Republic]]\n|termlength               = No fixed term\n|termlength_qualified     = Remains in office while commanding the confidence of the [[National Assembly (France)|National Assembly]] and the [[President of France|President of the Republic]]\n|constituting_instrument  = [[Constitution of France|Constitution of 4 October 1958]] \n|precursor                = \n|formation                = 8 January 1959\n|first                    = [[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]]\n|salary                   = \u20ac9,940 per month\n|website                  = {{URL|http://www.economie.gouv.fr/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Ministry of Culture''' ({{lang-fr|Minist\u00e8re de la Culture}}) is the [[Ministry (government department)|ministry]] of the [[Government of France]] in charge of [[List of museums in France|national museums]] and the ''[[Monument historique|monuments historiques]]''. Its goal is to maintain the French identity through the promotion and protection of the arts (visual, plastic, theatrical, musical, dance, architectural, literary, televisual and cinematographic) on national soil and abroad. Its budget is mainly dedicated to the management of the [[Archives Nationales (France)|Archives Nationales]] (six national sites and hundred decentralised storage facilities) and the regional ''Maisons de la culture'' (culture centres).\n\nIts main office is in the [[Palais-Royal]] in the [[1st arrondissement of Paris]] on the [[Rue de Valois]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culturecommunication.gouv.fr/ |title=Accueil |website=Minist\u00e8re de la Culture |language=fr |access-date=7 May 2016 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160511161520/http://www.culturecommunication.gouv.fr/ |archive-date=11 May 2016 |quote=Nous contacter: 3, rue de Valois, 75001 Paris}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.culture.gouv.fr/public/mistral/merimee_fr?ACTION=CHERCHER&FIELD_1=REF&VALUE_1=PA00085993 |title=Monuments historiques: \u00e9difice / site: Domaine national du Palais-Royal (ancien Palais Cardinal), comprenant Conseil d'Etat, Conseil Constitutionnel, Minist\u00e8re de la Culture, th\u00e9\u00e2tre de la Com\u00e9die Fran\u00e7aise |website=[[Base M\u00e9rim\u00e9e]] |language=fr |access-date=7 May 2016 |quote=place du Palais-Royal ; 1 \u00e0 7 rue de Valois ; 2 \u00e0 8 rue de Montpensier ; place Colette.}}</ref> It is headed by the Minister of Culture, a cabinet member. The current officeholder has been [[Franck Riester]] since 16 October 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://publishingperspectives.com/2018/10/publisher-francoise-nyssen-out-as-french-minister-of-culture/ |title=Publisher Fran\u00e7oise Nyssen Is Out as France's Minister of Culture |last=Snaije |first=Olivia |date=16 October 2018 |website=Publishing Perspectives |access-date=18 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Palais Royal @ Paris (34375405432).jpg|thumb|left|The [[Palais-Royal]] in [[Paris]] houses the ministry's head office as well as the [[Constitutional Council (France)|Constitutional Council]]]]\n\nDeriving from the [[Italian Renaissance|Italian]] and [[Duchy of Burgundy|Burgundian]] courts of the [[Renaissance]], the notion that the state had a key role to play in the sponsoring of artistic production and that the arts were linked to national prestige was found in France from at least the 16th century on. During the pre-revolutionary period, these ideas are apparent in such things as the creation of the [[Acad\u00e9mie fran\u00e7aise]], the [[Acad\u00e9mie de peinture et de sculpture]] and other state-sponsored institutions of artistic production, and through the cultural policies of [[Louis XIV of France|Louis XIV]]'s minister [[Jean-Baptiste Colbert]].\n\nThe modern post of Minister of Culture was created by [[Charles de Gaulle]] in 1959 and the first officeholders was the writer [[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]]. Malraux was responsible for realising the goals of the ''droit \u00e0 la culture'' (\"right to culture\"), an idea which had been incorporated in the [[Constitution of France]] and the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] (1948), by democratising access to culture, while also achieving the [[Gaullism|Gaullist]] aim of elevating the \"grandeur\" (\"greatness\") of post-war France.  To this end, he created numerous regional cultural centres throughout France and actively sponsored the arts. Malraux's artistic tastes included the modern arts and the avant-garde, but on the whole he remained conservative.\n\n[[File:Archives nationales Pierrefitte 1.jpg|thumb|left|One of France's six National Archives sites operated by the Ministry of Culture, in [[Pierrefitte-sur-Seine]]]]\nUnder President [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]] the Minister of Culture was [[Jack Lang (French politician)|Jack Lang]] who showed himself to be far more open to popular cultural production, including [[jazz]], [[rock and roll]], [[rap music]], [[graffiti]], [[cartoon]]s, [[comic books]], [[fashion]] and [[food]]. His famous phrase \"\u00e9conomie et culture, m\u00eame combat\" (\"economy and culture: it's the same fight\") is representative of his commitment to cultural democracy and to active national sponsorship and participation in cultural production. In addition to the creation of the ''[[F\u00eate de la Musique]]'' and overseeing the French Revolution bicentennial (1989), he was in charge of the [[Grands Projets of Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand|massive architectural program]] of the [[Fran\u00e7ois Mitterrand]] years (the so-called ''Grands travaux'' or \"Great Works\") that gave permission for the building of the [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale]], the new [[Louvre]], the [[Arab World Institute]], the [[Mus\u00e9e d'Orsay]], the [[Op\u00e9ra-Bastille]], the \"[[Grande Arche]]\" of [[La D\u00e9fense]] (the Parisian business quarter), the new seat of the [[French Ministry for the Economy and Finance]], the [[Jean-Marie Tjibaou Cultural Centre]], and the [[Cit\u00e9 des Sciences et de l'Industrie]] and [[Cit\u00e9 de la Musique]], both in the [[Parc de la Villette]].\n\nThe Ministry of [[Jacques Toubon]] was notable for a number of laws (the \"[[Toubon Law]]s\") enacted for the preservation of the [[French language]], both in advertisements (all ads must include a French translation of foreign words) and on the radio (35% of songs on French radio stations must be in French), ostensibly in reaction to the presence of English.\n{{-}}\n==Ministers of Culture==\nThe following people were appointed as Minister of Culture of France:\n{{Div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* February 1959: [[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]]\n* June 1969: [[Edmond Michelet]]\n* October 1970: [[Andr\u00e9 Bettencourt]]\n* January 1971: {{ill|Jacques Duhamel|fr}}\n* April 1973: [[Maurice Druon]]\n* March 1974: [[Alain Peyrefitte]]\n* June 1974: {{ill|Michel Guy|fr}}\n* August 1976: [[Fran\u00e7oise Giroud]]\n* March 1977: [[Michel d'Ornano]]\n* April 1978: [[Jean-Philippe Lecat]]\n* March 1981: [[Michel d'Ornano]]\n* May 1981: [[Jack Lang (French politician)|Jack Lang]]\n* March 1986: [[Fran\u00e7ois L\u00e9otard]]\n* May 1988: [[Jack Lang (French politician)|Jack Lang]]\n* March 1993: [[Jacques Toubon]]\n* May 1995: [[Philippe Douste-Blazy]]\n* June 1997: [[Catherine Trautmann]]\n* March 2000: [[Catherine Tasca]]\n* May 2002: [[Jean-Jacques Aillagon]]\n* March 2004: [[Renaud Donnedieu de Vabres]]\n* May 2007: [[Christine Albanel]]\n* June 2009: [[Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric Mitterrand]]\n* May 2012: [[Aur\u00e9lie Filippetti]]\n* August 2014: [[Fleur Pellerin]]\n* February 2016: [[Audrey Azoulay]]\n* May 2017: [[Fran\u00e7oise Nyssen]]\n* October 2018: [[Franck Riester]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Names of the Ministry of Culture==\nSince the French constitution does not identify specific ministers (merely speaking of \"the minister in charge of\" this or that), each government may label each ministry as they wish, or even have a broader ministry in charge of several governmental sectors. Hence, the ministry has gone through a number of different names:\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break|width=50%}}\n* 1959: ''Minist\u00e8re des Affaires culturelles''\n* 1974: ''Minist\u00e8re des Affaires culturelles et de l'Environnement''\n* 1974: ''Secr\u00e9tariat d'\u00c9tat \u00e0 la Culture''\n* 1976: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de l'Environnement''\n* 1978: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de la Communication''\n* 1981: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture''\n* 1986: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de la Communication''\n* 1988: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture, de la Communication, des Grands Travaux et du Bicentenaire''\n{{col-break}}\n* 1991: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de la Communication''\n* 1992: ''Minist\u00e8re de l'\u00c9ducation nationale et de la Culture''\n* 1993: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de la Francophonie''\n* 1995: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture''\n* 1997: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture et de la Communication''\n* 2017: ''Minist\u00e8re de la Culture''\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Organisation==\n\n=== Central administration===\nThe Ministry of Culture is made up of a variety of internal divisions, including:\n* ''Direction de l'administration g\u00e9n\u00e9rale'' (DAG)\n* ''Direction de l'architecture et du patrimoine'' (DAPA) in charge of national monuments and heritage\n** ''Inventaire g\u00e9n\u00e9ral du patrimoine culturel'' maintains extensive databases of historical sites and objects via the [[Base M\u00e9rim\u00e9e]] and ''[[monument historique]]'' status.\n* ''Direction des archives de France'' (DAF) in charge of the [[Archives nationales (France)|National Archives]]\n* ''Direction du livre et de la lecture'' (DLL) in charge of [[French literature]] and the book trade\n* ''Direction de la musique, de la danse, du th\u00e9\u00e2tre et des spectacles'' (DMDTS) in charge of [[French culture|music, dance and theater]]\n* ''Direction des Mus\u00e9es de France'' (DMF) in charge of national museums\n\nThe Ministry has access to one inter-ministerial division:\n* ''Direction du d\u00e9veloppement des m\u00e9dias'' (DDM) in charge of developing and expanding the [[Media of France|French media]] (although French public television is run through the public-service company [[France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions]])\n\nThe Ministry also runs three \"delegations\" (administrative boards):\n* ''D\u00e9l\u00e9gation aux arts plastiques'' (DAP) in charge of the visual and sculptural arts\n* ''D\u00e9l\u00e9gation au d\u00e9veloppement et aux affaires internationales'' (DDAI) in charge of international affairs and French art\n* ''D\u00e9l\u00e9gation g\u00e9n\u00e9rale \u00e0 la langue fran\u00e7aise et aux langues de France'' (DGLFLF) in charge of the [[French language]] and [[languages of France]]\n\nFinally, the Ministry shares in the management of the National Centre of [[French cinema|Cinema]] (Centre national de la cin\u00e9matographie), a public institution.<ref>Go to their link [http://www.cnc.fr here].</ref>\n\nThe [[Alliance fran\u00e7aise]] is run by the [[Ministry of Europe and Foreign Affairs]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051210074418/http://www.culture.gouv.fr/culture/min/index-min.htm Ministry of Culture]</ref>\n\n===Other services===\nOn the national level, the Ministry also runs:\n* [[R\u00e9gion in France|Regional]] Cultural Affairs (Direction r\u00e9gionale des affaires culturelles, DRAC)\n* [[D\u00e9partement in France|Department]]al Architecture and Monuments (Services d\u00e9partementaux de l'architecture et du patrimoine, SDAP)\n* [[D\u00e9partement in France|Department]]al Archives under the direction of the [[Departmental councils (France)|departmental councils]]\n* [[Centre National de la Danse]], institution for the study and preservation of dance<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnd.fr/en/page/21-missions |title=Missions |website=Centre national de la danse |access-date=18 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural activities==\nThe Ministry of Culture is responsible for, or a major sponsor of, a number of annual cultural activities, including the ''[[F\u00eate de la Musique]]'', the [[Maison de la culture de Grenoble]], the ''[[Festival d'Avignon]]'', the [[Public Establishment of the Palace, Museum and National Estate of Versailles]], the [[Joconde]] (online database of objects in French museums), the [[Base M\u00e9rim\u00e9e]] (database of listed heritage monuments), and the [[Ma\u00eetre d'art]] program.\n\n==Further reading==\n* Nancy Marmer, \"The New Culture: France '82,\" ''Art in America,'' December 1982, pp.&nbsp;115\u2013123, 181-189.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscatinline}}\n{{Portal|France|Society|Politics}}\n*{{official|http://www.culture.gouv.fr/ }} {{in lang|fr}}\n*[http://www.culture.fr/en/sections/ Culture Portal of the Ministry of Culture] (Page index in English, documents in French)\n*[http://culture.fr Culture Portal of the Ministry of Culture] {{in lang|fr}}\n**[https://web.archive.org/web/*/http://www.culture.fr/cgi-bin/cookie-test-en English pages] (Archive)\n\n{{Ministers of Culture of France}}\n{{French Government}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Minister Of Culture (France)}}\n[[Category:French Ministers of Culture| ]]\n[[Category:French culture]]\n[[Category:Culture ministers]]\n", "name_user": "AlbertoDV", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eMinistros de Cultura)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ministry_of_Culture_(France)"}
{"title_page": "Samrong BTS station", "text_new": "{{Infobox station\n| name = [[File:BTS E15.svg|40px]]<br/>Samrong\n| native_name = \u0e2a\u0e33\u0e42\u0e23\u0e07\n| native_name_lang = th\n| other_name = \n| type = {{rint|bangkok|Sukhumvit}}\n{{rint|bangkok|Yellow}}\n| image = BTS_Samrong_station.jpg\n| address = [[Mueang Samut Prakan District|Mueang Samut Prakan]], [[Samut Prakan Province|Samut Prakan]], [[Thailand]]\n| owned = [[Bangkok Metropolitan Administration]] (BMA)\n| operator            = [[BTS Group Holdings|Bangkok Mass Transit System<br>Public Company Limited]] (BTSC)\n| coordinates = {{coord|13.647363|100.596153}}\n| line = {{rail color box|system=BTS|line=Sukhumvit}}\n{{rail color box|system=Bangkok MRT|line=Yellow}} ''(Yellow Line opening 2021)''\n| other = \n| code = E15 (Sukhumvit line)<br/>''YL25 (Yellow line)''\n| opened = 3 April 2017\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = \n | services=\n{{s-rail|title=Bangkok Rapid Transit}}\n{{s-line|system=BTS|line=Sukhumvit|previous=Bearing|next=Pu Chao|type=North|type2=East}}\n}}\n\n[[File:BTS E15 Traditional station sign (MRTA Standard).svg|thumb|Samrong Station Traditional sign]]\n'''Samrong''' ({{lang-th|\u0e2a\u0e16\u0e32\u0e19\u0e35\u0e2a\u0e33\u0e42\u0e23\u0e07}}, {{RTGS|''Sathani Samrong''}}, {{IPA-th|s\u0101.t\u02b0\u01ce\u02d0.n\u012b\u02d0 s\u01cem.r\u014d\u02d0\u014b|pron}}) is a [[Bangkok Skytrain|BTS Skytrain]] station, on the [[Sukhumvit Line]] in [[Samut Prakan]], [[Thailand]].\n\nTrial operation began in March 2017, and the station was officially opened by Prime Minister [[Prayut Chan-o-cha]] on 3 April 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30311133|title=Public to get free trial, as Samrong BTS station now opens \u2013 The Nation|work=The Nation|access-date=2017-04-03|language=en}}</ref> with passengers able to ride the extension for free for a month beginning on 4 April 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://coconuts.co/bangkok/news/bts-offers-free-rides-new-station-first-samut-prakarn/|title=BTS offers free rides to new station, first in Samut Prakarn {{!}} Coconuts Bangkok|date=2017-03-16|work=Coconuts|access-date=2017-04-01|language=en-US}}</ref> It was the eastern terminus of the line, until the opening of the other stations of the [[Sukhumvit Line]] Extension (East) on 6 December 2018. In future it will connect to the [[MRT Yellow Line]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pattayamail.com/thailandnews/bearing-samrong-segment-bts-green-line-put-trial-run-167271|title=Bearing-Samrong segment of BTS Green Line put on trial run - Pattaya It is one of the 2 stations which have an island platform, the other to be Siam station. Mail|last=Mail|first=Pattaya|date=2017-03-16|work=Pattaya Mail|access-date=2017-04-01|language=en-US}}</ref> It is one of only three BTS stations to have island platforms, with the other being [[Siam BTS station|Siam]], [[Ha Yaek Lat Phrao BTS station|Ha Yaek Lat Phrao]] and [[Wat Phra Si Mahathat BTS station|Wat Phra Si Mahathat station]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bangkok Skytrain]]\n{{Sukhumvit Line navbox}}\n\n[[Category:BTS Skytrain stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2017]]\n\n\n{{Bangkok-geo-stub}}\n{{Thailand-rail-transport-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox station\n| name = [[File:BTS E15.svg|40px]]<br/>Samrong\n| native_name = \u0e2a\u0e33\u0e42\u0e23\u0e07\n| native_name_lang = th\n| other_name = \n| type = {{rint|bangkok|Sukhumvit}}\n{{rint|bangkok|Yellow}}\n| image = BTS_Samrong_station.jpg\n| address = [[Mueang Samut Prakan District|Mueang Samut Prakan]], [[Samut Prakan Province|Samut Prakan]], [[Thailand]]\n| owned = [[Bangkok Metropolitan Administration]] (BMA)\n| operator            = [[BTS Group Holdings|Bangkok Mass Transit System<br>Public Company Limited]] (BTSC)\n| coordinates = {{coord|13.647363|100.596153}}\n| line = {{rail color box|system=BTS|line=Sukhumvit}}\n{{rail color box|system=Bangkok MRT|line=Yellow}} ''(Yellow Line opening 2021)''\n| other = \n| code = E15 (Sukhumvit line)<br/>''YL25 (Yellow line)''\n| opened = 3 April 2017\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = \n | services=\n{{s-rail|title=Bangkok Rapid Transit}}\n{{s-line|system=BTS|line=Sukhumvit|previous=Bearing|next=Pu Chao|type=North|type2=East}}\n}}\n\n[[File:BTS E15 Traditional station sign (MRTA Standard).svg|thumb|Samrong Station Traditional sign]]\n'''Samrong''' ({{lang-th|\u0e2a\u0e16\u0e32\u0e19\u0e35\u0e2a\u0e33\u0e42\u0e23\u0e07}}, {{RTGS|''Sathani Samrong''}}, {{IPA-th|s\u0101.t\u02b0\u01ce\u02d0.n\u012b\u02d0 s\u01cem.r\u014d\u02d0\u014b|pron}}) is a [[Bangkok Skytrain|BTS Skytrain]] station, on the [[Sukhumvit Line]] in [[Samut Prakan]], [[Thailand]].\n\nTrial operation began in March 2017, and the station was officially opened by Prime Minister [[Prayut Chan-o-cha]] on 3 April 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/news/national/30311133|title=Public to get free trial, as Samrong BTS station now opens \u2013 The Nation|work=The Nation|access-date=2017-04-03|language=en}}</ref> with passengers able to ride the extension for free for a month beginning on 4 April 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://coconuts.co/bangkok/news/bts-offers-free-rides-new-station-first-samut-prakarn/|title=BTS offers free rides to new station, first in Samut Prakarn {{!}} Coconuts Bangkok|date=2017-03-16|work=Coconuts|access-date=2017-04-01|language=en-US}}</ref> It was the eastern terminus of the line, until the opening of the other stations of the [[Sukhumvit Line]] Extension (East) on 6 December 2018. In future it will connect to the [[MRT Yellow Line]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pattayamail.com/thailandnews/bearing-samrong-segment-bts-green-line-put-trial-run-167271|title=Bearing-Samrong segment of BTS Green Line put on trial run - Pattaya It is one of the 2 stations which have an island platform, the other to be Siam station. Mail|last=Mail|first=Pattaya|date=2017-03-16|work=Pattaya Mail|access-date=2017-04-01|language=en-US}}</ref> It is one of only three BTS stations to have island platforms, with the other being [[Siam BTS Station|Siam]] and [[Ha Yaek Lat Phrao BTS station|Ha Yaek Lat Phrao]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bangkok Skytrain]]\n{{Sukhumvit Line navbox}}\n\n[[Category:BTS Skytrain stations]]\n[[Category:Railway stations opened in 2017]]\n\n\n{{Bangkok-geo-stub}}\n{{Thailand-rail-transport-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Oum13928", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samrong_BTS_station"}
{"title_page": "Crep Protect", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Crep Protect|timestamp=20200415175515|year=2020|month=April|day=15|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Crep Protect|date=15 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|British based footwear accessories developer}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name         = Crep Protect Ltd.\n| logo         = Crep Protect Logo.jpg\n| logo_caption = \n| type         = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| owners       = Undercover Brothers Ltd. & Jason Black\n| industry     = Shoe Care Brand\n| products     = Specialised [[Sneakers|Sneaker]] care products & [[insoles]]\n| foundation   = {{start date and age|2013|df=yes}} <ref name=endevourmagazine/>\n| location     = [[London, England]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| founders      = Imran, Nohman and Rizwan Ahmed with Jason Black(Co-founders)\n| key_people   = Nohman & Imran Ahmed (Co-directors)\n| homepage     = {{URL|crepprotect.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Crep Protect Ltd.''', trading as 'Crep Protect' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] based specialised footwear accessories developer and shoecare brand.\n\n==History==\n\nCrep Protect was founded in 2013  and was later incorporated in November 2014 by Jason Black (J2K) & brothers Imran, Nohman, and Rizwan Ahmed. The Ahmed brothers grew up involved with their family business, a [[carpet]] and [[fabric]] store, which was a source of inspiration for their development of a [[trainers]] cleaner that tweaked the formula of carpet cleaning products. In collaboration with [[Grime (music genre)|Grime]] artist J2K (Jason Black), they spent a year of development using [[hydrophobic]] [[Nanotechnology]] in order to create the 'Crep Protect' product <ref>{{cite web |last1=Supernova |first1=Jamz |title=Jamz Supernova - DIY Generation with J2K - BBC Sounds |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/p0427prg |website=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>. J2k had previous attempts at business ventures and saw this opportunity as a 'no brainer', using his contacts to promote the product within the music scene resulting in the company gaining the attention of retailer Bank Fashion, owned by [[JD Sports]] <ref>{{cite web |last1=Journals of the World |title=Crep Protect |url=https://journalsoftheworld.com/2016/10/02/crepprotect/ |website=Journals of the World |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=2 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Supernova |first1=Jamz |title=Jamz Supernova - DIY Generation with J2K - BBC Sounds |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/p0427prg |website=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Boyce |title=From the Forefront of Grime to Creating the UK's Leading Sneaker Care Product |url=https://thehundreds.com/blogs/content/j2k-crep-protect |website=The Hundreds |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Companies House |title=CREP PROTECT LIMITED - Overview (free company information from Companies House) |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/09223288 |website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Grant |first1=Dionne |title=Training Day: Rapper J2k's footwear business is booming {{!}} The Voice Online |url=https://archive.voice-online.co.uk/article/training-day-rapper-j2ks-footwear-business-booming |website=archive.voice-online.co.uk |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Liam |title=Brothers clean up by caring for trainers |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/brothers-clean-up-by-caring-for-trainers-rtkp9z2hs |website=The Times |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>. \n\nBy 2015 Crep Protect had grown internationally, through partnerships with major retailers [[Foot Locker|Footlocker]], [[Urban Outfitters]] and [[JD Sports]] as well as collaborations with the [[NBA]] and [[Red Bull]] <ref>{{cite web |last1=Magazine |first1=Mr Trapped |title=Crep Protect Co-Founder J2K talks to us about the NBA Collaboration - Interview |url=https://trappedmagazine.com/crep-protect-co-founder-j2k-talks-us-nba-collaboration-interview/ |website=Trapped Magazine |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=7 December 2015}}</ref> and the company won Best Footwear innovation of the year at the 2016 [[Drapers]] Footwear Awards <ref>{{cite web |last1=Geoghegan |first1=Jill |title=Which are the UK's fastest-growing private fashion firms? |url=https://www.drapersonline.com/news/which-are-the-uks-fastest-growing-private-fashion-firms/7033305.article |website=Drapers |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>. In 2017, the company opened their first sneaker cleaning & [[consignment]] store which gained 2nd Place at the [[FX (magazine)|FX]] International Interior Design Awards in 2017 <ref>{{cite web |last1=Sawyer |first1=Jonathan |title=Crep Protect Opens Sneaker Consignment & Cleaning Store in London |url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/crep-protect-london-store/ |website=Highsnobiety |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Best Architectural Projects - External Reference |url=https://externalreference.com/projects/pbl17 |website=externalreference.com |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. In the same year J2K stepped down from his role as a co-director, remaining a major shareholder, in order to focus on other projects <ref>{{cite web |last1=Pellat |first1=Corey |title=J2K Has Announced He's Leaving Crep Protect To Work On Other Projects |url=https://www.complex.com/sneakers/2017/01/j2k-leaves-crep-protect |website=Complex |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>.  For his work, J2K (Jason Black) was recognised in the 2020 Black [[Powerlist]], recognising Britain's most influential people of African, African Caribbean and African American heritage for his contributions in the Business, Corporate, Financiers & Entrepreneurs sector <ref>{{cite web |last1=Mills |first1=Kelly-Ann |title=Raheem Sterling joins Meghan and Stormzy in top 100 most influential black Brits |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/black-powerlist-2020-raheem-sterling-20721033 |website=mirror |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>.\n\nDuring the first few years of operations the company saw rapid growth which saw it listed second in the 2018 [[Sunday Times Fast Track 100]] list of Britains fastest-growing companies by sales. Crep Protect had a 3-year annual sales rise of 190.7% in 2018, hitting \u00a327.5m<ref>{{cite web |title=Fast Track - Crep Protect |url=https://www.fasttrack.co.uk/company_profile/crep-protect/ |website=Fast Track |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. In 2018, the company reached export sales of \u00a320.2m and a 2-year average international sales growth of 151.8% which resulted in it being ranked 9th in the [[The Sunday Times]] International Fast Track 2019 rankings <ref>{{cite web |last1=Sunday Times |title=Sunday Times International Track 200 - Crep Protect |url=https://www.fasttrack.co.uk/company_profile/crep-protect-2/ |website=Fast Track}}</ref>. 2019 also saw Crep Protect diversify it's product range, with the launch of a range of [[insoles]] and partnering to launch a range of co-branded products and provide a branded space in [[Adidas]] new Londnon flagship store offering cleaning and customisation services <ref>{{cite web |last1=Complex |title=Crep Protect Takes Another Giant Step Forward with Innovative and Customisable 'Ultimate Gel' Insoles |url=https://www.complex.com/sneakers/2020/03/crep-protect-ultimate-gel-insoles |website=Complex |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wilson |first1=Tayler |title=Crep Protect and adidas_LDN team up for collaboration |url=https://mixmag.net/read/crep-protect-adidas-ldn-collaboration-fashion |website=Mixmag |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pellatt |first1=Corey |title=adidas and Crep Protect Bring a 360-Degree Sneaker Selfie Booth to Oxford Street in Latest Collaboration |url=https://www.complex.com/sneakers/2020/01/adidas-crep-protect-360-degree-sneaker-selfie |website=Complex |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |title=Crep Protect Offers Free Sneaker Customisation In Partnership With adidas Originals |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/fashion/crep-protect-offers-free-sneaker-customisation-in-partnership-with-adidas-originals |website=Clash Magazine |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>.\n\nIn February 2020, the company was issued a first gazette notice with threat of being dissolved and struck-off the register at [[Companies House]] however this action was swiftly discontinued<ref>{{cite web |last1=Companies House |title=CREP PROTECT LIMITED - Filing history (free information from Companies House) |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/09223288/filing-history |website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>. 2020 also saw the company strike promotional deals with the [[Chicago Huntsmen]] as well as sponsoring [[Oxford United F.C.]] <ref>{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Trent |title=Call of Duty League Franchise Chicago Huntsmen Partners With Crep Protect |url=https://esportsobserver.com/creps-protect-chicago-huntsmen/ |website=The Esports Observer\uff5chome of essential esports business news and insights |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Team Crep |title=Crep Protect Set to Sponsor Oxford United F.C. in Upcoming FA Cup Tie \u2013 Crep Protect {{!}} Home |url=https://crepprotect.com/crep-protect-set-to-sponsor-oxford-united-f-c-in-upcoming-fa-cup-tie/ |website=Crep Protect |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n===Niche market===\nAs one of the founders puts it \u201cThe shoe care industry is often ignored, it\u2019s often just an item for sale in the store that you\u2019re pushed to buy, even though you don\u2019t really want it.\"  Because of the high price point only high tier retailers stock the product.  Some would say they have reinvented shoe care products and by creating a culture around it, having lasting success.<ref name=endevourmagazine/>  The company currently has distribution centres in the UK, Belgium, China, and the USA. In 2019 tt sold 16 million cleaning kits.<ref name=endevourmagazine/>\n\n===Presentedby===\nPresentedby is one of the go-to places for sneakerheads, influencers, and bloggers in the U.K. capital.<ref name=endevourmagazine>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/charlie-sloth-crep-protect-presentedby/|title=Charlie Sloth Visits Presentedby Store in London to Chat Sneakers & More|date=April 13, 2018}}</ref>  The store was founded by the three brothers that started crep protect.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.littlegatepublishing.com/2020/01/crep-protect/|title=Crep Protect: A foot in the door|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Community involvement and sponsorships==\n* Crep Protect is the main sponsor of the Venice Basketball League aka Veniceball of Los Angeles.  In March 2019 helped launch the Watts Oasis with St. John\u2019s United Methodist Church and the Watts community council.<ref>{{cit web|url=https://veniceball.com/2019/03/28/the-watts-oasis-is-open-now-and-forever-special-thanks-to-crep-protect-and-the-community-at-large/|title=The Watts Oasis is Open now and forever, special thanks to Crep Protect and the community at large|date=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n*Has been a longtime supporter of sneaker conventions the largest of which is '''sneakerness London'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.magneticmag.com/2018/07/international-sneaker-convention-sneakerness-coming-to-london/|title=SNEAKERNESS GOES INTERNATIONAL: NEXT STOP LONDON|date=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n\n'''Cleaning Products & Tools'''\n* Crep Protect Spray\n* Crep Protect Wipes\n* Eraser\n* Cure Travel Kit \n* Headwear Spray\n\n'''Accessories'''\n* Laces\n* Insoles / Gel Insoles\n\n'''Miscellaneous'''\n* Crep Protect Pill\n* Mark on Pen\n* Storage Crate\n* Sneaker Tree\n\n==Awards==\n\n'''[[Drapers]] Footwear Awards'''\n* 2016 - Best Innovation - Winner\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:British companies established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Companies based in London]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Crep Protect|timestamp=20200415175515|year=2020|month=April|day=15|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Crep Protect|date=15 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|British based footwear accessories developer}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name         = Crep Protect Ltd.\n| logo         = Crep Protect Logo.jpg\n| logo_caption = \n| type         = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| owners       = Undercover Brothers Ltd. & Jason Black\n| industry     = Shoe Care Brand\n| products     = Specialised [[Sneakers|Sneaker]] care products & [[insoles]]\n| foundation   = {{start date and age|2013|df=yes}} <ref name=endevourmagazine/>\n| location     = [[London, England]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| founders      = Imran, Nohman and Rizwan Ahmed with Jason Black(Co-founders)\n| key_people   = Nohman & Imran Ahmed (Co-directors)\n| homepage     = {{URL|crepprotect.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Crep Protect Ltd.''', trading as 'Crep Protect' is a [[United Kingdom|British]] based specialised footwear accessories developer and shoecare brand.\n\n==History==\n\nCrep Protect was founded in 2013  and was later incorporated in November 2014 by Jason Black (J2K) & brothers Imran, Nohman, and Rizwan Ahmed. The Ahmed brothers grew up involved with their family business, a [[carpet]] and [[fabric]] store, which was a source of inspiration for their development of a [[trainers]] cleaner that tweaked the formula of carpet cleaning products. In collaboration with [[Grime (music genre)|Grime]] artist J2K (Jason Black), they spent a year of development using [[hydrophobic]] [[Nanotechnology]] in order to create the 'Crep Protect' product <ref>{{cite web |last1=Supernova |first1=Jamz |title=Jamz Supernova - DIY Generation with J2K - BBC Sounds |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/p0427prg |website=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>. J2k had previous attempts at business ventures and saw this opportunity as a 'no brainer', using his contacts to promote the product within the music scene resulting in the company gaining the attention of retailer Bank Fashion, owned by [[JD Sports]] <ref>{{cite web |last1=Journals of the World |title=Crep Protect |url=https://journalsoftheworld.com/2016/10/02/crepprotect/ |website=Journals of the World |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=2 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Supernova |first1=Jamz |title=Jamz Supernova - DIY Generation with J2K - BBC Sounds |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sounds/play/p0427prg |website=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Boyce |title=From the Forefront of Grime to Creating the UK's Leading Sneaker Care Product |url=https://thehundreds.com/blogs/content/j2k-crep-protect |website=The Hundreds |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Companies House |title=CREP PROTECT LIMITED - Overview (free company information from Companies House) |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/09223288 |website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Grant |first1=Dionne |title=Training Day: Rapper J2k's footwear business is booming {{!}} The Voice Online |url=https://archive.voice-online.co.uk/article/training-day-rapper-j2ks-footwear-business-booming |website=archive.voice-online.co.uk |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Liam |title=Brothers clean up by caring for trainers |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/brothers-clean-up-by-caring-for-trainers-rtkp9z2hs |website=The Times |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>. \n\nBy 2015 Crep Protect had grown internationally, through partnerships with major retailers [[Foot Locker|Footlocker]], [[Urban Outfitters]] and [[JD Sports]] as well as collaborations with the [[NBA]] and [[Red Bull]] <ref>{{cite web |last1=Magazine |first1=Mr Trapped |title=Crep Protect Co-Founder J2K talks to us about the NBA Collaboration - Interview |url=https://trappedmagazine.com/crep-protect-co-founder-j2k-talks-us-nba-collaboration-interview/ |website=Trapped Magazine |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=7 December 2015}}</ref> and the company won Best Footwear innovation of the year at the 2016 [[Drapers]] Footwear Awards <ref>{{cite web |last1=Geoghegan |first1=Jill |title=Which are the UK's fastest-growing private fashion firms? |url=https://www.drapersonline.com/news/which-are-the-uks-fastest-growing-private-fashion-firms/7033305.article |website=Drapers |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>. In 2017, the company opened their first sneaker cleaning & [[consignment]] store which gained 2nd Place at the [[FX (magazine)|FX]] International Interior Design Awards in 2017 <ref>{{cite web |last1=Sawyer |first1=Jonathan |title=Crep Protect Opens Sneaker Consignment & Cleaning Store in London |url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/crep-protect-london-store/ |website=Highsnobiety |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Best Architectural Projects - External Reference |url=https://externalreference.com/projects/pbl17 |website=externalreference.com |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. In the same year J2K stepped down from his role as a co-director, remaining a major shareholder, in order to focus on other projects <ref>{{cite web |last1=Pellat |first1=Corey |title=J2K Has Announced He's Leaving Crep Protect To Work On Other Projects |url=https://www.complex.com/sneakers/2017/01/j2k-leaves-crep-protect |website=Complex |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>.  For his work, J2K (Jason Black) was recognised in the 2020 Black [[Powerlist]], recognising Britain's most influential people of African, African Caribbean and African American heritage for his contributions in the Business, Corporate, Financiers & Entrepreneurs sector <ref>{{cite web |last1=Mills |first1=Kelly-Ann |title=Raheem Sterling joins Meghan and Stormzy in top 100 most influential black Brits |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/uk-news/black-powerlist-2020-raheem-sterling-20721033 |website=mirror |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>.\n\nDuring the first few years of operations the company saw rapid growth which saw it listed second in the 2018 [[Sunday Times Fast Track 100]] list of Britains fastest-growing companies by sales. Crep Protect had a 3-year annual sales rise of 190.7% in 2018, hitting \u00a327.5m<ref>{{cite web |title=Fast Track - Crep Protect |url=https://www.fasttrack.co.uk/company_profile/crep-protect/ |website=Fast Track |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>. In 2018, the company reached export sales of \u00a320.2m and a 2-year average international sales growth of 151.8% which resulted in it being ranked 9th in the [[The Sunday Times]] International Fast Track 2019 rankings <ref>{{cite web |last1=Sunday Times |title=Sunday Times International Track 200 - Crep Protect |url=https://www.fasttrack.co.uk/company_profile/crep-protect-2/ |website=Fast Track}}</ref>. 2019 also saw Crep Protect diversify it's product range, with the launch of a range of [[insoles]] and partnering to launch a range of co-branded products and provide a branded space in [[Adidas]] new Londnon flagship store offering cleaning and customisation services <ref>{{cite web |last1=Complex |title=Crep Protect Takes Another Giant Step Forward with Innovative and Customisable 'Ultimate Gel' Insoles |url=https://www.complex.com/sneakers/2020/03/crep-protect-ultimate-gel-insoles |website=Complex |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Wilson |first1=Tayler |title=Crep Protect and adidas_LDN team up for collaboration |url=https://mixmag.net/read/crep-protect-adidas-ldn-collaboration-fashion |website=Mixmag |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Pellatt |first1=Corey |title=adidas and Crep Protect Bring a 360-Degree Sneaker Selfie Booth to Oxford Street in Latest Collaboration |url=https://www.complex.com/sneakers/2020/01/adidas-crep-protect-360-degree-sneaker-selfie |website=Complex |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Clash |title=Crep Protect Offers Free Sneaker Customisation In Partnership With adidas Originals |url=https://www.clashmusic.com/fashion/crep-protect-offers-free-sneaker-customisation-in-partnership-with-adidas-originals |website=Clash Magazine |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>.\n\nIn February 2020, the company was issued a first gazette notice with threat of being dissolved and struck-off the register at [[Companies House]] however this action was swiftly discontinued<ref>{{cite web |last1=Companies House |title=CREP PROTECT LIMITED - Filing history (free information from Companies House) |url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/09223288/filing-history |website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk |accessdate=14 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref>. 2020 also saw the company strike promotional deals with the [[Chicago Huntsmen]] as well as sponsoring [[Oxford United F.C.]] <ref>{{cite web |last1=Murray |first1=Trent |title=Call of Duty League Franchise Chicago Huntsmen Partners With Crep Protect |url=https://esportsobserver.com/creps-protect-chicago-huntsmen/ |website=The Esports Observer\uff5chome of essential esports business news and insights |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=25 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Team Crep |title=Crep Protect Set to Sponsor Oxford United F.C. in Upcoming FA Cup Tie \u2013 Crep Protect {{!}} Home |url=https://crepprotect.com/crep-protect-set-to-sponsor-oxford-united-f-c-in-upcoming-fa-cup-tie/ |website=Crep Protect |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>.\n\n===Niche market===\nAs one of the founders puts it \u201cThe shoe care industry is often ignored, it\u2019s often just an item for sale in the store that you\u2019re pushed to buy, even though you don\u2019t really want it.\"  Because of the high price point only high tier retailers stock the product.  Some would say they have reinvented shoe care products and by creating a culture around it, having longterm success.<ref name=endevourmagazine/>  The company currently has distribution centres in the UK, Belgium, China, and the USA. In 2019 tt sold 16 million cleaning kits.<ref name=endevourmagazine/>\n\n===Presentedby===\nPresentedby is one of the go-to places for sneakerheads, influencers, and bloggers in the U.K. capital.<ref name=endevourmagazine>{{cite web|url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/charlie-sloth-crep-protect-presentedby/|title=Charlie Sloth Visits Presentedby Store in London to Chat Sneakers & More|date=April 13, 2018}}</ref>  The store was founded by the three brothers that started crep protect.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.littlegatepublishing.com/2020/01/crep-protect/|title=Crep Protect: A foot in the door|date=January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Community involvement and sponsorships==\n* Crep Protect is the main sponsor of the Venice Basketball League aka Veniceball of Los Angeles.  In March 2019 helped launch the Watts Oasis with St. John\u2019s United Methodist Church and the Watts community council.<ref>{{cit web|url=https://veniceball.com/2019/03/28/the-watts-oasis-is-open-now-and-forever-special-thanks-to-crep-protect-and-the-community-at-large/|title=The Watts Oasis is Open now and forever, special thanks to Crep Protect and the community at large|date=March 28, 2019}}</ref>\n*Has been a longtime supporter of sneaker conventions the largest of which is '''sneakerness London'''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.magneticmag.com/2018/07/international-sneaker-convention-sneakerness-coming-to-london/|title=SNEAKERNESS GOES INTERNATIONAL: NEXT STOP LONDON|date=July 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\n\n'''Cleaning Products & Tools'''\n* Crep Protect Spray\n* Crep Protect Wipes\n* Eraser\n* Cure Travel Kit \n* Headwear Spray\n\n'''Accessories'''\n* Laces\n* Insoles / Gel Insoles\n\n'''Miscellaneous'''\n* Crep Protect Pill\n* Mark on Pen\n* Storage Crate\n* Sneaker Tree\n\n==Awards==\n\n'''[[Drapers]] Footwear Awards'''\n* 2016 - Best Innovation - Winner\n\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:British companies established in 2012]]\n[[Category:Companies based in London]]\n", "name_user": "Grmike", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNiche market", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crep_Protect"}
{"title_page": "Houston, Renfrewshire", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n |country = Scotland\n |official_name = Houston\n |gaelic_name = Cille Pheadair\n |scots_name = Houstoun\n |os_grid_reference = NS404667\n |map_type = Scotland\n|static_image_name=Main Street, Houston, Renfrewshire (geograph 5906206).jpg\n|static_image_width=280\n|static_image_caption= Main Street in Houston\n |coordinates = {{coord|55.86697|-4.55207|display=inline,title}}\n |population = 6610\n |population_ref = (1991 census)\n |civil_parish = [[Houston and Killellan]]\n |unitary_scotland = [[Renfrewshire]]\n |lieutenancy_scotland = [[Renfrewshire (historic)|Renfrewshire]]\n |post_town = JOHNSTONE\n |postcode_district = PA6\n |postcode_area = PA \n |dial_code = 01505\n |constituency_westminster = [[Paisley and Renfrewshire North (UK Parliament constituency)|Paisley and Renfrewshire North]]\n |constituency_scottish_parliament = [[Renfrewshire North and West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Renfrewshire North and West]]<br>[[Renfrewshire South (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Renfrewshire South]]\n}}\n\n'''Houston''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|u\u02d0|s|t|\u0259n}} {{respell|HOOS|t\u0259n}}) is a [[village]] in the [[council areas of Scotland|council area]] of [[Renfrewshire]] and the larger historic [[counties of Scotland|county]] [[Renfrewshire (historic)|of the same name]] in the west [[central Lowlands]] of [[Scotland]].\n\nHouston lies within the [[Gryffe Valley]] on the banks of the [[River Gryffe]] {{convert|6|mi|km|0}} north-west of [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] and is the largest settlement in the [[civil parish]] of [[Houston and Killellan]], which covers the neighbouring village of [[Crosslee]] and a number of smaller settlements in the villages' rural hinterland.\n\nThe village grew around a 16th-century castle and parish church dedicated to [[Saint Peter]], which gave the area its former name of '''Kilpeter''' (\"''Cille Pheadair''\" in [[Scottish Gaelic]]). The present day old village dates mainly back to the 18th century and was a planned community, replacing earlier buildings. Historically, the economy was based around agriculture and, in common with a number of other Renfrewshire villages, cotton weaving. The old village was designated as a [[conservation area]] in 1968.\n\nFrom the middle of the 20th century, a larger area of residential settlement expanded the village into nearby areas such as [[Craigends]], removing the open country between Houston and Crosslee. These additions to the village have expanded its population considerably, changing its character chiefly to a [[dormitory settlement]] for nearby [[Glasgow]] and [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] with a largely service-based economy. \n\n==History==\n===Toponymy===\n[[Image:Houston House in Renfrewshire, Scotland.jpg|thumb|Houston House.]]\nHouston was originally known as Kilpeter. In the mid 12th century, the fee of Kilpeter was granted by [[Baldwin of Biggar|Baldwin of Biggar, Sheriff of Lanark]], to [[Hugh de Paduinan|Hugh of Pettinain]]. From Hugh, the lands eventually became known as Houston (meaning \"Hugh's ''tun'' or manor\").<ref>{{citation |last=Barrow |first=Geoffrey Wallis Steuart |author-link=G. W. S. Barrow |title=The kingdom of the Scots: government, church and society from the eleventh to the fourteenth century |publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]] |year=2003 |isbn=0 7486 1802 3 |pages=319\u2013320}}. \u2013 via [[Google Books]]</ref>\n\nIn a [[Papal Bull|Bull]] of [[Pope Honorius III|Pope Honorius]] in 1225-7, the churches of Kilmacolm and Houston are mentioned as \"ecclesiae de Kilmacolme et de Villa Hugonis\". In a later Bull of [[Pope Clement IV]] in 1265, the churches belonging to [[Paisley Abbey]] are listed including the church of \"Howston\".<ref>James Murray (Rev.), Kilmacolm: A Parish History, 1898</ref>\n\n===Early history===\nHouston had long been a site of human settlement. In the 1970s, a [[Bronze Age]] burial site was found at South Mound on the western edge of the village.<ref>See Morrison, A ''A Bronze Age burial site near South Mound, Houston, Renfrewshire'', Glasgow ArchaeolJ, 6 (1979), 20\u201345</ref> To the north-east lies Barochan Hill,<ref name=Canmore>{{Canmore |num=43107 |desc=Barochan Hill|access-date=2017-11-12}}</ref> the site of a [[Roman Empire|Roman]] fort.<ref name=\"survey\">{{cite web|url=http://ilwwcm.renfrewshire.gov.uk/pdfs/pt/ROFApplication1/pt-SiteGazetter0606.pdf |publisher=Renfrewshire Council |author=[[BAE Systems]] and Redrow Housing |date=2006-05-01 |accessdate=2009-06-30 |title=Royal Ordnance Bishopton: Site Gazetteer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722011954/http://ilwwcm.renfrewshire.gov.uk/pdfs/pt/ROFApplication1/pt-SiteGazetter0606.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-22 }}</ref> A later [[Antonine Wall|Antonine era]] fort was found on a farm near [[Bishopton, Renfrewshire|Bishopton]], less than 2 miles away.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bishopton Roman Fort|url=http://roman-britain.co.uk/places/bishopton.htm|website=Roman Britain|accessdate=11 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812193754/http://roman-britain.co.uk/places/bishopton.htm|archive-date=12 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe first village in Houston was constructed around the parish Church of St Peter and Houston Castle, now respectively the parish church and Houston House \u2013 largely 19th century buildings. Houston House and the castle which is partially incorporated within its structure date back to the time of Hugh of Pettinain and remained in the possession of his family who later became the [[Clan Houston|Houstons of Houston]].<ref name=\"communitywebsite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/Navigation-els-Houston(OurHistoryandHeritage)Homepage|publisher=Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=2009-06-30|title=Renfrewshire Community Website \u2013 Houston|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301035602/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/Navigation-els-Houston%28OurHistoryandHeritage%29Homepage|archive-date=1 March 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Castle stayed in the ownership of the family until 1740 when it was purchased by [[Glasgow]] [[tobacco lord]] Alexander Speirs of Elderslie.<ref name=\"visionofbritain.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/descriptions/entry_page.jsp;jsessionid=39753DBEB127C8CF32E951C389579B8A?text_id=120230&word=NULL|title=Houston - As described in F.H. Groome's Ordnance Gazetteer of Scotland (1882-4)|website=www.visionofbritain.org.uk}}</ref> Following ownership by five generations of the Speirs family, Houston House passed to Major David Crichton Maitland in 1959 and then to his son Mark Crichton Maitland in 1995 before being divided into a number of [[apartments|flats]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elderslie.org/ee_about.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701094550/http://www.elderslie.org/ee_about.php |archivedate=2011-07-01 }}</ref>\n[[Image:NorthStreetHouston.JPG|thumb|North Street, in the old village]] James McGuire MacRae was presented with the estate by his father's friend, [[Monkton, Ayrshire|James MacRae]]. It passed to his son, who demolished the castle and built the weavers cottages with the stones.<ref>Cuthbertson, David Cuningham (1945). ''Autumn in Kyle and the Charm of Cunninghame''. London : Jenkins. P. 35</ref> With this 18th-century change in ownership of the land therefore, the 'old village' was cleared from around the castle by the [[laird]]. The new village of some thirty five cottages constructed to the west in 1781 from the stone of the Castle, which was later to evolve into a [[country house]]. This new village \u2013 which forms the basis of the modern village \u2013 was a [[planned community]] built along two main streets: North Street and South Street and is an example of the 18th century Planned Village Movement.<ref>M. Pacione, ''Planning urban growth in Scotland: The new settlement option'' Scottish Geographical Journal, 1751-665X, Volume 122, Issue 1, 2006, Pages 32 \u2013 54</ref> The layout, straddling the Houston [[Burn (topography)|Burn]], provided washing facilities accessible to local people as well as supporting the small-scale [[weaving]] industry.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/AttachmentsByTitle/pt-as-Strathgryfe.pdf/$FILE/pt-as-Strathgryfe.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=13 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110919121604/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/AttachmentsByTitle/pt-as-Strathgryfe.pdf/$FILE/pt-as-Strathgryfe.pdf |archive-date=19 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This 'new village' is designated by the [[Renfrewshire]] authorities as a [[conservation village]].<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" /><ref name=\"conservation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/PT-AB-Houston-Conservation-Area|publisher=Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=2009-06-30|title=Renfrewshire Community Website \u2013 Houston Conservation Area|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428025938/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/PT-AB-Houston-Conservation-Area|archive-date=28 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA notable remnant of this move is the village's [[mercat cross]], which incorporates parts dating back to the 14th century. Due to the move from an original position on Kirk Road, and the fact that it incorporates a large [[sundial]], it has been placed at an unusual angle at the centre of the 'new' village. The mercat cross has become used as a symbol for the village.<ref>Being used, for example, in the badge of Houston Primary School; and to represent Houston in the arms of Gryffe High School where an image of Ranfurly Castle is used to represent [[Bridge of Weir]]</ref>\n\n===Modern history===\nBoth railway stations (on separate lines) built within the parish in the 19th century, [[Houston (Scotland) railway station|Houston and Crosslee Station]] and [[Georgetown (Scotland) railway station|Georgetown station]] (both now closed), bypassed the village itself. As a consequence, Houston did not experience the railway boom of nearby villages like [[Bridge of Weir]] and [[Kilmacolm]], expanding slowly until the later half of the 20th century when it became a popular [[commuter settlement]].<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" />\n\nThe main industry of the Houston between the 17th and 19th century was [[weaving]]. The [[River Gryffe]] later provided a cotton spinning industry with the creation of the [[Crosslee]] cotton mill with other small manufacturing concerns, such as embroidery, later opening in the village.<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" />\n\nIn July 2007, Houston was featured prominently in news reports around the [[United Kingdom]] after it was discovered that inhabitants of a house in the village were linked to the [[2007 Glasgow International Airport attack]] of 30 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-1273143,00.html?f=rss|title=Police Comb House Near Glasgow -Sky News-UK News<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref> The Houston Community Council observed that \"it is a sobering thought that such a situation could happen on our very doorstep and that even in a quiet, rural setting such as ours there can be people intent on disrupting the natural balance of things by violent means.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.houstoncommunitycouncil.co.uk/assets/literature/NOVEMBER%20AGM%202007.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006214106/http://www.houstoncommunitycouncil.co.uk/assets/literature/NOVEMBER%20AGM%202007.pdf |archive-date=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n[[Image:Houston Village Hall.JPG|thumb|Houston's Village Hall]]\n\n===Local government===\n:: ''See also: [[Houston and Killellan]]''\nHouston and its parish form part of the [[Renfrewshire]] [[council areas of Scotland|council area]]. For the 2007 local authority elections in Scotland, Houston was entered into a new four-councillor [[Ward (country subdivision)|ward]], Ward 9, alongside Crosslee and the town of [[Linwood, Renfrewshire|Linwood]] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20090321075553/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/Navigation-cs-Ward9HomePage Ward 9]).\n\nThe boundaries of the [[civil parishes in Scotland|civil parish]] of Houston and Kilellan follow the creation of a united [[ecclesiastical parish]] centred on Houston in the 18th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.houstonscotland.org.uk/kirk/our%20church.htm|title=Houston and Killellan Kirk<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|access-date=9 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106124721/http://www.houstonscotland.org.uk/kirk/our%20church.htm|archive-date=6 January 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The parish spreads over a wide rural hinterland including a number of nearby settlements, the most significant being [[Crosslee]], [[Craigends]] and Barochan.\n\nWith the decline of significance of the [[civil parish]] in local government, this area has largely become part of the Houston [[community council|Community Council]] area [https://web.archive.org/web/20090523042737/http://www.houstoncommunitycouncil.co.uk/]. The community council is chiefly a consultative body, forming a focus for local views, and has no statutory powers of its own.\n\n===Central government===\nHouston forms part of the [[Paisley and Renfrewshire North]] [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]] for elections to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. The current [[Member of Parliament]] for this area is [[Gavin Newlands]] MP. The constituency was created in 2005 following boundary changes with Houston previously forming part of the [[West Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|West Renfrewshire]] constituency.\n\nFor [[devolution|devolved]] matters, Houston is part of the [[Scottish Parliament]] [[Scottish Parliament constituencies and regions|constituency]] of [[Renfrewshire North and West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Renfrewshire North and West]], which straddles the boundary between the council areas of Inverclyde and Renfrewshire. Since 2011, the constituency [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] for the area is [[Derek Mackay]] MSP. The Renfrewshire North and West constituency forms part of the [[West of Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|West of Scotland]] [[Scottish Parliament constituencies and regions|Scottish Parliament electoral region]]. Seven further MSPs are elected for this region through the Scottish Parliament's [[Mixed member proportional representation|Additional Member electoral system]].\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[Image:Houston mercat cross.JPG|thumb|Houston's [[mercat cross]], used as a symbol of the village.]]\nHouston's historic village centre, located at the north-west edge of the village, is a designated conservation area. The area is home to the main village pubs, small shops and the village's Post Office. North Street and South Street are dominated by traditional white cottages, some dating to the 17th century. The old village was a planned community of houses largely built around the Houston Burn, which gave communal access to washing facilities.\n\nSome remains of the 16th century Houston Castle still exist largely in the grounds of the current Houston House. The area sits beside [[Houston and Killellan]] Kirk, the established ([[Church of Scotland]]) [[parish church]]. It is possible that [[Lord Darnley]], husband of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] resided at the castle for some years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourlocalhistory.co.uk/yew.html|title=The Craigends Yew-www.ourlocalhistory.co.uk<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Barochan Cross, an 11&nbsp;ft (3.4 metre) tall [[Celtic cross|Celtic Christian cross]] possibly dating to the 8th century, formerly lay just south of the Mill of Barochan in the parish. In the 19th century, it was moved to a knoll opposite Corsliehill closer to the village before finally being moved in the 20th century to [[Paisley Abbey]] where it now remains in order to protect it from further weathering.<ref name=\"survey\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/els-jh-HistoricBuildingsArchaeology|publisher=Renfrewshire Council|author=|date=|accessdate=2009-06-30|title=Archaeology in Renfrewshire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100310094522/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/els-jh-HistoricBuildingsArchaeology|archive-date=10 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Craigends Yew]] is an ancient [[yew tree]] in the parish, supposed to be the oldest living thing in Renfrewshire, with a potential age of around a thousand years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/Navigation-pt-Houston(VisitingRenfrewshire) |title=Archived copy |access-date=19 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210003121/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/Navigation-pt-Houston(VisitingRenfrewshire) |archive-date=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> There are two ancient wells in Houston, once considered to have healing powers. St Fillan's Well sits in the fields beside Kilallan Kirk and St Peter's Well that also gives its name to a locally brewed ale.\n\nThe [[parish church]], which is a congregation of the [[Church of Scotland]], lies to the east of the old village. A 19th century [[Roman Catholic]] church, St Fillan's, is to the south of Main Street.\n\n==Religion==\n[[Image:Houston Kirk.jpg|thumb|right|Houston & Killellan Kirk (parish church), in the grounds of Houston House. The steeple is obscured.]]\n[[File:St Peter's Well, Houston - view from the east & opening.jpg|thumb|[[St Peter's Well, Houston|St Peter's Well]], a historic holy well beside the village.]]\nHouston's has a long association with St Peter, providing the village's historic name of Kilpeter. Its current parish church, Houston and Killellan Church or [[Kirk]], lies in the grounds of Houston House. The Kirk was constructed in the 1870s, replacing a church on the same site constructed in 1775, and dedicated to [[Archibald Alexander Speirs]] of [[Elderslie]]. Following his death aged 28 while sitting as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[West Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|West Renfrewshire]], his mother provided the building costs as a memorial.\n\nThe current parish dates from 1771, when the parishes of Houston and Killellan were united. The former parish church in the nearby hamlet of [[St Fillan's Kirk, Seat and Well|Killellan]] was known as the [[St Fillan's Kirk, Seat and Well|Church of St Fillan]], which the name of the settlement derives. The former church building was left redundant by the unification and was abandoned. The ruin, dated 1635 but believed to have originated in the 10th or 11th century,<ref name=\"elderslie.org\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.elderslie.org/kilallankirk.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119055900/http://www.elderslie.org/kilallankirk.php |archive-date=19 November 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> still stands some {{convert|4|mi|km|0}} west of the centre of Houston on the [[Barochan Cross]] Road. This church is now held by the Kilallan Kirk Preservation Trust following its donation by Elderslie Estates in 2005 and is a scheduled historic monument.<ref name=\"elderslie.org\"/> An annual evening service is held amongst the ruins in July by the congregation of the united parish. The church's manse, which is immediately adjacent to it, also finds continued use as a private residence and is thought to be the oldest existing dwellinghouse in Renfrewshire.<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" /> [[St Fillan's Kirk, Seat and Well|St Fillan's Holy Well]] and [[St Fillan's Kirk, Seat and Well|St Fillan's Seat]] are located near to the old kirk.\n\n[[St Peter's Well, Houston|St Peter's Well]] stands in a field below Greenhill Farm on Chapel Road close to the site of a pre-Reformation chapel and is a rare example of a covered or house holy well, the waters of which were once thought to ensure the safe return of travellers such as pilgrims.\n\nThe Houston and Kilellan [[church hall]] on Main Street was built immediately following the [[Disruption of 1843]] as a separate congregation forming part of the [[Free Church of Scotland (1843-1900)|Free Church of Scotland]], and later the [[United Free Church of Scotland]] being known during this time as the West Kirk. Following the reunification of the United Free Church and the established Church of Scotland in 1929, the West Kirk existed as a second Church of Scotland congregation in the village until a fire destroyed much of the building in March 1941. The lack of a building caused the two congregations to again worship in the same parish church. The West Kirk building was fully restored by 1953, taking its place as the church hall it remains to this day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.houstonscotland.org.uk/kirk/our%20church.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 April 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106124721/http://www.houstonscotland.org.uk/kirk/our%20church.htm |archive-date=6 January 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHouston and Kilellan Kirk is currently the second richest church in Scotland, after Paisley Cathedral.\n\nSt. Fillan's [[Roman Catholic Church]], also on Main Street, was established in 1841 on a property called \"Four Windings\" now remembered in the name of an adjacent street.\n\n==Economy==\nChiefly serving a [[dormitory town|commuter village]], Houston's chief local economic activity is [[agriculture]], with some [[tertiary sector]] businesses such as local shops and public houses serving residents and visitors. There are a number of these shops and pubs in the old village, and a number of shops located on the boundary with [[Crosslee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scottish-places.info/towns/townfirst1158.html|title=Crosslee from The Gazetteer for Scotland|website=www.scottish-places.info}}</ref>\n\n===Public houses and brewing===\nThe parish supports a number of [[public house]]s, with two located in the historic village centre: the Fox and Hounds on South Street and the Houston Inn on North Street, established in 1779 and 1784 respectively. Until 2010, a third, the Cross Keys Inn, lay on Main Street, with a name derived from the crossed keys symbol of [[St Peter]] as a reference to the village's original name, Kilpeter. It has since operated as a restaurant. A further restaurant and public house, the River Inn, lies in Crosslee and was formerly the Crosslee Inn and the Pine Trees.<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" />\n\nThe village hosts a regular beer festival/<ref>http://www.list.co.uk/event/178765-beer-festival-fox-and-hounds-houston/</ref> A [[microbrewery]], the [[Houston Brewing Company]], also formerly operated from a building adjacent to the Fox and Hounds.<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" />\n\n==Culture and community==\nThere are a number of community organisations and events that take place in the village. The village's main park, Houston Public Park, is adjacent to the old village, with others at South Street and Ardgryffe Park among the more modern housing developments.\n\nHouston Public Park is the venue for the village's annual agricultural show, taking place in the summer and organised by the Houston and Killellan Agricultural Society. Another significant local event is the Kirk Carnival, organised by the parish church and focused around the church hall and Carrick Centre on Main Street, which involves a parade and a number of stalls and entertainments and including the local primary schools.\n\nIn 1992, Strathgryffe Tennis Squash and Fitness Club, opened with support from the [[Lawn Tennis Association]] and the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|National Lottery]] Sports Fund, is also located in the village.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strathgryffe.net/club/club-history|title=Club History|website=Strathgryffe Tennis, Squash and Fitness Club}}</ref> An [[Equestrianism|equestrian]] club, the Kilmacolm and Kilallan Riding Club is based on the boundary of the parish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kilmacolmridingclub.org.uk/|title=Kilmacolm and Kilallan Riding Club|website=www.kilmacolmridingclub.org.uk}}</ref> A [[foxhunting|foxhunt]], the Lanarkshire and Renfrewshire Foxhounds, has operated from kennels in the village since 1850.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lanarkandrenfrew.com/|title=Lanarkshire & Renfrewshire Foxhounds|website=lanarkandrenfrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe village also hosts a [[lawn bowls]] club, the John G. Fleming Bowling Club, which was founded the local landowner whose name it bears to mark the [[diamond jubilee]] of [[Queen Victoria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jgflemingbc.co.uk/aboutus.html|title=J.G. Fleming Bowling Club - About Us|website=www.jgflemingbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[Gryffe High School]] is a non-denominational [[co-educational]] [[state school|state]] [[secondary school]] which serves the village and surrounding settlements, most particularly neighbouring [[Bridge of Weir]].<ref name=\"HMIE\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hmie.gov.uk/documents/inspection/8633436GryffeHS1.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100325211205/http://www.hmie.gov.uk/documents/inspection/8633436GryffeHS1.html |archive-date=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The school has a strong academic reputation, and in 2009 was ranked as the seventh best-performing state secondary school in [[Scotland]] by [[The Times]] newspaper's league tables.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/parentpower/league_tables.php?t=state_secondary_schools_in_scotland |location=London |work=The Times |url-status=dead |first=Anushka |last=Asthana |title=The top 50 state secondary schools in Scotland |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605011336/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/parentpower/league_tables.php?t=state_secondary_schools_in_scotland |archivedate=June 5, 2010 }}</ref> Also in 2009, the school was praised in a report by [[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Education]].<ref name=\"HMIE\" />\n\nThere are two [[primary school]]s in Houston. Houston Primary School is a non-denominational school, whereas St Fillan's Primary School is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[faith school]]. Both are co-educational state schools.  As stated above, Gryffe High School is the non-denominational secondary for the village whereas St. Benedict's High School is the Roman Catholic secondary serving Houston along with Bridge of Weir (which St. Fillan's also serves).\n\nThe 'old schoolhouse' at the north end of Main Street in the old village centre has been converted into self-catering accommodation and the former school at the south end of Main Street now exists as a community building known as the Carrick Centre.\n\n==Public services==\nThe [[territorial police force]] covering Houston is the [[Police Service of Scotland]]. It is part of the Renfrewshire and Inverclyde division and the Renfrew area Command. The nearest local [[police station]] is at [[Johnstone]].<ref>https://www.scotland.police.uk/your-community/renfrewshire-and-inverclyde/renfrew/houston-crosslee-and-linwood/</ref> There was a police station and police house in the village opened in the mid-1940s, which was closed in 2001.<ref>http://www.lands-tribunal-scotland.org.uk/decisions/LTS.LO.2000.42.html</ref> \n\nFor judicial purposes, the Houston forms part of the [[sheriffdom]] of North Strathclyde and [[prosecutor|public prosecutions]] are directed by the [[Procurator Fiscal]] for [[Argyll and Clyde]]. The [[Scottish Fire and Rescue Service]] is the statutory [[fire services in Scotland|fire and rescue service]] covering the village and maintains three fire stations in Renfrewshire with the closest at Johnstone.<ref>https://www.firescotland.gov.uk/media/1239511/renfrewshire_local_fire_and_rescue_plan_2018.pdf</ref> \n\n[[NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde]] is the [[NHS Scotland|National Health Service Board]] providing [[Publicly funded health care|public health care]]. The nearest major hospitals with [[accident and emergency]] facilities is the [[Royal Alexandra Hospital, Paisley|Royal Alexandra Hospital]] in Paisley. There is one medical practice in the village, which is linked to another surgery in Bridge of Weir.<ref>https://www.nhsggc.org.uk/locations/gp-surgeries/strathgryffe-medical-practice/#</ref>\n\n[[Water industry|Water]] and [[sewerage]] is provided by [[Scottish Water]], a public body, and water and sewerage charges are collected alongside [[council tax]] by [[Renfrewshire Council]], the local authority, on its behalf. Renfrewshire Council is also responsible for the provision of [[waste management]] in the area.<ref>s.30, Environmental Protection Act 1990 as amended</ref> The local [[Distribution Network Operator]], the organisation licensed to transmit electricity from the [[National Grid (UK)|National Grid]] to consumers, is [[Scottish Power]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.energylinx.co.uk/distribution_network_operators.htm|publisher=energylinx.co.uk|year=2007|accessdate=5 February 2008|title=Electricity Distribution Network Operators|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114055937/http://www.energylinx.co.uk/distribution_network_operators.htm|archivedate=14 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nThere is a [[Post Office Ltd|Post Office]] branch in the village and the [[postal town]], with a larger delivery centre, is [[Johnstone]].<ref>https://www.postoffice.co.uk/branch-finder/1178598/houston</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090523042737/http://www.houstoncommunitycouncil.co.uk/ Houston Community Council website]\n* [http://www.happyhaggis.co.uk/renfrewshire.htm A Renfrewshire History website] \u2013 with an in-depth summary of selected Renfrewshire settlements, including Houston.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070503150422/http://craigends.net/ History of Craigends Estate]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vCkupiGBg5Y Video footage of St Peter's Well]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aGW5h0z6U5w Video footage of St Fillan's Well at Kilallan.]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x_z8i-ASNPk Video footage of St Fillan's Seat]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TkkvAYOuqCo Video footage of St Fillan's Kirk]\n{{Renfrewshire}}{{Strathgryffe}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Renfrewshire]]\n[[Category:Strathgryffe]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n |country = Scotland\n |official_name = Houston\n |gaelic_name = Cille Pheadair\n |scots_name = Houstoun\n |os_grid_reference = NS404667\n |map_type = Scotland\n|static_image_name=Geograph-5906206-by-Thomas-Nugent.jpg\n|static_image_width=280\n|static_image_caption= Main Street in Houston\n |coordinates = {{coord|55.86697|-4.55207|display=inline,title}}\n |population = 6610\n |population_ref = (1991 census)\n |civil_parish = [[Houston and Killellan]]\n |unitary_scotland = [[Renfrewshire]]\n |lieutenancy_scotland = [[Renfrewshire (historic)|Renfrewshire]]\n |post_town = JOHNSTONE\n |postcode_district = PA6\n |postcode_area = PA \n |dial_code = 01505\n |constituency_westminster = [[Paisley and Renfrewshire North (UK Parliament constituency)|Paisley and Renfrewshire North]]\n |constituency_scottish_parliament = [[Renfrewshire North and West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Renfrewshire North and West]]<br>[[Renfrewshire South (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Renfrewshire South]]\n}}\n\n'''Houston''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|u\u02d0|s|t|\u0259n}} {{respell|HOOS|t\u0259n}}) is a [[village]] in the [[council areas of Scotland|council area]] of [[Renfrewshire]] and the larger historic [[counties of Scotland|county]] [[Renfrewshire (historic)|of the same name]] in the west [[central Lowlands]] of [[Scotland]].\n\nHouston lies within the [[Gryffe Valley]] on the banks of the [[River Gryffe]] {{convert|6|mi|km|0}} north-west of [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] and is the largest settlement in the [[civil parish]] of [[Houston and Killellan]], which covers the neighbouring village of [[Crosslee]] and a number of smaller settlements in the villages' rural hinterland.\n\nThe village grew around a 16th-century castle and parish church dedicated to [[Saint Peter]], which gave the area its former name of '''Kilpeter''' (\"''Cille Pheadair''\" in [[Scottish Gaelic]]). The present day old village dates mainly back to the 18th century and was a planned community, replacing earlier buildings. Historically, the economy was based around agriculture and, in common with a number of other Renfrewshire villages, cotton weaving. The old village was designated as a [[conservation area]] in 1968.\n\nFrom the middle of the 20th century, a larger area of residential settlement expanded the village into nearby areas such as [[Craigends]], removing the open country between Houston and Crosslee. These additions to the village have expanded its population considerably, changing its character chiefly to a [[dormitory settlement]] for nearby [[Glasgow]] and [[Paisley, Renfrewshire|Paisley]] with a largely service-based economy. \n\n==History==\n===Toponymy===\n[[Image:Houston House in Renfrewshire, Scotland.jpg|thumb|Houston House.]]\nHouston was originally known as Kilpeter. In the mid 12th century, the fee of Kilpeter was granted by [[Baldwin of Biggar|Baldwin of Biggar, Sheriff of Lanark]], to [[Hugh de Paduinan|Hugh of Pettinain]]. From Hugh, the lands eventually became known as Houston (meaning \"Hugh's ''tun'' or manor\").<ref>{{citation |last=Barrow |first=Geoffrey Wallis Steuart |author-link=G. W. S. Barrow |title=The kingdom of the Scots: government, church and society from the eleventh to the fourteenth century |publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]] |year=2003 |isbn=0 7486 1802 3 |pages=319\u2013320}}. \u2013 via [[Google Books]]</ref>\n\nIn a [[Papal Bull|Bull]] of [[Pope Honorius III|Pope Honorius]] in 1225-7, the churches of Kilmacolm and Houston are mentioned as \"ecclesiae de Kilmacolme et de Villa Hugonis\". In a later Bull of [[Pope Clement IV]] in 1265, the churches belonging to [[Paisley Abbey]] are listed including the church of \"Howston\".<ref>James Murray (Rev.), Kilmacolm: A Parish History, 1898</ref>\n\n===Early history===\nHouston had long been a site of human settlement. In the 1970s, a [[Bronze Age]] burial site was found at South Mound on the western edge of the village.<ref>See Morrison, A ''A Bronze Age burial site near South Mound, Houston, Renfrewshire'', Glasgow ArchaeolJ, 6 (1979), 20\u201345</ref> To the north-east lies Barochan Hill,<ref name=Canmore>{{Canmore |num=43107 |desc=Barochan Hill|access-date=2017-11-12}}</ref> the site of a [[Roman Empire|Roman]] fort.<ref name=\"survey\">{{cite web|url=http://ilwwcm.renfrewshire.gov.uk/pdfs/pt/ROFApplication1/pt-SiteGazetter0606.pdf |publisher=Renfrewshire Council |author=[[BAE Systems]] and Redrow Housing |date=2006-05-01 |accessdate=2009-06-30 |title=Royal Ordnance Bishopton: Site Gazetteer |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722011954/http://ilwwcm.renfrewshire.gov.uk/pdfs/pt/ROFApplication1/pt-SiteGazetter0606.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-22 }}</ref> A later [[Antonine Wall|Antonine era]] fort was found on a farm near [[Bishopton, Renfrewshire|Bishopton]], less than 2 miles away.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bishopton Roman Fort|url=http://roman-britain.co.uk/places/bishopton.htm|website=Roman Britain|accessdate=11 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160812193754/http://roman-britain.co.uk/places/bishopton.htm|archive-date=12 August 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe first village in Houston was constructed around the parish Church of St Peter and Houston Castle, now respectively the parish church and Houston House \u2013 largely 19th century buildings. Houston House and the castle which is partially incorporated within its structure date back to the time of Hugh of Pettinain and remained in the possession of his family who later became the [[Clan Houston|Houstons of Houston]].<ref name=\"communitywebsite\">{{cite web|url=http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/Navigation-els-Houston(OurHistoryandHeritage)Homepage|publisher=Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=2009-06-30|title=Renfrewshire Community Website \u2013 Houston|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301035602/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/Navigation-els-Houston%28OurHistoryandHeritage%29Homepage|archive-date=1 March 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Castle stayed in the ownership of the family until 1740 when it was purchased by [[Glasgow]] [[tobacco lord]] Alexander Speirs of Elderslie.<ref name=\"visionofbritain.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/descriptions/entry_page.jsp;jsessionid=39753DBEB127C8CF32E951C389579B8A?text_id=120230&word=NULL|title=Houston - As described in F.H. Groome's Ordnance Gazetteer of Scotland (1882-4)|website=www.visionofbritain.org.uk}}</ref> Following ownership by five generations of the Speirs family, Houston House passed to Major David Crichton Maitland in 1959 and then to his son Mark Crichton Maitland in 1995 before being divided into a number of [[apartments|flats]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elderslie.org/ee_about.php |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-28 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110701094550/http://www.elderslie.org/ee_about.php |archivedate=2011-07-01 }}</ref>\n[[Image:NorthStreetHouston.JPG|thumb|North Street, in the old village]] James McGuire MacRae was presented with the estate by his father's friend, [[Monkton, Ayrshire|James MacRae]]. It passed to his son, who demolished the castle and built the weavers cottages with the stones.<ref>Cuthbertson, David Cuningham (1945). ''Autumn in Kyle and the Charm of Cunninghame''. London : Jenkins. P. 35</ref> With this 18th-century change in ownership of the land therefore, the 'old village' was cleared from around the castle by the [[laird]]. The new village of some thirty five cottages constructed to the west in 1781 from the stone of the Castle, which was later to evolve into a [[country house]]. This new village \u2013 which forms the basis of the modern village \u2013 was a [[planned community]] built along two main streets: North Street and South Street and is an example of the 18th century Planned Village Movement.<ref>M. Pacione, ''Planning urban growth in Scotland: The new settlement option'' Scottish Geographical Journal, 1751-665X, Volume 122, Issue 1, 2006, Pages 32 \u2013 54</ref> The layout, straddling the Houston [[Burn (topography)|Burn]], provided washing facilities accessible to local people as well as supporting the small-scale [[weaving]] industry.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/AttachmentsByTitle/pt-as-Strathgryfe.pdf/$FILE/pt-as-Strathgryfe.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=13 October 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110919121604/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/AttachmentsByTitle/pt-as-Strathgryfe.pdf/$FILE/pt-as-Strathgryfe.pdf |archive-date=19 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This 'new village' is designated by the [[Renfrewshire]] authorities as a [[conservation village]].<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" /><ref name=\"conservation\">{{cite web|url=http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/PT-AB-Houston-Conservation-Area|publisher=Renfrewshire Council|accessdate=2009-06-30|title=Renfrewshire Community Website \u2013 Houston Conservation Area|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120428025938/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/PT-AB-Houston-Conservation-Area|archive-date=28 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nA notable remnant of this move is the village's [[mercat cross]], which incorporates parts dating back to the 14th century. Due to the move from an original position on Kirk Road, and the fact that it incorporates a large [[sundial]], it has been placed at an unusual angle at the centre of the 'new' village. The mercat cross has become used as a symbol for the village.<ref>Being used, for example, in the badge of Houston Primary School; and to represent Houston in the arms of Gryffe High School where an image of Ranfurly Castle is used to represent [[Bridge of Weir]]</ref>\n\n===Modern history===\nBoth railway stations (on separate lines) built within the parish in the 19th century, [[Houston (Scotland) railway station|Houston and Crosslee Station]] and [[Georgetown (Scotland) railway station|Georgetown station]] (both now closed), bypassed the village itself. As a consequence, Houston did not experience the railway boom of nearby villages like [[Bridge of Weir]] and [[Kilmacolm]], expanding slowly until the later half of the 20th century when it became a popular [[commuter settlement]].<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" />\n\nThe main industry of the Houston between the 17th and 19th century was [[weaving]]. The [[River Gryffe]] later provided a cotton spinning industry with the creation of the [[Crosslee]] cotton mill with other small manufacturing concerns, such as embroidery, later opening in the village.<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" />\n\nIn July 2007, Houston was featured prominently in news reports around the [[United Kingdom]] after it was discovered that inhabitants of a house in the village were linked to the [[2007 Glasgow International Airport attack]] of 30 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/article/0,,30100-1273143,00.html?f=rss|title=Police Comb House Near Glasgow -Sky News-UK News<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref> The Houston Community Council observed that \"it is a sobering thought that such a situation could happen on our very doorstep and that even in a quiet, rural setting such as ours there can be people intent on disrupting the natural balance of things by violent means.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.houstoncommunitycouncil.co.uk/assets/literature/NOVEMBER%20AGM%202007.pdf |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006214106/http://www.houstoncommunitycouncil.co.uk/assets/literature/NOVEMBER%20AGM%202007.pdf |archive-date=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n[[Image:Houston Village Hall.JPG|thumb|Houston's Village Hall]]\n\n===Local government===\n:: ''See also: [[Houston and Killellan]]''\nHouston and its parish form part of the [[Renfrewshire]] [[council areas of Scotland|council area]]. For the 2007 local authority elections in Scotland, Houston was entered into a new four-councillor [[Ward (country subdivision)|ward]], Ward 9, alongside Crosslee and the town of [[Linwood, Renfrewshire|Linwood]] ([https://web.archive.org/web/20090321075553/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/Navigation-cs-Ward9HomePage Ward 9]).\n\nThe boundaries of the [[civil parishes in Scotland|civil parish]] of Houston and Kilellan follow the creation of a united [[ecclesiastical parish]] centred on Houston in the 18th century.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.houstonscotland.org.uk/kirk/our%20church.htm|title=Houston and Killellan Kirk<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=|access-date=9 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106124721/http://www.houstonscotland.org.uk/kirk/our%20church.htm|archive-date=6 January 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The parish spreads over a wide rural hinterland including a number of nearby settlements, the most significant being [[Crosslee]], [[Craigends]] and Barochan.\n\nWith the decline of significance of the [[civil parish]] in local government, this area has largely become part of the Houston [[community council|Community Council]] area [https://web.archive.org/web/20090523042737/http://www.houstoncommunitycouncil.co.uk/]. The community council is chiefly a consultative body, forming a focus for local views, and has no statutory powers of its own.\n\n===Central government===\nHouston forms part of the [[Paisley and Renfrewshire North]] [[United Kingdom constituencies|constituency]] for elections to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] in the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. The current [[Member of Parliament]] for this area is [[Gavin Newlands]] MP. The constituency was created in 2005 following boundary changes with Houston previously forming part of the [[West Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|West Renfrewshire]] constituency.\n\nFor [[devolution|devolved]] matters, Houston is part of the [[Scottish Parliament]] [[Scottish Parliament constituencies and regions|constituency]] of [[Renfrewshire North and West (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Renfrewshire North and West]], which straddles the boundary between the council areas of Inverclyde and Renfrewshire. Since 2011, the constituency [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] for the area is [[Derek Mackay]] MSP. The Renfrewshire North and West constituency forms part of the [[West of Scotland (Scottish Parliament electoral region)|West of Scotland]] [[Scottish Parliament constituencies and regions|Scottish Parliament electoral region]]. Seven further MSPs are elected for this region through the Scottish Parliament's [[Mixed member proportional representation|Additional Member electoral system]].\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[Image:Houston mercat cross.JPG|thumb|Houston's [[mercat cross]], used as a symbol of the village.]]\nHouston's historic village centre, located at the north-west edge of the village, is a designated conservation area. The area is home to the main village pubs, small shops and the village's Post Office. North Street and South Street are dominated by traditional white cottages, some dating to the 17th century. The old village was a planned community of houses largely built around the Houston Burn, which gave communal access to washing facilities.\n\nSome remains of the 16th century Houston Castle still exist largely in the grounds of the current Houston House. The area sits beside [[Houston and Killellan]] Kirk, the established ([[Church of Scotland]]) [[parish church]]. It is possible that [[Lord Darnley]], husband of [[Mary, Queen of Scots]] resided at the castle for some years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourlocalhistory.co.uk/yew.html|title=The Craigends Yew-www.ourlocalhistory.co.uk<!-- Bot generated title -->|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe Barochan Cross, an 11&nbsp;ft (3.4 metre) tall [[Celtic cross|Celtic Christian cross]] possibly dating to the 8th century, formerly lay just south of the Mill of Barochan in the parish. In the 19th century, it was moved to a knoll opposite Corsliehill closer to the village before finally being moved in the 20th century to [[Paisley Abbey]] where it now remains in order to protect it from further weathering.<ref name=\"survey\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/els-jh-HistoricBuildingsArchaeology|publisher=Renfrewshire Council|author=|date=|accessdate=2009-06-30|title=Archaeology in Renfrewshire|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100310094522/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/els-jh-HistoricBuildingsArchaeology|archive-date=10 March 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Craigends Yew]] is an ancient [[yew tree]] in the parish, supposed to be the oldest living thing in Renfrewshire, with a potential age of around a thousand years.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/Navigation-pt-Houston(VisitingRenfrewshire) |title=Archived copy |access-date=19 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120210003121/http://www.renfrewshire.gov.uk/ilwwcm/publishing.nsf/Content/Navigation-pt-Houston(VisitingRenfrewshire) |archive-date=10 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> There are two ancient wells in Houston, once considered to have healing powers. St Fillan's Well sits in the fields beside Kilallan Kirk and St Peter's Well that also gives its name to a locally brewed ale.\n\nThe [[parish church]], which is a congregation of the [[Church of Scotland]], lies to the east of the old village. A 19th century [[Roman Catholic]] church, St Fillan's, is to the south of Main Street.\n\n==Religion==\n[[Image:Houston Kirk.jpg|thumb|right|Houston & Killellan Kirk (parish church), in the grounds of Houston House. The steeple is obscured.]]\n[[File:St Peter's Well, Houston - view from the east & opening.jpg|thumb|[[St Peter's Well, Houston|St Peter's Well]], a historic holy well beside the village.]]\nHouston's has a long association with St Peter, providing the village's historic name of Kilpeter. Its current parish church, Houston and Killellan Church or [[Kirk]], lies in the grounds of Houston House. The Kirk was constructed in the 1870s, replacing a church on the same site constructed in 1775, and dedicated to [[Archibald Alexander Speirs]] of [[Elderslie]]. Following his death aged 28 while sitting as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[West Renfrewshire (UK Parliament constituency)|West Renfrewshire]], his mother provided the building costs as a memorial.\n\nThe current parish dates from 1771, when the parishes of Houston and Killellan were united. The former parish church in the nearby hamlet of [[St Fillan's Kirk, Seat and Well|Killellan]] was known as the [[St Fillan's Kirk, Seat and Well|Church of St Fillan]], which the name of the settlement derives. The former church building was left redundant by the unification and was abandoned. The ruin, dated 1635 but believed to have originated in the 10th or 11th century,<ref name=\"elderslie.org\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.elderslie.org/kilallankirk.php |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081119055900/http://www.elderslie.org/kilallankirk.php |archive-date=19 November 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> still stands some {{convert|4|mi|km|0}} west of the centre of Houston on the [[Barochan Cross]] Road. This church is now held by the Kilallan Kirk Preservation Trust following its donation by Elderslie Estates in 2005 and is a scheduled historic monument.<ref name=\"elderslie.org\"/> An annual evening service is held amongst the ruins in July by the congregation of the united parish. The church's manse, which is immediately adjacent to it, also finds continued use as a private residence and is thought to be the oldest existing dwellinghouse in Renfrewshire.<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" /> [[St Fillan's Kirk, Seat and Well|St Fillan's Holy Well]] and [[St Fillan's Kirk, Seat and Well|St Fillan's Seat]] are located near to the old kirk.\n\n[[St Peter's Well, Houston|St Peter's Well]] stands in a field below Greenhill Farm on Chapel Road close to the site of a pre-Reformation chapel and is a rare example of a covered or house holy well, the waters of which were once thought to ensure the safe return of travellers such as pilgrims.\n\nThe Houston and Kilellan [[church hall]] on Main Street was built immediately following the [[Disruption of 1843]] as a separate congregation forming part of the [[Free Church of Scotland (1843-1900)|Free Church of Scotland]], and later the [[United Free Church of Scotland]] being known during this time as the West Kirk. Following the reunification of the United Free Church and the established Church of Scotland in 1929, the West Kirk existed as a second Church of Scotland congregation in the village until a fire destroyed much of the building in March 1941. The lack of a building caused the two congregations to again worship in the same parish church. The West Kirk building was fully restored by 1953, taking its place as the church hall it remains to this day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.houstonscotland.org.uk/kirk/our%20church.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 April 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106124721/http://www.houstonscotland.org.uk/kirk/our%20church.htm |archive-date=6 January 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHouston and Kilellan Kirk is currently the second richest church in Scotland, after Paisley Cathedral.\n\nSt. Fillan's [[Roman Catholic Church]], also on Main Street, was established in 1841 on a property called \"Four Windings\" now remembered in the name of an adjacent street.\n\n==Economy==\nChiefly serving a [[dormitory town|commuter village]], Houston's chief local economic activity is [[agriculture]], with some [[tertiary sector]] businesses such as local shops and public houses serving residents and visitors. There are a number of these shops and pubs in the old village, and a number of shops located on the boundary with [[Crosslee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scottish-places.info/towns/townfirst1158.html|title=Crosslee from The Gazetteer for Scotland|website=www.scottish-places.info}}</ref>\n\n===Public houses and brewing===\nThe parish supports a number of [[public house]]s, with two located in the historic village centre: the Fox and Hounds on South Street and the Houston Inn on North Street, established in 1779 and 1784 respectively. Until 2010, a third, the Cross Keys Inn, lay on Main Street, with a name derived from the crossed keys symbol of [[St Peter]] as a reference to the village's original name, Kilpeter. It has since operated as a restaurant. A further restaurant and public house, the River Inn, lies in Crosslee and was formerly the Crosslee Inn and the Pine Trees.<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" />\n\nThe village hosts a regular beer festival/<ref>http://www.list.co.uk/event/178765-beer-festival-fox-and-hounds-houston/</ref> A [[microbrewery]], the [[Houston Brewing Company]], also formerly operated from a building adjacent to the Fox and Hounds.<ref name=\"communitywebsite\" />\n\n==Culture and community==\nThere are a number of community organisations and events that take place in the village. The village's main park, Houston Public Park, is adjacent to the old village, with others at South Street and Ardgryffe Park among the more modern housing developments.\n\nHouston Public Park is the venue for the village's annual agricultural show, taking place in the summer and organised by the Houston and Killellan Agricultural Society. Another significant local event is the Kirk Carnival, organised by the parish church and focused around the church hall and Carrick Centre on Main Street, which involves a parade and a number of stalls and entertainments and including the local primary schools.\n\nIn 1992, Strathgryffe Tennis Squash and Fitness Club, opened with support from the [[Lawn Tennis Association]] and the [[National Lottery (United Kingdom)|National Lottery]] Sports Fund, is also located in the village.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.strathgryffe.net/club/club-history|title=Club History|website=Strathgryffe Tennis, Squash and Fitness Club}}</ref> An [[Equestrianism|equestrian]] club, the Kilmacolm and Kilallan Riding Club is based on the boundary of the parish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kilmacolmridingclub.org.uk/|title=Kilmacolm and Kilallan Riding Club|website=www.kilmacolmridingclub.org.uk}}</ref> A [[foxhunting|foxhunt]], the Lanarkshire and Renfrewshire Foxhounds, has operated from kennels in the village since 1850.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lanarkandrenfrew.com/|title=Lanarkshire & Renfrewshire Foxhounds|website=lanarkandrenfrew.com}}</ref>\n\nThe village also hosts a [[lawn bowls]] club, the John G. Fleming Bowling Club, which was founded the local landowner whose name it bears to mark the [[diamond jubilee]] of [[Queen Victoria]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jgflemingbc.co.uk/aboutus.html|title=J.G. Fleming Bowling Club - About Us|website=www.jgflemingbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n[[Gryffe High School]] is a non-denominational [[co-educational]] [[state school|state]] [[secondary school]] which serves the village and surrounding settlements, most particularly neighbouring [[Bridge of Weir]].<ref name=\"HMIE\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hmie.gov.uk/documents/inspection/8633436GryffeHS1.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=3 April 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100325211205/http://www.hmie.gov.uk/documents/inspection/8633436GryffeHS1.html |archive-date=25 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The school has a strong academic reputation, and in 2009 was ranked as the seventh best-performing state secondary school in [[Scotland]] by [[The Times]] newspaper's league tables.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/parentpower/league_tables.php?t=state_secondary_schools_in_scotland |location=London |work=The Times |url-status=dead |first=Anushka |last=Asthana |title=The top 50 state secondary schools in Scotland |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100605011336/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/parentpower/league_tables.php?t=state_secondary_schools_in_scotland |archivedate=June 5, 2010 }}</ref> Also in 2009, the school was praised in a report by [[Her Majesty's Inspectorate of Education]].<ref name=\"HMIE\" />\n\nThere are two [[primary school]]s in Houston. Houston Primary School is a non-denominational school, whereas St Fillan's Primary School is a [[Roman Catholic]] [[faith school]]. Both are co-educational state schools.  As stated above, Gryffe High School is the non-denominational secondary for the village whereas St. Benedict's High School is the Roman Catholic secondary serving Houston along with Bridge of Weir (which St. Fillan's also serves).\n\nThe 'old schoolhouse' at the north end of Main Street in the old village centre has been converted into self-catering accommodation and the former school at the south end of Main Street now exists as a community building known as the Carrick Centre.\n\n==Public services==\nThe [[territorial police force]] covering Houston is the [[Police Service of Scotland]]. It is part of the Renfrewshire and Inverclyde division and the Renfrew area Command. The nearest local [[police station]] is at [[Johnstone]].<ref>https://www.scotland.police.uk/your-community/renfrewshire-and-inverclyde/renfrew/houston-crosslee-and-linwood/</ref> There was a police station and police house in the village opened in the mid-1940s, which was closed in 2001.<ref>http://www.lands-tribunal-scotland.org.uk/decisions/LTS.LO.2000.42.html</ref> \n\nFor judicial purposes, the Houston forms part of the [[sheriffdom]] of North Strathclyde and [[prosecutor|public prosecutions]] are directed by the [[Procurator Fiscal]] for [[Argyll and Clyde]]. The [[Scottish Fire and Rescue Service]] is the statutory [[fire services in Scotland|fire and rescue service]] covering the village and maintains three fire stations in Renfrewshire with the closest at Johnstone.<ref>https://www.firescotland.gov.uk/media/1239511/renfrewshire_local_fire_and_rescue_plan_2018.pdf</ref> \n\n[[NHS Greater Glasgow and Clyde]] is the [[NHS Scotland|National Health Service Board]] providing [[Publicly funded health care|public health care]]. The nearest major hospitals with [[accident and emergency]] facilities is the [[Royal Alexandra Hospital, Paisley|Royal Alexandra Hospital]] in Paisley. There is one medical practice in the village, which is linked to another surgery in Bridge of Weir.<ref>https://www.nhsggc.org.uk/locations/gp-surgeries/strathgryffe-medical-practice/#</ref>\n\n[[Water industry|Water]] and [[sewerage]] is provided by [[Scottish Water]], a public body, and water and sewerage charges are collected alongside [[council tax]] by [[Renfrewshire Council]], the local authority, on its behalf. Renfrewshire Council is also responsible for the provision of [[waste management]] in the area.<ref>s.30, Environmental Protection Act 1990 as amended</ref> The local [[Distribution Network Operator]], the organisation licensed to transmit electricity from the [[National Grid (UK)|National Grid]] to consumers, is [[Scottish Power]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.energylinx.co.uk/distribution_network_operators.htm|publisher=energylinx.co.uk|year=2007|accessdate=5 February 2008|title=Electricity Distribution Network Operators|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080114055937/http://www.energylinx.co.uk/distribution_network_operators.htm|archivedate=14 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nThere is a [[Post Office Ltd|Post Office]] branch in the village and the [[postal town]], with a larger delivery centre, is [[Johnstone]].<ref>https://www.postoffice.co.uk/branch-finder/1178598/houston</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090523042737/http://www.houstoncommunitycouncil.co.uk/ Houston Community Council website]\n* [http://www.happyhaggis.co.uk/renfrewshire.htm A Renfrewshire History website] \u2013 with an in-depth summary of selected Renfrewshire settlements, including Houston.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070503150422/http://craigends.net/ History of Craigends Estate]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=vCkupiGBg5Y Video footage of St Peter's Well]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aGW5h0z6U5w Video footage of St Fillan's Well at Kilallan.]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x_z8i-ASNPk Video footage of St Fillan's Seat]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TkkvAYOuqCo Video footage of St Fillan's Kirk]\n{{Renfrewshire}}{{Strathgryffe}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Renfrewshire]]\n[[Category:Strathgryffe]]\n", "name_user": "Bjh21", "label": "safe", "comment": "(GR)File renamed:File:Geograph-5906206-by-Thomas-Nugent.jpg\u2192File:Main Street, Houston, Renfrewshire (geograph 5906206).jpgUse a descriptive name (c:COM:FRcriterion 2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Houston,_Renfrewshire"}
{"title_page": "Nokia 1", "text_new": "{{short description|Media franchise}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Distinguish|Nokia N1}}\n{{Infobox mobile phone\n| name                   = Nokia 1\n| logo                   = \n| logo caption           = \n| image                  = 20200423 Nokia 1.jpg\n| caption                = \n| aka                    = \n| brand                  = [[Nokia]]\n| developer              = [[HMD Global]]\n| manufacturer           = [[Foxconn]]\n| slogan                 = ''Step up to smarter''<ref name=\"Nokia-Int-Page\">{{cite web |title=Nokia 1 |publisher=Nokia |url=https://www.nokia.com/en_int/phones/nokia-1 |accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n| releasedate            = \n| predecessor            = [[Nokia Asha]]<br />[[Nokia X family]]\n| successor              = [[Nokia 1 Plus]]\n| related                = [[Nokia 2]]<br />[[Nokia 3]]<br/>[[Nokia 5]]\n| type                   = [[Smartphone]]\n| generation             = 1st\n| lifespan               = \n| discontinued           = {{Start date and age|2019|10|28|df=yes}}\n| dimensions             = 133.6 x 67.78 x 9.5mm\n| weight                 = 131g (including battery)\n| os                     = '''Original:''' [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[Android Oreo|8.1 \"Oreo\"]]<br />'''Current:''' [[Android Pie|Android 9.0 \"Pie\"]]<br />([[Android Go]])\n| soc                    = [[MediaTek]] MT6737M\n| cpu                    = [[Multi-core processor|Quad-core]] 1.1 GHz [[ARM Cortex-A53]]\n| gpu                    = Mali-T720\n| memory                 = 1 GB [[LPDDR3]] RAM\n| storage                = 8 GB [[eMMC]]\n| battery                = User-removable, 2150 mAh<br/>Standby: up to 15 days<br/>Talk time: up to 9 hours\n| memory_card            = microSD up to 128GB\n| input                  = \n| display                = {{convert|4.5|in|mm|abbr=on}} <br />854x480 [[pixels|px]] FWVGA IPS<br /> 16:9 aspect ratio\n| rear_camera            = 5 [[Megapixel|MP]] with auto-focus and an [[LED]] flash<ref name=\"TechRadar\">{{cite news |last=Cameron |first=Sean |title=Nokia 1 review |website=[[TechRadar]] |publisher=Future US Inc |date=2019-03-04 |url=https://www.techradar.com/reviews/nokia-1-review/3 |accessdate=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n| front_camera           = 2 MP with [[fixed-focus lens]]\n| sound                  = Mono speaker, 3.5 mm stereo audio jack\n| connectivity           = Wi-Fi 802.11 b/g/n,<br/>[[Bluetooth]]\u00ae 4.2,<br/>[[GPS]]/[[Assisted GPS|AGPS]] + [[Mobile phone tracking|cellular]] and [[Wi-Fi positioning system|Wi-Fi positioning]]\n| media                  = FM radio<br/>Playback formats: 3G2, 3GP, AAC, AMR, M4A, MKV, MP3, MP4\n| colors                 = Warm Red, Dark Blue\n| connectors and sensors = USB 2.0 via [[MicroUSB]],<br/>Single or dual [[Nano-SIM]]\n| title                  = \n| unitssold              = \n| unitsshipped           = \n| website                = {{url|https://nokia.com/en_int/phones/nokia-1}}\n| other                  = Dust and drip protection (IP52)\n}}\n{{short description|Nokia-branded Android Go smartphone by HMD Global}}{{Short description|Nokia-branded entry-level Android smartphone}}\n\n'''Nokia 1''' is a [[Nokia]]-branded budget [[Android Go]] [[smartphone]], developed by [[HMD Global]]. It was launched at the [[Mobile World Congress]] 2018, in [[Barcelona, Spain]] on 25 February 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hmdglobal.com/press/2018-02-25-mwc-announcements/ |title=The Home of Nokia phones |website=HMD Global Oy |accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> This device, along with the [[Nokia 8 Sirocco]], completes the lineup of Nokia-branded Android devices.<ref>{{Cite news |title=The Nokia 1 joins Google's Android Go effort with removable Xpress-on covers |work=The Verge |url= https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/25/17049976/nokia-1-android-go-release-date-pricing-mwc-2018 |accessdate=2018-02-25}}</ref> The phone also has separately sold removable back covers known as Xpress-on, a brand that first appeared on the [[Nokia 5110]].<ref name=\"pocket-lint.com\">{{cite news |url= https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/news/nokia/143746-nokia-1-android-go-phone-reintroduces-xpress-on-covers |title=Nokia 1 Android Go phone reintroduces Xpress-on covers - Pocket-lint |website=www.pocket-lint.com |accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref> This was the first time the Xpress-on name was used since the [[Nokia Lumia 710]] in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://blog.gsmarena.com/nokia-lumia-710-eligible-for-free-xpress-on-covers-from-nokia/ | title=Nokia Lumia 710 eligible for free Xpress-on covers from Nokia}}</ref><ref name=\"pocket-lint.com\"/>\n\n==Specifications==\n===Hardware===\nNokia 1 has a quad-core 1.1&nbsp;GHz [[ARM Cortex-A53|Cortex-A53]] Mediatek MT6737M CPU, 1 GB of RAM and 8&nbsp;GB of internal storage that can be expanded using a microSD card of up to 128 GB.\n\nThe device also has a 4.5-inch [[IPS LCD]] display, a 5 MP rear camera with auto-focus and an LED flash, and a 2 MP front-facing camera.<ref name=\"gsmarena\"/>\n\nThe 2150 mAh user-removable Li-Ion battery<ref name=\"gsmarena\">{{cite web |title=Nokia 1 Specifications |publisher=GSM Arena |url=https://www.gsmarena.com/nokia_1-9052.php |accessdate=July 9, 2018}}</ref> allows for up to 15 days of standby time and up to 9 hours of talk time. The smartphone's back covers are available in Warm Red, Dark Blue, and light blue colors.<ref name=\"gsmarena\"/>\n\n===Software===\nNokia 1 is shipped with Android 8.1 Oreo (Go edition), and gets continuous security updates every month for up to 3 years.<ref name=\"NokiaMob\">{{cite news |author=Stipe |title=Nokia 1 receiving the May 2019 security update |website=Nokiamob |location=Croatia |date=2019-05-28 |url= https://nokiamob.net/2019/05/28/nokia-1-receiving-the-may-2019-security-update/ |accessdate=2019-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nokia 1 update rolling out with May 2019 Android security patch |publisher=BGR India |date=2019-05-30 |url= https://www.bgr.in/news/nokia-1-update-rolling-out-with-may-2019-android-security-patch/ |accessdate=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n\nIn late June 2019, HMD began rolling out the Android 9 Pie (Go edition) for Nokia 1.<ref>{{cite news |author=Sagar |title=Nokia 1 gets Android Pie Go update |publisher=GSM Arena |date=2019-06-25 |url= https://www.gsmarena.com/nokia_1_android_pie_go_update-news-37769.php |accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nNokia 1 generally received mixed reviews. ''[[TechRadar]]'' praised the device's battery life, customisable back cover and durable design, while criticising its poor performance, dim screen and poor speaker.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.techradar.com/in/reviews/nokia-1-review |title=Nokia 1 review |date=March 2019 |first=Sean |last=Cameron |website=TechRadar India |accessdate=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.nokia.com/en_int/phones/nokia-1}}\n* https://www.nokia.com/phones/en_int/security-updates\n\n{{HMD Global}}\n{{Nokia phones}}\n{{Android smartphones}}\n\n[[Category:Nokia mobile phones]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) devices]]\n[[Category:Nokia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Nokia N1}}\n{{Infobox mobile phone\n| name                   = Nokia 1\n| logo                   = \n| logo caption           = \n| image                  = 20200423 Nokia 1.jpg\n| caption                = \n| aka                    = \n| brand                  = [[Nokia]]\n| developer              = [[HMD Global]]\n| manufacturer           = [[Foxconn]]\n| slogan                 = ''Step up to smarter''<ref name=\"Nokia-Int-Page\">{{cite web |title=Nokia 1 |publisher=Nokia |url=https://www.nokia.com/en_int/phones/nokia-1 |accessdate=11 June 2018}}</ref>\n| releasedate            = \n| predecessor            = [[Nokia Asha]]<br />[[Nokia X family]]\n| successor              = [[Nokia 1 Plus]]\n| related                = [[Nokia 2]]<br />[[Nokia 3]]<br/>[[Nokia 5]]\n| type                   = [[Smartphone]]\n| generation             = 1st\n| lifespan               = \n| discontinued           = {{Start date and age|2019|10|28|df=yes}}\n| dimensions             = 133.6 x 67.78 x 9.5mm\n| weight                 = 131g (including battery)\n| os                     = '''Original:''' [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[Android Oreo|8.1 \"Oreo\"]]<br />'''Current:''' [[Android Pie|Android 9.0 \"Pie\"]]<br />([[Android Go]])\n| soc                    = [[MediaTek]] MT6737M\n| cpu                    = [[Multi-core processor|Quad-core]] 1.1 GHz [[ARM Cortex-A53]]\n| gpu                    = Mali-T720\n| memory                 = 1 GB [[LPDDR3]] RAM\n| storage                = 8 GB [[eMMC]]\n| battery                = User-removable, 2150 mAh<br/>Standby: up to 15 days<br/>Talk time: up to 9 hours\n| memory_card            = microSD up to 128GB\n| input                  = \n| display                = {{convert|4.5|in|mm|abbr=on}} <br />854x480 [[pixels|px]] FWVGA IPS<br /> 16:9 aspect ratio\n| rear_camera            = 5 [[Megapixel|MP]] with auto-focus and an [[LED]] flash<ref name=\"TechRadar\">{{cite news |last=Cameron |first=Sean |title=Nokia 1 review |website=[[TechRadar]] |publisher=Future US Inc |date=2019-03-04 |url=https://www.techradar.com/reviews/nokia-1-review/3 |accessdate=2019-06-19}}</ref>\n| front_camera           = 2 MP with [[fixed-focus lens]]\n| sound                  = Mono speaker, 3.5 mm stereo audio jack\n| connectivity           = Wi-Fi 802.11 b/g/n,<br/>[[Bluetooth]]\u00ae 4.2,<br/>[[GPS]]/[[Assisted GPS|AGPS]] + [[Mobile phone tracking|cellular]] and [[Wi-Fi positioning system|Wi-Fi positioning]]\n| media                  = FM radio<br/>Playback formats: 3G2, 3GP, AAC, AMR, M4A, MKV, MP3, MP4\n| colors                 = Warm Red, Dark Blue\n| connectors and sensors = USB 2.0 via [[MicroUSB]],<br/>Single or dual [[Nano-SIM]]\n| title                  = \n| unitssold              = \n| unitsshipped           = \n| website                = {{url|https://nokia.com/en_int/phones/nokia-1}}\n| other                  = Dust and drip protection (IP52)\n}}\n{{short description|Nokia-branded Android Go smartphone by HMD Global}}{{Short description|Nokia-branded entry-level Android smartphone}}\n\n'''Nokia 1''' is a [[Nokia]]-branded budget [[Android Go]] [[smartphone]], developed by [[HMD Global]]. It was launched at the [[Mobile World Congress]] 2018, in [[Barcelona, Spain]] on 25 February 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hmdglobal.com/press/2018-02-25-mwc-announcements/ |title=The Home of Nokia phones |website=HMD Global Oy |accessdate=25 February 2018}}</ref> This device, along with the [[Nokia 8 Sirocco]], completes the lineup of Nokia-branded Android devices.<ref>{{Cite news |title=The Nokia 1 joins Google's Android Go effort with removable Xpress-on covers |work=The Verge |url= https://www.theverge.com/2018/2/25/17049976/nokia-1-android-go-release-date-pricing-mwc-2018 |accessdate=2018-02-25}}</ref> The phone also has separately sold removable back covers known as Xpress-on, a brand that first appeared on the [[Nokia 5110]].<ref name=\"pocket-lint.com\">{{cite news |url= https://www.pocket-lint.com/phones/news/nokia/143746-nokia-1-android-go-phone-reintroduces-xpress-on-covers |title=Nokia 1 Android Go phone reintroduces Xpress-on covers - Pocket-lint |website=www.pocket-lint.com |accessdate=26 February 2018}}</ref> This was the first time the Xpress-on name was used since the [[Nokia Lumia 710]] in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://blog.gsmarena.com/nokia-lumia-710-eligible-for-free-xpress-on-covers-from-nokia/ | title=Nokia Lumia 710 eligible for free Xpress-on covers from Nokia}}</ref><ref name=\"pocket-lint.com\"/>\n\n==Specifications==\n===Hardware===\nNokia 1 has a quad-core 1.1&nbsp;GHz [[ARM Cortex-A53|Cortex-A53]] Mediatek MT6737M CPU, 1 GB of RAM and 8&nbsp;GB of internal storage that can be expanded using a microSD card of up to 128 GB.\n\nThe device also has a 4.5-inch [[IPS LCD]] display, a 5 MP rear camera with auto-focus and an LED flash, and a 2 MP front-facing camera.<ref name=\"gsmarena\"/>\n\nThe 2150 mAh user-removable Li-Ion battery<ref name=\"gsmarena\">{{cite web |title=Nokia 1 Specifications |publisher=GSM Arena |url=https://www.gsmarena.com/nokia_1-9052.php |accessdate=July 9, 2018}}</ref> allows for up to 15 days of standby time and up to 9 hours of talk time, if mobile internet, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, GPS, and accelerometer are switched off.\n\nThe smartphone's back covers are available in Warm Red, Dark Blue, and light blue colors.<ref name=\"gsmarena\"/>\n\n===Software===\nNokia 1 is shipped with Android 8.1 Oreo (Go edition), and gets continuous security updates every month for up to 3 years.<ref name=\"NokiaMob\">{{cite news |author=Stipe |title=Nokia 1 receiving the May 2019 security update |website=Nokiamob |location=Croatia |date=2019-05-28 |url= https://nokiamob.net/2019/05/28/nokia-1-receiving-the-may-2019-security-update/ |accessdate=2019-06-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Nokia 1 update rolling out with May 2019 Android security patch |publisher=BGR India |date=2019-05-30 |url= https://www.bgr.in/news/nokia-1-update-rolling-out-with-may-2019-android-security-patch/ |accessdate=2019-06-20}}</ref>\n\nIn late June 2019, HMD began rolling out the Android 9 Pie (Go edition) for Nokia 1.<ref>{{cite news |author=Sagar |title=Nokia 1 gets Android Pie Go update |publisher=GSM Arena |date=2019-06-25 |url= https://www.gsmarena.com/nokia_1_android_pie_go_update-news-37769.php |accessdate=2019-06-26}}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\nNokia 1 generally received mixed reviews. ''[[TechRadar]]'' praised the device's battery life, customisable back cover and durable design, while criticising its poor performance, dim screen and poor speaker.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.techradar.com/in/reviews/nokia-1-review |title=Nokia 1 review |date=March 2019 |first=Sean |last=Cameron |website=TechRadar India |accessdate=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.nokia.com/en_int/phones/nokia-1}}\n* https://www.nokia.com/phones/en_int/security-updates\n\n{{HMD Global}}\n{{Nokia phones}}\n{{Android smartphones}}\n\n[[Category:Nokia mobile phones]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) devices]]\n[[Category:Nokia]]\n\n\n{{technology-stub}}\n", "name_user": "RedBulbBlueBlood9911", "label": "safe", "comment": "Transferring draft to mainspace", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nokia_1"}
{"title_page": "1931\u201332 F.B.C. Juventus season", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club season\n|club = [[Juventus|Foot-Ball Club Juventus]]\n|season = 1931-32\n|manager = [[Carlo Carcano]]\n|chairman = [[Edoardo Agnelli]]\n|chrtitle= President\n|stadium = [[Stadio Olimpico Grande Torino|Stadio Benito Mussolini]]\n|league = [[Serie A]]\n|league result = [[1931-32 Serie A|1\u00ba]] (in [[1932 Mitropa Cup|Mitropa Cup]])\n|cup1 = [[Mitropa Cup]]\n|cup1 result = [[1932 Mitropa Cup|Semifinals]]\n|league topscorer = [[Raimundo Orsi]] (20)\n|season topscorer = [[Raimundo Orsi|Orsi]] (23)\n\n|pattern_la1 = _juve2\n|leftarm1 = ffffff\n|pattern_b1 =_juve193236h\n|body1 = ffffff\n|pattern_ra1 = _juve2\n|rightarm1 = ffffff\n|shorts1 = ffffff\n|pattern_so1 = _juve\n|socks1 = 000000\n\n|prevseason = [[1930\u201331 F.B.C. Juventus season|1930-31]]\n|nextseason = [[1932\u201333 F.B.C. Juventus season|1932-33]]\n}}\n\nDuring the 1931\u201332 season '''Foot-Ball Club Juventus''' competed in Serie A and Mitropa Cup.\n\n==Summary==\nThe club transferred new players in to the roster such as [[Enzo Rosa]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myjuve.com/player/172914/|title=Enzo Rosa signed with Juventus|publisher=myjuve.com}}</ref> and Brazilian [[Pietro Sernagiotto]] (who had  an agreement with Genova).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/?action=read&idnotizia=12096|title=Sernagiotto|publisher=tuttojuve.com}}</ref> Juventus clinched its second title in a row with 54 points<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital32.html|publisher=RSSSF.com|title=Season 1931-32}}</ref> one more from the previous campaign surpassing runner-up Bologna thanks to a powerful offense scoring 89 goals (65 in away) and conceded only 38.\n\nAlso [[Raimundo Orsi]] with 20 goals (included 5 penalties) became 5th best topscorer of the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juworld.net/stagioni-partite-amichevoli.asp?idstagione=35|publisher=juworld.net|title= Orsi goals season|language=Italian}}</ref>\n\n